2712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\"> JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602777/Liverpool-boss-Brendan-Rodgers-Well-unleash-power-Anfield-against-City.html\"> Roar us to title! We\'ll unleash power of Anfield against City, says Liverpool boss Rodgers</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602794/It-feels-just-like-1980s-But-glory-days-finally-return-Anfield.html\"> Rodgers\' rampant Liverpool feel just like the legendary 1980s sides... but will the glory days finally return to Anfield?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602889/Suarez-Sturridge-Sterling-Aguero-Co-Liverpool-edge-combined-title-chasing-XI.html\"> MARTIN KEOWN: Suarez, Sturridge and Sterling over Aguero and Co... why Liverpool have the edge in my combined title-chasing XI</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601436/Something-Weekend-Liverpool-vs-Manchester-City-Arsenal-vs-Wigan-Athletic-Hull-City-vs-Sheffield-United-centre-stage-football-preview.html\"> SOMETHING FOR THE WEEKEND: Liverpool and Man City\'s title showdown and FA Cup semis take centre stage as Hillsborough is remembered 25 years on</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602272/Sheffield-Wednesday-dedicate-programme-page-96-Liverpool-fans.html\"> Sheffield Wednesday dedicate programme front page to 96 Liverpool fans who died at Hillsborough</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603082/Hillsborough-25th-Anniversary-Milan-fans-emotional-tribute-Liverpool-victims-1989-European-Cup-semi-final-video.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603082/Hillsborough-25th-Anniversary-Milan-fans-emotional-tribute-Liverpool-victims-1989-European-Cup-semi-final-video.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"The night Milan fans paid tribute to the 96 victims of Hillsborough with spine-tingling rendition of You\'ll Never Walk Alone\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603082/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">147</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603082-1D0BEB2700000578-858_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:57:56','2014-04-12 15:38:45'),(32,'b67eb4f720031ae52a0c1d8c86dfb43f1ddc265f57b61466246590bd0b0b204f','dailymail',NULL,'JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html',' I was at Villa Park for the other FA semi-final between Everton and Norwich on that fateful dayOnly when we got back to Liverpool did we realise the full extent of what had happened at HillsboroughUp and down the country children are going to ask why matches are kicking off seven minutes later this weekendIt\'s important they and future generations understand what happenedThe Liverpool players will need to make sure their emotions don\'t get the better of them against Manchester City in this weekend\'s title decider By Jamie Carragher Published: 16:13 EST, 11 April 2014 | Updated: 08:28 EST, 12 April 2014 5,253 shares 165 View comments Hillsborough. Say the word to those of a certain age on Merseyside and almost all will be able to tell you where they were, and what they were doing, on April 15, 1989. I was at Villa Park on what turned out to be the darkest day in English football’s history. Everton were playing Norwich in the FA Cup semi-final, Pat Nevin scored the winning goal and it should have been one of the great days of my young life. Instead it was anything but. I remember an announcement being made at half-time to say the other semi-final between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest had been abandoned but as these were the days before mobile phones and social media nobody knew why. VIDEO Scroll to the bottom for Dalglish, Whelan and Evans on the Hillsborough tribute game  Dark day for football: Many Merseysiders of a certain age remember where they were on April 15, 1989   Tragedy: Fans try to get away from the crush of the crowd as they pour into Hillsborough - 96 people died Tribute: Steven Gerrard and Jamie Carragher present the \'Freedom of the City\' to the Hillsborough Families Support Group in 2009 Kennedy: It\'s a fantastic opportunity to pay a tribute to the 96 From joy to sadness: Carragher witnessed Pat Nevin\'s Everton goal against Norwich in the other Cup semi-final    More from Jamie Carragher...   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Sterling, Barkley and Januzaj are included but who else makes my list of top young players this season? 11/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend 11/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance 04/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: After QPR turned down Zlatan, here\'s my top five stars who got away 28/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Everyone used to fear them, but Arsenal now have no pace or power 28/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Moyes faces a big dilemma over how he gets the best out of United\'s £37m man Mata 21/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Ronaldo needs a Zidane moment to become a true great 21/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER EXCLUSIVE: Beating United at Old Trafford was twice as good as 2009... this would be up there with the glory days of Shankly and Paisley 17/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Premier League title would be Gerrard’s reward for staying loyal 14/03/14   VIEW FULL ARCHIVE It was only when I got into the car with my dad that we began to learn of the horrors that unfolded 70 miles away in Sheffield. We travelled back from Birmingham in near silence, worrying about my cousin, Jamie, and all the other Liverpool fans who we knew had gone to Hillsborough. Only when we got back did we hear the full extent. I was only 11 then and my final memory of the day was when the BBC announced Match of the Day had been cancelled out of respect to those who had died. Everyone we knew, thankfully, came home. For the families of the 96, however, the nightmare was just beginning and it is a national disgrace that they were made to  suffer for so long. Those families have fought tirelessly for justice over the past 25 years and at Anfield tomorrow, before Liverpool’s showdown with Manchester City, then again on Tuesday, when the annual Memorial Service is staged, we will pay tribute to the ones who so tragically passed away. Across Stanley Park, Everton will do the same, as pictures of the service will be beamed on to a big screen at Goodison Park; Everton have stood shoulder-to-shoulder with Liverpool over Hillsborough, which is why  you should never class it as a one-football-club tragedy. It wasn’t. It affected the whole city, as Evertonians had family, friends and work colleagues at Hillsborough. The rivalry between the clubs is intense but, for this particular matter, the bond is unbreakable. When I started attending the Memorial Service as a Liverpool player in 1996, I understood what had happened, but it was only after I became a father in 2002 that I really got a sense of perspective on the agony those parents who lost sons and daughters must have endured. At times during those services, when I heard the congregation singing for ‘justice’, I lost hope that they would ever get a resolution but their resolve, courage and determination to keep fighting has been inspirational, not just to everyone at the club but around the city and far beyond.  Leader: Liverpool manager Kenny Dalglish sees the horror of the Hillsborough disaster first hand   Memorial: Scarves, shirts and the plaque at the Shankly Gates at Anfield marking the 20th anniversary in 2009   Unbreakable bond: An Everton and Liverpool fan stand together on Goodison Park in tribute to the 96 in 2012    The families of the 96 got their  breakthrough in 2009, at the 20th Anniversary Memorial Service. Andy Burnham, who was then the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, addressed the crowd but he was shouted down. Afterwards, I attended a reception at Liverpool Town Hall with Steven Gerrard and Kenny Dalglish as the families were being honoured with the Freedom of the City; Burnham was visibly shaken by what had happened and he said that night: ‘We will get to the bottom of this.’ Hopefully, now that the fresh inquests into the deaths have started, some form of closure will arrive at some point in the near future, but that does not mean what happened that day in Sheffield can ever be forgotten.  Liverpool Ambassador: Club legend Dalglish went to all 96 funerals and even attended four in one day   Respect: The clock at Hillsborough is stopped at 15.06, the time the game was stopped (left), while Sheffield Wednesday have paid tribute on the cover of the match programme for Saturday\'s game with Blackburn (right) Never forget: Liverpool fans show their respect to the people who died before a home game at Anfield Speech: Andy Burham insisted \'we will get to the bottom of this\' after speaking at the 2009 memorial service  Up and down the country this weekend, young children will be going to games and asking their  parents why all matches are kicking off seven minutes later than they are normally scheduled, after a period of silence. It is important they, and future generations, understand what happened. No stadium will carry the feeling like Anfield; Liverpool’s players will have to use the emotion to their advantage and not let it affect them the way it happened to Manchester United when they marked the 50th anniversary of the Munich Air Disaster against Manchester City. Anfield is unique when it comes to generating atmosphere on special occasions. As a player, you try to block the noise out when the game begins but you are always conscious of the impact it can have and tomorrow could be a day to rival St Etienne in 1977 or Chelsea in 2005. I played in the latter game, the Champions League semi-final, and it was the most intense atmosphere I experienced. When Liverpool’s fans build up a head of steam, they can influence the result of a game and that certainly happened against Chelsea nine years ago. Super sub: David Fairclough scores for Liverpool against St Etienne in the 1977 European Cup quarter-final Famous night: Liverpool frontman Luis Garcia (second right) celebrates after scoring against Chelsea in 2005     Team effort: Carragher punches the air and celebrates with goalkeeper Jerzy Dudek after beating Chelsea  There is a month of the campaign to go but it feels like the title decider. A draw would let Chelsea back in, assuming they beat Swansea, but the way Liverpool and City are playing, there should be goals. Liverpool need three points. City, with a game in hand, would be the happier if it is a stalemate. Incidentally, the last time Liverpool were involved in a title race, in 2009, it came in the year of a significant Hillsborough anniversary. We finished second that season, despite our best efforts. It would be fitting, then, if Brendan Rodgers and his squad could go one step better this time.  Runners-up: Steven Gerrard celebrates scoring against Man United when Liverpool finished second in 2009    TOP FIVE... YOUNG PLAYERS OF THE YEAR Luis Suarez is odds-on to win PFA Player of the Year but less clear-cut is who will receive the Young Player’s award. Eden Hazard and Daniel Sturridge are the favourites but these five young stars also deserve to be high up in people’s thinking.  Clear favourite: Liverpool frontman Luis Suarez is odds-on to win the PFA Player of the Year award   Boy in Blue: Chelsea wideman Eden Hazard has been one of the standout performers for the Blues this season   Natural goalscorer: Liverpool striker Daniel Sturridge has been lethal in front of the goal for the Reds     1. Raheem Sterling There was always a buzz around Raheem when I was at Liverpool but this season he has shown there is substance to the hype. He has been brilliant since getting back into the team, adding goals to his speed on the flanks, and he looks set to go to the World Cup.  Living up to the hype: Liverpool frontman Raheem Sterling has added goals to his game this season     2. Ross Barkley Back in August, when I wrote my second column for Sportsmail, I highlighted the Everton midfielder as one to watch and he has done nothing but improve. An explosive talent, with energy and two great feet, he is another who Roy Hodgson will come calling for in June.  One to watch: Ross Barkley has constantly improved this season as Everton challenge for fourth     3. Luke Shaw Scouts have been flocking to St Mary’s to see Shaw in action and it is no wonder the top clubs want to prise the left back away from Southampton. If he moves this summer, Shaw will command a huge fee but it will be warranted as he has consistently impressed.  Top talent: Southampton\'s Luke Shaw has attracted attention from a host of rival Premier League clubs      4. Adnan Januzaj Manchester United have endured a disappointing campaign but the one bright spot has been the emergence of Januzaj. He’s played 32 games, which is a lot for a 19-year-old, but he has a big future. I liked what I saw of him in pre-season and he has built on that impression.  Bright spot: Adnan Januzaj has shined in an otherwise disappointing campaign for Manchester United     5. John Stones Roberto Martinez is not afraid to give young players opportunities if they are good enough and Stones has impressed since being given his Everton chance. I like the way he uses the ball and it was interesting to see he completed 39 of the 40 passes he attempted against Arsenal last week.  Taking his chances: Everton defender John Stones (left) is equally adept at passing as he his tackling     Hull manager Steve Bruce deserves more credit There has been a lot of talk about who should be crowned Manager of the Year and the vote seems to be split between Brendan Rodgers and Roberto Martinez. Tony Pulis, of course, is also in the running thanks to the outstanding job he has done with Crystal Palace, but why has there not been more made of Steve Bruce’s work at Hull? hen Hull came up last season, many would have had them in their three picks for relegation but it looks like they are going to stay in the Barclays Premier League quite comfortably and they could even crown the campaign with success in the FA Cup.  Under the radar: Steve Bruce has guided Hull to mid-table and could crown the season with Cup success    Bruce, who wants his teams to play in the right style and spirit, deserves to lead Hull out against Sheffield United at Wembley tomorrow and I doubt anyone would begrudge him if he returned next month and climbed the 107 steps to get the trophy, 20 years after he did so as Manchester United’s captain. It used to be said he would be a contender to take over the reins from Sir Alex Ferguson one day but there is a chance an even bigger job might come on his radar in the future, particularly if he puts silverware on his CV. Should the FA keep with their current mantra of wanting an Englishman to manage the England team, I’m sure Bruce would come into their thoughts. He turned down the chance to win an England cap when he was in his 30s but there is little chance he would turn down the FA a second time.  Captain fantastic: Bruce (left) holds aloft the FA Cup in 1994 following Man United\'s final win over Chelsea      Dalglish: We laugh at same stories every time we\'re back together Whelan: I will drive Kenny home to make sure he starts me Evans: It\'s nice to have a Premier League which is competitive   More... Staunton: I still find it hard to talk about the horror I saw that day at Hillsborough Dalglish says families of the 96 have to come before anyone else on eve of Hillsborough anniversary Sheffield Wednesday dedicate programme front page to 96 Liverpool fans who died at Hillsborough Hillsborough remembered: Why all this weekend\'s matches are kicking off seven minutes late on 25th anniversary We\'ll win it for the 96: Hillsborough driving Liverpool to the title, says Rodgers Hillsborough remembered: The horrors of that sun-kissed Saturday will haunt me forever, by Jeff Powell  Share or comment on this article 5.2kshares','\n<ul class=\"article-summary sport\"><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">I was at Villa Park for the other FA semi-final between Everton and Norwich on that fateful day</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Only when we got back to Liverpool did we realise the full extent of what had happened at Hillsborough</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Up and down the country children are going to ask why matches are kicking off seven minutes later this weekend</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">It\'s important they and future generations understand what happened</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">The Liverpool players will need to make sure their emotions don\'t get the better of them against Manchester City in this weekend\'s title decider <br/></font></b></li></ul>\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1076287/Jamie-Carragher.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jamie Carragher</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 16:13 EST, 11 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 08:28 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 5,253</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">165</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Hillsborough. Say the word to those of a certain age on Merseyside and almost all will be able to tell you where they were, and what they were doing, on April 15, 1989.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I was at Villa Park on what turned out to be the darkest day in English football’s history. Everton were playing Norwich in the FA Cup semi-final, Pat Nevin scored the winning goal and it should have been one of the great days of my young life.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Instead it was anything but. I remember an announcement being made at half-time to say the other semi-final between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest had been abandoned but as these were the days before mobile phones and social media nobody knew why.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b><font color=\"FFFFFF\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(12, 172, 12);\">VIDEO</span></font> Scroll to the bottom for Dalglish, Whelan and Evans on the Hillsborough tribute game</b><br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Dark day for football: Many Merseysiders of a certain age remember where they were on April 15, 1989\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"418\" id=\"i-aa830e81\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-14F4F5B8000005DC-601_634x418.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Dark day for football: Many Merseysiders of a certain age remember where they were on April 15, 1989</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Tragedy: Fans try to get away from the crush of the crowd as they pour into Hillsborough - 96 people died\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-a40c0e3c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D00561100000578-665_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Tragedy: Fans try to get away from the crush of the crowd as they pour into Hillsborough - 96 people died<br/></p><div class=\"artSplitter\"><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Tribute: Steven Gerrard and Jamie Carragher present the \'Freedom of the City\' to the Hillsborough Families Support Group in 2009\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"428\" id=\"i-aa9b0e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D07DFE900000578-413_634x428.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Tribute: Steven Gerrard and Jamie Carragher present the \'Freedom of the City\' to the Hillsborough Families Support Group in 2009</p><div class=\"moduleFull\"> <a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3452206583001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Kennedy: It\'s a fantastic opportunity to pay a tribute to the 96</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/video-undefined-1CFF33B800000578-476_636x364.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"From joy to sadness: Carragher witnessed Pat Nevin\'s Everton goal against Norwich in the other Cup semi-final\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"403\" id=\"i-a74f0e55\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D09A99500000578-124_634x403.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">From joy to sadness: Carragher witnessed Pat Nevin\'s Everton goal against Norwich in the other Cup semi-final</p> </div><p> </p> </div><p> </p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"item\"> <div class=\"columnist-archive-narrow bogr1\"> <span class=\"tl\"> </span> <span class=\"tr\"> </span> <h3>More from Jamie Carragher...</h3> <ul> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602715/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Daniel-Sturridge-Eden-Hazard-lead-way-five-young-players-year.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Sterling, Barkley and Januzaj are included but who else makes my list of top young players this season?</a> <span class=\"date\">11/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend</a> <span class=\"date\">11/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance</a> <span class=\"date\">04/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592009/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-After-QPR-turned-Zlatan-heres-five-stars-got-away.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: After QPR turned down Zlatan, here\'s my top five stars who got away</a> <span class=\"date\">28/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2591855/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Everyone-used-fear-Arsenal-no-pace-power.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Everyone used to fear them, but Arsenal now have no pace or power</a> <span class=\"date\">28/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2586565/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Manchester-United-boss-David-Moyes-faces-big-dilemma-Juan-Mata.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Moyes faces a big dilemma over how he gets the best out of United\'s £37m man Mata</a> <span class=\"date\">21/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2586438/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Cristiano-Ronaldo-needs-Zinedine-Zidane-moment-true-great.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Ronaldo needs a Zidane moment to become a true great</a> <span class=\"date\">21/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2583008/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-EXCLUSIVE-This-win-twice-good-2009-Liverpool-major-title-contenders.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER EXCLUSIVE: Beating United at Old Trafford was twice as good as 2009... this would be up there with the glory days of Shankly and Paisley</a> <span class=\"date\">17/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2581300/Steven-Gerrard-deserves-win-Premier-League-loyalty-Liverpool-Jamie-Carragher.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Premier League title would be Gerrard’s reward for staying loyal</a> <span class=\"date\">14/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"columnist-1076287/Jamie-Carragher.html\">VIEW FULL ARCHIVE</a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It was only when I got into the car with my dad that we began to learn of the horrors that unfolded 70 miles away in Sheffield. We travelled back from Birmingham in near silence, worrying about my cousin, Jamie, and all the other Liverpool fans who we knew had gone to Hillsborough. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Only when we got back did we hear the full extent. I was only 11 then and my final memory of the day was when the BBC announced Match of the Day had been cancelled out of respect to those who had died. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Everyone we knew, thankfully, came home. For the families of the 96, however, the nightmare was just beginning and it is a national disgrace that they were made to  suffer for so long.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Those families have fought tirelessly for justice over the past 25 years and at Anfield tomorrow, before Liverpool’s showdown with Manchester City, then again on Tuesday, when the annual Memorial Service is staged, we will pay tribute to the ones who so tragically passed away.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Across Stanley Park, Everton will do the same, as pictures of the service will be beamed on to a big screen at Goodison Park; Everton have stood shoulder-to-shoulder with Liverpool over Hillsborough, which is why  you should never class it as a one-football-club tragedy.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It wasn’t. It affected the whole city, as Evertonians had family, friends and work colleagues at Hillsborough. The rivalry between the clubs is intense but, for this particular matter, the bond is unbreakable.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">When I started attending the Memorial Service as a Liverpool player in 1996, I understood what had happened, but it was only after I became a father in 2002 that I really got a sense of perspective on the agony those parents who lost sons and daughters must have endured.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">At times during those services, when I heard the congregation singing for ‘justice’, I lost hope that they would ever get a resolution but their resolve, courage and determination to keep fighting has been inspirational, not just to everyone at the club but around the city and far beyond.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Leader: Liverpool manager Kenny Dalglish sees the horror of the Hillsborough disaster first hand\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a7ba0e60\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D0055FD00000578-616_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Leader: Liverpool manager Kenny Dalglish sees the horror of the Hillsborough disaster first hand</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Memorial: Scarves, shirts and the plaque at the Shankly Gates at Anfield marking the 20th anniversary in 2009\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"414\" id=\"i-a4b50e45\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D05520500000578-849_634x414.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Memorial: Scarves, shirts and the plaque at the Shankly Gates at Anfield marking the 20th anniversary in 2009</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unbreakable bond: An Everton and Liverpool fan stand together on Goodison Park in tribute to the 96 in 2012\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"473\" id=\"i-a8a30e7a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1510F5D6000005DC-986_634x473.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unbreakable bond: An Everton and Liverpool fan stand together on Goodison Park in tribute to the 96 in 2012</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The families of the 96 got their  breakthrough in 2009, at the 20th Anniversary Memorial Service. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Andy Burnham, who was then the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, addressed the crowd but he was shouted down. Afterwards, I attended a reception at Liverpool Town Hall with Steven Gerrard and Kenny Dalglish as the families were being honoured with the Freedom of the City; Burnham was visibly shaken by what had happened and he said that night: ‘We will get to the bottom of this.’</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Hopefully, now that the fresh inquests into the deaths have started, some form of closure will arrive at some point in the near future, but that does not mean what happened that day in Sheffield can ever be forgotten.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Liverpool Ambassador: Club legend Dalglish went to all 96 funerals and even attended four in one day\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"458\" id=\"i-a66e0e5a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D054B0700000578-719_634x458.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Liverpool Ambassador: Club legend Dalglish went to all 96 funerals and even attended four in one day</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Respect: The clock at Hillsborough is stopped at 15.06, the time the 1989 semi-final was stopped (left), while Sheffield Wednesday have paid tribute on the cover of the programme for Saturday\'s match with Blackburn (right)\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"497\" id=\"i-9c6c0e46\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D054FBF00000578-27_306x497.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Respect: The clock at Hillsborough is stopped at 15.06, the time the 1989 semi-final was stopped (left), while Sheffield Wednesday have paid tribute on the cover of the programme for Saturday\'s match with Blackburn (right)\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"497\" id=\"i-9b930e3d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D075FB900000578-19_306x497.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Respect: The clock at Hillsborough is stopped at 15.06, the time the game was stopped (left), while Sheffield Wednesday have paid tribute on the cover of the match programme for Saturday\'s game with Blackburn (right)<br/></p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Never forget: Liverpool fans show their respect to the people who died before a home game at Anfield\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a7c90e66\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D0055BB00000578-988_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Never forget: Liverpool fans show their respect to the people who died before a home game at Anfield</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Speech: Andy Burham insisted \'we will get to the bottom of this\' after speaking at the 2009 memorial service\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"409\" id=\"i-a6f60e63\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-0477F026000005DC-940_634x409.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Speech: Andy Burham insisted \'we will get to the bottom of this\' after speaking at the 2009 memorial service</p> </div><p> </p> </div><p> </p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Up and down the country this weekend, young children will be going to games and asking their  parents why all matches are kicking off seven minutes later than they are normally scheduled, after a period of silence. It is important they, and future generations, understand what happened. No stadium will carry the feeling like Anfield; Liverpool’s players will have to use the emotion to their advantage and not let it affect them the way it happened to Manchester United when they marked the 50th anniversary of the Munich Air Disaster against Manchester City.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Anfield is unique when it comes to generating atmosphere on special occasions. As a player, you try to block the noise out when the game begins but you are always conscious of the impact it can have and tomorrow could be a day to rival St Etienne in 1977 or Chelsea in 2005.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I played in the latter game, the Champions League semi-final, and it was the most intense atmosphere I experienced. When Liverpool’s fans build up a head of steam, they can influence the result of a game and that certainly happened against Chelsea nine years ago.</font></p>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Super sub: David Fairclough scores for Liverpool against St Etienne in the 1977 European Cup quarter-final\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"438\" id=\"i-a6eb0e61\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-027E056B0000044D-329_634x438.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Super sub: David Fairclough scores for Liverpool against St Etienne in the 1977 European Cup quarter-final</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Famous night: Liverpool frontman Luis Garcia (second right) celebrates after scoring against Chelsea in 2005\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"460\" id=\"i-a5000e48\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-0283906B0000044D-214_634x460.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Famous night: Liverpool frontman Luis Garcia (second right) celebrates after scoring against Chelsea in 2005</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Team effort: Carragher punches the air and celebrates with goalkeeper Jerzy Dudek after beating Chelsea\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"426\" id=\"i-a6540e59\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-0283B32B0000044D-752_634x426.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Team effort: Carragher punches the air and celebrates with goalkeeper Jerzy Dudek after beating Chelsea</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There is a month of the campaign to go but it feels like the title decider. A draw would let Chelsea back in, assuming they beat Swansea, but the way Liverpool and City are playing, there should be goals. Liverpool need three points. City, with a game in hand, would be the happier if it is a stalemate.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Incidentally, the last time Liverpool were involved in a title race, in 2009, it came in the year of a significant Hillsborough anniversary. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">We finished second that season, despite our best efforts. It would be fitting, then, if Brendan Rodgers and his squad could go one step better this time.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Runners-up: Steven Gerrard celebrates scoring against Man United when Liverpool finished second in 2009\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"444\" id=\"i-9d5a0e51\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-03E5BBC1000005DC-61_634x444.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Runners-up: Steven Gerrard celebrates scoring against Man United when Liverpool finished second in 2009</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p></p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">TOP FIVE... YOUNG PLAYERS OF THE YEAR</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Luis Suarez is odds-on to win PFA Player of the Year but less clear-cut is who will receive the Young Player’s award. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Eden Hazard and Daniel Sturridge are the favourites but these five young stars also deserve to be high up in people’s thinking.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Clear favourite: Liverpool frontman Luis Suarez is odds-on to win the PFA Player of the Year award\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"425\" id=\"i-a84d0e61\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1CB20B2C00000578-402_634x425.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Clear favourite: Liverpool frontman Luis Suarez is odds-on to win the PFA Player of the Year award</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Boy in Blue: Chelsea wideman Eden Hazard has been one of the standout performers for the Blues this season\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"436\" id=\"i-a9450e6a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-06DCB76A00000514-117_634x436.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Boy in Blue: Chelsea wideman Eden Hazard has been one of the standout performers for the Blues this season</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Natural goalscorer: Liverpool striker Daniel Sturridge has been lethal in front of the goal for the Reds\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"433\" id=\"i-a8d00e67\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1B099BE900000578-106_634x433.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Natural goalscorer: Liverpool striker Daniel Sturridge has been lethal in front of the goal for the Reds</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">1. Raheem Sterling </font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">There was always a buzz around Raheem when I was at Liverpool but this season he has shown there is substance to the hype. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He has been brilliant since getting back into the team, adding goals to his speed on the flanks, and he looks set to go to the World Cup.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Living up to the hype: Liverpool frontman Raheem Sterling has added goals to his game this season\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"442\" id=\"i-aa570e7a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1B4BB6D600000578-398_634x442.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Living up to the hype: Liverpool frontman Raheem Sterling has added goals to his game this season</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">2. Ross Barkley </font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Back in August, when I wrote my second column for <i>Sportsmail</i>, I highlighted the Everton midfielder as one to watch and he has done nothing but improve. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">An explosive talent, with energy and two great feet, he is another who Roy Hodgson will come calling for in June.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"One to watch: Ross Barkley has constantly improved this season as Everton challenge for fourth\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"417\" id=\"i-a8330e63\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1CE2417E00000578-118_634x417.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">One to watch: Ross Barkley has constantly improved this season as Everton challenge for fourth</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">3. Luke Shaw </font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Scouts have been flocking to St Mary’s to see Shaw in action and it is no wonder the top clubs want to prise the left back away from Southampton. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">If he moves this summer, Shaw will command a huge fee but it will be warranted as he has consistently impressed.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Top talent: Southampton\'s Luke Shaw has attracted attention from a host of rival Premier League clubs\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"405\" id=\"i-a45d0e38\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-0668A55300000514-141_634x405.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Top talent: Southampton\'s Luke Shaw has attracted attention from a host of rival Premier League clubs</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">4. Adnan Januzaj </font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Manchester United have endured a disappointing campaign but the one bright spot has been the emergence of Januzaj. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He’s played 32 games, which is a lot for a 19-year-old, but he has a big future. I liked what I saw of him in pre-season and he has built on that impression.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Bright spot: Adnan Januzaj has shined in an otherwise disappointing campaign for Manchester United\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"494\" id=\"i-aaa60e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1CDE782C00000578-332_634x494.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Bright spot: Adnan Januzaj has shined in an otherwise disappointing campaign for Manchester United</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">5. John Stones </font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Roberto Martinez is not afraid to give young players opportunities if they are good enough and Stones has impressed since being given his Everton chance. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">I like the way he uses the ball and it was interesting to see he completed 39 of the 40 passes he attempted against Arsenal last week.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Taking his chances: Everton defender John Stones (left) is equally adept at passing as he his tackling\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"429\" id=\"i-a6e10e59\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1CE2384100000578-545_634x429.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Taking his chances: Everton defender John Stones (left) is equally adept at passing as he his tackling</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Hull manager Steve Bruce deserves more credit</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There has been a lot of talk about who should be crowned Manager of the Year and the vote seems to be split between Brendan Rodgers and Roberto Martinez.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Tony Pulis, of course, is also in the running thanks to the outstanding job he has done with Crystal Palace, but why has there not been more made of Steve Bruce’s work at Hull? <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">hen Hull came up last season, many would have had them in their three picks for relegation but it looks like they are going to stay in the Barclays Premier League quite comfortably and they could even crown the campaign with success in the FA Cup.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Under the radar: Steve Bruce has guided Hull to mid-table and could crown the season with Cup success\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"424\" id=\"i-a6180e4f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D0913A500000578-615_634x424.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Under the radar: Steve Bruce has guided Hull to mid-table and could crown the season with Cup success</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Bruce, who wants his teams to play in the right style and spirit, deserves to lead Hull out against Sheffield United at Wembley tomorrow and I doubt anyone would begrudge him if he returned next month and climbed the 107 steps to get the trophy, 20 years after he did so as Manchester United’s captain.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It used to be said he would be a contender to take over the reins from Sir Alex Ferguson one day but there is a chance an even bigger job might come on his radar in the future, particularly if he puts silverware on his CV.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Should the FA keep with their current mantra of wanting an Englishman to manage the England team, I’m sure Bruce would come into their thoughts. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He turned down the chance to win an England cap when he was in his 30s but there is little chance he would turn down the FA a second time.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Captain fantastic: Bruce (left) holds aloft the FA Cup in 1994 following Man United\'s final win over Chelsea\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"438\" id=\"i-a3680e3d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-00674246000004B0-482_634x438.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Captain fantastic: Bruce (left) holds aloft the FA Cup in 1994 following Man United\'s final win over Chelsea</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3452153365001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Dalglish: We laugh at same stories every time we\'re back together</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/video-undefined-1CFF33C200000578-767_636x364.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3452154924001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Whelan: I will drive Kenny home to make sure he starts me</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/video-undefined-1CFF33B000000578-868_636x364.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3452208709001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Evans: It\'s nice to have a Premier League which is competitive</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/video-undefined-1CFF33BE00000578-929_636x364.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597755/Staunton-I-hard-talk-horror-I-saw-day-Hillsborough.html\"> Staunton: I still find it hard to talk about the horror I saw that day at Hillsborough</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602266/Kenny-Dalglish-led-Liverpool-mourning-Hillsborough-tragedy.html\"> Dalglish says families of the 96 have to come before anyone else on eve of Hillsborough anniversary</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602272/Sheffield-Wednesday-dedicate-programme-page-96-Liverpool-fans.html\"> Sheffield Wednesday dedicate programme front page to 96 Liverpool fans who died at Hillsborough</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602268/Hillsborough-remembered-Why-weekends-matches-kicking-seven-minutes-late-25th-anniversary.html\"> Hillsborough remembered: Why all this weekend\'s matches are kicking off seven minutes late on 25th anniversary</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598360/Well-win-96-Hillsborough-driving-Liverpool-title-says-Brendan-Rodgers.html\"> We\'ll win it for the 96: Hillsborough driving Liverpool to the title, says Rodgers</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602254/Hillsborough-remembered-The-horrors-sun-kissed-Saturday-haunt-forever-Jeff-Powell.html\"> Hillsborough remembered: The horrors of that sun-kissed Saturday will haunt me forever, by Jeff Powell</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2602712/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">5.2k</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/11/article-2602712-1D0A438E00000578-580_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:57:57','2014-04-12 15:28:49'),(33,'11442c7ed7e9c87e68d521a083c0278b67240f5f651ae1d5eed384e2dd0de0cb','dailymail',NULL,'Lukaku and Barry returning home will rip up the Champions League dreams of Everton and Martinez THE NUMBERS GAME','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html',' By Charlie Skillen Follow @@charlieskillen Published: 07:27 EST, 12 April 2014 | Updated: 08:17 EST, 12 April 2014 25 shares 53 View comments MATCH ZONEClick here for your ultimate stats guide to all the big games, including heat maps All good things come to an end. For Roberto Martinez and Everton, that finale could come all too abruptly. As the Toffees continue their assault on Champions League qualification, many - particularly those in north London - have questioned the morals of three key players being loaned in from top clubs. Gareth Barry has been the lynchpin in allowing Martinez\'s free-flowing midfield, Gerard Deulofeu has shown off his exquisite talent in spells and Romelu Lukaku has spent all season proving to everyone that Chelsea do, in fact, have a top-class striker.  Deadly duo: Gareth Barry (left) and Romelu Lukaku have had a terrific season on loan at Everton The truth is that Everton have worked a flawed system flawlessly. It is an undesirable state of affairs that Lukaku can hurt Chelsea\'s rivals when not even based in west London. Even better for Lukaku, who gets first-team football away from Stamford Bridge and the pressure of being second fiddle. Everton get a Champions League quality player. But if Martinez\'s men do break into the top four, it is hard to see them carrying on that momentum shorn of those three players.  Back of the net: Lukaku wheels away having notches Everton\'s second goal in their 3-0 win over Arsenal last Sunday Christian Benteke\'s injury means Lukaku will be 100 per cent leading the line for Belgium at the World Cup. If it\'s true that Jose Mourinho doesn\'t see him as part of his first-team plans for Chelsea, the World Cup will be the ultimate shop window, where Lukaku\'s value rockets to the kind of £30million fees a level above where Everton are able to play. Everton with LukakuPlayed 25 - Won 16 - Drawn 6 - Lost 3Goals per game: 1.9Win percentage: 64%Points per game: 2.2Everton without LukakuPlayed 7 - Won 3 - Drawn 3 - Lost 2Goals per game: 0.7Win percentage: 29%Points per game: 1.3 This would mean a major revamp of Everton\'s attack. The Toffees have won just 1.3 points per game without the Belgian as opposed to 2.2 with him in the side. Naturally, the Toffees’ potency is also greatly reduced, with them relying on Steven Naismith or Kevin Mirallas for goals. With Lukaku, Everton manage 1.9 goals per game, and just 0.7 without him. His 76 shots are the most of any Everton player, with him and Mirallas far and away the most forward-thinking Toffees. Losing this without replacement would be catastrophic. Everton shots this seasonLukaku 76Mirallas 75Barkley 68Osman 45Coleman 27 Lukaku may have grabbed all the headlines, but it is the capture from Manchester City who has made the team tick the most. Gareth Barry has used the temporary switch to reinvigorate a career on its last legs to become one of the league\'s vital midfielders. It\'s impossible to overstate what Barry gives the team. His steady and assured role allows players like James McCarthy and Ross Barkley to impose their style on the opposition.   More... Everton boss Martinez keen to sign on-loan Lukaku on a permanent deal from Chelsea Everton would be nowhere near Champions League without loan stars like Lukaku... but where would your side be in the table? Martinez blasts loan criticism as \'ridiculous\' and \'lazy\' as Everton march towards Europe MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan) Lukaku transfer hinders on World Cup as Chelsea hope strong display from Belgium star will increase asking price Loan star Barry will have to take wage cut if he wants to stay at Everton  Marksman: Lukaku has taken more shots than any other Everton player this season as he leads the attack    Everton with BarryPlayed 27 - Won 17 - Drawn 6 - Lost 4Average Goals for: 1.7Average Goals against: 0.9Win percentage: 63%Points per game: 2.1Everton without BarryPlayed 5 - Won 1 - Drawn 3 - Lost 1Average Goals for: 1Average Goals against: 1.2Win percentage: 20%Points per game: 1.2 Martinez has struggled by without his midfield lynchpin in just five Premier League games this season, with Everton winning only one. They also concede over a goal a game without the former England man as opposed to 0.9 with him in the side. He is central to everything Everton do. Barry has the most touches on the ball in a game than any other player in the side, and his number of passes over a game comes in only behind Yaya Toure and David Silva, central stars for high-flying Manchester City.  Driving force: Barry plays a pivotal role in building Toffee attacks from his deep-lying midfield position    Touches per game: EvertonBarry: 83.4Baines: 82.8Jagielka: 69.8Coleman: 65.4McCarthy: 64.5 Passes per game: Premier LeagueYaya Toure: 70.7David Silva: 70.5Gareth Barry: 67.4Michael Carrick: 66.9Aaron Ramsey: 66.9 His heat map in last weekend’s 3-0 destruction of Arsenal shows what he offers the team. He completely controlled the crucial area just inside Everton’s half, allowing the rest of the midfield to kill off the lacklustre Gunners.  Influence: Gareth Barry\'s heatmap against Arsenal demonstrates just how much influence he has for Everton  It’s no overstatement to say that Barry has been one of the best midfielders in the league this season. To replace what he gives Everton usually costs an absolute premium. Midfielders who can enjoy that level of control over possession in a Premier League game are a valuable commodity. Good news then, that Barry seems the most likely out of any of the loan charges to pen a permanent deal at Goodison Park in the summer. Even so, his aging years mean he\'s still not a long-term solution. Someone who would be is Gerard Deulofeu. One of the major talking points in England in the fallout of Barcelona\'s proposed transfer ban is that the playmaker will now stay with the Catalan giants. While it was previously thought he may have been a slight level below what Barcelona need – not that that stops you being a superb player for 99 per cent of teams – they will now be looking to Deulofeu for fresh blood.  On target: Another loanee Gerard Deulofeu has also shown his class at times this season for Everton  Deulofeu has played only in fits and starts while he get to grips with the experience of playing in an honours-chasing side, and has also been overshadowed by the emergence of Ross Barkley, but his class has been clear. It’s another bright young talent that won’t be plying his trade at Goodison Park. The problem with this route to the top is you generally only get to do it once. Manchester City, Chelsea and Barcelona might not be as open to lending top talent to a fellow Champions League club. While Roberto Martinez has performed miracles this season, his greatest trick will come this summer when he has to Sellotape his side back together over the chasms that Lukaku and Barry will leave. Do that and carry on from where they left off, and even Arsene Wenger won’t have anything to moan about.  Mastermind: Roberto Martinez will need to perform more miracles next season without Barry and Lukaku    More... Everton boss Martinez keen to sign on-loan Lukaku on a permanent deal from Chelsea Everton would be nowhere near Champions League without loan stars like Lukaku... but where would your side be in the table? Martinez blasts loan criticism as \'ridiculous\' and \'lazy\' as Everton march towards Europe MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan) Lukaku transfer hinders on World Cup as Chelsea hope strong display from Belgium star will increase asking price Loan star Barry will have to take wage cut if he wants to stay at Everton  Share or comment on this article 25shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1091291/Charlie-Skillen.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Charlie Skillen</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@charlieskillen\">Follow @@charlieskillen</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 07:27 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 08:17 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Lukaku and Barry returning home will rip up the Champions League dreams of Everton and Martinez\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 25</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">53</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<div class=\"art-insert sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>MATCH ZONE</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/matchzone/index.html#matchzone\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Click here for your ultimate stats guide to all the big games, including heat maps</font></a><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">All good things come to an end. For Roberto Martinez and Everton, that finale could come all too abruptly.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As the Toffees continue their assault on Champions League qualification, many - particularly those in north London - have questioned the morals of three key players being loaned in from top clubs.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Gareth Barry has been the lynchpin in allowing Martinez\'s free-flowing midfield, Gerard Deulofeu has shown off his exquisite talent in spells and Romelu Lukaku has spent all season proving to everyone that Chelsea do, in fact, have a top-class striker.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Deadly duo: Gareth Barry (left) and Romelu Lukaku have had a terrific season on loan at Everton\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"451\" id=\"i-a8110e64\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1CF040B400000578-597_634x451.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Deadly duo: Gareth Barry (left) and Romelu Lukaku have had a terrific season on loan at Everton</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The truth is that Everton have worked a flawed system flawlessly. It is an undesirable state of affairs that Lukaku can hurt Chelsea\'s rivals when not even based in west London.</font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Even better for Lukaku, who gets first-team football away from Stamford Bridge and the pressure of being second fiddle. Everton get a Champions League quality player.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">But if Martinez\'s men do break into the top four, it is hard to see them carrying on that momentum shorn of those three players.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Back of the net: Lukaku wheels away having notches Everton\'s second goal in their 3-0 win over Arsenal last Sunday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"388\" id=\"i-a9530e75\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1CE20AA400000578-196_634x388.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Back of the net: Lukaku wheels away having notches Everton\'s second goal in their 3-0 win over Arsenal last Sunday</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Christian Benteke\'s injury means Lukaku will be 100 per cent leading the line for Belgium at the World Cup.</font></p></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">If it\'s true that Jose Mourinho doesn\'t see him as part of his first-team plans for Chelsea, the World Cup will be the ultimate shop window, where Lukaku\'s value rockets to the kind of £30million fees a level above where Everton are able to play.</font></p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Everton with Lukaku</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Played 25 - Won 16 - Drawn 6 - Lost 3</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Goals per game: 1.9</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Win percentage: 64%</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Points per game: 2.2</font><br/></p><p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Everton without Lukaku</font></b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Played 7 - Won 3 - Drawn 3 - Lost 2</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Goals per game: 0.7</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Win percentage: 29%</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Points per game: 1.3</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This would mean a major revamp of Everton\'s attack. The Toffees have won just 1.3 points per game without the Belgian as opposed to 2.2 with him in the side.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Naturally, the Toffees’ potency is also greatly reduced, with them relying on Steven Naismith or Kevin Mirallas for goals. With Lukaku, Everton manage 1.9 goals per game, and just 0.7 without him.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">His 76 shots are the most of any Everton player, with him and Mirallas far and away the most forward-thinking Toffees. Losing this without replacement would be catastrophic.</font></p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Everton shots this season</font></b><br/></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Lukaku 76</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Mirallas 75</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Barkley 68</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Osman 45</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Coleman 27</font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Lukaku may have grabbed all the headlines, but it is the capture from Manchester City who has made the team tick the most.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Gareth Barry has used the temporary switch to reinvigorate a career on its last legs to become one of the league\'s vital midfielders.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It\'s impossible to overstate what Barry gives the team. His steady and assured role allows players like James McCarthy and Ross Barkley to impose their style on the opposition.</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2603070/Everton-boss-Roberto-Martinez-keen-sign-loan-Roberto-Lukaku-permanent-deal-Chelsea.html\"> Everton boss Martinez keen to sign on-loan Lukaku on a permanent deal from Chelsea</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602289/Everton-near-Champions-League-without-loan-signings-table-proves.html\"> Everton would be nowhere near Champions League without loan stars like Lukaku... but where would your side be in the table?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601623/Roberto-Martinez-defends-Evertons-loan-tactics-slamming-ridiculous-critics.html\"> Martinez blasts loan criticism as \'ridiculous\' and \'lazy\' as Everton march towards Europe</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599917/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Everton-fairytale-hooked-shame-built-50m-loan-sham-Lukaku-Barry-Deulofeu-Wengers-right-moan.html\"> MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan)</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599706/Romelu-Lukaku-transfer-hinders-World-Cup-Chelsea-hope-strong-display-Belgium-star-increase-asking-price.html\"> Lukaku transfer hinders on World Cup as Chelsea hope strong display from Belgium star will increase asking price</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597861/Loan-star-Gareth-Barry-wage-cut-wants-stay-Everton.html\"> Loan star Barry will have to take wage cut if he wants to stay at Everton</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Marksman: Lukaku has taken more shots than any other Everton player this season as he leads the attack\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"421\" id=\"i-a6d70e52\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1CF1394000000578-852_634x421.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Marksman: Lukaku has taken more shots than any other Everton player this season as he leads the attack</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Everton with Barry</b><br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Played 27 - Won 17 - Drawn 6 - Lost 4<br/>Average Goals for: 1.7<br/>Average Goals against: 0.9<br/>Win percentage: 63%<br/>Points per game: 2.1<br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Everton without Barry<br/></b></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Played 5 - Won 1 - Drawn 3 - Lost 1<br/>Average Goals for: 1<br/>Average Goals against: 1.2<br/>Win percentage: 20%<br/>Points per game: 1.2</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"></font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Martinez has struggled by without his midfield lynchpin in just five Premier League games this season, with Everton winning only one. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">They also concede over a goal a game without the former England man as opposed to 0.9 with him in the side.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He is central to everything Everton do. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Barry has the most touches on the ball in a game than any other player in the side, and his number of passes over a game comes in only behind Yaya Toure and David Silva, central stars for high-flying Manchester City.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Driving force: Barry plays a pivotal role in building Toffee attacks from his deep-lying midfield position\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-a98e0e6c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1CE22EC200000578-390_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Driving force: Barry plays a pivotal role in building Toffee attacks from his deep-lying midfield position</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"><p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Touches per game: Everton</font></b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Barry: 83.4<br/>Baines: 82.8<br/>Jagielka: 69.8<br/>Coleman: 65.4<br/>McCarthy: 64.5</font> <br/></p></div> <div class=\"splitRight\"><p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Passes per game: Premier League</font></b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yaya Toure: 70.7<br/>David Silva: 70.5<br/>Gareth Barry: 67.4<br/>Michael Carrick: 66.9<br/>Aaron Ramsey: 66.9</font> <br/></p></div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">His heat map in last weekend’s 3-0 destruction of Arsenal shows what he offers the team. He completely controlled the crucial area just inside Everton’s half, allowing the rest of the midfield to kill off the lacklustre Gunners</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Influence: Gareth Barry\'s heatmap against Arsenal demonstrates just how much influence he has for Everton\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"457\" id=\"i-998c0e26\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1D0C317900000578-63_634x457.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Influence: Gareth Barry\'s heatmap against Arsenal demonstrates just how much influence he has for Everton</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It’s no overstatement to say that Barry has been one of the best midfielders in the league this season. To replace what he gives Everton usually costs an absolute premium. Midfielders who can enjoy that level of control over possession in a Premier League game are a valuable commodity.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Good news then, that Barry seems the most likely out of any of the loan charges to pen a permanent deal at Goodison Park in the summer. Even so, his aging years mean he\'s still not a long-term solution.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Someone who would be is Gerard Deulofeu. One of the major talking points in England in the fallout of Barcelona\'s proposed transfer ban is that the playmaker will now stay with the Catalan giants.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">While it was previously thought he may have been a slight level below what Barcelona need – not that that stops you being a superb player for 99 per cent of teams – they will now be looking to Deulofeu for fresh blood.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"On target: Another loanee Gerard Deulofeu has also shown his class at times this season for Everton\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"342\" id=\"i-ac5c0e8c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1CC4CE6E00000578-299_634x342.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">On target: Another loanee Gerard Deulofeu has also shown his class at times this season for Everton</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Deulofeu has played only in fits and starts while he get to grips with the experience of playing in an honours-chasing side, and has also been overshadowed by the emergence of Ross Barkley, but his class has been clear. It’s another bright young talent that won’t be plying his trade at Goodison Park.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The problem with this route to the top is you generally only get to do it once. Manchester City, Chelsea and Barcelona might not be as open to lending top talent to a fellow Champions League club.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">While Roberto Martinez has performed miracles this season, his greatest trick will come this summer when he has to Sellotape his side back together over the chasms that Lukaku and Barry will leave.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Do that and carry on from where they left off, and even Arsene Wenger won’t have anything to moan about.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Mastermind: Roberto Martinez will need to perform more miracles next season without Barry and Lukaku\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-aae40e7d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1D0A4CEC00000578-275_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Mastermind: Roberto Martinez will need to perform more miracles next season without Barry and Lukaku</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2603070/Everton-boss-Roberto-Martinez-keen-sign-loan-Roberto-Lukaku-permanent-deal-Chelsea.html\"> Everton boss Martinez keen to sign on-loan Lukaku on a permanent deal from Chelsea</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602289/Everton-near-Champions-League-without-loan-signings-table-proves.html\"> Everton would be nowhere near Champions League without loan stars like Lukaku... but where would your side be in the table?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601623/Roberto-Martinez-defends-Evertons-loan-tactics-slamming-ridiculous-critics.html\"> Martinez blasts loan criticism as \'ridiculous\' and \'lazy\' as Everton march towards Europe</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599917/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Everton-fairytale-hooked-shame-built-50m-loan-sham-Lukaku-Barry-Deulofeu-Wengers-right-moan.html\"> MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan)</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599706/Romelu-Lukaku-transfer-hinders-World-Cup-Chelsea-hope-strong-display-Belgium-star-increase-asking-price.html\"> Lukaku transfer hinders on World Cup as Chelsea hope strong display from Belgium star will increase asking price</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597861/Loan-star-Gareth-Barry-wage-cut-wants-stay-Everton.html\"> Loan star Barry will have to take wage cut if he wants to stay at Everton</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/THE-NUMBERS-GAME-Martinez-worked-wonders-Evertons-Champions-League-dream-theyll-torn-apart-Lukaku-Barry-returning-home.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Lukaku and Barry returning home will rip up the Champions League dreams of Everton and Martinez\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603116/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">25</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-2603116-1D0C33AE00000578-453_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:57:57','2014-04-12 15:17:00'),(34,'bbf0f0149c2919a79d796d44398cd1432bda072cf08bad76899fe8a641adb849','dailymail',NULL,'Gary Monk wants Swansea City skipper Ashley Williams to prolong stay amidst Napoli interest','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603148/Gary-Monk-wants-Swansea-City-skipper-Ashley-Williams-prolong-stay-amidst-Napoli-interest.html',' By John Drayton Published: 07:57 EST, 12 April 2014 | Updated: 07:57 EST, 12 April 2014 7 shares 0 View comments  Garry Monk wants Swansea and Wales captain Ashley Williams to remain with the Barclays Premier League club \'for as long as possible.\' Williams, 29, has just over a year left on his existing Swansea contract and Italian heavyweights Napoli - the Swans\' Europa League conquerors this season - are among those thought to be tracking him.  Captain fantastic: Swansea City boss Gary Monk wants skipper Ashley Williams to prolong his stay in Wales   No nonsense: Defender Williams (left) just has over a year left on his contract at the Liberty Stadium  \'What he does for the club, I would have him here for as long as possible,\' Swansea head coach Monk said. \'He has been linked with clubs for a few years - it is what happens with good players. He\'s an important player that, as a club, we should keep as long as possible. \'He is a good guy who cares for the club and wants the best for us. I know he is happy here and I don\'t see a problem. \'I haven\'t had a conversation about his future. I speak to him frequently, but it\'s about the football, things we can improve and the defensive side of things, giving him things what he can take on to the pitch to influence the rest of the guys.\'  All smiles: Napoli, managed by former Liverpool boss Rafael Benitez, have been linked with a move for Williams  Williams will be an integral part of Swansea\'s plan to beat title-chasing Chelsea at the Liberty Stadium on Sunday, when a win for Monk\'s men would effectively erase any lingering relegation fears. The game comes just five days after Chelsea booked a Champions League semi-final place by knocking out Paris St Germain, and Monk is fully aware of the challenge that awaits.  \'I don\'t buy we could catch them cold after midweek,\' he added. \'The players they have through the squad are top-class players. I am sure they will make changes, but whoever comes in is top-class. \'They are not pushing for the title for no reason. They have experience and class all over the pitch. It\'s an extremely tough game, but a challenge we are looking forward to and have to relish.  Vital: Monk has described Williams as an \'important player\' for Swansea and wants him to stay for many years  \'The journey this club (Swansea) has been on and fighting for is to be on this level, to compete against these sort of teams, and we have to make sure we continue that.\' Swansea will go into the Chelsea clash following a 1-0 defeat Hull last weekend, which came as a jolt, given that Monk had seen his team draw with Arsenal and beat Norwich in their previous two games. Swansea are currently six points above the relegation zone. After Chelsea, their remaining fixtures are against Newcastle, Aston Villa, Southampton and Sunderland.  History: As captain, Williams (centre) led Swansea to the Capital One Cup trophy last season  \'I was very annoyed with the (Hull) performance. The training was very good, the sessions very competitive,\' Monk said. \'As a manager all you can do is get it to that level and understand fully what is expected that they do it on a Saturday. That\'s the disappointment - the work they put in and we end up with a performance like that. \'If you had to say mathematically, we need two more wins. I want it, and we\'re aware of it. But we want more, we want consistency. We have been too inconsistent this season.  Moving on: Monk wants his side to bounce back against Chelsea after losing 1-0 at Hull last weekend  \'It is not as if it is small inconsistencies. We have performed brilliantly, then against Hull we were very, very poor. \'It is too big a gap. The best teams stay at a level, and that is what I want for the rest of the season.\'  Share or comment on this article 7shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=John+Drayton\" rel=\"nofollow\">John Drayton</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 07:57 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 07:57 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603148/Gary-Monk-wants-Swansea-City-skipper-Ashley-Williams-prolong-stay-amidst-Napoli-interest.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603148/Gary-Monk-wants-Swansea-City-skipper-Ashley-Williams-prolong-stay-amidst-Napoli-interest.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Monk wants Swansea skipper Williams to prolong stay amidst Napoli interest\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 7</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2603148/Gary-Monk-wants-Swansea-City-skipper-Ashley-Williams-prolong-stay-amidst-Napoli-interest.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">0</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Garry Monk wants Swansea and Wales captain Ashley Williams to remain with the Barclays Premier League club \'for as long as possible.\'</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Williams, 29, has just over a year left on his existing Swansea contract and Italian heavyweights Napoli - the Swans\' Europa League conquerors this season - are among those thought to be tracking him.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Captain fantastic: Swansea City boss Gary Monk wants skipper Ashley Williams to prolong his stay in Wales\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"454\" id=\"i-5d090d3d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/article-0-1A4BD27700000578-787_634x454.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Captain fantastic: Swansea City boss Gary Monk wants skipper Ashley Williams to prolong his stay in Wales</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No nonsense: Defender Williams (left) just has over a year left on his contract at the Liberty Stadium\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"415\" id=\"i-aa670e74\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/