PSG.html\"> Mourinho will NOT face action after running on to pitch to celebrate Chelsea win over PSG</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601783/Blues-fans-club-pay-Mourinhos-8-000-FA-fine-Aston-Villa-sending-off.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601783/Blues-fans-club-pay-Mourinhos-8-000-FA-fine-Aston-Villa-sending-off.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Blues fans club together to pay Mourinho\'s £8,000 FA fine after Aston Villa sending off\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601783/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">588</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601396-1C52C0EA00000578-873_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:46','2014-04-10 23:50:57'),(102,'d287c153cccc0cfcdf19e47bee762b844bc66cc0cb911faec00da5e303009444','dailymail',NULL,'Newcastle in talks over Perez, Man Utd line up Milinkovic-Savic trial and Kaboul is wanted by Fiorentina THE TRANSFER COLUMN','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html',' Newcastle open talks with Tenerife over striker Ayoze PerezManchester United set to offer week-long trial to Serbian goalkeeper Vanja Milinkovic-SavicRicardo Rodriguez is a Fulham target if they beat the dropTottenham defender Younes Kaboul is a target for FiorentinaLeeds are monitoring Southend goalkeeper Daniel BentleyBlackpool in talks over a summer deal for Dutch defender Tom BeugelsdijkSunderland forward Emanuele Giaccherini interesting West Ham, Hull and Genoa By SIMON JONES Published: 09:59 EST, 10 April 2014 | Updated: 11:54 EST, 10 April 2014 34 shares 23 View comments More transfer news from Simon Jones Liverpool scouts set to run rule over Markovic again as Man United hover Newcastle United have opened preliminary talks with Tenerife over striker Ayoze Perez. The 20-year-old has been watched by the likes of Real Madrid, Manchester City, Arsenal, Everton and Swansea over the past 12 months and is considered a forward of good potential having scored 16 goals in 29 games this season in the Spanish second division. Newcastle are looking for at least two strikers for next season with Lyon\'s Alexandre Lacazette still a possibility while they are also among clubs to have asked about taking Arsenal\'s Joel Campbell on loan after his impressive displays for Olympiacos in the Champions League. Montpellier midfielder Remy Cabella remains a target for Newcastle while Manchester City defender Micah Richards is another Newcastle have an interest in.  Deals: Newcastle are targeting Tenerife\'s Ayoze Perez left), while Man Utd are to trial Vanja Milinkovic-Savic       Man United line up trial for young Serbian goalkeeper Manchester United are to offer a week-long trial to Serbian goalkeeper Vanja Milinkovic-Savic. The 17-year-old has recently agreed a new deal with FK Vojvodina but they are happy to let him visit United with the prospect of a decent fee should he impress. Milinkovic-Savic is due to arrive next Wednesday, April 16. He is also attracting interest from Spanish clubs.   Rodriguez a Fulham target... if they stay up Fulham coach Felix Magath is keen on Wolfsburg left back Ricardo Rodriguez should he manage to stay in the Premier League. Rodriguez, 21, has been watched by Liverpool, Chelsea, Arsenal and Manchester United scouts this season as they all search for left backs for next season. However, although the Switzerland defender has continued to impress they have moved on to other targets at this stage. Wolfsburg may look to sell after the World Cup in June when they hope his value increases and Magath hopes he will be in a position to bid.  Lined up: Fulham will pursue a deal with Wolfsburg for left back Ricardo Rodriguez (right) if they stay up  More... TRANSFER COLUMN: City hold Aguero talks to keep \'irreplaceable\' star striker out of Real Madrid\'s clutches Tottenham rejoin race for Remy as Besiktas eye summer move for defender Kaboul Poyet promises out-of-favour Giaccherini he still has a part to play in Premier League relegation run-in Poyet tells Giaccherini to take his chance as Vergini and Ustari prepare for Sunderland debuts at home to Kidderminster Newcastle forced to refund Southampton fans £12,000 after overcharging for tickets THE TRANSFER COLUMN: Arsenal eyes deals for Mandzukic and Rojo, Everton an option for Lukaku and Skrtel staying put Kaboul wanted by Fiorentina Fiorentina have firmed up their interest in Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul. The 28-year-old has one more year left on contract and is weighing up his options with Sevilla also keen to take him. Fiorentina are keen to offer a three-year contract if they can get prise him out of Tottenham on a relatively cheap deal. Sevilla are looking at options to replace Federico Fazio who has been watched by Everton several times this season. The 27-year-old Argentinian centre back has also come under consideration at Liverpool, Arsenal and Manchester United.  Wanted: Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul (left) is one of Fiorentina\'s top targets this summer  Leeds trying to drive deal for Southend keeper Bentley Leeds United are monitoring Southend goalkeeper Daniel Bentley. The 20-year-old, who stands at 6ft 4in tall, has impressed with his performances in League Two this season and Leeds see potential in him to become a top player. England keeper Jack Butland will return to Stoke City at the end of this season and there remain question marks over the future of Paddy Kenny. Plenty of activity is expected at Leeds over he coming months with owner Massimo Cellino looking to restructure the squad. Jimmy Kebe will also return to Crystal Palace following his loan while Michael Brown, Danny Pugh and Paul Green are out of contract.  Poised: Leeds boss Brian McDermott (left) and owner Massimo Cellino are tracking Southend\'s Daniel Bentley  Blackpool negotiating deal for Dutch defender Beugeldijk Blackpool are in talks over a summer deal for Dutch defender Tom Beugelsdijk. The 23-year-old centre back is out-of-contract with ADO Den Haag in the summer and is free to discuss terms with foreign clubs. Beugelsdijk was at Blackpool\'s game with Derby County on Tuesday to see their 3-1 defeat and held discussions with club officials over a potential deal before returning to Holland.  Brave: Tom Beugelsdijk of ADO Den Haag (left) looks to be off to Blackpool at some point this summer  Giaccherini interesting West Ham, Hull and Genoa West Ham, Hull and Genoa are showing tentative interest in Sunderland winger Emanuele Giaccherini. The 28-year-old has only shown his ability in flashes this season and has been seen as something of an unnecessary luxury while Sunderland have been battling relegation.  Off target: Sunderland\'s Emanuele Giaccherini (right) is wanted by West Ham, Hull and Genoa in his native Italy    More... TRANSFER COLUMN: City hold Aguero talks to keep \'irreplaceable\' star striker out of Real Madrid\'s clutches Tottenham rejoin race for Remy as Besiktas eye summer move for defender Kaboul Poyet promises out-of-favour Giaccherini he still has a part to play in Premier League relegation run-in Poyet tells Giaccherini to take his chance as Vergini and Ustari prepare for Sunderland debuts at home to Kidderminster Newcastle forced to refund Southampton fans £12,000 after overcharging for tickets THE TRANSFER COLUMN: Arsenal eyes deals for Mandzukic and Rojo, Everton an option for Lukaku and Skrtel staying put   Share or comment on this article 34shares','\n<ul class=\"article-summary sport\"><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Newcastle open talks with Tenerife over striker Ayoze Perez</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Manchester United set to offer week-long trial to Serbian goalkeeper Vanja Milinkovic-Savic</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Ricardo Rodriguez is a Fulham target if they beat the drop</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul is a target for Fiorentina</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Leeds are monitoring Southend goalkeeper Daniel Bentley</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Blackpool in talks over a summer deal for Dutch defender Tom Beugelsdijk</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size:1.4em;\">Sunderland forward Emanuele Giaccherini interesting West Ham, Hull and Genoa<br/></font></b></li></ul>\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1089596/SIMON-JONES.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">SIMON JONES</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 09:59 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 11:54 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Newcastle in talks over Perez, Man Utd line up Milinkovic-Savic trial and Kaboul is wanted by Fiorentina\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 34</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">23</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>More transfer news from Simon Jones</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601524/Liverpool-eye-Markovic-United-hover-Benfica-rising-star.html\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"></font></a><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601524/Liverpool-eye-Markovic-United-hover-Benfica-rising-star.html\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Liverpool scouts set to run rule over Markovic again as Man United hover</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"></font> </a></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Newcastle United have opened preliminary talks with Tenerife over striker Ayoze Perez.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The 20-year-old has been watched by the likes of Real Madrid, Manchester City, Arsenal, Everton and Swansea over the past 12 months and is considered a forward of good potential having scored 16 goals in 29 games this season in the Spanish second division.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Newcastle are looking for at least two strikers for next season with Lyon\'s Alexandre Lacazette still a possibility while they are also among clubs to have asked about taking Arsenal\'s Joel Campbell on loan after his impressive displays for Olympiacos in the Champions League.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Montpellier midfielder Remy Cabella remains a target for Newcastle while Manchester City defender Micah Richards is another Newcastle have an interest in.</font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Newcastle target Ayoze Perez of Tenerife\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a4830e3d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1D00310C00000578-811_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Young Swedish goalkeeper Vanja Milinkovic-Savic\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-acb70e89\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CFFDF0700000578-809_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Deals: Newcastle are targeting Tenerife\'s Ayoze Perez left), while Man Utd are to trial Vanja Milinkovic-Savic<br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Man United line up trial for young Serbian goalkeeper<br/></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Manchester United are to offer a week-long trial to Serbian goalkeeper Vanja Milinkovic-Savic. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The 17-year-old has recently agreed a new deal with FK Vojvodina but they are happy to let him visit United with the prospect of a decent fee should he impress. Milinkovic-Savic is due to arrive next Wednesday, April 16. He is also attracting interest from Spanish clubs.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Rodriguez a Fulham target... if they stay up<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Fulham coach Felix Magath is keen on Wolfsburg left back Ricardo Rodriguez should he manage to stay in the Premier League.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Rodriguez, 21, has been watched by Liverpool, Chelsea, Arsenal and Manchester United scouts this season as they all search for left backs for next season. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">However, although the Switzerland defender has continued to impress they have moved on to other targets at this stage. Wolfsburg may look to sell after the World Cup in June when they hope his value increases and Magath hopes he will be in a position to bid.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Lined up: Fulham will pursue a deal with Wolfsburg for left back Ricardo Rodriguez (right) if they stay up\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"394\" id=\"i-aa330e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CDC421F00000578-692_634x394.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Lined up: Fulham will pursue a deal with Wolfsburg for left back Ricardo Rodriguez (right) if they stay up</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598829/City-hold-Aguero-talks-irreplaceable-star-striker-Real-Madrids-clutches.html\"> TRANSFER COLUMN: City hold Aguero talks to keep \'irreplaceable\' star striker out of Real Madrid\'s clutches</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2587211/Tottenham-rejoin-race-Loic-Remy-Besiktas-eye-summer-defender-Younes-Kaboul.html\"> Tottenham rejoin race for Remy as Besiktas eye summer move for defender Kaboul</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2582743/Sunderland-manager-Gus-Poyet-says-Emanuele-Giaccherini-role-play-Premier-League-run-in.html\"> Poyet promises out-of-favour Giaccherini he still has a part to play in Premier League relegation run-in</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2545680/Poyet-tells-Giaccherini-chance-Vergini-Ustari-prepare-Sunderland-debuts-home-Kidderminster.html\"> Poyet tells Giaccherini to take his chance as Vergini and Ustari prepare for Sunderland debuts at home to Kidderminster</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600987/Newcastle-refund-Southampton-fans-12-000-overcharging-tickets.html\"> Newcastle forced to refund Southampton fans £12,000 after overcharging for tickets</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596005/Arsenal-eyes-deals-Mandzukic-Rojo-Everton-option-Lukaku-Skrtel-staying-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\"> THE TRANSFER COLUMN: Arsenal eyes deals for Mandzukic and Rojo, Everton an option for Lukaku and Skrtel staying put</a></li> </ul> </div> <br/> </div>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Kaboul wanted by Fiorentina<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Fiorentina have firmed up their interest in Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The 28-year-old has one more year left on contract and is weighing up his options with Sevilla also keen to take him.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Fiorentina are keen to offer a three-year contract if they can get prise him out of Tottenham on a relatively cheap deal.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Sevilla are looking at options to replace Federico Fazio who has been watched by Everton several times this season. The 27-year-old Argentinian centre back has also come under consideration at Liverpool, Arsenal and Manchester United.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Wanted: Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul (left) is one of Fiorentina\'s top targets this summer\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"399\" id=\"i-a9cf0e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CB238AD00000578-705_634x399.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Wanted: Tottenham defender Younes Kaboul (left) is one of Fiorentina\'s top targets this summer</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Leeds trying to drive deal for Southend keeper Bentley<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Leeds United are monitoring Southend goalkeeper Daniel Bentley.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The 20-year-old, who stands at 6ft 4in tall, has impressed with his performances in League Two this season and Leeds see potential in him to become a top player.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">England keeper Jack Butland will return to Stoke City at the end of this season and there remain question marks over the future of Paddy Kenny. Plenty of activity is expected at Leeds over he coming months with owner Massimo Cellino looking to restructure the squad.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Jimmy Kebe will also return to Crystal Palace following his loan while Michael Brown, Danny Pugh and Paul Green are out of contract.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Poised: Leeds boss Brian McDermott (left) and owner Massimo Cellino are tracking Southend\'s Daniel Bentley\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"383\" id=\"i-aa020e72\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CF0DC4700000578-231_634x383.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Poised: Leeds boss Brian McDermott (left) and owner Massimo Cellino are tracking Southend\'s Daniel Bentley</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Blackpool negotiating deal for Dutch defender Beugeldijk<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Blackpool are in talks over a summer deal for Dutch defender Tom Beugelsdijk. The 23-year-old centre back is out-of-contract with ADO Den Haag in the summer and is free to discuss terms with foreign clubs.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Beugelsdijk was at Blackpool\'s game with Derby County on Tuesday to see their 3-1 defeat and held discussions with club officials over a potential deal before returning to Holland.</font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Brave: Tom Beugelsdijk of ADO Den Haag (left) looks to be off to Blackpool at some point this summer\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"397\" id=\"i-8f4a0e10\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CB23EC600000578-2_634x397.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Brave: Tom Beugelsdijk of ADO Den Haag (left) looks to be off to Blackpool at some point this summer</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Giaccherini interesting West Ham, Hull and Genoa<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">West Ham, Hull and Genoa are showing tentative interest in Sunderland winger Emanuele Giaccherini. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The 28-year-old has only shown his ability in flashes this season and has been seen as something of an unnecessary luxury while Sunderland have been battling relegation.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Off target: Sunderland\'s Emanuele Giaccherini (right) is wanted by West Ham, Hull and Genoa in his native Italy\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"398\" id=\"i-9d5c0e4a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1CCE97C200000578-12_634x398.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Off target: Sunderland\'s Emanuele Giaccherini (right) is wanted by West Ham, Hull and Genoa in his native Italy</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598829/City-hold-Aguero-talks-irreplaceable-star-striker-Real-Madrids-clutches.html\"> TRANSFER COLUMN: City hold Aguero talks to keep \'irreplaceable\' star striker out of Real Madrid\'s clutches</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2587211/Tottenham-rejoin-race-Loic-Remy-Besiktas-eye-summer-defender-Younes-Kaboul.html\"> Tottenham rejoin race for Remy as Besiktas eye summer move for defender Kaboul</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2582743/Sunderland-manager-Gus-Poyet-says-Emanuele-Giaccherini-role-play-Premier-League-run-in.html\"> Poyet promises out-of-favour Giaccherini he still has a part to play in Premier League relegation run-in</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2545680/Poyet-tells-Giaccherini-chance-Vergini-Ustari-prepare-Sunderland-debuts-home-Kidderminster.html\"> Poyet tells Giaccherini to take his chance as Vergini and Ustari prepare for Sunderland debuts at home to Kidderminster</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600987/Newcastle-refund-Southampton-fans-12-000-overcharging-tickets.html\"> Newcastle forced to refund Southampton fans £12,000 after overcharging for tickets</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596005/Arsenal-eyes-deals-Mandzukic-Rojo-Everton-option-Lukaku-Skrtel-staying-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\"> THE TRANSFER COLUMN: Arsenal eyes deals for Mandzukic and Rojo, Everton an option for Lukaku and Skrtel staying put</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/Newcastle-talks-Perez-Man-Utd-line-Milinkovic-Savic-trial-Kaboul-wanted-Fiorentina-THE-TRANSFER-COLUMN.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Newcastle in talks over Perez, Man Utd line up Milinkovic-Savic trial and Kaboul is wanted by Fiorentina\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601580/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">34</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601580-1D0038C700000578-199_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:47','2014-04-10 18:54:33'),(103,'765d48c16fa8f4bbe0bc2069827288bef0cc5c2561515ba8ec0930b408d8d39c','dailymail',NULL,'MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE: I\'m not anti-Everton, I\'m just against the loan system - but the foolish paranoia of football fans never ceases to amaze me','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html',' By Martin Samuel - Debate Published: 03:33 EST, 10 April 2014 | Updated: 10:55 EST, 10 April 2014 131 shares 164 View comments  So, first, a little history. On April 30, 2003, I wrote a column in The Times that said Sam Allardyce should be the Manager of the Year for keeping Bolton Wanderers up, but actually I hoped they went down. The reason I gave was that Bolton’s team was built around foreign loan signings, while the other threatened team, West Ham United, had some of the best young English players in the country. Sam thinks I’ve had it in for him ever since. I don’t think he remembers the praise in the piece and he took it personally, rather than as a commentary on the loan system. Since then, I’ve written repeatedly about temporary transfers, the stockpiling of players by major clubs, the whole dodgy area of gentlemen’s agreements and mates lending to mates, and the way football could be, if we would only wean ourselves off this devalued process. Not just in Premier League football, either. I wrote about Watford in the Championship last season, and Parma in Serie A this year. I wrote about Ryman League clubs Ware and Waltham Forest with more than 100 players passing through their books in one season, and Hameur Bouazza who in 2008-09 season played for Charlton Athletic against Birmingham City and Birmingham City against Charlton Athletic, while actually being owned by a third club, Fulham.  Sensitive soul: Sam Allardyce (left) kept Bolton up in 2003 with a number of loan players  And on Wednesday I wrote about the positive impact loans have had on Everton’s season and how this would appear incompatible with financial fair play and the way it clamps down on overspending clubs for artificially inflating their league position. Had Everton bought all of their squad this season they may have fallen foul of FFP, but with loans they get around the system. That is not right, surely. It is just inflation by another means. Doing so, just as I did 11 years ago, I made sure to make clear that the club had done nothing wrong, and the system was at fault. I praised Everton’s manager, Roberto Martinez and his chairman Bill Kenwright. I said I wanted Everton to finish top four, and it would be a welcome change. It turns out Big Sam is not the only sensitive soul in the Premier League. It turns out he is not the only one who consumes his news selectively, with a well-balanced chip on each shoulder. Debate about the incompatibility of FFP and the loan system? Zip. People thinking I had a pop at their club. Everybody. So, for the last time: I like Everton, I want Everton to do well. I don’t like the loan system. I think we would be better off without it. Oh, what the hell. Here’s the column if you can be bothered to read it. Judging by what follows, you won’t be alone if you can’t.  Why does everyone think this is a new issue? Everton took Glen Keeley from Blackburn Rovers on loan in 1982 – that was 32 years ago. Everton, like Arsenal, send players out on loan, too. Last month Apostolos Vellios went on loan to Blackpool. It\'s part of the game and is essential for the development of young players. Ross Barkley was sent out on loan a number of times. This is a ridiculous non-issue. No-one cared about it for decades and now because one club does it well, everyone wants to have a moan. Darren K, Liverpool. To fill in the gaps, Everton have seven players out on loan, and Ross Barkley was loaned to Sheffield Wednesday in 2012 and Leeds United in 2013. Keeley played 32 minutes for Everton and was sent off in the Merseyside derby for fouling Kenny Dalglish. His loan came with the option of a permanent move that, unsurprisingly, did not come to fruition. None of this matters, of course. A long list of historic examples is not the same as a counter argument, Darren. More young players came through when the loan system was not used so voraciously by clubs because a manager had to make do with what he had rather than searching for quick solutions elsewhere. Are any of the loan players in the first-team at Everton young and British? No. So, potentially, they are blocking that path for young British players.  Loan stars: Borini, Lukaku, Kallstrom and Remy, with a proponent of the system, Sam Allardyce Jose Mourinho: Now is not the time to discuss Lukaku\'s future   At least they\'re happy with the system: Roberto Martinez (centre) and Romelu Lukaku (left) celebrate the on-loan striker\'s goal against Arsenal  Big clubs are able to buy up too much of the young talent pool so the clubs simply can\'t develop them all into first team players. The loan system was the answer, but banning them from playing against their parent club was always wrong. Ultimately, it should not be possible to loan to a club unless they\'re in a lower league. Players were developed perfectly well in the days when Football League players from Divisions Two to Four were largely the young, up and coming group and the big clubs had a much smaller youth squad. It was better for the youngsters, with more regular first team competition, and better for the other leagues. Usednurse, Scottish Borders. Modern football has whole teams with a core of loaned players, whereas four decades ago a loan was exactly that – a way of overcoming a short-term emergency, like having every full-back at the club injured, or a glorified trial with a view to a permanent move. Continental clubs had a very active long-term loan system and we copied it from them. Has it made our football better, or given more opportunities to young British players? Hardly. You miss the most glaring fact of all. All clubs can use the loan system, while not all can go and spend £100m at the drop of a hat. Support Grass Roots, Liverpool. I think you’re missing a glaring fact, actually. Without the loan system, clubs would not be able to stockpile players and transfer fees would come down, meaning Everton might be able to afford the likes of Romelu Lukaku, without it costing the earth. Now that’s a sound system. And so is this.  Let\'s imagine you\'re in a country where there is a huge gap in both income and wealth between a minority of rich and a majority of those who just about make ends meet. The poorer majority cannot survive without receiving more income and therefore need money to invest, but don\'t have the inherent wealth to do so. Your suggestion would be to ban banks lending money to the poor, thus cementing in place the existing distribution of income and wealth? The poor stay poor and the rich get richer? Astoundingly good logic. StevenNaismith, Liverpool. You left out one factor, Steven. Players. Your analogy does not work because football in this case does not conform to the rules of a market economy, because there is a human commodity in the middle of the bands of rich and poor. Without loans, the rich would be unable to stockpile players, who would sign short-term contracts, request transfers, or stay with their smaller club of origin, therefore forcing the costs down for the poor. I think there are also occasions where big clubs use strategic loans to strengthen lower-level teams and improve those chances against rival opposition. For example, Jose Mourinho might have calculated at the beginning of the season that if Lukaku could score against Manchester City, Manchester United, Arsenal, Tottenham Hotspur and Liverpool, it\'s almost like he is scoring for Chelsea. Billy Shears, Manchester. Quite right, Billy. Technically, Chelsea could stockpile goalkeepers, loan 10 of them out and ensure they will play more than half of their league games against a reserve goalkeeper. Loan players should be free to play against their parent club, as they do in UEFA tournaments - unless, like Chelsea, the parent club has inserted a clause making such a collision prohibitive. Meaning, that if they draw Atletico Madrid in this month\'s semi-final, or play them in the final, Chelsea get to choose the opposition goalkeeper. Now, isn\'t that healthy?  Here\'s the point: Everton could not afford Lukaku and Gareth Barry (right) so their current position is inflated Pardew: Remy, Lukaku and Barry were the best loan signings  All players should have an annual financial fair play value based on annualised expense such as wages, plus current transfer value based on the market. Gsyblue, Guernsey. Good idea, but whose ledger will it occupy? Are Chelsea liable for Lukaku, to stop further stockpiling, or is the cost placed with Everton, to curb the motivation of building a team around loans? So what kind of loans should Everton deal in - the Glazer kind which allowed them to buy Manchester United? Tom, London. Neither is healthy, Tom; yet both are accepted strategies in football business. Blaming the Glazers for using the rules is no different to blaming Everton. It appears that it is OK if your loan signings scrape survival in the Premier League but as soon as they start firing you towards the Champions League it is screwing the system? Poor article with undertones suggesting that Samuel is basically saying plucky little Everton should know their place and are knowingly cheating. MikeyEFC87, Liverpool. Don’t put words in my mouth Mike. I couldn’t have made my positive feelings for Everton clearer; in fact I went out of my way to praise them. As stated in the preamble, I have always spoken out against the loan system, at both ends of the league, and in the middle. If your loan signings scrape survival, that means you have stayed up at the expense of another club, with players that are not yours. And that isn’t right, either. In a column published on May 13, 2009, I made that point about Norwich City’s survival in the Championship with 12 loan signings in 2007-08. I notice how when Arsenal beat us in the FA Cup nothing was said, but as soon as we beat them convincingly in the league loans became a massive problem. The biggest issue with the transfer and loan market is that mega-rich clubs are overinflating prices. When managers complain maybe they should look at the reason why there are so many players loaned. Efcdan, Deeside. Sort of my point, Dan. That is why I said Everton were not to blame. They are exploiting a flawed system and a problem exacerbated by the wealthiest clubs.  Not to blame: Everton are exploiting a flawed system that allows them to loan Lukaku, Barry and Deufoleu    I find it interesting that people prefer to see stability in the managerial hot-seat but are OK with players being at three clubs in the space of a year like Wilfried Zaha. The big benefit of the loan system is to develop younger players, so should there be an age cap? Players like Gareth Barry have been around for years - if a club wants him, they know what they\'re getting. Tucky1919, Lincoln. I’d like to see the whole system abolished, Tucky, but if we’re talking reform an age cap would certainly be a start. So naughty Manchester City have bought a 16-year-old from Feyenoord, who previously would have made his name at that club? Undoubtedly, this is a harmful trend for smaller clubs, but is it all the fault of FFP and Michel Platini? Newsflash, this has been happening for years. Teams like Chelsea and Arsenal have been shopping in youth academies in the Netherlands and Feyenoord have been losing their greatest talents, just like Ajax. It has nothing to do with FFP. Charles, Amsterdam. Yes, it has been a problem for many years but with financial fair play it is set to mushroom as clubs seek to circumvent the system. That was my point. Arsene Wenger wasn’t talking about stopping loans. He simply said that it is a shame players like Lukaku aren’t allowed to play against their teams. That makes sense, in my opinion. Khalid Ahmed, Oslo. Actually, he was talking about ending a substantial element of the loan system, Khalid. Here is what he said: \'I believe if you want to continue the loan system, we have to make the players available against the teams that loan them, or the system is not defendable. It\'s just a protection of the clubs who loan the players out to hurt the opponents and they have no risk at all. I think the best would be that the players are only loaned in lower divisions or abroad, and even abroad I\'m not completely convinced it is right.\' So Wenger would outlaw the loan transfers of Lukaku, Barry and Gerard Deulofeu in Everton’s case, as they are either in the same division or between major European clubs. He went a bit further than just saying they should be able to play against the parent club.  Bold move: Arsene Wenger would outlaw the loaning of players to teams in the same division  What does it matter? Is it more of a fairytale that Everton are bought out by a billionaire and given hundreds of millions to spend on success? Entrepreneur, Manchester. No – but let’s not pretend Bill Kenwright has not been seeking that option as a way out for his club. Indeed, he was castigated quite viciously by some Everton fans for being unable to find a wealthy buyer. It is called financial management, well within the fair play rules. As a football fan, would you rather Lukaku was on the bench at Chelsea, or playing week in, week out, at Everton? Loan transfers are not exactly free and some fail to work out, like Victor Moses at Liverpool. Jambo Jambo, South Africa. Firstly, I didn’t say it was outside the rules, quite the opposite. Secondly, the choice shouldn’t be between the loan and the bench. How about Everton sign Lukaku permanently for realistic money – the third way that is never considered because we have the loan system. The main difference is that if a rich owner pulls the plug then a club still has to pay inflated wages and may get in financial trouble. When loans end a club would typically just not be as good. Thomas, Watford. So their status has been artificially inflated, yes? Again, sort of my point. I feel the biggest flaw with the whole system is the amount of players a club is allowed to loan out. Fair enough with under-20’s gaining first-team experience in competitive football but above that there should be a strict limit. If a club was only allowed to loan out five players over 21 then players and agents would have to take that into account. Rot in the reserves or choose another team that offers more football. David, Southport. Once more, it’s a start David, albeit a rather generous one. Five over-21 loans per club? That’s 100 in the Premier League alone before we’ve even started on the stockpiled youth signings.  Temporary solution: Loic Remy has made a huge impact on Newcastle\'s season on loan from QPR  Your view of the loan system is flawed. Not all clubs can compete financially with the likes of Manchester City and Chelsea. Everton certainly can\'t, so without the loan system would probably be where they are, despite having impressive youngsters and England internationals such as Leighton Baines, Phil Jagielka and Ross Barkley. They also have internationals from South Africa and the United States. So, if you are happy to keep the same few teams challenging for honours take away the loan system. If you prefer the most amazing competitive league keep it and allow smaller teams to compete. Don\'t blame Everton, applaud them for using the system well. Bye Bye Venkys, Preston. Everton has international footballers on permanent contracts? Big deal. So does every club. Don’t you see, it is the loan system that keeps clubs like Manchester City and Chelsea empowered and transfer fees high. Take it away and Everton could afford the players that are beyond them – just as it was in the old days. Unless you know any other time in football when Everton could not afford to buy Chelsea’s reserve striker or an aging midfield player that could not get in Manchester City’s team, and needed to make a temporary arrangement? Because I don’t. While I agree that we are lucky to have Lukaku, some of our top players this season have been Steven Naismith, James McCarthy, Seamus Coleman, Barkley and Baines. Not a loan player in sight. Please reanalyse Everton\'s season based on the whole team instead of trying to cast us as lucky one-timers. Lucy27, Chester. Lucy, I didn’t analyse Everton’s season, beyond praising them. I analysed the loan system, an aspect of football I was writing about when Lukaku was nine.  The same deal: Fabio Borini is on loan at Sunderland from Liverpool  So, basically, this loan system, which has been in place since I can remember in the Seventies and Eighties, is only flawed because it is working in our favour? Lukaku and Barry have been excellent, Deulofeu great in bits but hardly a regular. So is it Everton’s fault that Moses and others have not been as successful? All the top clubs throughout the Premier League and Europe use the loan system. Barry would be a substitute at best for City, Lukaku likewise at Chelsea and Deulofeu would be in Barcelona\'s B team, so is this not down to Martinez and his good management skills rather than a flawed loan system? Seems the media are worried about Everton gatecrashing the Champions League and denying Sky’s favoured clubs the extra cash and spending power. Dave EFC, Liverpool. Oh, get a grip and read the column. \'Roberto Martinez has done an outstanding job… an extraordinary feat and great for the English game…a new club breaking into the staid elite is always welcome…Everton are winning the popular vote… very smart in exploiting the nuances of the player market and good luck to them in that…\' It never ceases to amaze me, the circle the wagons, foolish paranoia, that is the default mechanism of many fans faced with even the mildest criticism of his club. I have been writing about the flaws, inconsistences, danger and weaknesses of the loan system for many years now. There is no point illustrating this argument using failed deals or mid-table clubs of no consequence. The harmful effects of the loan system are most keenly felt when a major issue is directly influenced – such as relegation, promotion or qualification to the Champions League. Bolton Wanderers staying up in 2003 was another example. Is that so hard to comprehend? I suppose Arsenal picking up Mikel Arteta, a key player for Everton, was fair game just because they could pay for him. Freespeechman, Liverpool. Yes, like when Everton bought Leighton Baines or James McCarthy from Wigan Athletic, Phil Jagielka from Sheffield United or Joleon Lescott from Wolverhampton Wanderers. Same thing.  Rarely seen: Kim Kallstrom has barely featured on loan at Arsenal  The loan system is designed to even the gap between the mega-rich and the other clubs and to give young players game time. Upthetofees, Wirral. No it isn’t. If the richest clubs thought any gap was truly being closed they would vote against it. The loan system is there because it allows the wealthy to keep overinflated squads and the poor to feed off their scraps. Usually, it only influences relegation and mid-table issues so the elite do not care; this season it may play a part in Champions League qualification. It will be interesting to see what happens next season. By being so good, Everton may have spoiled it for everyone. Give over, Coleman, McCarthy and Barkley have arguably contributed more than Barry and Deulofeu was out injured for months. Do you even watch the games? Daninjapan, Tokyo. Yes, and live, not just on television. Anyway, how are things at Shimizu S-Pulse? Is it more immoral utilising a completely legal loan system for a locally ran team, or spending half a billion on foreign players and leaving your academy out in the cold, with Arab money? Answer me that. Everton tend to loan a couple players every season due to lack of funds. Why have you just spoken up now? Because it\'s been a success? Where were you when Jo, Segundo Castillo and Matteo Ferrari came in? MHartley93, Liverpool. I was writing negative articles about the loan system, mate, which you obviously weren’t reading because unless the word Everton appears in the headline you’re probably not interested. Here’s the conclusion from that column about Bolton in 2003. \'I fear the influx of a league of Boltons, of managers who take the notion of a Player of the Month rather too literally, of talent that is borrowed as casually as next-door\'s power drill by bosses not as worldly-wise as Sam Allardyce. My concern is that when Allardyce\'s magic stops working - as one day it must, just as Wimbledon fell off the tightrope, and Lennie Lawrence couldn\'t save Charlton Athletic for ever - nothing will remain of what once was a great English football club. All there will be is people trying on Bolton shirts.\' So there are my credentials in writing about loans: 11 years of solid disapproval. I’m not sure you can find my old Times stuff online any more. So here (and here) are just a couple of links from the last two seasons. If Everton get Champions League football they can afford to buy Lukaku and Deulofeu. Manred1905, London. And I hope they do. But would Chelsea sell now Everton are a threat?  Potential benefit: By scoring in the Champions league, Joel Campbell could have done parent club Arsenal a favour  This difference is that Everton play in the same league as Chelsea. Arsenal are not in the Greek Super League and don\'t benefit when their loaned players can\'t play against them. Lukaku should have been in the Everton team versus Chelsea. That\'s the difference. GRB, Chandra. So the teams that Joel Campbell helped remove from the Champions League didn’t potentially benefit Arsenal? If we want to talk about unfair perhaps we need to mention the fact that teams such as Manchester United are able to spend £37m on one player during a transfer window? The transfer system must be revised with no deals taking place during the season. This may also place greater value on youth players. Pablo78, Liverpool. They bought the player with their own money, Pablo. Why is this unfair? Maybe if the likes of Manchester United, Manchester City, Arsenal, Chelsea and Liverpool had B teams like in Spain then these players wouldn’t be so freely available on loan. It would also help with developing English kids. Steven, Liverpool. I agree, Steven. A strong B-team league would definitely help. What about the players’ point of view? Lukaku was loaned to West Bromwich Albion last season where he was very successful. With the World Cup this summer he obviously wants to play as often as possible, and would not have been picked having spent two seasons as a substitute at Chelsea. Andy, Bridport. Andy, I can see what is in it for Lukaku, for Everton and for Chelsea – I just don’t think it is in the wider interests of the game. Never have.  Thumbs up: Manchester United bought Juan Mata with their own money, which is absolutely fine  This article is very harsh on Everton. How can you blame them for loaning players? Every other club does it. DBO-LFC, Liverpool. \'So let’s start by saying that the club challenging Arsenal for fourth place has done nothing wrong.\' Maybe I should have made it clearer. ‘The club challenging Arsenal for fourth place’? The one I said had ‘done nothing wrong’? That’s Everton. Short of writing in capital letters, maybe crayon, I don’t know what more I can do here. No mention of how well the £12m signing McCarthy has played, how Coleman and Baines look revitalised, or praise for blooding a 19-year-old in big games. Sie2003, Stafford. Yes, completely ignored, unless you include that oblique statement about Martinez doing \'an outstanding job\'. No-one moaned last season when Lukaku was at West Brom, but then again the media don\'t like Everton rocking the Premier League boat, unsettling their chosen few teams who should win everything every season. Petedil, Liverpool. Nobody is moaning. The reason Lukaku made less of a ripple at West Brom was because his presence made the difference between upper mid-table and lower mid-table so, basically, no difference at all. Surely you can appreciate why his impact at Everton is attracting more attention? And don’t give me that cobblers about wanting to see the same teams win all the time. One of the reasons I am so opposed to financial fair play is because it cements the elite in place. I think Everton have done a great job this season. I hope they snatch that fourth place. But I worry what they will do when Lukaku is gone. Take away his goals and where would they be? Ryan Smith, Newtown. Right, so let’s project. Say Everton qualify for the Champions League, which most people hope they do. Then Chelsea take Lukaku back. Unless Martinez is incredibly astute in the transfer market, Everton’s potential will be reduced. They may fail to make it through the preliminary rounds or go out at group stage – considering they are sure to be seeded in pot four. That then has a negative impact on the English game through co-efficient points. The leagues that have relied most heavily on loan trading are the ones that have gradually lost their Champions League berths – Italy for instance. Why, because teams qualify with an artificial squad list, are then weakened the following season and fall short. There has to be a better way.  One and only: Henrik Larsson scores his solitary league goal while on loan at Manchester United  So when Henrik Larsson scored a raft of goals to win Manchester United the league whilst on loan – that was OK then? Pavlos, Wigan. No it wasn’t. But just to stop you making a fool of yourself in the pub as well as on this forum, the stack of league goals scored by Larsson during his loan spell in 2006-07 amounted to one. The 70th minute third goal in a 4-0 home win over Watford. They probably would have managed it without him. You are basing the progress of a team on the input of a few players. It is like saying take Luis Suarez, Daniel Sturridge and Steven Gerrard out of the Liverpool line-up and they wouldn\'t be where they are. And it\'s true, on both counts – but that shouldn\'t take the achievement away. TheHumbleEgg, Liverpool. Well, yes it should in one way, because those Liverpool players belong to the club, in Gerrard’s case since his schooldays, while the Everton trio are passing through on temporary arrangements. I do like it, though, when a people comprehensively undermine their own arguments. Makes my job a lot easier – and reminds me a little of this.  Maybe a better story would have been how Arsenal got wellied by a team costing less than Mesut Ozil. Jmcd, London. Except it didn’t really, did it? In these days of FFP, the true cost of a team is made illusionary because of the loan system. That’s the point. As a Toffee, this is more about Lukaku in my view and the fact that super-rich clubs like Chelsea are the real beneficiaries as they loan out almost 30 potential first team players. Everton have been made the focus of how the loan system is wrong when as usual it is the rich that are pulling the strings and have all the control. Everton may get Champions League but who will score the goals next season? We\'ll have to pay £25m or try to get another loan, but it\'s doubtful a top competing club in the Premier League would loan to a genuine rival. So maybe another club gets Chelsea\'s largesse. Meanwhile, Chelsea’s traditional rivals, such as Arsenal, miss out on UEFA’s money and it weakens their appeal in attracting top players. Who\'s the real beneficiary of that? Rich, Jersey. An Evertonian looking further ahead than May? You’ll be ducked as a witch, Rich. Yes, the loan players are important to Everton, but they\'re not everything. Lukaku hasn\'t been a 20 goals plus striker, Deulofeu is a squad player who has been used sparingly. What about our home grown talents of Barkley and John Stones, the resurgence of Leon Osman, the improvement of players like Kevin Mirallas and Naismith, the talent of our fantastic full backs and the solid central defensive partnership? Not forgetting Tim Howard\'s great season. Martinez should be judged on this and people will see that there\'s more to Everton than a couple of loan signings. Simon Smith, United Kingdom. Indeed there is Simon; but this is bigger than just a debate around one club. The fact that Everton have other good permanent players doesn’t suddenly validate the loan system. The two events are unrelated.  Unrelated: The fact Everton have good permanent players such as Kevin Mirallas doesn\'t validate the loan system  You can get loans in as long as you don\'t threaten to break into the media’s beloved top four. Luke, England. And what top four would that be, Luke? Does it include Manchester United, because they’re seventh right now? I know, I know. It’s tough when the facts don’t fit your stupid conspiracy theory. The defence have always been solid and the arrival of McCarthy has been a very shrewd move. Deulofeu has only been used a handful of times and Lukaku has been indifferent. Yet again it’s the same old story: little old Everton upsetting the Sky five, which we can’t have. Daleefc1878, Ipswich. Yes we talk of nothing else in press rooms. \'How are we going to stop Everton,\' we cry. How is this any different than clubs who just buy success? The team that Martinez inherited was already fantastic and he has just had to tweak it to his style of play. As for Everton struggling without Marouane Fellaini if we get into the Champions League, I doubt with the style of play we have now he would fit into the current squad. Gedi88, Liverpool. Ged, that is my argument. The two systems are imperfect, yet we have a holier-than-thou attitude to throwing money at a football club, while turning a blind eye to the artificial inflation via the loan system. I don’t blame Everton for using the part of the market that suits their needs; I just think there is a better way, and that it would benefit Everton long-term, too, by forcing prices down. And here’s another thought. Does Jack Rodwell leave if he knows he has to make Manchester City’s first-team to play, and cannot escape with a loan? Because I think, without the loan system, he is still your player. Maybe you would be better advised to look at the mega rich clubs who buy all the best players and then use naming rights to invest money and bypass the financial fair play rules. There is no level playing field out there, so stop whinging about our loans. J18efc00, Liverpool. I’m not whinging about your loans, but the loan system. I do find it comical, though, that people talk so piously about all other forms of advancement, except the one that benefits their club. No mention of the 27 Chelsea players out on loan then? More than the whole Everton squad. Sutty, St Helens. No, because I’ve written about them in previous columns. I try to make them different, you know. I find the regular readers prefer it.  Not the only one: Lukakau is one of many Chelsea players out on loan - a subject touched on in previous columns  Well done Everton. It\'s about time a club other than the Sky five broke into the closed shop of the media darlings. They have done it within the rules, rather than going out and spending millions on players, like Juan Mata in the transfer window. Goldfish1, Liverpool. This is really just another attack on teams who dare to threaten the status quo of Sky’s Big Four. If you\'re working within the system that is in place then that should be the end of it. Indeed, it could be argued that the loan system has evolved as a consequence of Sky throwing funds at football and the elite clubs over the last few years. They have been able to accumulate squads of expensive talent whilst others have been left to pick up the crumbs which fall from the top table, made worse with the oil money from wealthy foreign owners. Football used to be sport with a little bit of business; today it\'s a business, with a little bit of sport. Mark, Durham. Of course, some of us remember the original breakaway five in 1990: Manchester United, Liverpool, Tottenham Hotspur, Arsenal – and Everton. So let’s drop all this nonsense about oligarchs and Arabs and poor little Everton. When Everton had the money and the power, they couldn’t wait to stuff everybody else and tried to cut the deal that ended in the formation of the Premier League. They were no different to the elite clubs now. And just because everyone keeps quiet and works within the system doesn’t mean it is correct. Slavery was a system; so was Stalinism. Come on Martin – Everton have lucked in to a great manager. Arsenal, Tottenham and Manchester United all had their chance to appoint Martinez but Everton have an owner who lives and breathes football. Sadly, he has very little money compared to the big clubs, so Everton have used the loan system. Zipdip, Harwich. Look, I don’t want this debate to turn into an edition of Mystic Mart but the idea I haven’t given Martinez credit is beginning to jar. In this column from May 13 last year, I placed him among the names I thought Manchester City should have considered before Manuel Pellegrini. Here’s the quote: \'Could Pellegrini have won the FA Cup with Wigan Athletic, as Martinez did on Saturday? Could he have got Wigan playing better football than Manchester City? Yesterday’s FA Cup defeat may have come as a bit of a shock, the discovery that there is a Spanish manager playing better football and working tiny miracles 25 miles down the road.\' As for Bill Kenwright, I cannot think of a chairman I admire more. I would regard him as a friend and I hope that warmth came cross when I interviewed him for the paper on September 9, 2011, at a time when a group of Everton fans were campaigning to get him out.  Credit where it\'s due: Roberto Martinez has been given plenty of praise  This is nonsense. Financial fair play was brought in to stop clubs becoming overly indebted to their owners. By loaning high quality players Everton are reducing their financial risks. This is entirely consistent with the principles behind the FFP rules. Daiwaijai, Hong Kong. A loan player is not an asset. I am pretty sure FFP requires a club to develop its assets. And building success on temporary players did not exactly stand Bolton in good stead, long term. So it begins. How dare upstarts Everton get into top five? Stop bashing us - if you don’t like the loan system, speak to the Football Association. Steve, Liverpool. I would Steve, but they’re all cowering under the sofa in case someone mentions that Nicolas Anelka business again. If it gets them Champions League football and increased income to balance the books, it is not bad business. I prefer it to oil money. Alan, Liverpool. Yes, but why? Both are forms of artificial inflation. Why moralise around one but not the other? I seem to recall West Ham United loaned a certain Andrew Carroll and nothing was said. Michael, Liverpool. And the reason, Michael? Because Carroll’s presence had minimal impact. I don’t like the loan system; therefore I didn’t like Carroll’s loan to West Ham or any of the loans the club has arranged this season. QED. I don\'t care. If it\'s right that teams like Manchester City and Chelsea can be bought overnight and transformed into league dominating outfits, I think it\'s only fair that clubs who struggle to attract huge investment can find alternative methods of making the league more competitive. Rchappy88, Burnley. Yes, but it’s on their terms. Don’t you get it? This competition exists only on conditions set by the very clubs you deplore. If Everton start to challenge Chelsea, do you think they’ll get any more players? If Brendan Rodgers wasn’t Jose Mourinho’s mate, and Liverpool seen as mostly harmless, would they have got Victor Moses? Say Moses was a roaring success and was stopping a loan-free Everton team full of local talent coming fourth right now? Is it fair that who you know, or whose back you scratch, gets you a player? I wonder if Mourinho would have loaned out Moses and Lukaku if they could have played against him like they can in the Spanish and German leagues? Arsène, Finsbury Park. Short answer: no. You wrote: \'Barry, a squad player at Manchester City and now 33, but even so he might have commanded £6m as a permanent transfer in the summer.\' Barry is out of contract this summer and was offered to Everton for £1m in January. God only knows where you\'re getting £6m from. PJC83, Warrington. Because January isn’t the summer. Come on mate, we did the months of the year in primary school. What you are saying is that you want the Sky Four as it once was to always be on top. Everton cannot compete financially with most clubs but actually have the best manager. This seems to upset you for some reason. You should applaud Everton and what we\'ve done, upsetting the chosen few. Good coaching actually improves players like Barry, Lukaku and Deulofeu. God help us if Everton actually win the Champions League. Who are you going to blame then? Trobbo66, Plano, Texas. I’m very sorry that you didn’t understand the column Robbo. You’re probably good at something else. Whittlin’ maybe. New rules that need to be implemented: Clubs can only allow players that live within 30 minutes drive of their training ground into the academy. Clubs are not allowed to have contact with players that live outside the catchment area. Clubs cannot tell a player to move to a certain area to comply with rule 1. Only players aged 21 and under can go out on loan. Maximum of three loan signings at each club. Reduce squad size to 23 and abolish the unlimited players under the age of 21 rule. Maximum of 18 players that are not from the club\'s academy allowed in the first team squad. Transfer of teenage players prohibited. Contracted players under the age of 20 cannot move to another club.  Clubs from each country can only sign overseas players that are within 350 miles of their country when they reach 21 years of age. Clubs can only sign players from countries beyond 350 miles when the player reaches 22 years of age. I hope Sepp Blatter reads this. Scott Shelby, Birmingham. Yeah, Scott. He’s a big fan of this column. In fact, he phoned in and requested this one.  Interesting point, but what do you expect clubs like Everton to do? Ignore the possibility of borrowing these players? The system is flawed but Everton must be congratulated for making the best of what is available to them. If they finish above United, even, I will be very impressed. Mick, Bergerac. Won’t we all, Mick? To answer your question, I expect Everton to carry on doing exactly what they are doing now. I would in their position. I took issue with the system, not the club. That is what has been missed here. Before even reading the comments I knew there would be several people, presumably Everton supporters, throwing a wobbly, thinking it\'s an attack on their club and playing the victim card. Read the article, it concerns the contradictions of modern football, and it\'s not the first time Martin Samuel has talked about the stupidity of FFP and the consequences for poorer clubs and players. From the elite staying the elite, to clubs hoarding young players or making nearly their whole first XI up from loans. Plastics Everywhere, United Kingdom. Ah, my hero. Thanks mate, whoever you are. Rather than concentrating on the fact Everton are doing very well but happen to have loaned a few players, how about using your journalistic skill to investigate comments made by the Premier League chief executive a few weeks ago concerning Manchester United’s fall from grace and how it could affect the league financially? Could this not be construed to mean that bigger clubs are being favoured on decisions? If this is the way the Premier League think then it could be open to corruption. El Bob, Liverpool. What, Bob, you mean use my journalistic skills to write about Richard Scudamore’s comments as I did two weeks ago? Try to keep up. Look at Watford last season, challenging all the way in the Championship because of the loan system, yet this season they are nowhere near the same standard because many of the players went back. Qwerty123, Brighton. And so close to promotion via the play-offs, too. Can you imagine? It would have been carnage had they got up and then the rules changed. I was accused of having it in for them, too, I seem to remember. Maybe I just don’t like the theme from Z Cars. Everton are well within the FA rulebook and they deserve all the plaudits they get. What if Lukaku and the rest had ended up at Arsenal and propelled them to the title? Would it have been right then? Saj, Manchester. No.  What a difference: Watford nearly got promoted last season with a raft of loan players  What a bitter and ignorant article. First of all, Everton are a club that has nine league titles, roughly the same as Tottenham, Manchester City and Chelsea combined. Only Arsenal, Manchester United and Liverpool have finished in the top four of English football more times. Yes, football didn\'t begin in 1992 like some would lead you to believe, so Everton making fourth spot wouldn\'t exactly be a fairytale. We are not Wigan Athletic. Lukaku has scored 13 goals this year, so Everton are not relying on him like Liverpool are with Suarez, either. Our team is still built around our defence, where our attack starts. Rdsnuke, Liverpool. And your history is relevant to this debate how? Oh, I see you resent all these upstart clubs taking what you think is rightfully yours. And you think you should be able to claim it back, no matter how that is achieved, while patronising Wigan, the club that sold you two of your best players and helped groom your manager. Nice. No, football didn’t begin in 1992 mate. So once again, the five clubs whose threatened breakaway culminated in the formation of the Premier League: Manchester United, Tottenham, Arsenal, Liverpool – and Everton. Funny how this wasn\'t a problem for the ten years that Everton have utilised the loan system for players like Royston Drenthe. This is lazy journalism from someone who doesn\'t watch Everton enough to know that their most consistent performers have been ones they own. DailyTonedMail, Liverpool. No, that’s a lazy argument from someone who hasn’t followed my writing enough to realise that I’ve been detailing the shortcomings of the loan system for more than 10 years, using examples other than Everton. If the loan system was not in place, where would the likes of Lukaku and Deulofeu gain the valuable experience of playing in our Premier League? Everton have at least six young players out on loan to lower division teams getting regular game time and both the borrowing clubs and Everton are getting the benefit. If those players improve to the point that when they return to Everton, they can press for first team places. That is a win-win situation for all and needs to be left alone. Bluebyyou, Tonypandy. So maybe if Everton didn’t have to play Chelsea’s loan players, the Everton players that are out on loan might get a game. Then, maybe Lukaku would have signed for a club that gave him first team football because transfer fees would come down without a stockpiling elite inflating the market. Now there’s a real win-win. Coleman, loan? Baines, loan? Miralles, loan? McCarthy, loan? Stones, loan? Naismith, loan? Barkley, loan? Howard, loan? No. The team isn\'t just built on three players. BlueEFC, Liverpool. No, but it’s not built on eight, either. Wenger: eat, sleep, moan, repeat. llort, SW4. I like that. Very funny. A reference to this, for those didn’t get it. (There’s a bit of language near the start, so not for easily upset, although that does seem to apply to a lot of people on here today.)  As a Manchester City fan I\'m delighted that the so called Big Four is now becoming the Big Six or Seven. For far too long United, Liverpool and Arsenal dominated the Champions League places and then Chelsea came along and put a spanner in the works. City\'s emergence has caused that much angst amongst the elite that they had to dream up FFP in an attempt to retain the status quo. Fortunately, they haven\'t got the brains to get that right either. So, Toffees, enjoy every minute of this season, hope you only lose one more game (you know which one) but snatch that last Champions League spot. At least two teams every season are going to have to live with no Champions League qualification; it might as well be Arsenal who join United in the Europa League. David, Manchester. With obvious exceptions, most want Everton in the Champions League – or any new club really. I just think all clubs would have more chance if this loan system ended, so the wealthiest could no longer run squads of 40 with half out on loan, and those other good players were then spread through the league. Permanently. The loan system is far from ideal but it\'s a damn sight more honest that having some foreign billionaire with little real interest in the game descend from nowhere to transform a middle of the road club into a serious contender. Both Chelsea and Manchester City were nothing remarkable until they were able to buy success off the shelf. When their benefactors get bored they will undoubtedly return from where they came. It is because of clubs like Everton who do well through sheer hard work and shrewd management that we don\'t yet have the situation that exists in Scotland where two rich clubs win everything in sight every year and the rest make up the numbers. Clive59, Wigan. No, Clive, it’s because of Chelsea and City that we’re not Scotland. (And it’s one up there now, not two.) They are the only ones to break the domination of Manchester United and Arsenal. Take them away and we would have become a two club league the moment Blackburn Rovers faded. Players are currently on loan in the Premier League at Sunderland (five), Fulham (five), West Ham (four), Hull City (three), Stoke City (three), Aston Villa (two), Newcastle United (two). Don\'t hear you complaining about any of them, or is it because a team outside of the big money five are making the system work in their favour? Why not campaign for a squad cap if you want fairness? Say a maximum of 22 players or 27 for clubs in Europe. Oh that\'s right, because it wouldn\'t suit the money five who want to splash their billions to have the best players on their books. Everton never made the rules, we just operate within them and we should be applauded for making the best of a ridiculous system instead of being denigrated. BlueAidan, Liverpool. Did you just copy and paste those statistics, because they are far from complete? There’s the two I mentioned at Arsenal for a start. Why don’t I go through each club individually? Well, let’s say I wrote about John Guidetti and Oussama Assaidi at Stoke. The response would be simple. It doesn’t make any difference, these players are peripheral to the narrative of the Premier League season and Stoke are mid-table, affecting nobody. So to draw attention to the issue the loans have to be an extreme case (like Watford last season, or the current situation at Parma in Italy) or be having an impact on a major issue. Isn’t that obvious? As for your point about capping squad numbers, that already happens. Major clubs get around it with, guess what?  No difference: Oussama Assaidi has had minimal impact on the wider Premier League while on loan at Stoke  You are right again. I\'d much rather see Chelsea spend £32m on Willian just so Tottenham don\'t get him and £12m on Salah so Liverpool don\'t get him. Also there is no sham in United paying £37m for a Chelsea reserve to try and preserve their top four status because let’s face it everyone wants to see the same finish year after year. Are you the same Martin Samuel who last year was praising Queens Park Rangers for spending £22m on Loic Remy and Christopher Samba on unsustainable wages? That worked out well didn\'t it? Jez, Liverpool. Well, every time I watch Chelsea Willian is in the team, so I’d say there was more to that than spite. Same with Mohamed Salah, who is 21 and still a squad man, but is often on the bench. I didn’t actually use the word sham anywhere in the column, and certainly not about Everton, so I don’t think it applies to the Mata transfer any more than it applies to Everton buying McCarthy from Wigan. These were just January transfers and perfectly routine. As for Samba and Remy, I didn’t praise QPR, merely defended their right to have a go at getting out of trouble. Sadly, the club was too diseased for it to work. Even so, they got the transfer fee back for Samba while Remy is on loan at Newcastle, which I keep reading here is a fantastic opportunity for him to get first-team football and for a little club with an average gate of 50,365 owned by one of the five richest men in the country to get a striker they couldn’t otherwise afford. It’s a Christmas miracle, really. It is beginning to worry me that this spotlight is being shone on our loan players at this point of the season. Nobody cared about them last August when they first arrived and everyone was highly complementary towards Martinez for being astute enough to sign them. Now it seems that it\'s not OK because we might actually achieve something. This whole debate is begrudging. Dicey69, Ireland. Why are you worried? Everton have done nothing wrong. It’s not as if anyone could take fourth place from you if you got it. There is no conspiracy to deny your club anything. In fact, most neutrals – myself included – would be delighted if Everton got top four this season. The praise for Martinez and Kenwright in their astute use of the loan system in August remains. But I don’t like the system and never have. If Moses scores the winner in a game that clinches the title for Liverpool, should the goal be disallowed because he is on loan? Of course not. Colefc, Bootle. How about if he misses a sitter and Chelsea win the title, though; or refuses to play because he fears for his future at Stamford Bridge if that happened? What if we did away with a system that created these dilemmas, traded players like the old days and watched fees fall so that – the very cream of the crop aside – Everton could afford to buy who they damn well liked? And wouldn’t lose Rodwell to City because the player would know he might not make the first team and couldn’t be loaned out, so would be better off staying put. Until next time.   More... MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan) Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Chelsea 2-0 PSG (agg: 3-3): Ba strikes late to send Blues through on away goals MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football    Read more: MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan) Chelsea going Dutch and Parma\'s squad of two hundred and twenty six (yes, you read that right, 226) show that the transfer market is now more like a cattle market... football needs to beef up loan rules Martin Samuel: Why Watford are a snapshot of all that\'s wrong with the modern game Share or comment on this article 131shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1076417/Martin-Samuel---Debate.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Martin Samuel - Debate</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 03:33 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 10:55 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE: I\'m not anti-Everton, I\'m just against the loan system - but the foolish paranoia of football fans never ceases to amaze me\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 131</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">164</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So, first, a little history. On April 30, 2003, I wrote a column in The Times that said Sam Allardyce should be the Manager of the Year for keeping Bolton Wanderers up, but actually I hoped they went down. The reason I gave was that Bolton’s team was built around foreign loan signings, while the other threatened team, West Ham United, had some of the best young English players in the country. Sam thinks I’ve had it in for him ever since. I don’t think he remembers the praise in the piece and he took it personally, rather than as a commentary on the loan system.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Since then, I’ve written repeatedly about temporary transfers, the stockpiling of players by major clubs, the whole dodgy area of gentlemen’s agreements and mates lending to mates, and the way football could be, if we would only wean ourselves off this devalued process. Not just in Premier League football, either. I wrote about Watford in the Championship last season, and Parma in Serie A this year. I wrote about Ryman League clubs Ware and Waltham Forest with more than 100 players passing through their books in one season, and Hameur Bouazza who in 2008-09 season played for Charlton Athletic against Birmingham City and Birmingham City against Charlton Athletic, while actually being owned by a third club, Fulham. </span><br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Sensitive soul: Sam Allardyce (left) kept Bolton up in 2003 with a number of loan players\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"398\" id=\"i-a6490e5b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-00640F5B00000258-266_634x398.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Sensitive soul: Sam Allardyce (left) kept Bolton up in 2003 with a number of loan players</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And on Wednesday I wrote about the positive impact loans have had on Everton’s season and how this would appear incompatible with financial fair play and the way it clamps down on overspending clubs for artificially inflating their league position. Had Everton bought all of their squad this season they may have fallen foul of FFP, but with loans they get around the system. That is not right, surely. It is just inflation by another means. Doing so, just as I did 11 years ago, I made sure to make clear that the club had done nothing wrong, and the system was at fault. I praised Everton’s manager, Roberto Martinez and his chairman Bill Kenwright. I said I wanted Everton to finish top four, and it would be a welcome change.</font></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It turns out Big Sam is not the only sensitive soul in the Premier League. It turns out he is not the only one who consumes his news selectively, with a well-balanced chip on each shoulder. Debate about the incompatibility of FFP and the loan system? Zip. People thinking I had a pop at their club. Everybody. So, for the last time: I like Everton, I want Everton to do well. I don’t like the loan system. I think we would be better off without it. Oh, what the hell. <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599917/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Everton-fairytale-hooked-shame-built-50m-loan-sham-Lukaku-Barry-Deulofeu-Wengers-right-moan.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\">Here’s the column</a> if you can be bothered to read it. Judging by what follows, you won’t be alone if you can’t.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Why does everyone think this is a new issue? Everton took Glen Keeley from Blackburn Rovers on loan in 1982 – that was 32 years ago. Everton, like Arsenal, send players out on loan, too. Last month Apostolos Vellios went on loan to Blackpool. It\'s part of the game and is essential for the development of young players. Ross Barkley was sent out on loan a number of times. This is a ridiculous non-issue. No-one cared about it for decades and now because one club does it well, everyone wants to have a moan. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Darren K, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">To fill in the gaps, Everton have seven players out on loan, and Ross Barkley was loaned to Sheffield Wednesday in 2012 and Leeds United in 2013. Keeley played 32 minutes for Everton and was sent off in the Merseyside derby for fouling Kenny Dalglish. His loan came with the option of a permanent move that, unsurprisingly, did not come to fruition. None of this matters, of course. A long list of historic examples is not the same as a counter argument, Darren. More young players came through when the loan system was not used so voraciously by clubs because a manager had to make do with what he had rather than searching for quick solutions elsewhere. Are any of the loan players in the first-team at Everton young and British? No. So, potentially, they are blocking that path for young British players.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Loan stars: Borini, Lukaku, Kallstrom and Remy, with a proponent of the system, Sam Allardyce\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"439\" id=\"i-ab1e0e80\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFD1C5400000578-806_634x439.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Loan stars: Borini, Lukaku, Kallstrom and Remy, with a proponent of the system, Sam Allardyce</p><div class=\"moduleFull\"><a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3430733408001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Jose Mourinho: Now is not the time to discuss Lukaku\'s future</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/video-undefined-1CD58CD400000578-46_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"At least they\'re happy with the system: Roberto Martinez (centre) and Romelu Lukaku (left) celebrate the on-loan striker\'s goal against Arsenal\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"426\" id=\"i-a77d0e5d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE2091400000578-791_634x426.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">At least they\'re happy with the system: Roberto Martinez (centre) and Romelu Lukaku (left) celebrate the on-loan striker\'s goal against Arsenal</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Big clubs are able to buy up too much of the young talent pool so the clubs simply can\'t develop them all into first team players. The loan system was the answer, but banning them from playing against their parent club was always wrong. Ultimately, it should not be possible to loan to a club unless they\'re in a lower league. Players were developed perfectly well in the days when Football League players from Divisions Two to Four were largely the young, up and coming group and the big clubs had a much smaller youth squad. It was better for the youngsters, with more regular first team competition, and better for the other leagues. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Usednurse, Scottish Borders. </span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Modern football has whole teams with a core of loaned players, whereas four decades ago a loan was exactly that – a way of overcoming a short-term emergency, like having every full-back at the club injured, or a glorified trial with a view to a permanent move. Continental clubs had a very active long-term loan system and we copied it from them. Has it made our football better, or given more opportunities to young British players? Hardly. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You miss the most glaring fact of all. All clubs can use the loan system, while not all can go and spend £100m at the drop of a hat. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Support Grass Roots, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I think you’re missing a glaring fact, actually. Without the loan system, clubs would not be able to stockpile players and transfer fees would come down, meaning Everton might be able to afford the likes of Romelu Lukaku, without it costing the earth. Now that’s a sound system. And so is this.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/AILMVTf2AL8\" width=\"640\"></iframe><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Let\'s imagine you\'re in a country where there is a huge gap in both income and wealth between a minority of rich and a majority of those who just about make ends meet. The poorer majority cannot survive without receiving more income and therefore need money to invest, but don\'t have the inherent wealth to do so. Your suggestion would be to ban banks lending money to the poor, thus cementing in place the existing distribution of income and wealth? The poor stay poor and the rich get richer? Astoundingly good logic. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">StevenNaismith, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You left out one factor, Steven. Players. Your analogy does not work because football in this case does not conform to the rules of a market economy, because there is a human commodity in the middle of the bands of rich and poor. Without loans, the rich would be unable to stockpile players, who would sign short-term contracts, request transfers, or stay with their smaller club of origin, therefore forcing the costs down for the poor.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I think there are also occasions where big clubs use strategic loans to strengthen lower-level teams and improve those chances against rival opposition. For example, Jose Mourinho might have calculated at the beginning of the season that if Lukaku could score against Manchester City, Manchester United, Arsenal, Tottenham Hotspur and Liverpool, it\'s almost like he is scoring for Chelsea. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Billy Shears, Manchester.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Quite right, Billy. Technically, Chelsea could stockpile goalkeepers, loan 10 of them out and ensure they will play more than half of their league games against a reserve goalkeeper. Loan players should be free to play against their parent club, as they do in UEFA tournaments - unless, like Chelsea, the parent club has inserted a clause making such a collision prohibitive. Meaning, that if they draw Atletico Madrid in this month\'s semi-final, or play them in the final, Chelsea get to choose the opposition goalkeeper. Now, isn\'t that healthy?<br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Here\'s the point: Everton could not afford Lukaku\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a8800e5e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE218C300000578-710_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"One of many: Gareth Barry has been marginalised at Manchester City because of their huge squad\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a9f00e71\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE21B2D00000578-377_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Here\'s the point: Everton could not afford Lukaku and Gareth Barry (right) so their current position is inflated<br/></p><div class=\"moduleFull\"><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3385493677001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Pardew: Remy, Lukaku and Barry were the best loan signings</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/24/video-undefined-1C890F9100000578-398_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">All players should have an annual financial fair play value based on annualised expense such as wages, plus current transfer value based on the market. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Gsyblue, Guernsey.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Good idea, but whose ledger will it occupy? Are Chelsea liable for Lukaku, to stop further stockpiling, or is the cost placed with Everton, to curb the motivation of building a team around loans? </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So what kind of loans should Everton deal in - the Glazer kind which allowed them to buy Manchester United? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Tom, London.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Neither is healthy, Tom; yet both are accepted strategies in football business. Blaming the Glazers for using the rules is no different to blaming Everton.  </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It appears that it is OK if your loan signings scrape survival in the Premier League but as soon as they start firing you towards the Champions League it is screwing the system? Poor article with undertones suggesting that Samuel is basically saying plucky little Everton should know their place and are knowingly cheating. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">MikeyEFC87, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Don’t put words in my mouth Mike. I couldn’t have made my positive feelings for Everton clearer; in fact I went out of my way to praise them. As stated in the preamble, I have always spoken out against the loan system, at both ends of the league, and in the middle. If your loan signings scrape survival, that means you have stayed up at the expense of another club, with players that are not yours. And that isn’t right, either. In a column published on May 13, 2009, I made that point about Norwich City’s survival in the Championship with 12 loan signings in 2007-08.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I notice how when Arsenal beat us in the FA Cup nothing was said, but as soon as we beat them convincingly in the league loans became a massive problem. The biggest issue with the transfer and loan market is that mega-rich clubs are overinflating prices. When managers complain maybe they should look at the reason why there are so many players loaned. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Efcdan, Deeside.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Sort of my point, Dan. That is why I said Everton were not to blame. They are exploiting a flawed system and a problem exacerbated by the wealthiest clubs.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Not to blame: Everton are exploiting a flawed system that allows them to loan Lukaku, Barry and Deufoleu\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"468\" id=\"i-aa7c0e7e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CF0B2E100000578-881_634x468.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Not to blame: Everton are exploiting a flawed system that allows them to loan Lukaku, Barry and Deufoleu</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I find it interesting that people prefer to see stability in the managerial hot-seat but are OK with players being at three clubs in the space of a year like Wilfried Zaha. The big benefit of the loan system is to develop younger players, so should there be an age cap? Players like Gareth Barry have been around for years - if a club wants him, they know what they\'re getting. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Tucky1919, Lincoln.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I’d like to see the whole system abolished, Tucky, but if we’re talking reform an age cap would certainly be a start.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So naughty Manchester City have bought a 16-year-old from Feyenoord, who previously would have made his name at that club? Undoubtedly, this is a harmful trend for smaller clubs, but is it all the fault of FFP and Michel Platini? Newsflash, this has been happening for years. Teams like Chelsea and Arsenal have been shopping in youth academies in the Netherlands and Feyenoord have been losing their greatest talents, just like Ajax. It has nothing to do with FFP. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Charles, Amsterdam.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, it has been a problem for many years but with financial fair play it is set to mushroom as clubs seek to circumvent the system. That was my point.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Arsene Wenger wasn’t talking about stopping loans. He simply said that it is a shame players like Lukaku aren’t allowed to play against their teams. That makes sense, in my opinion. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Khalid Ahmed, Oslo.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Actually, he was talking about ending a substantial element of the loan system, Khalid. Here is what he said: \'I believe if you want to continue the loan system, we have to make the players available against the teams that loan them, or the system is not defendable. It\'s just a protection of the clubs who loan the players out to hurt the opponents and they have no risk at all. I think the best would be that the players are only loaned in lower divisions or abroad, and even abroad I\'m not completely convinced it is right.\' So Wenger would outlaw the loan transfers of Lukaku, Barry and Gerard Deulofeu in Everton’s case, as they are either in the same division or between major European clubs. He went a bit further than just saying they should be able to play against the parent club. <br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Bold move: Arsene Wenger would outlaw the loaning of players to teams in the same division\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"399\" id=\"i-ab000e82\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE26AE700000578-260_634x399.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Bold move: Arsene Wenger would outlaw the loaning of players to teams in the same division</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What does it matter? Is it more of a fairytale that Everton are bought out by a billionaire and given hundreds of millions to spend on success? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Entrepreneur, Manchester.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No – but let’s not pretend Bill Kenwright has not been seeking that option as a way out for his club. Indeed, he was castigated quite viciously by some Everton fans for being unable to find a wealthy buyer.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It is called financial management, well within the fair play rules. As a football fan, would you rather Lukaku was on the bench at Chelsea, or playing week in, week out, at Everton? Loan transfers are not exactly free and some fail to work out, like Victor Moses at Liverpool. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Jambo Jambo, South Africa.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Firstly, I didn’t say it was outside the rules, quite the opposite. Secondly, the choice shouldn’t be between the loan and the bench. How about Everton sign Lukaku permanently for realistic money – the third way that is never considered because we have the loan system.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The main difference is that if a rich owner pulls the plug then a club still has to pay inflated wages and may get in financial trouble. When loans end a club would typically just not be as good. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Thomas, Watford.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So their status has been artificially inflated, yes? Again, sort of my point.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I feel the biggest flaw with the whole system is the amount of players a club is allowed to loan out. Fair enough with under-20’s gaining first-team experience in competitive football but above that there should be a strict limit. If a club was only allowed to loan out five players over 21 then players and agents would have to take that into account. Rot in the reserves or choose another team that offers more football. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">David, Southport.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Once more, it’s a start David, albeit a rather generous one. Five over-21 loans per club? That’s 100 in the Premier League alone before we’ve even started on the stockpiled youth signings.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Temporary solution: Loic Remy has made a huge impact on Newcastle\'s season on loan from QPR\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"641\" id=\"i-ae7b0e9c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFCFBB400000578-465_634x641.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Temporary solution: Loic Remy has made a huge impact on Newcastle\'s season on loan from QPR</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Your view of the loan system is flawed. Not all clubs can compete financially with the likes of Manchester City and Chelsea. Everton certainly can\'t, so without the loan system would probably be where they are, despite having impressive youngsters and England internationals such as Leighton Baines, Phil Jagielka and Ross Barkley. They also have internationals from South Africa and the United States. So, if you are happy to keep the same few teams challenging for honours take away the loan system. If you prefer the most amazing competitive league keep it and allow smaller teams to compete. Don\'t blame Everton, applaud them for using the system well. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Bye Bye Venkys, Preston.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Everton has international footballers on permanent contracts? Big deal. So does every club. Don’t you see, it is the loan system that keeps clubs like Manchester City and Chelsea empowered and transfer fees high. Take it away and Everton could afford the players that are beyond them – just as it was in the old days. Unless you know any other time in football when Everton could not afford to buy Chelsea’s reserve striker or an aging midfield player that could not get in Manchester City’s team, and needed to make a temporary arrangement? Because I don’t.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">While I agree that we are lucky to have Lukaku, some of our top players this season have been Steven Naismith, James McCarthy, Seamus Coleman, Barkley and Baines. Not a loan player in sight. Please reanalyse Everton\'s season based on the whole team instead of trying to cast us as lucky one-timers. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Lucy27, Chester.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Lucy, I didn’t analyse Everton’s season, beyond praising them. I analysed the loan system, an aspect of football I was writing about when Lukaku was nine.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"The same deal: Fabio Borini is on loan at Sunderland from Liverpool\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"375\" id=\"i-ab050e7d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CEA753E00000578-531_634x375.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">The same deal: Fabio Borini is on loan at Sunderland from Liverpool</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So, basically, this loan system, which has been in place since I can remember in the Seventies and Eighties, is only flawed because it is working in our favour? Lukaku and Barry have been excellent, Deulofeu great in bits but hardly a regular. So is it Everton’s fault that Moses and others have not been as successful? All the top clubs throughout the Premier League and Europe use the loan system. Barry would be a substitute at best for City, Lukaku likewise at Chelsea and Deulofeu would be in Barcelona\'s B team, so is this not down to Martinez and his good management skills rather than a flawed loan system? Seems the media are worried about Everton gatecrashing the Champions League and denying Sky’s favoured clubs the extra cash and spending power. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Dave EFC, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Oh, get a grip and read the column. \'Roberto Martinez has done an outstanding job… an extraordinary feat and great for the English game…a new club breaking into the staid elite is always welcome…Everton are winning the popular vote… very smart in exploiting the nuances of the player market and good luck to them in that…\' It never ceases to amaze me, the circle the wagons, foolish paranoia, that is the default mechanism of many fans faced with even the mildest criticism of his club. I have been writing about the flaws, inconsistences, danger and weaknesses of the loan system for many years now. There is no point illustrating this argument using failed deals or mid-table clubs of no consequence. The harmful effects of the loan system are most keenly felt when a major issue is directly influenced – such as relegation, promotion or qualification to the Champions League. Bolton Wanderers staying up in 2003 was another example. Is that so hard to comprehend? </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I suppose Arsenal picking up Mikel Arteta, a key player for Everton, was fair game just because they could pay for him. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Freespeechman, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, like when Everton bought Leighton Baines or James McCarthy from Wigan Athletic, Phil Jagielka from Sheffield United or Joleon Lescott from Wolverhampton Wanderers. Same thing.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Rarely seen: Kim Kallstrom has barely featured on loan at Arsenal\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"441\" id=\"i-ad7f0e92\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFCF7B600000578-268_634x441.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Rarely seen: Kim Kallstrom has barely featured on loan at Arsenal</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The loan system is designed to even the gap between the mega-rich and the other clubs and to give young players game time. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Upthetofees, Wirral.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No it isn’t. If the richest clubs thought any gap was truly being closed they would vote against it. The loan system is there because it allows the wealthy to keep overinflated squads and the poor to feed off their scraps. Usually, it only influences relegation and mid-table issues so the elite do not care; this season it may play a part in Champions League qualification. It will be interesting to see what happens next season. By being so good, Everton may have spoiled it for everyone.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Give over, Coleman, McCarthy and Barkley have arguably contributed more than Barry and Deulofeu was out injured for months. Do you even watch the games? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Daninjapan, Tokyo.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, and live, not just on television. Anyway, how are things at Shimizu S-Pulse?</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Is it more immoral utilising a completely legal loan system for a locally ran team, or spending half a billion on foreign players and leaving your academy out in the cold, with Arab money? Answer me that. Everton tend to loan a couple players every season due to lack of funds. Why have you just spoken up now? Because it\'s been a success? Where were you when Jo, Segundo Castillo and Matteo Ferrari came in? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">MHartley93, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I was writing negative articles about the loan system, mate, which you obviously weren’t reading because unless the word Everton appears in the headline you’re probably not interested. Here’s the conclusion from that column about Bolton in 2003. \'I fear the influx of a league of Boltons, of managers who take the notion of a Player of the Month rather too literally, of talent that is borrowed as casually as next-door\'s power drill by bosses not as worldly-wise as Sam Allardyce. My concern is that when Allardyce\'s magic stops working - as one day it must, just as Wimbledon fell off the tightrope, and Lennie Lawrence couldn\'t save Charlton Athletic for ever - nothing will remain of what once was a great English football club. All there will be is people trying on Bolton shirts.\' So there are my credentials in writing about loans: 11 years of solid disapproval. I’m not sure you can find my old Times stuff online any more. So <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2416860/Chelseas-Dutch-enclave-shows-transfer-market-like-cattle-market--Martin-Samuel.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> (and <a href=\"/sport/article-2208564/Watford-snapshot-thats-wrong-modern-football-Martin-Samuel.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>) are just a couple of links from the last two seasons.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If Everton get Champions League football they can afford to buy Lukaku and Deulofeu. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Manred1905, London.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And I hope they do. But would Chelsea sell now Everton are a threat?</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Potential benefit: By scoring in the Champions league, Joel Campbell could have done parent club Arsenal a favour\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"346\" id=\"i-ab260e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFD3E6300000578-152_634x346.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Potential benefit: By scoring in the Champions league, Joel Campbell could have done parent club Arsenal a favour</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This difference is that Everton play in the same league as Chelsea. Arsenal are not in the Greek Super League and don\'t benefit when their loaned players can\'t play against them. Lukaku should have been in the Everton team versus Chelsea. That\'s the difference. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">GRB, Chandra.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So the teams that Joel Campbell helped remove from the Champions League didn’t potentially benefit Arsenal?</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If we want to talk about unfair perhaps we need to mention the fact that teams such as Manchester United are able to spend £37m on one player during a transfer window? The transfer system must be revised with no deals taking place during the season. This may also place greater value on youth players. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Pablo78, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">They bought the player with their own money, Pablo. Why is this unfair?</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Maybe if the likes of Manchester United, Manchester City, Arsenal, Chelsea and Liverpool had B teams like in Spain then these players wouldn’t be so freely available on loan. It would also help with developing English kids. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Steven, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I agree, Steven. A strong B-team league would definitely help.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What about the players’ point of view? Lukaku was loaned to West Bromwich Albion last season where he was very successful. With the World Cup this summer he obviously wants to play as often as possible, and would not have been picked having spent two seasons as a substitute at Chelsea. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Andy, Bridport.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Andy, I can see what is in it for Lukaku, for Everton and for Chelsea – I just don’t think it is in the wider interests of the game. Never have.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Thumbs up: Manchester United bought Juan Mata with their own money, which is absolutely fine\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"355\" id=\"i-ac270e8a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CF8F17F00000578-709_634x355.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Thumbs up: Manchester United bought Juan Mata with their own money, which is absolutely fine</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This article is very harsh on Everton. How can you blame them for loaning players? Every other club does it. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">DBO-LFC, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">\'So let’s start by saying that the club challenging Arsenal for fourth place has done nothing wrong.\' Maybe I should have made it clearer. ‘The club challenging Arsenal for fourth place’? The one I said had ‘done nothing wrong’? That’s Everton. Short of writing in capital letters, maybe crayon, I don’t know what more I can do here.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No mention of how well the £12m signing McCarthy has played, how Coleman and Baines look revitalised, or praise for blooding a 19-year-old in big games. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Sie2003, Stafford.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, completely ignored, unless you include that oblique statement about Martinez doing \'an outstanding job\'.  </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No-one moaned last season when Lukaku was at West Brom, but then again the media don\'t like Everton rocking the Premier League boat, unsettling their chosen few teams who should win everything every season. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Petedil, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Nobody is moaning. The reason Lukaku made less of a ripple at West Brom was because his presence made the difference between upper mid-table and lower mid-table so, basically, no difference at all. Surely you can appreciate why his impact at Everton is attracting more attention? And don’t give me that cobblers about wanting to see the same teams win all the time. One of the reasons I am so opposed to financial fair play is because it cements the elite in place. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I think Everton have done a great job this season. I hope they snatch that fourth place. But I worry what they will do when Lukaku is gone. Take away his goals and where would they be? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Ryan Smith, Newtown.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Right, so let’s project. Say Everton qualify for the Champions League, which most people hope they do. Then Chelsea take Lukaku back. Unless Martinez is incredibly astute in the transfer market, Everton’s potential will be reduced. They may fail to make it through the preliminary rounds or go out at group stage – considering they are sure to be seeded in pot four. That then has a negative impact on the English game through co-efficient points. The leagues that have relied most heavily on loan trading are the ones that have gradually lost their Champions League berths – Italy for instance. Why, because teams qualify with an artificial squad list, are then weakened the following season and fall short. There has to be a better way.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"One and only: Henrik Larsson scores his solitary league goal while on loan at Manchester United\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"402\" id=\"i-a6530e53\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-0636B7160000044D-357_634x402.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">One and only: Henrik Larsson scores his solitary league goal while on loan at Manchester United</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So when Henrik Larsson scored a raft of goals to win Manchester United the league whilst on loan – that was OK then? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Pavlos, Wigan.</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">No it wasn’t. But just to stop you making a fool of yourself in the pub as well as on this forum, the stack of league goals scored by Larsson during his loan spell in 2006-07 amounted to one. The 70th minute third goal in a 4-0 home win over Watford. They probably would have managed it without him.</span>  <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You are basing the progress of a team on the input of a few players. It is like saying take Luis Suarez, Daniel Sturridge and Steven Gerrard out of the Liverpool line-up and they wouldn\'t be where they are. And it\'s true, on both counts – but that shouldn\'t take the achievement away. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">TheHumbleEgg, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Well, yes it should in one way, because those Liverpool players belong to the club, in Gerrard’s case since his schooldays, while the Everton trio are passing through on temporary arrangements. I do like it, though, when a people comprehensively undermine their own arguments. Makes my job a lot easier – and reminds me a little of this.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/hC9NYuExSzo\" width=\"640\"></iframe><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Maybe a better story would have been how Arsenal got wellied by a team costing less than Mesut Ozil. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Jmcd, London.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Except it didn’t really, did it? In these days of FFP, the true cost of a team is made illusionary because of the loan system. That’s the point.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As a Toffee, this is more about Lukaku in my view and the fact that super-rich clubs like Chelsea are the real beneficiaries as they loan out almost 30 potential first team players. Everton have been made the focus of how the loan system is wrong when as usual it is the rich that are pulling the strings and have all the control. Everton may get Champions League but who will score the goals next season? We\'ll have to pay £25m or try to get another loan, but it\'s doubtful a top competing club in the Premier League would loan to a genuine rival. So maybe another club gets Chelsea\'s largesse. Meanwhile, Chelsea’s traditional rivals, such as Arsenal, miss out on UEFA’s money and it weakens their appeal in attracting top players. Who\'s the real beneficiary of that? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Rich, Jersey.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">An Evertonian looking further ahead than May? You’ll be ducked as a witch, Rich.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, the loan players are important to Everton, but they\'re not everything. Lukaku hasn\'t been a 20 goals plus striker, Deulofeu is a squad player who has been used sparingly. What about our home grown talents of Barkley and John Stones, the resurgence of Leon Osman, the improvement of players like Kevin Mirallas and Naismith, the talent of our fantastic full backs and the solid central defensive partnership? Not forgetting Tim Howard\'s great season. Martinez should be judged on this and people will see that there\'s more to Everton than a couple of loan signings. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Simon Smith, United Kingdom.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Indeed there is Simon; but this is bigger than just a debate around one club. The fact that Everton have other good permanent players doesn’t suddenly validate the loan system. The two events are unrelated.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unrelated: The fact Everton have good permanent players such as Kevin Mirallas doesn\'t validate the loan system\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"358\" id=\"i-a86a0e6b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE2293700000578-659_634x358.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unrelated: The fact Everton have good permanent players such as Kevin Mirallas doesn\'t validate the loan system</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You can get loans in as long as you don\'t threaten to break into the media’s beloved top four. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Luke, England.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And what top four would that be, Luke? Does it include Manchester United, because they’re seventh right now? I know, I know. It’s tough when the facts don’t fit your stupid conspiracy theory.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The defence have always been solid and the arrival of McCarthy has been a very shrewd move. Deulofeu has only been used a handful of times and Lukaku has been indifferent. Yet again it’s the same old story: little old Everton upsetting the Sky five, which we can’t have. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Daleefc1878, Ipswich.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes we talk of nothing else in press rooms. \'How are we going to stop Everton,\' we cry.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">How is this any different than clubs who just buy success? The team that Martinez inherited was already fantastic and he has just had to tweak it to his style of play. As for Everton struggling without Marouane Fellaini if we get into the Champions League, I doubt with the style of play we have now he would fit into the current squad. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Gedi88, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Ged, that is my argument. The two systems are imperfect, yet we have a holier-than-thou attitude to throwing money at a football club, while turning a blind eye to the artificial inflation via the loan system. I don’t blame Everton for using the part of the market that suits their needs; I just think there is a better way, and that it would benefit Everton long-term, too, by forcing prices down. And here’s another thought. Does Jack Rodwell leave if he knows he has to make Manchester City’s first-team to play, and cannot escape with a loan? Because I think, without the loan system, he is still your player.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Maybe you would be better advised to look at the mega rich clubs who buy all the best players and then use naming rights to invest money and bypass the financial fair play rules. There is no level playing field out there, so stop whinging about our loans. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">J18efc00, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I’m not whinging about your loans, but the loan system. I do find it comical, though, that people talk so piously about all other forms of advancement, except the one that benefits their club. </font></span><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No mention of the 27 Chelsea players out on loan then? More than the whole Everton squad. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Sutty, St Helens.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No, because I’ve written about them in previous columns. I try to make them different, you know. I find the regular readers prefer it.  <br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Not the only one: Lukakau is one of many Chelsea players out on loan - a subject touched on in previous columns\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"419\" id=\"i-9bdf0e39\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE238D300000578-52_634x419.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Not the only one: Lukakau is one of many Chelsea players out on loan - a subject touched on in previous columns</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Well done Everton. It\'s about time a club other than the Sky five broke into the closed shop of the media darlings. They have done it within the rules, rather than going out and spending millions on players, like Juan Mata in the transfer window. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Goldfish1, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This is really just another attack on teams who dare to threaten the status quo of Sky’s Big Four. If you\'re working within the system that is in place then that should be the end of it. Indeed, it could be argued that the loan system has evolved as a consequence of Sky throwing funds at football and the elite clubs over the last few years. They have been able to accumulate squads of expensive talent whilst others have been left to pick up the crumbs which fall from the top table, made worse with the oil money from wealthy foreign owners. Football used to be sport with a little bit of business; today it\'s a business, with a little bit of sport. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Mark, Durham.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Of course, some of us remember the original breakaway five in 1990: Manchester United, Liverpool, Tottenham Hotspur, Arsenal – and Everton. So let’s drop all this nonsense about oligarchs and Arabs and poor little Everton. When Everton had the money and the power, they couldn’t wait to stuff everybody else and tried to cut the deal that ended in the formation of the Premier League. They were no different to the elite clubs now. And just because everyone keeps quiet and works within the system doesn’t mean it is correct. Slavery was a system; so was Stalinism.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Come on Martin – Everton have lucked in to a great manager. Arsenal, Tottenham and Manchester United all had their chance to appoint Martinez but Everton have an owner who lives and breathes football. Sadly, he has very little money compared to the big clubs, so Everton have used the loan system. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Zipdip, Harwich.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Look, I don’t want this debate to turn into an edition of Mystic Mart but the idea I haven’t given Martinez credit is beginning to jar. In this column from May 13 last year, I placed him among the names I thought Manchester City should have considered before Manuel Pellegrini. Here’s the quote: \'Could Pellegrini have won the FA Cup with Wigan Athletic, as Martinez did on Saturday? Could he have got Wigan playing better football than Manchester City? Yesterday’s FA Cup defeat may have come as a bit of a shock, the discovery that there is a Spanish manager playing better football and working tiny miracles 25 miles down the road.\' As for Bill Kenwright, I cannot think of a chairman I admire more. I would regard him as a friend and I hope that warmth came cross when I interviewed him for the paper on September 9, 2011, at a time when a group of Everton fans were campaigning to get him out. <br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Credit where it\'s due: Roberto Martinez has been given plenty of praise\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"344\" id=\"i-a88e0e65\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CE2411F00000578-840_634x344.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Credit where it\'s due: Roberto Martinez has been given plenty of praise</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This is nonsense. Financial fair play was brought in to stop clubs becoming overly indebted to their owners. By loaning high quality players Everton are reducing their financial risks. This is entirely consistent with the principles behind the FFP rules. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Daiwaijai, Hong Kong.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">A loan player is not an asset. I am pretty sure FFP requires a club to develop its assets. And building success on temporary players did not exactly stand Bolton in good stead, long term.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So it begins. How dare upstarts Everton get into top five? Stop bashing us - if you don’t like the loan system, speak to the Football Association. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Steve, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I would Steve, but they’re all cowering under the sofa in case someone mentions that Nicolas Anelka business again. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If it gets them Champions League football and increased income to balance the books, it is not bad business. I prefer it to oil money. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Alan, Liverpool. </span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, but why? Both are forms of artificial inflation. Why moralise around one but not the other? </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I seem to recall West Ham United loaned a certain Andrew Carroll and nothing was said. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Michael, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And the reason, Michael? Because Carroll’s presence had minimal impact. I don’t like the loan system; therefore I didn’t like Carroll’s loan to West Ham or any of the loans the club has arranged this season. QED. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I don\'t care. If it\'s right that teams like Manchester City and Chelsea can be bought overnight and transformed into league dominating outfits, I think it\'s only fair that clubs who struggle to attract huge investment can find alternative methods of making the league more competitive. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Rchappy88, Burnley.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yes, but it’s on their terms. Don’t you get it? This competition exists only on conditions set by the very clubs you deplore. If Everton start to challenge Chelsea, do you think they’ll get any more players? If Brendan Rodgers wasn’t Jose Mourinho’s mate, and Liverpool seen as mostly harmless, would they have got Victor Moses? Say Moses was a roaring success and was stopping a loan-free Everton team full of local talent coming fourth right now? Is it fair that who you know, or whose back you scratch, gets you a player?</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I wonder if Mourinho would have loaned out Moses and Lukaku if they could have played against him like they can in the Spanish and German leagues? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Arsène, Finsbury Park.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Short answer: no. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You wrote: \'Barry, a squad player at Manchester City and now 33, but even so he might have commanded £6m as a permanent transfer in the summer.\' Barry is out of contract this summer and was offered to Everton for £1m in January. God only knows where you\'re getting £6m from. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">PJC83, Warrington.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Because January isn’t the summer. Come on mate, we did the months of the year in primary school.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What you are saying is that you want the Sky Four as it once was to always be on top. Everton cannot compete financially with most clubs but actually have the best manager. This seems to upset you for some reason. You should applaud Everton and what we\'ve done, upsetting the chosen few. Good coaching actually improves players like Barry, Lukaku and Deulofeu. God help us if Everton actually win the Champions League. Who are you going to blame then? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Trobbo66, Plano, Texas.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I’m very sorry that you didn’t understand the column Robbo. You’re probably good at something else. Whittlin’ maybe.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">New rules that need to be implemented: Clubs can only allow players that live within 30 minutes drive of their training ground into the academy. Clubs are not allowed to have contact with players that live outside the catchment area. Clubs cannot tell a player to move to a certain area to comply with rule 1. Only players aged 21 and under can go out on loan. Maximum of three loan signings at each club. Reduce squad size to 23 and abolish the unlimited players under the age of 21 rule. Maximum of 18 players that are not from the club\'s academy allowed in the first team squad. Transfer of teenage players prohibited. Contracted players under the age of 20 cannot move to another club.  Clubs from each country can only sign overseas players that are within 350 miles of their country when they reach 21 years of age. Clubs can only sign players from countries beyond 350 miles when the player reaches 22 years of age. I hope Sepp Blatter reads this. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Scott Shelby, Birmingham.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yeah, Scott. He’s a big fan of this column. In fact, he phoned in and requested this one.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/gVWLrloeToA\" width=\"640\"></iframe><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Interesting point, but what do you expect clubs like Everton to do? Ignore the possibility of borrowing these players? The system is flawed but Everton must be congratulated for making the best of what is available to them. If they finish above United, even, I will be very impressed. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Mick, Bergerac.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Won’t we all, Mick? To answer your question, I expect Everton to carry on doing exactly what they are doing now. I would in their position. I took issue with the system, not the club. That is what has been missed here. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Before even reading the comments I knew there would be several people, presumably Everton supporters, throwing a wobbly, thinking it\'s an attack on their club and playing the victim card. Read the article, it concerns the contradictions of modern football, and it\'s not the first time Martin Samuel has talked about the stupidity of FFP and the consequences for poorer clubs and players. From the elite staying the elite, to clubs hoarding young players or making nearly their whole first XI up from loans. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Plastics Everywhere, United Kingdom.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Ah, my hero. Thanks mate, whoever you are. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Rather than concentrating on the fact Everton are doing very well but happen to have loaned a few players, how about using your journalistic skill to investigate comments made by the Premier League chief executive a few weeks ago concerning Manchester United’s fall from grace and how it could affect the league financially? Could this not be construed to mean that bigger clubs are being favoured on decisions? If this is the way the Premier League think then it could be open to corruption. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">El Bob, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What, Bob, you mean use my journalistic skills to write about Richard Scudamore’s comments as I did two weeks ago? Try to keep up.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Look at Watford last season, challenging all the way in the Championship because of the loan system, yet this season they are nowhere near the same standard because many of the players went back. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Qwerty123, Brighton.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And so close to promotion via the play-offs, too. Can you imagine? It would have been carnage had they got up and then the rules changed. I was accused of having it in for them, too, I seem to remember. Maybe I just don’t like the theme from Z Cars.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Everton are well within the FA rulebook and they deserve all the plaudits they get. What if Lukaku and the rest had ended up at Arsenal and propelled them to the title? Would it have been right then? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Saj, Manchester.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"What a difference: Watford nearly got promoted last season with a raft of loan players\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"384\" id=\"i-ac5e0e88\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFDAB2600000578-180_634x384.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">What a difference: Watford nearly got promoted last season with a raft of loan players</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What a bitter and ignorant article. First of all, Everton are a club that has nine league titles, roughly the same as Tottenham, Manchester City and Chelsea combined. Only Arsenal, Manchester United and Liverpool have finished in the top four of English football more times. Yes, football didn\'t begin in 1992 like some would lead you to believe, so Everton making fourth spot wouldn\'t exactly be a fairytale. We are not Wigan Athletic. Lukaku has scored 13 goals this year, so Everton are not relying on him like Liverpool are with Suarez, either. Our team is still built around our defence, where our attack starts. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Rdsnuke, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And your history is relevant to this debate how? Oh, I see you resent all these upstart clubs taking what you think is rightfully yours. And you think you should be able to claim it back, no matter how that is achieved, while patronising Wigan, the club that sold you two of your best players and helped groom your manager. Nice. No, football didn’t begin in 1992 mate. So once again, the five clubs whose threatened breakaway culminated in the formation of the Premier League: Manchester United, Tottenham, Arsenal, Liverpool – and Everton. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Funny how this wasn\'t a problem for the ten years that Everton have utilised the loan system for players like Royston Drenthe. This is lazy journalism from someone who doesn\'t watch Everton enough to know that their most consistent performers have been ones they own. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">DailyTonedMail, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No, that’s a lazy argument from someone who hasn’t followed my writing enough to realise that I’ve been detailing the shortcomings of the loan system for more than 10 years, using examples other than Everton. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If the loan system was not in place, where would the likes of Lukaku and Deulofeu gain the valuable experience of playing in our Premier League? Everton have at least six young players out on loan to lower division teams getting regular game time and both the borrowing clubs and Everton are getting the benefit. If those players improve to the point that when they return to Everton, they can press for first team places. That is a win-win situation for all and needs to be left alone. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Bluebyyou, Tonypandy.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So maybe if Everton didn’t have to play Chelsea’s loan players, the Everton players that are out on loan might get a game. Then, maybe Lukaku would have signed for a club that gave him first team football because transfer fees would come down without a stockpiling elite inflating the market. Now there’s a real win-win. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Coleman, loan? Baines, loan? Miralles, loan? McCarthy, loan? Stones, loan? Naismith, loan? Barkley, loan? Howard, loan? No. The team isn\'t just built on three players. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">BlueEFC, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No, but it’s not built on eight, either. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Wenger: eat, sleep, moan, repeat. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">llort, SW4.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I like that. Very funny. A reference to this, for those didn’t get it. (There’s a bit of language near the start, so not for easily upset, although that does seem to apply to a lot of people on here today.)</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/3QJE1uP_1gk\" width=\"640\"></iframe><br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As a Manchester City fan I\'m delighted that the so called Big Four is now becoming the Big Six or Seven. For far too long United, Liverpool and Arsenal dominated the Champions League places and then Chelsea came along and put a spanner in the works. City\'s emergence has caused that much angst amongst the elite that they had to dream up FFP in an attempt to retain the status quo. Fortunately, they haven\'t got the brains to get that right either. So, Toffees, enjoy every minute of this season, hope you only lose one more game (you know which one) but snatch that last Champions League spot. At least two teams every season are going to have to live with no Champions League qualification; it might as well be Arsenal who join United in the Europa League.<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"> David, Manchester.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">With obvious exceptions, most want Everton in the Champions League – or any new club really. I just think all clubs would have more chance if this loan system ended, so the wealthiest could no longer run squads of 40 with half out on loan, and those other good players were then spread through the league. Permanently.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The loan system is far from ideal but it\'s a damn sight more honest that having some foreign billionaire with little real interest in the game descend from nowhere to transform a middle of the road club into a serious contender. Both Chelsea and Manchester City were nothing remarkable until they were able to buy success off the shelf. When their benefactors get bored they will undoubtedly return from where they came. It is because of clubs like Everton who do well through sheer hard work and shrewd management that we don\'t yet have the situation that exists in Scotland where two rich clubs win everything in sight every year and the rest make up the numbers. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Clive59, Wigan.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No, Clive, it’s because of Chelsea and City that we’re not Scotland. (And it’s one up there now, not two.) They are the only ones to break the domination of Manchester United and Arsenal. Take them away and we would have become a two club league the moment Blackburn Rovers faded.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Players are currently on loan in the Premier League at Sunderland (five), Fulham (five), West Ham (four), Hull City (three), Stoke City (three), Aston Villa (two), Newcastle United (two). Don\'t hear you complaining about any of them, or is it because a team outside of the big money five are making the system work in their favour? Why not campaign for a squad cap if you want fairness? Say a maximum of 22 players or 27 for clubs in Europe. Oh that\'s right, because it wouldn\'t suit the money five who want to splash their billions to have the best players on their books. Everton never made the rules, we just operate within them and we should be applauded for making the best of a ridiculous system instead of being denigrated.<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"> BlueAidan, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Did you just copy and paste those statistics, because they are far from complete? There’s the two I mentioned at Arsenal for a start. Why don’t I go through each club individually? Well, let’s say I wrote about John Guidetti and Oussama Assaidi at Stoke. The response would be simple. It doesn’t make any difference, these players are peripheral to the narrative of the Premier League season and Stoke are mid-table, affecting nobody. So to draw attention to the issue the loans have to be an extreme case (like Watford last season, or the current situation at Parma in Italy) or be having an impact on a major issue. Isn’t that obvious? As for your point about capping squad numbers, that already happens. Major clubs get around it with, guess what?</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No difference: Oussama Assaidi has had minimal impact on the wider Premier League while on loan at Stoke\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"378\" id=\"i-ac5b0e8d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFDB1A400000578-671_634x378.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">No difference: Oussama Assaidi has had minimal impact on the wider Premier League while on loan at Stoke</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You are right again. I\'d much rather see Chelsea spend £32m on Willian just so Tottenham don\'t get him and £12m on Salah so Liverpool don\'t get him. Also there is no sham in United paying £37m for a Chelsea reserve to try and preserve their top four status because let’s face it everyone wants to see the same finish year after year. Are you the same Martin Samuel who last year was praising Queens Park Rangers for spending £22m on Loic Remy and Christopher Samba on unsustainable wages? That worked out well didn\'t it? <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Jez, Liverpool.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Well, every time I watch Chelsea Willian is in the team, so I’d say there was more to that than spite. Same with Mohamed Salah, who is 21 and still a squad man, but is often on the bench. I didn’t actually use the word sham anywhere in the column, and certainly not about Everton, so I don’t think it applies to the Mata transfer any more than it applies to Everton buying McCarthy from Wigan. These were just January transfers and perfectly routine. As for Samba and Remy, I didn’t praise QPR, merely defended their right to have a go at getting out of trouble. Sadly, the club was too diseased for it to work. Even so, they got the transfer fee back for Samba while Remy is on loan at Newcastle, which I keep reading here is a fantastic opportunity for him to get first-team football and for a little club with an average gate of 50,365 owned by one of the five richest men in the country to get a striker they couldn’t otherwise afford. It’s a Christmas miracle, really.</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It is beginning to worry me that this spotlight is being shone on our loan players at this point of the season. Nobody cared about them last August when they first arrived and everyone was highly complementary towards Martinez for being astute enough to sign them. Now it seems that it\'s not OK because we might actually achieve something. This whole debate is begrudging. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Dicey69, Ireland.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Why are you worried? Everton have done nothing wrong. It’s not as if anyone could take fourth place from you if you got it. There is no conspiracy to deny your club anything. In fact, most neutrals – myself included – would be delighted if Everton got top four this season. The praise for Martinez and Kenwright in their astute use of the loan system in August remains. But I don’t like the system and never have. </font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If Moses scores the winner in a game that clinches the title for Liverpool, should the goal be disallowed because he is on loan? Of course not. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Colefc, Bootle.</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">How about if he misses a sitter and Chelsea win the title, though; or refuses to play because he fears for his future at Stamford Bridge if that happened? What if we did away with a system that created these dilemmas, traded players like the old days and watched fees fall so that – the very cream of the crop aside – Everton could afford to buy who they damn well liked? And wouldn’t lose Rodwell to City because the player would know he might not make the first team and couldn’t be loaned out, so would be better off staying put. Until next time. </font></span></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599917/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Everton-fairytale-hooked-shame-built-50m-loan-sham-Lukaku-Barry-Deulofeu-Wengers-right-moan.html\"> MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan)</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599868/Chelsea-2-0-PSG-agg-3-3-Chelsea-win-away-goals-Ba-strikes-late-send-Blues-through.html\"> Chelsea 2-0 PSG (agg: 3-3): Ba strikes late to send Blues through on away goals</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\"> MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<br/>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"item\" data-track-module=\"am-external-links^external-links\" id=\"external-source-links\"> <span>Read more:</span> <ul> <li><a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2599917/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Everton-fairytale-hooked-shame-built-50m-loan-sham-Lukaku-Barry-Deulofeu-Wengers-right-moan.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">MARTIN SAMUEL: Everton fairytale has us hooked - shame it\'s built on £50m loan sham of Lukaku, Barry and Deulofeu (so Wenger\'s right to moan)</a></li> <li><a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2416860/Chelseas-Dutch-enclave-shows-transfer-market-like-cattle-market--Martin-Samuel.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Chelsea going Dutch and Parma\'s squad of two hundred and twenty six (yes, you read that right, 226) show that the transfer market is now more like a cattle market... football needs to beef up loan rules</a></li> <li><a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"/sport/article-2208564/Watford-snapshot-thats-wrong-modern-football-Martin-Samuel.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Martin Samuel: Why Watford are a snapshot of all that\'s wrong with the modern game</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/MARTIN-SAMUEL-THE-DEBATE-Im-not-anti-Everton-Im-just-against-loan-foolish-paranoia-football-fans-never-ceases-amaze-me.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE: I\'m not anti-Everton, I\'m just against the loan system - but the foolish paranoia of football fans never ceases to amaze me\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601297/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">131</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601297-1CFD1C5400000578-682_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:49','2014-04-10 17:55:52'),(104,'76d7f418093bd4842aa85d4ae6eba50e6f5ae1f5da8546ce54e9a770b8271ede','dailymail',NULL,'Premier League teams can\'t cope with Arjen Robben, says Martin Keown','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html',' By Martin Keown Follow @@martinkeown5 Published: 04:32 EST, 10 April 2014 | Updated: 08:08 EST, 10 April 2014 74 shares 41 View comments  TACKLE KEOWN Email your questions to Martin HERE Or send your tweets to #tacklekeown Martin Keown answered your questions once again in this week\'s brilliant #TackleKeown. The former Arsenal and England defender believes Chelsea full back Cesar Azpilicueta could be the one to stop Arjen Robben in the Champions League, after the Dutchman dumped Manchester United out of the competition on Wednesday night. Plus, with the London Marathon coming up this weekend, Martin reveals who the fittest player he ever teamed up with was. Here\'s a clue, it\'s between two Arsenal strikers who both played for France. Scroll down to find out who it is and to read all the answers from this week\'s Q&A as they came in.  Conqueror: Arjen Robben celebrates after Bayern Munich\'s Champions League victory over Manchester United  Martin Keown Host commentator Auto-update 13:30 And that\'s your lot We\'ve had some brilliant questions again today. Thanks for joining me for another #TackleKeown. I\'ll be back at the same time, same place next week for more of the same. Until then... 13:26 And today\'s final question: How do you see the Champions League semi-finals going? (From George K via email) A: I don’t think Chelsea will want to face Real Madrid until the final. They have some players who may still not see eye to eye with Jose Mourinho after his spell there and with their quality I feel they would put Chelsea out. He will probably say it would be beautiful to play his former team in the final, but it will be tough, especially as he didn’t achieve European success with them. He will not want somebody else to win that 10th European Cup for Real, he wouldn’t feel like the special one any more. I think Chelsea would love to play Atletico. Jose might feel he has their number after playing them in Spain but Diego Simeone has created some team. I watched them play Real earlier in the season and the whole match was explosive. Challenges were flying in and Simeone creates a frenzy around games. That could make it difficult for Chelsea, but I’m sure they would rather face them than Real or the mighty Bayern. Surprise package: Atletico\'s Koke (left) and David Villa celebrate the decisive goal against Barcelona 13:22 Q: Is this the end of an era for Barcelona? (From Joe in Milton Keynes) A: It feels like it, Joe. We have been saying it for a few years and I think Pep Guardiola saw the end coming. Nobody could understand why he left but he can justify it now. They were a phenomenal side but they haven’t reached those same heights again. The team hasn’t evolved, they don’t seem to have the same energy levels they had in the past and defensively they have been vulnerable for a long time. The transfer embargo will hurt them, because they need a world class central defender. It doesn’t help either that because they set the benchmark their performances have been analysed to death. Teams have figured out how to stop them. Brick wall: Lionel Messi (left) was unable to net against Atletico Madrid Main man: Pep Guardiola is currently taking Europe by storm with Bayern 13:16 Q: Simple question. City or Liverpool? (From Martin in Cheshire) A: This is such a massive game and it’s incredibly hard to predict. Liverpool are flying and Anfield has returned to its former glory. They are terrorising teams there now and if you go and beat them at home, it’s now an upset. Sunday is the kind of game that you’d love to be at live, because the atmosphere will be incredible. City will be incredibly tough opposition but with the significance of the game and the emotion of the Hillsborough anniversary, it’s important for the Liverpool players to keep their heads. But if they get a result, that will give them some extra belief that they can go on and win the title. Key man: David Silva could be crucial for Manchester City against Liverpool Leading star: Luis Suarez is the top scorer in the Premier League 13:14 Q: It\'s the marathon this weekend, who was the fittest player you played with? (From Scott F in the USA) A: I always thought Thierry Henry and Nicolas Anelka were ahead of anybody else. Henry was rapid but he could do any range and any distance. I always felt that no matter how fast or far he ran he was always holding back. I remember doing a pre-season run for Arsene Wenger when we were told to go at three-quarter pace and see how far we could go. I think Anelka arrived a day later than everybody else so didn’t have the rest of the team to pace himself, but he ended up going about a lap and a half further than everybody else and you realised just how fit he was. They both ran with such high intensity but could go for so long. At Aston Villa under Graham Taylor it was more of a map and compass pre-season. We would just run everywhere and I remember in particular Gordon Cowans playing in midfield – he was a player that could just run all day. Speed freaks: Thierry Henry (right) and Nicolas Anelka (left) were renowned for their physicality 13:10 Q: You played for them both - who do you want to finish fourth Arsenal or Everton? (From TrueBlue) A: It probably won’t surprise anyone, but I always like to see Arsenal do well. I still know a lot of the staff and some of the players there so I will always look out for them. But if anybody else were to get into that top four ahead of them I’d love it to be Everton. It really is a great club and there is something special about Merseyside. The people all passionately love their football and Everton has always prided itself on playing good football. My memories of playing there are all about trying to pass and get the ball moving through the midfield, always looking to emulate that great trio of Alan Ball, Colin Harvey and Howard Kendall. Weight of expectation: Romelu Lukaku (back) could fire Everton into the Champions League 13:07 Q: Who do you think will win the Masters? (From Shane in Texas) A: It’s a shame that Tiger is not there because you always feel lucky to get to watch one of the greats of any sport competing regularly. Without him there I’d like to see Rory McIlroy finally get it together and win, or maybe Ian Poulter. I’ve met Poulter and he is a massive Arsenal fan, but I can’t help think if golf was a team game he’d be player of the year every year! He needs to turn up this weekend and tell himself it’s a Ryder Cup and he could do it. If it’s not a European, I always think Phil Mickelson is so good to watch. I’d love to get out and play a bit more myself but I only ever manage about three or four rounds a year. Occasionally I can hit it like the pros, but inconsistency is a problem for me. I can have eight or nine good holes but never a full round! And no matter what I do, there is always a mystery shot. I can do everything the same but there is always one shot where you wonder, ‘How on earth did it end up over there?’ Eyes on the prize: Rory McIlroy (left) is out to claim the green jacket in Augusta 13:01 Q: Arjen Robben - diver or danger man? (From Suzy in Liverpool) A: A bit of both really! He still threw in two or three major dives last night and the ref just ignored him. It’s a shame he’s got that element to his game because he is a fantastic player, but it was interesting to see the ref largely ignored it. They should punish him more. When he falls over and gets a free kick, it will invariably punish the opposition because he always does it in dangerous areas. I don’t think he’d be so keen to go down in the centre circle! Looking for it? Arjen Robben goes down under a challenge from Patrice Evra 12:56 Q: Mourinho ran down the touchline after Chelsea\'s second goal, what\'s the most bonkers thing you saw Arsene Wenger do after a goal was scored? (Jeff via email) A: I haven’t seen him do too much celebrating to be honest. In our day the aggression and celebration was shown mostly by the players and he was almost apologising with his body language for our behaviour! The last few away games have been tough and he has seemed quite passive, but I think he’s worked bloody hard to keep his cool given what’s happened against Everton and Chelsea! With him, when you win he just has that beaming smile and the lack of success must be tormenting him. I know how hard he works so it would be good to see a cup win put the smile back on his face. Chaos: Jose Mourinho (right) sprinted down the touchline after Demba Ba scored Understated: Arsene Wenger (right) rarely shows his emotions. Martin says that was left to the players 12:49 Q: Fulham v Norwich feels like a Cup Final. What was the most important league game you ever played in? And who do you think will win? (From Isreal, a Fulham fan) A: The smart money goes on a draw, though I think of the two teams Fulham are perhaps more likely to win this. With three managers in a season, the players will feel like they have been in a washing machine. The same will go for Norwich this week after they sacked Chris Hughton. It can destroy hearts and minds when bosses come and go but you do get a feeling of a fresh start with new ideas. Those ideas will have to click quickly because this is a huge game. I think if Norwich get anything from the game, even with the fixtures to come I think they will be safe. In terms of my own career it’s hard to put a finger on a particular game. When I was relegated with Villa we went down against Sheffield Wednesday, but in truth we were down long before that. We still felt we had a chance but the game became desperate and disjointed. At the other end I remember a 1-0 win over Derby in 1998 when Emmanuel Petit scored. That was huge for our title run in. We also beat Bolton 1-0 away that season and Christopher Wreh scored. He’d had two shots from distance before, one went over the bar and the almost out of the ground, so when he took aim again I had to look away. But I heard the roar, knew we’d scored and we managed to hold on to a 1-0 win, even though I was sent off! End of the road: Chris Hughton was axed as Norwich manager Massive: Emmanuel Petit celebrates his crucial Arsenal goal against Derby County Back in the day: Martin, pictured in 1987, remembers his time at Aston Villa 12:42 Q: If Arsenal lose to Wigan, should Wenger go? Even you – as one of his strongest supporters – must be losing the faith. (From Gooner Ron) A: Only Arsene Wenger can answer that, Ron, and I think it’s a question to be asked if it happens. His future is in his own hands and it will be him who decides when to leave. He will not be pushed out of that club. It would be a huge blow if he didn’t win the FA Cup and you can feel the pressure and expectancy building. It almost feels for the fans that the cup has been won already but it never works like that. I know how Wenger works and he’s nothing but positive. He won’t be showing any worries or concerns, if there are any, to the players and he will be well aware of Wigan’s phenomenal second half of season and what they did to Man City. The players will know there’s a chance but you have to make sure you want it more than them. It really is an us or them situation now, whether it’s Man United, Wigan or Bayern Munich. I remember tricky FA Cup semi-finals against Wolves in 1998 and Sheffield United in 2003. Both were scrappy games but we came through them. It’s important Arsenal do the same against Wigan.  In his own hands: Only Arsene Wenger will decide when he leaves the Emirates Stadium Underdogs: Arsenal must be wary of the threat of Wigan at Wembley 12:37 Q: What is wrong with Wayne Rooney? (From Michelle Wells in Oxford) A: Is this the time of year when we start to batter Wayne? I don’t think there’s much wrong with him, Michelle, and he has had a good season. Last night he wasn’t fully fit but still doing a job for his team against one of the best sides in world football. For the first hour they were performing as well as they have done all season. United never really had enough quality possession of the ball to give to Wayne and he was surviving off scraps. He did not look quite as sharp but you never saw him complaining, he just got on with it. Lay off him! Wayne Rooney didn\'t get much service against Bayern Munich 12:30 The first question of the day: Why can’t English teams deal with Robben? You’d have used a reducer on him, surely? (From Adam in Portsmouth) Answer: I don’t think we’re alone there, Adam! He scored the winner in the 2013 Champions League final against Borussia Dortmund, so even German defences couldn’t stop him and Dortmund knocked out Real Madrid last year. He’s just a good player. The team gets enough of the ball team to feed him as regularly as he requires. Inverted wingers are in vogue and when he comes inside, it looks so easy for him on the edge of the box. It will be interesting if they draw Chelsea in the semi-final because he will be against a right-footer in Cesar Azpilicueta. That would make it much easier for him to put in a reducer! When Robben cuts in on his strong foot Azpilicueta will immediately be able to make a challenge, whereas if you’re left-footed you have to run alongside and poke it away. Though sometimes I wonder deep down how much he is annoying Pep Guardiola. Pep likes everything two touch with quick passing, whereas Robben can be a tad selfish to say the least! Top dog: Arjen Robben tormented Manchester United at the Allianz Roaring: Martin Keown believes Cesar Azpilicueta could be the man to stop Robben 12:25 Good afternoon! I\'ll be tackling all your questions in just five minutes. There\'s a lot to get through so stay tuned {\"id\":\"2601394\",\"channel\":\"/sport\",\"pageUrl\":\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\",\"status\":\"running\",\"greenBox\":{\"title\":\"TACKLE KEOWN\",\"body\":\"<ul>\\n<li>\\n<div class=\\\"eightySevenRHS\\\">\\n<div class=\\\"image-wrap\\\"><img class=\\\"blkBorder\\\" src=\\\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2013/08/13/article-2390040-0E47052E00000578-441_87x85.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Tackle Keown: Ask Martin your questions\\\" width=\\\"87\\\" height=\\\"85\\\" /></div>\\n</div>\\n<a href=\\\"mailto:tacklekeown@mailonline.co.uk\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"><font style=\\\"font-size: 1.8em;\\\">Email your questions to Martin HERE </font></a></li>\\n<li><font style=\\\"font-size: 1.8em;\\\">Or send your tweets to #tacklekeown</font> </li>\\n</ul>\"},\"modifiedOrder\":1} 0 0  More... Jones vows to return Man United to the top after disastrous season comes to a close Ramsey \'ready\' to start in the semi-final, says Wenger ahead of Wembley date What the German papers say: United woke the Bayern beast and Muller is king Moyes: Players will still want to come to Old Trafford despite no Champions League Courtois will NOT play against Chelsea if we draw them, Atletico president confirms We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title?     Share or comment on this article 74shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1047409/Martin-Keown.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Martin Keown</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@martinkeown5\">Follow @@martinkeown5</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 04:32 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 08:08 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"TACKLE KEOWN: Why Azpilicueta could be just the man to stop rampant Robben... and who was the fittest star I ever played with?\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 74</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">41</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">TACKLE KEOWN</span><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\" style=\"text-align: left; font-weight: bold;\"><ul><li> <div class=\"eightySevenRHS\"> <img alt=\"Martin Keown\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"85\" id=\"i-8dde0e13\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601394-1B84095B000005DC-161_87x85.jpg\" width=\"87\"/> </div><a href=\"mailto:tacklekeown@mailonline.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\">Email your questions to Martin HERE </font></a></li><li><font style=\" font-size: 1.8em;\">Or send your tweets to #tacklekeown</font> <br/></li></ul></div></div></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Martin Keown answered your questions once again in this week\'s brilliant #TackleKeown.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The former Arsenal and England defender believes Chelsea full back Cesar Azpilicueta could be the one to stop Arjen Robben in the Champions League, after the Dutchman dumped Manchester United out of the competition on Wednesday night.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Plus, with the London Marathon coming up this weekend, Martin reveals who the fittest player he ever teamed up with was. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Here\'s a clue, it\'s between two Arsenal strikers who both played for France.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Scroll down to find out who it is and to read all the answers from this week\'s Q&amp;A as they came in. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Conqueror: Arjen Robben celebrates after Bayern Munich\'s Champions League victory over Manchester United\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"398\" id=\"i-a8f80e6f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601394-1CF9686300000578-255_634x398.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Conqueror: Arjen Robben celebrates after Bayern Munich\'s Champions League victory over Manchester United</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\">  <div class=\"home item html_snippet_module\"> <!-- Live commentary 2 --> <div data-app-version=\"3\" data-refresh-time=\"\" id=\"lc-commentary-container\"> <div class=\"lc-host-commentator cleared\"> <ul> <li> <img src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/commentators/60x60_martin_keown.png\"/> <b>Martin Keown</b> <p>Host commentator</p> </li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-live-update\"> <span class=\"lc-manual-update\"> <span class=\"lc-commentary-newitems-info\"> <a class=\"lc-update-qty\" href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.showNewPosts()\"></a> </span> </span> <div class=\"onoffswitch\" id=\"lc-auto-refresh-switch\"> <input class=\"onoffswitch-checkbox\" id=\"lc-auto-refresh\" name=\"onoffswitch\" type=\"checkbox\"/> <label class=\"onoffswitch-label\" for=\"lc-auto-refresh\"> <div class=\"onoffswitch-inner\"></div> <div class=\"onoffswitch-switch\"></div> </label> </div> <!--[if (IE)|(lt IE 9)]> <input type=\"checkbox\" name=\"onoffswitch\" class=\"lc-IE78\" id=\"lc-auto-refresh\"> <![endif]--> <label class=\"lc-auto-update\" for=\"lc-auto-refresh\">Auto-update</label> </div> <div id=\"lc-commentary-posts\"><div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-13\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/match/60x60_crowd.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/commentators/60x60_martin_keown.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:30 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>And that\'s your lot</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p>We\'ve had some brilliant questions again today. Thanks for joining me for another #TackleKeown. I\'ll be back at the same time, same place next week for more of the same. Until then...</p> </div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'13\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'13\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-12\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/trophies/60x60_champions_league.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_chelsea.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:26 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>And today\'s final question: How do you see the Champions League semi-finals going? (From George K via email)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em>A: I don’t think Chelsea will want to face Real Madrid until the final. They have some players who may still not see eye to eye with Jose Mourinho after his spell there and with their quality I feel they would put Chelsea out. </em></p> <p><em>He will probably say it would be beautiful to play his former team in the final, but it will be tough, especially as he didn’t achieve European success with them. He will not want somebody else to win that 10th European Cup for Real, he wouldn’t feel like the special one any more. I think Chelsea would love to play Atletico. </em></p> <p><em>Jose might feel he has their number after playing them in Spain but Diego Simeone has created some team. I watched them play Real earlier in the season and the whole match was explosive. </em></p> <p><em>Challenges were flying in and Simeone creates a frenzy around games. That could make it difficult for Chelsea, but I’m sure they would rather face them than Real or the mighty Bayern.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132778110_lc_galleryImage_MADRID_SPAIN_APRIL_09_Kok.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Surprise package: Atletico\'s Koke (left) and David Villa celebrate the decisive goal against Barcelona</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'12\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'12\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-11\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/champ_league/60x60_barcelona.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/flags/60x60_spain.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:22 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Is this the end of an era for Barcelona? (From Joe in Milton Keynes)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: It feels like it, Joe. We have been saying it for a few years and I think Pep Guardiola saw the end coming. Nobody could understand why he left but he can justify it now. </em></p> <p><em>They were a phenomenal side but they haven’t reached those same heights again. The team hasn’t evolved, they don’t seem to have the same energy levels they had in the past and defensively they have been vulnerable for a long time. </em></p> <p><em>The transfer embargo will hurt them, because they need a world class central defender. It doesn’t help either that because they set the benchmark their performances have been analysed to death. Teams have figured out how to stop them.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132523942_lc_galleryImage_Barcelona_s_Lionel_Messi_.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Brick wall: Lionel Messi (left) was unable to net against Atletico Madrid</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132607202_lc_galleryImage_TOPSHOTS_Bayern_Munich_s_.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Main man: Pep Guardiola is currently taking Europe by storm with Bayern</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'11\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'11\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-10\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_man_city.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_liverpool.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:16 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Simple question. City or Liverpool? (From Martin in Cheshire)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: This is such a massive game and it’s incredibly hard to predict. Liverpool are flying and Anfield has returned to its former glory. </em></p> <p><em>They are terrorising teams there now and if you go and beat them at home, it’s now an upset. Sunday is the kind of game that you’d love to be at live, because the atmosphere will be incredible. </em></p> <p><em>City will be incredibly tough opposition but with the significance of the game and the emotion of the Hillsborough anniversary, it’s important for the Liverpool players to keep their heads. </em></p> <p><em>But if they get a result, that will give them some extra belief that they can go on and win the title.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132153817_lc_galleryImage_Manchester_City_s_David_S.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Key man: David Silva could be crucial for Manchester City against Liverpool</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132256451_lc_galleryImage_LIVERPOOL_ENGLAND_MARCH_3.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Leading star: Luis Suarez is the top scorer in the Premier League</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'10\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'10\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-9\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_arsenal.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/flags/60x60_france.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:14 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: It\'s the marathon this weekend, who was the fittest player you played with? (From Scott F in the USA)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: I always thought Thierry Henry and Nicolas Anelka were ahead of anybody else. Henry was rapid but he could do any range and any distance. I always felt that no matter how fast or far he ran he was always holding back. </em></p> <p><em>I remember doing a pre-season run for Arsene Wenger when we were told to go at three-quarter pace and see how far we could go. I think Anelka arrived a day later than everybody else so didn’t have the rest of the team to pace himself, but he ended up going about a lap and a half further than everybody else and you realised just how fit he was</em><em>.</em></p> <p><em> They both ran with such high intensity but could go for so long. At Aston Villa under Graham Taylor it was more of a map and compass pre-season. We would just run everywhere and I remember in particular Gordon Cowans playing in midfield – he was a player that could just run all day.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397132015546_lc_galleryImage_ANELKA_HENRY_France_s_soc.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Speed freaks: Thierry Henry (right) and Nicolas Anelka (left) were renowned for their physicality</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'9\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'9\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-8\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_everton.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_arsenal.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:10 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: You played for them both - who do you want to finish fourth Arsenal or Everton? (From TrueBlue)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: It probably won’t surprise anyone, but I always like to see Arsenal do well. I still know a lot of the staff and some of the players there so I will always look out for them. But if anybody else were to get into that top four ahead of them I’d love it to be Everton. </em></p> <p><em>It really is a great club and there is something special about Merseyside. The people all passionately love their football and Everton has always prided itself on playing good football. </em></p> <p><em>My memories of playing there are all about trying to pass and get the ball moving through the midfield, always looking to emulate that great trio of Alan Ball, Colin Harvey and Howard Kendall.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397131790190_lc_galleryImage_Everton_s_Sylvain_Distin_.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Weight of expectation: Romelu Lukaku (back) could fire Everton into the Champions League</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'8\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'8\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-7\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:07 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Who do you think will win the Masters? (From Shane in Texas)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: It’s a shame that Tiger is not there because you always feel lucky to get to watch one of the greats of any sport competing regularly. </em></p> <p><em>Without him there I’d like to see Rory McIlroy finally get it together and win, or maybe Ian Poulter. I’ve met Poulter and he is a massive Arsenal fan, but I can’t help think if golf was a team game he’d be player of the year every year! </em></p> <p><em>He needs to turn up this weekend and tell himself it’s a Ryder Cup and he could do it. If it’s not a European, I always think Phil Mickelson is so good to watch. I’d love to get out and play a bit more myself but I only ever manage about three or four rounds a year.</em></p> <p><em> Occasionally I can hit it like the pros, but inconsistency is a problem for me. I can have eight or nine good holes but never a full round! And no matter what I do, there is always a mystery shot. I can do everything the same but there is always one shot where you wonder, ‘How on earth did it end up over there?’</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397131635886_lc_galleryImage_epa04161039_Carolina_Wozn.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Eyes on the prize: Rory McIlroy (left) is out to claim the green jacket in Augusta</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'7\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'7\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-6\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/champ_league/60x60_bayern_munich.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_man_utd.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">13:01 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Arjen Robben - diver or danger man? (From Suzy in Liverpool)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: A bit of both really! He still threw in two or three major dives last night and the ref just ignored him. It’s a shame he’s got that element to his game because he is a fantastic player, but it was interesting to see the ref largely ignored it. </em></p> <p><em>They should punish him more. When he falls over and gets a free kick, it will invariably punish the opposition because he always does it in dangerous areas. I don’t think he’d be so keen to go down in the centre circle!</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397131218894_lc_galleryImage_Manchester_United_s_Engli.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Looking for it? Arjen Robben goes down under a challenge from Patrice Evra</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'6\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'6\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-5\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_chelsea.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_arsenal.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:56 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Mourinho ran down the touchline after Chelsea\'s second goal, what\'s the most bonkers thing you saw Arsene Wenger do after a goal was scored? (Jeff via email)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: I haven’t seen him do too much celebrating to be honest. In our day the aggression and celebration was shown mostly by the players and he was almost apologising with his body language for our behaviour! </em></p> <p><em>The last few away games have been tough and he has seemed quite passive, but I think he’s worked bloody hard to keep his cool given what’s happened against Everton and Chelsea! </em></p> <p><em>With him, when you win he just has that beaming smile and the lack of success must be tormenting him. </em></p> <p><em>I know how hard he works so it would be good to see a cup win put the smile back on his face.</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130970383_lc_galleryImage_SPT_GCK_080414_Football_C.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Chaos: Jose Mourinho (right) sprinted down the touchline after Demba Ba scored</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397131014274_lc_galleryImage_Arsenal_v_AS_Roma_pre_sea.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Understated: Arsene Wenger (right) rarely shows his emotions. Martin says that was left to the players</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'5\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'5\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-4\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_fulham.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_norwich.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:49 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: Fulham v Norwich feels like a Cup Final. What was the most important league game you ever played in? And who do you think will win? (From Isreal, a Fulham fan)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: The smart money goes on a draw, though I think of the two teams Fulham are perhaps more likely to win this. With three managers in a season, the players will feel like they have been in a washing machine. </em></p> <p><em>The same will go for Norwich this week after they sacked Chris Hughton. It can destroy hearts and minds when bosses come and go but you do get a feeling of a fresh start with new ideas. Those ideas will have to click quickly because this is a huge game. </em></p> <p><em>I think if Norwich get anything from the game, even with the fixtures to come I think they will be safe. In terms of my own career it’s hard to put a finger on a particular game. </em></p> <p><em>When I was relegated with Villa we went down against Sheffield Wednesday, but in truth we were down long before that. We still felt we had a chance but the game became desperate and disjointed.</em></p> <p><em> At the other end I remember a 1-0 win over Derby in 1998 when Emmanuel Petit scored. That was huge for our title run in. We also beat Bolton 1-0 away that season and Christopher Wreh scored. He’d had two shots from distance before, one went over the bar and the almost out of the ground, so when he took aim again I had to look away. </em></p> <p><em>But I heard the roar, knew we’d scored and we managed to hold on to a 1-0 win, even though I was sent off!</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130573949_lc_galleryImage_NORWICH_ENGLAND_MARCH_22_.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">End of the road: Chris Hughton was axed as Norwich manager</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130683404_lc_galleryImage_Arsenal_v_Derby_County_Pr.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Massive: Emmanuel Petit celebrates his crucial Arsenal goal against Derby County</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130724181_lc_galleryImage__THIS_IMAGE_HAS_NOT_YET_B.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Back in the day: Martin, pictured in 1987, remembers his time at Aston Villa</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'4\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'4\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-3\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_arsenal.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/trophies/60x60_fa_cup.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:42 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: If Arsenal lose to Wigan, should Wenger go? Even you – as one of his strongest supporters – must be losing the faith. (From Gooner Ron)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: Only Arsene Wenger can answer that, Ron, and I think it’s a question to be asked if it happens. His future is in his own hands and it will be him who decides when to leave. </em></p> <p><em>He will not be pushed out of that club. It would be a huge blow if he didn’t win the FA Cup and you can feel the pressure and expectancy building. It almost feels for the fans that the cup has been won already but it never works like that. </em></p> <p><em>I know how Wenger works and he’s nothing but positive. He won’t be showing any worries or concerns, if there are any, to the players and he will be well aware of Wigan’s phenomenal second half of season and what they did to Man City. </em></p> <p><em>The players will know there’s a chance but you have to make sure you want it more than them. </em></p> <p><em>It really is an us or them situation now, whether it’s Man United, Wigan or Bayern Munich. I remember tricky FA Cup semi-finals against Wolves in 1998 and Sheffield United in 2003. Both were scrappy games but we came through them. It’s important Arsenal do the same against Wigan. </em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130090504_lc_galleryImage_File_photo_dated_29_03_20.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">In his own hands: Only Arsene Wenger will decide when he leaves the Emirates Stadium</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397130246699_lc_galleryImage_Wigan_s_Crainey_celebrate.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Underdogs: Arsenal must be wary of the threat of Wigan at Wembley</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'3\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'3\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-2\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_man_utd.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/trophies/60x60_champions_league.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:37 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Q: What is wrong with Wayne Rooney? (From Michelle Wells in Oxford)</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>A</strong>: Is this the time of year when we start to batter Wayne? I don’t think there’s much wrong with him, Michelle, and he has had a good season. </em></p> <p><em>Last night he wasn’t fully fit but still doing a job for his team against one of the best sides in world football. For the first hour they were performing as well as they have done all season. </em></p> <p><em>United never really had enough quality possession of the ball to give to Wayne and he was surviving off scraps. He did not look quite as sharp but you never saw him complaining, he just got on with it. </em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397129677994_lc_galleryImage_MUNICH_GERMANY_APRIL_09_W.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Lay off him! Wayne Rooney didn\'t get much service against Bayern Munich</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'2\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'2\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-1\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/teams/60x60_man_utd.png\"/> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/champ_league/60x60_bayern_munich.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:30 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <h4> <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601106/Can-shattered-Rooney-regain-old-magic-United-striker-struggles-Bayern-defeat.html\" target=\"_blank\"><b>The first question of the day: Why can’t English teams deal with Robben? You’d have used a reducer on him, surely? (From Adam in Portsmouth)</b></a> </h4> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p><em><strong>Answer</strong>: I don’t think we’re alone there, Adam! He scored the winner in the 2013 Champions League final against Borussia Dortmund, so even German defences couldn’t stop him and Dortmund knocked out Real Madrid last year. </em></p> <p><em>He’s just a good player. The team gets enough of the ball team to feed him as regularly as he requires. Inverted wingers are in vogue and when he comes inside, it looks so easy for him on the edge of the box. </em></p> <p><em>It will be interesting if they draw Chelsea in the semi-final because he will be against a right-footer in Cesar Azpilicueta. That would make it much easier for him to put in a reducer! </em></p> <p><em>When Robben cuts in on his strong foot Azpilicueta will immediately be able to make a challenge, whereas if you’re left-footed you have to run alongside and poke it away.</em></p> <p><em>Though sometimes I wonder deep down how much he is annoying Pep Guardiola. Pep likes everything two touch with quick passing, whereas Robben can be a tad selfish to say the least!</em></p> </div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397129308134_lc_galleryImage_Bayern_s_Arjen_Robben_cel.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Top dog: Arjen Robben tormented Manchester United at the Allianz</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <img class=\"lc-post-image\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/1397129476511_lc_galleryImage_LONDON_ENGLAND_APRIL_08_C.JPG\"/> <b class=\"lc-image-caption\">Roaring: Martin Keown believes Cesar Azpilicueta could be the man to stop Robben</b> <div class=\"lc-clear\"></div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'1\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'1\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> <div class=\"lc-commentary-post cleared\" id=\"lc-id-0\"> <div class=\"lc-icons\"> <img class=\"lc-icon\" src=\"http://i.mol.im/i/furniture/live_commentary/football_icons/match/60x60_crowd.png\"/> <div class=\"lc-post-time\">12:25 </div> </div> <div class=\"lc-title-container\"> <span><b>Good afternoon!</b></span> </div> <div class=\"lc-post-body\"> <p>I\'ll be tackling all your questions in just five minutes. There\'s a lot to get through so stay tuned</p> </div> <ul class=\"lc-social\"> <li class=\"lc-facebook\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToFB, \'0\', \'facebook\')\"></span></li> <li class=\"lc-twitter\"><span onclick=\"window.LiveCommentary.socialShare(postToTWTTR, \'0\', \'twitter\', window.twitterVia)\"></span></li> </ul> </div> </div> <span id=\"lc-metadata\" style=\"display:none\">{\"id\":\"2601394\",\"channel\":\"/sport\",\"pageUrl\":\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\",\"status\":\"running\",\"greenBox\":{\"title\":\"TACKLE KEOWN\",\"body\":\"&lt;ul&gt;\\n&lt;li&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"eightySevenRHS\\\"&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"image-wrap\\\"&gt;&lt;img class=\\\"blkBorder\\\" src=\\\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2013/08/13/article-2390040-0E47052E00000578-441_87x85.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Tackle Keown: Ask Martin your questions\\\" width=\\\"87\\\" height=\\\"85\\\" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;a href=\\\"mailto:tacklekeown@mailonline.co.uk\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"&gt;&lt;font style=\\\"font-size: 1.8em;\\\"&gt;Email your questions to Martin HERE &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;font style=\\\"font-size: 1.8em;\\\"&gt;Or send your tweets to #tacklekeown&lt;/font&gt; &lt;/li&gt;\\n&lt;/ul&gt;\"},\"modifiedOrder\":1}</span> <span id=\"lc-latest-modification-time\" style=\"display:none\">0</span> <span id=\"lc-latest-modification-order\" style=\"display:none\">0</span> <link href=\"http://livecommentary.dailymail.co.uk/apps/livecommentary_public/css/commentary.css?cb=1395314270\" rel=\"stylesheet\"/> <link href=\"http://livecommentary.dailymail.co.uk/apps/livecommentary_public/css/sport/commentary.css?cb=1395314270\" rel=\"stylesheet\"/> </div> <!-- FOR IE7 and below - must include before JSON.parse --> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601406/Phil-Jones-vows-return-Manchester-United-disastrous-season-comes-close.html\"> Jones vows to return Man United to the top after disastrous season comes to a close</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601317/Aaron-Ramsey-ready-start-semi-final-says-Arsene-Wenger-ahead-Wembley-date.html\"> Ramsey \'ready\' to start in the semi-final, says Wenger ahead of Wembley date</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601345/What-German-papers-say-United-woke-Bayern-beast-Muller-king.html\"> What the German papers say: United woke the Bayern beast and Muller is king</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601290/David-Moyes-Players-want-come-Old-Trafford-despite-no-Champions-League.html\"> Moyes: Players will still want to come to Old Trafford despite no Champions League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601145/Thibaut-Courtois-not-play-against-Chelsea-Atletico-Madrid.html\"> Courtois will NOT play against Chelsea if we draw them, Atletico president confirms</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601064/Were-final-four-whos-going-clinch-Champions-League-title.html\"> We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title?</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/TACKLE-KEOWN-LIVE-English-teams-cope-Arjen-Robben.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"TACKLE KEOWN: Why Azpilicueta could be just the man to stop rampant Robben... and who was the fittest star I ever played with?\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601394/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">74</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601394-1CFF637800000578-688_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:50','2014-04-10 15:08:58'),(105,'ce26f244f111dbb58f8c1e68e8a7c343df364b04d4dbded9807dd110271ebbbe','dailymail',NULL,'Arjen Robben is skinny, arrogant and loves to dive but should be recognised','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html',' By Craig Hope Follow @@CraigHope01 Published: 04:58 EST, 10 April 2014 | Updated: 07:31 EST, 10 April 2014 110 shares 171 View comments  He scores goals, he creates them, he is exciting to watch and is among the game\'s most decorated players – yet still we do not celebrate Arjen Robben as one of Europe\'s greatest. Perhaps it\'s the diving, his appetite for deception leaving a sour taste. Perhaps it\'s his self-assured nature, a confidence which borders on arrogance. Perhaps it\'s because he is so successful, winning major titles in four European countries and a Champions League. But it\'s about time we recognised Robben for the terrorising talent that he is – just ask Manchester United. VIDEO: Scroll down to watch the fall and falls of Arjen Robben  Main man: Arjen Robben was among the scorers as Bayern Munich knocked Manchester United out of Europe Not much to him: Robben may be slight but he has been a constant thorn in the side of Europe\'s top teams  Robben at a glanceAge: 30Position: ForwardClub career2000–2002     Groningen 28 app/10 goals2002–2004     PSV 70/222004–2007     Chelsea 105/192007–2009     Real Madrid  65/132009–             Bayern Munich 157/87Robben has directly contributed to eight of Bayern’s 21 goals in the Champions League this season with four goals and four assistsInternational careerHolland 73 apps/22 goals The winger was at his unforgiving finest against David Moyes\' men on Wednesday night, seizing upon the slightest slip to turn the tie in favour of his side, Bayern Munich. Thanks to Robben, the Bavarians are through to the last four, on course to become the first team in history to defend the Champions League. His killer contributions against United were separated by just eight minutes. First, with the contest at 1-1, he stole a yard to serve up a teasing delivery which was poked home by team-mate Thomas Muller. Still, though, the visitors needed just one goal to progress. Enter Arjen. Gliding into the penalty area in trademark fashion, United knew what was coming as he fashioned an opening for his lethal left. But despite knowledge of such intent they were powerless to prevent Robben taking aim for the bottom corner and finding it, albeit via a deflection off Nemanja Vidic. Game over. reputation taking a dive: Robben has been much criticised for his antics, including his tendency to go to ground Come on: Robben won a contentious penalty against Arsenal in the Champions League this season Debate: Robben and Wayne Rooney have a disagreement during the second leg at the Allianz Arena  More... Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Can shattered Rooney regain his old magic? United striker struggles in Bayern defeat \'Kings of the Cup\'... Bayern fans reveal impressive mosaic as they chase second straight Champions League triumph We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title? Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night The Holland winger was, deservedly, man-of-the-match, just as he was 11 months ago on these shores as he scored the goal which sealed Bayern\'s status as the continent\'s No 1, netting the winner in the Champions League final against Borussia Dortmund at Wembley. It was his first European crown, some 13 years after making his debut as a 16-year-old for FC Groningen in the Eredivisie. It is a career which has taken in PSV, Chelsea, Real Madrid and, for the past five years, Bayern. Arguably, though, he has never been more dangerous, shown by his return of more than one goal every two games last season. Indeed, his career stats are better than one in three, 152 from 423 matches. Then there are his assists, 14 this season already surpassing last year\'s total of 12. The fall and falls of Robben  Back in the day: Robben won the Community Shield, Premier League and League Cup with Chelsea   Crowning glory: Robben celebrates winning the Champions League with Bayern Munich last season Pulling the trigger: Robben scored the winning goal against Borussia Dortmund to clinch the trophy Robben scores with sublime lob as Bayern defeat Dortmund 3-0  With the benefit of age – he turned 30 this year – has Robben matured into a player capable of marrying his goals and guile like never before? He is already a World Cup runner-up but the likelihood is he won\'t be talked of as one of the stars-in-waiting ahead of this summer\'s contest. Rather, it will be the likes of Wayne Rooney – who he outclassed on Wednesday – who will be the subject of such eulogy. By that point Robben could be heading to Brazil with another Champions League winner\'s medal to add to his already glistening collection of silverware. With the flying Dutchman in this form you might just fancy Holland to go one better than they did in South Africa four years ago.  Easy does it: Robben helped Bayern romp to the Bundesliga title this season  Arjen Robben\'s hat-trick for Bayern Munich against Schalke Laden: Robben won La Liga with Real Madrid (left) and shot to prominence as a youngster with PSV (right) Arjen Robben extends Bayern Munich contract to 2017    More... Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Can shattered Rooney regain his old magic? United striker struggles in Bayern defeat \'Kings of the Cup\'... Bayern fans reveal impressive mosaic as they chase second straight Champions League triumph We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title? Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night     Share or comment on this article 110shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=Craig+Hope\" rel=\"nofollow\">Craig Hope</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@CraigHope01\">Follow @@CraigHope01</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 04:58 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 07:31 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Robben is skinny, arrogant and loves to dive, but it\'s about time we recognised his terrorising talent\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 110</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">171</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He scores goals, he creates them, he is exciting to watch and is among the game\'s most decorated players – yet still we do not celebrate Arjen Robben as one of Europe\'s greatest.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Perhaps it\'s the diving, his appetite for deception leaving a sour taste. Perhaps it\'s his self-assured nature, a confidence which borders on arrogance. Perhaps it\'s because he is so successful, winning major titles in four European countries and a Champions League.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">But it\'s about time we recognised Robben for the terrorising talent that he is – just ask Manchester United.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b><font color=\"FFFFFF\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(12, 172, 12);\">VIDEO:</span></font> Scroll down to watch the fall and falls of Arjen Robben</b><br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Main man: Arjen Robben was among the scorers as Bayern Munich knocked Manchester United out of Europe\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"410\" id=\"i-5da40d39\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CF96F7300000578-276_634x410.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Main man: Arjen Robben was among the scorers as Bayern Munich knocked Manchester United out of Europe</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Bayern Munich\'s Dutch midfielder Arjen Robben\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5ceb0d32\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CF966B400000578-426_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Arjen Robben celebrates victory over Manchester United\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-514e0d04\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CF968B700000578-63_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Not much to him: Robben may be slight but he has been a constant thorn in the side of Europe\'s top teams<br/></p></div> <p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>Robben at a glance</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>Age</b>: 30</font></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>Position: </b>Forward<br/></font></p><p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Club career</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">2000–2002     <b>Groningen </b>28 app/10 goals<br/>2002–2004     <b>PSV </b>70/22<br/>2004–2007     <b>Chelsea </b>105/19<br/>2007–2009     <b>Real Madrid  </b>65/13<br/>2009–             <b>Bayern Munich</b> 157/87</font></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Robben has directly contributed to eight of Bayern’s 21 goals in the Champions League this season with four goals and four assists</font></p><p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">International career</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>Holland </b>73 apps/22 goals<br/></font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The winger was at his unforgiving finest against David Moyes\' men on Wednesday night, seizing upon the slightest slip to turn the tie in favour of his side, Bayern Munich.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Thanks to Robben, the Bavarians are through to the last four, on course to become the first team in history to defend the Champions League.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">His killer contributions against United were separated by just eight minutes. First, with the contest at 1-1, he stole a yard to serve up a teasing delivery which was poked home by team-mate Thomas Muller.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Still, though, the visitors needed just one goal to progress. Enter Arjen. Gliding into the penalty area in trademark fashion, United knew what was coming as he fashioned an opening for his lethal left. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">But despite knowledge of such intent they were powerless to prevent Robben taking aim for the bottom corner and finding it, albeit via a deflection off Nemanja Vidic. Game over.</font></p>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"reputation taking a dive: Robben has been much criticised for his antics, including his tendency to go to ground\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"453\" id=\"i-5b800d2a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1C344C4E00000578-160_634x453.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">reputation taking a dive: Robben has been much criticised for his antics, including his tendency to go to ground</p> </div><p> </p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Come on: Robben won a contentious penalty against Arsenal in the Champions League this season\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"406\" id=\"i-5b690d2a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1C344C5A00000578-336_634x406.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Come on: Robben won a contentious penalty against Arsenal in the Champions League this season</p> </div><p> </p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Debate: Robben and Wayne Rooney have a disagreement during the second leg at the Allianz Arena\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"428\" id=\"i-5e4c0d45\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CF99A0C00000578-821_634x428.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Debate: Robben and Wayne Rooney have a disagreement during the second leg at the Allianz Arena</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601106/Can-shattered-Rooney-regain-old-magic-United-striker-struggles-Bayern-defeat.html\"> Can shattered Rooney regain his old magic? United striker struggles in Bayern defeat</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601066/Bayern-Munich-fans-reveal-impressive-Kings-Cup-mosaic.html\"> \'Kings of the Cup\'... Bayern fans reveal impressive mosaic as they chase second straight Champions League triumph</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601064/Were-final-four-whos-going-clinch-Champions-League-title.html\"> We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601037/Moyes-trips-learning-curve-United-crash-Champions-League.html\"> Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601023/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Manchester-United-4-2-agg-Player-ratings.html\"> Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Holland winger was, deservedly, man-of-the-match, just as he was 11 months ago on these shores as he scored the goal which sealed Bayern\'s status as the continent\'s No 1, netting the winner in the Champions League final against Borussia Dortmund at Wembley.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It was his first European crown, some 13 years after making his debut as a 16-year-old for FC Groningen in the Eredivisie. It is a career which has taken in PSV, Chelsea, Real Madrid and, for the past five years, Bayern.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Arguably, though, he has never been more dangerous, shown by his return of more than one goal every two games last season.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Indeed, his career stats are better than one in three, 152 from 423 matches. Then there are his assists, 14 this season already surpassing last year\'s total of 12. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\">  <a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3417085460001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">The fall and falls of Robben</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/video-undefined-1CBD55B200000578-652_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Back in the day: Robben won the Community Shield, Premier League and League Cup with Chelsea\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"404\" id=\"i-57210cfe\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-0089365800000514-481_634x404.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Back in the day: Robben won the Community Shield, Premier League and League Cup with Chelsea</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Robben celebrates winning the Champions League with Bayern Munich last year\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-60470d5e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-19FFD797000005DC-749_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Arjen Robben of Bayern Munich celebrates with the trophy after victory in the UEFA Champions League final\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-57e30d03\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-076304D900000514-542_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Crowning glory: Robben celebrates winning the Champions League with Bayern Munich last season<br/></p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Pulling the trigger: Robben scored the winning goal against Borussia Dortmund to clinch the trophy\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"363\" id=\"i-62cd0d77\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-19FFBF9F000005DC-406_634x363.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Pulling the trigger: Robben scored the winning goal against Borussia Dortmund to clinch the trophy</p><div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-2864518768001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Robben scores with sublime lob as Bayern defeat Dortmund 3-0</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2013/11/25/video-undefined-19A1B54400000578-594_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div><p> </p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">With the benefit of age – he turned 30 this year – has Robben matured into a player capable of marrying his goals and guile like never before?</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He is already a World Cup runner-up but the likelihood is he won\'t be talked of as one of the stars-in-waiting ahead of this summer\'s contest. Rather, it will be the likes of Wayne Rooney – who he outclassed on Wednesday – who will be the subject of such eulogy.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">By that point Robben could be heading to Brazil with another Champions League winner\'s medal to add to his already glistening collection of silverware.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">With the flying Dutchman in this form you might just fancy Holland to go one better than they did in South Africa four years ago.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Easy does it: Robben helped Bayern romp to the Bundesliga title this season\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"416\" id=\"i-5ee90d4a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CFD73C800000578-943_634x416.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Easy does it: Robben helped Bayern romp to the Bundesliga title this season  </p><div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3329137969001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Arjen Robben\'s hat-trick for Bayern Munich against Schalke</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/12/video-undefined-1C37CD1700000578-537_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Arjen Robben, Ruud van Nistelrooy and Wesley Sneijder of Real Madrid hold aloft the La Liga trophy\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5e800d40\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CFD746F00000578-181_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"PSV Eindhoven\'s Arjen Robben with his \'Johan Cruyff Award\' given to him for being the best young player in the Dutch Eredivisie\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5c6f0d2a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CFD741700000578-602_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Laden: Robben won La Liga with Real Madrid (left) and shot to prominence as a youngster with PSV (right)<br/></p><div class=\"moduleFull\"> <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3367430866001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Arjen Robben extends Bayern Munich contract to 2017</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/20/video-undefined-1C731D8D00000578-944_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601106/Can-shattered-Rooney-regain-old-magic-United-striker-struggles-Bayern-defeat.html\"> Can shattered Rooney regain his old magic? United striker struggles in Bayern defeat</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601066/Bayern-Munich-fans-reveal-impressive-Kings-Cup-mosaic.html\"> \'Kings of the Cup\'... Bayern fans reveal impressive mosaic as they chase second straight Champions League triumph</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601064/Were-final-four-whos-going-clinch-Champions-League-title.html\"> We\'re down to the final four... but who\'s going to clinch the Champions League title?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601037/Moyes-trips-learning-curve-United-crash-Champions-League.html\"> Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601023/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Manchester-United-4-2-agg-Player-ratings.html\"> Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><br/></p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/Robben-skinny-arrogant-loves-dive-recognised.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Robben is skinny, arrogant and loves to dive, but it\'s about time we recognised his terrorising talent\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601416/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">110</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-0-1CFD558700000578-227_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:51','2014-04-10 14:31:02'),(106,'9daf707f5bf1a22b72bbdad2caa523627317735ea06c4663438f2ceee3f9c32b','dailymail',NULL,'Jurgen Klopp should swap Borussia Dortmund for the Premier League','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html',' By Adam Shergold Follow @@adamjshergold Published: 05:02 EST, 10 April 2014 | Updated: 06:39 EST, 10 April 2014 205 shares 111 View comments  As Marco Reus slid the ball into the unguarded net, the Westfalenstadion exploded and so did the manager. In a fabulously spontaneous expression of joy, Jurgen Klopp bounded across his technical area and then leapt a good five foot into the air with fists pumping and legs kicking. It was an exuberant celebration, yet at the same time characteristic of a manager who has been a breath of fresh air for not only Borussia Dortmund but wider German and European football. Is Klopp bringing his hip hop to England? Taking off: Klopp sprinted down the touchline after Dortmund scored their winner against Wolfsburg on Saturday and capped it off with a terrific leap Kapow! Klopp soars through the air with arms punching and legs kicking A reason to celebrate: Klopp was marking a winning goal by Marco Reus that saw Dortmund beat Wolfsburg   England calling: Klopp would attract a lot of interest from Premier League clubs if he decided to leave Borussia Dortmund and take up a new challenge  After all, why celebrate with modesty and reserve when you can soar through the air like Michael Jordan or a ninja from Street Fighter? The goal turned out to be Dortmund\'s winner against Wolfsburg and strengthened their hold on second place in the Bundesliga. But after Real Madrid put paid to their hopes of a second consecutive Champions League final three days later, that runners-up spot is about the best Klopp and Dortmund can hope for. The golden age brought about by Klopp has passed almost as quickly as it came. Bayern Munich have restored the natural order. It\'s time for Klopp to take another great leap. Jose Mourinho memorably sprinted down a touchline too. That was back in 2004, when his Porto side stunned Manchester United in the Champions League at Old Trafford.  End of the line: Klopp has won two Bundesliga titles with Dortmund but they now trail Bayern by a long way   Far out in front: Bayern Munich are currently 20 points clear of Dortmund at the top of the Bundesliga, having already secured the title  Jurgen Klopp takes off like Michael Jordan celebrating Reus goal   Jumping for joy: Jose Mourinho lit up the Premier League after making this famous touchline dash  KLOPP\'S RECORD AS A PLAYERMainz (1989-2001) 337 league games, 52 goalsAS A MANAGERMainz (February 2001-June 2008)Games 270 Won 109 Drawn 78 Lost 83 (40.37 per cent win record)Borussia Dortmund (July 2008-)Games 262 Won 152 Drawn 59 Lost 51(58.02 per cent win record) Within another 12 months, he was lighting up the Premier League with Chelsea. Mourinho broke the mould, he was smart, suave, supercilious and ultimately successful. Now it\'s time for cool and colourful Klopp to take the leap and come to England. The Premier League would be a far more interesting place with him. He would break the mould too. The marketplace is bustling if Klopp should choose to have a stroll through. There might be changes afoot at Arsenal or Manchester United. He might fancy a challenge like Aston Villa, West Ham or West Bromwich. What\'s sure is that a fair proportion of the Premier League clubs would want to hire a man who guided an unfancied and under-performing Dortmund side to successive Bundesliga titles and the final of the European Cup. He would be a crowd pleaser as well. Touchline long jump aside, his interviews are rarely boring and his English is already very good.  Deep in thought: Klopp pictured during his press conference ahead of this week\'s Champions League second leg against Real Madrid   Falling short: Klopp remonstrates with the officials after Dortmund lost 2-0 to Real Madrid, exiting the Champions League 3-2 on aggregate   Dejection: Kevin Grosskreutz reacts after Dortmund\'s exit  KLOPP\'S TROPHY CABINET BORUSSIA DORTMUNDBundesliga 2010-2011, 2011-2012DFB-Pokal 2011-2012DFL-Supercup 2013UEFA Champions League runner-up 2012-2013INDIVIDUALGerman Manager of the Year 2011,2012FIFA World Coach of the Year runner-up 2013 Klopp compares his team\'s style on the pitch to thrash metal - offensive, high-intensity and high-tempo. You would certainly get good value for your season ticket, as Dortmund\'s yellow walls have for the last five years. The 46-year-old is still, comparatively, a managerial novice but you sense he\'s well equipped for the rigours of the Premier League, which we know can be unforgiving. There\'s also the sense that Klopp has done all he can for Dortmund. With their wonderful 80,000-capacity arena and legions of fans, Dortmund had been sleeping giants since the late 1990s and endured their share of financial hardships. Klopp roused and reinvigorated them, restoring pride and smashing the domestic hegemony of rivals Bayern. Supporting and watching BVB was suddenly the height of chic, the hipster\'s choice. They reached the high water mark in beating Real Madrid 4-1 before an ecstatic Westfalenstadion this time last year, with Robert Lewandowski scoring all four - yet they ended the season without a trophy. Dortmund manager Jurgen Klopp sent off for incredible rage at...  Last gasp: Arjen Robben scored the winner as Bayern beat Borussia 2-1 in the 2013 Champions League final at Wembley   Missing out: Klopp consoles Kevin Grosskreutz after Dortmund\'s best season finished without silverware Familiar sight: Bayern parade the Champions League trophy after their triumph at Wembley  More... Dortmund 2-0 Real Madrid (agg 2-3): Reus double not quite enough as Ronaldo-less Madrid sneak through by finest margin Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Messi blamed for Barcelona\'s defeat after running just 1 mile more than the KEEPER The Happy One? After Mourinho\'s moans, the Premier League are to move Chelsea\'s fixtures to aid their European quest Bale to pen six-year adidas contract extension, joining the elite with £20m jackpot deal At Wembley, Arjen Robben\'s late winner for Bayern, sealing the Treble, left Klopp and co heart-broken. Mario Gotze defected to Bavaria and Lewandowski is about to follow. Realistically, Klopp has taken them as far as he can. Just look at the 20-point gulf to Bayern in the Bundesliga table. Bayern were crowned champions on March 25, an embarrassingly early title conclusion for a league that wins many plaudits for the effective and fan-friendly way in which things are done. But what league is competitive when the best team can poach the best two players of the side in second place? And unfortunately, that could be just the beginning for Borussia as wealthy, carnivorous clubs around Europe strip them of their best players. There is constant speculation that the likes of Marco Reus, Ilkay Gundogan and Sven Bender are about to move, perhaps to the Premier League.  Open to offers: Marco Reus could be the next of Dortmund\'s golden generation to leave   Until next year: The next time Gareth Bale faces Robert Lewandowski, the Pole will be in Bayern colours   Incoming: Dortmund have signed the Hertha Berlin forward Adrian Ramos to replace Lewandowski  This phenomenally strong and entertaining side, who have scaled such great heights together, will be dismantled. All good things must pass. On Wednesday, Borussia announced the signing of Hertha Berlin\'s Colombian striker Adrian Ramos. He\'s undoubtedly prolific but bringing in a 28-year-old to replace Lewandowski doesn\'t inspire confidence in a long-term plan. It\'s time for Klopp to make a clean break of it, enjoy a change of scenery and begin a new project in the Premier League. Like Mourinho, we\'ll quickly grow to love him. Or at least grudgingly admire his success.  More... Dortmund 2-0 Real Madrid (agg 2-3): Reus double not quite enough as Ronaldo-less Madrid sneak through by finest margin Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Messi blamed for Barcelona\'s defeat after running just 1 mile more than the KEEPER The Happy One? After Mourinho\'s moans, the Premier League are to move Chelsea\'s fixtures to aid their European quest Bale to pen six-year adidas contract extension, joining the elite with £20m jackpot deal  Share or comment on this article 205shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=Adam+Shergold\" rel=\"nofollow\">Adam Shergold</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@adamjshergold\">Follow @@adamjshergold</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 05:02 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 06:39 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Klopp has taken Borussia Dortmund as far as he can... it\'s time the colourful German took a leap to the Premier League\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 205</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">111</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As Marco Reus slid the ball into the unguarded net, the Westfalenstadion exploded and so did the manager. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">In a fabulously spontaneous expression of joy, Jurgen Klopp bounded across his technical area and then leapt a good five foot into the air with fists pumping and legs kicking. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It was an exuberant celebration, yet at the same time characteristic of a manager who has been a breath of fresh air for not only Borussia Dortmund but wider German and European football. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"><div class=\"moduleFull\"><a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3452073421001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Is Klopp bringing his hip hop to England?</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/video-undefined-1CFE177B00000578-498_638x364.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <img alt=\"Taking off: Klopp sprinted down the touchline after Dortmund scored their winner against Wolfsburg on Saturday and capped it off with a terrific leap\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"360\" id=\"i-a9f70e72\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CE6B16500000578-559_634x360.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Taking off: Klopp sprinted down the touchline after Dortmund scored their winner against Wolfsburg on Saturday and capped it off with a terrific leap</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Kapow! Klopp soars through the air with arms punching and legs kicking\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"343\" id=\"i-9bd00e34\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CE6B15100000578-36_634x343.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Kapow! Klopp soars through the air with arms punching and legs kicking</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"A reason to celebrate: Klopp was marking a winning goal by Marco Reus that saw Dortmund beat Wolfsburg\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"404\" id=\"i-acc80e89\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CDCD26D00000578-580_634x404.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">A reason to celebrate: Klopp was marking a winning goal by Marco Reus that saw Dortmund beat Wolfsburg</p> </div><p> </p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"England calling: Klopp would attract a lot of interest from Premier League clubs if he decided to leave Borussia Dortmund and take up a new challenge\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-ab130e78\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF8BD1100000578-616_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">England calling: Klopp would attract a lot of interest from Premier League clubs if he decided to leave Borussia Dortmund and take up a new challenge</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">After all, why celebrate with modesty and reserve when you can soar through the air like Michael Jordan or a ninja from Street Fighter? </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The goal turned out to be Dortmund\'s winner against Wolfsburg and strengthened their hold on second place in the Bundesliga.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">But after Real Madrid put paid to their hopes of a second consecutive Champions League final three days later, that runners-up spot is about the best Klopp and Dortmund can hope for.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The golden age brought about by Klopp has passed almost as quickly as it came. Bayern Munich have restored the natural order. It\'s time for Klopp to take another great leap. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Jose Mourinho memorably sprinted down a touchline too. That was back in 2004, when his Porto side stunned Manchester United in the Champions League at Old Trafford.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"End of the line: Klopp has won two Bundesliga titles with Dortmund but they now trail Bayern by a long way\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"408\" id=\"i-9e8a0e51\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF18DF900000578-24_634x408.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">End of the line: Klopp has won two Bundesliga titles with Dortmund but they now trail Bayern by a long way</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Far out in front: Bayern Munich are currently 20 points clear of Dortmund at the top of the Bundesliga, having already secured the title\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"398\" id=\"i-9c2c0e42\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-07757DEC00000514-27_634x398.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Far out in front: Bayern Munich are currently 20 points clear of Dortmund at the top of the Bundesliga, having already secured the title  </p><div class=\"moduleFull\"><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3440057917001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Jurgen Klopp takes off like Michael Jordan celebrating Reus goal</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/video-undefined-1CE6D23D00000578-57_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Jumping for joy: Jose Mourinho lit up the Premier League after making this famous touchline dash\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"488\" id=\"i-a7180e6e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-040224D6000005DC-937_634x488.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Jumping for joy: Jose Mourinho lit up the Premier League after making this famous touchline dash</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>KLOPP\'S RECORD </b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p> <b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">AS A PLAYER</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Mainz (1989-2001)</b> <br/> 337 league games, 52 goals</font></p><p><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">AS A MANAGER</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Mainz (February 2001-June 2008)</b><br/><b>Games</b> 270 <b>Won </b>109 <b>Drawn</b> 78 <b>Lost</b> 83 (40.37 per cent win record)</font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Borussia Dortmund (July 2008-)</b><br/><b>Games </b>262 <b>Won </b>152 <b>Drawn </b>59 <b>Lost </b>51<br/>(58.02 per cent win record)<br/></font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Within another 12 months, he was lighting up the Premier League with Chelsea. Mourinho broke the mould, he was smart, suave, supercilious and ultimately successful. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Now it\'s time for cool and colourful Klopp to take the leap and come to England. The Premier League would be a far more interesting place with him. He would break the mould too. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The marketplace is bustling if Klopp should choose to have a stroll through. There might be changes afoot at Arsenal or Manchester United. He might fancy a challenge like Aston Villa, West Ham or West Bromwich. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What\'s sure is that a fair proportion of the Premier League clubs would want to hire a man who guided an unfancied and under-performing Dortmund side to successive Bundesliga titles and the final of the European Cup.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He would be a crowd pleaser as well. Touchline long jump aside, his interviews are rarely boring and his English is already very good. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Deep in thought: Klopp pictured during his press conference ahead of this week\'s Champions League second leg against Real Madrid\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-a92e0e66\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CE9934800000578-371_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Deep in thought: Klopp pictured during his press conference ahead of this week\'s Champions League second leg against Real Madrid</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Falling short: Klopp remonstrates with the officials after Dortmund lost 2-0 to Real Madrid, exiting the Champions League 3-2 on aggregate\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"421\" id=\"i-a9be0e6e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF5A52400000578-667_634x421.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Falling short: Klopp remonstrates with the officials after Dortmund lost 2-0 to Real Madrid, exiting the Champions League 3-2 on aggregate</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Dejection: Kevin Grosskreutz reacts after Dortmund\'s exit\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"389\" id=\"i-acb00e96\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF5A2AC00000578-757_634x389.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Dejection: Kevin Grosskreutz reacts after Dortmund\'s exit</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>KLOPP\'S TROPHY CABINET</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p> <b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">BORUSSIA DORTMUND</font></b></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>Bundesliga </b>2010-2011, 2011-2012</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>DFB-Pokal</b> 2011-2012</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>DFL-Supercup</b> 2013</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>UEFA Champions League runner-up </b>2012-2013</font><br/><br/><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">INDIVIDUAL</font></b><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>German Manager of the Year</b> 2011,2012</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b>FIFA World Coach of the Year runner-up</b> 2013 </font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Klopp compares his team\'s style on the pitch to thrash metal - offensive, high-intensity and high-tempo. You would certainly get good value for your season ticket, as Dortmund\'s yellow walls have for the last five years. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The 46-year-old is still, comparatively, a managerial novice but you sense he\'s well equipped for the rigours of the Premier League, which we know can be unforgiving. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There\'s also the sense that Klopp has done all he can for Dortmund. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">With their wonderful 80,000-capacity arena and legions of fans, Dortmund had been sleeping giants since the late 1990s and endured their share of financial hardships.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Klopp roused and reinvigorated them, restoring pride and smashing the domestic hegemony of rivals Bayern. Supporting and watching BVB was suddenly the height of chic, the hipster\'s choice.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">They reached the high water mark in beating Real Madrid 4-1 before an ecstatic Westfalenstadion this time last year, with Robert Lewandowski scoring all four - yet they ended the season without a trophy.</font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\">  <div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-2681031290001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Dortmund manager Jurgen Klopp sent off for incredible rage at...</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2013/09/19/video-undefined-1BE83A1D000005DC-719_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Last gasp: Arjen Robben scored the winner as Bayern beat Borussia 2-1 in the 2013 Champions League final at Wembley\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"416\" id=\"i-a0770e6c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-19FFB7A8000005DC-53_634x416.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Last gasp: Arjen Robben scored the winner as Bayern beat Borussia 2-1 in the 2013 Champions League final at Wembley</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Missing out: Klopp consoles Kevin Grosskreutz after Dortmund\'s best season finished without silverware\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-b05e0ebb\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-19FFCA9F000005DC-879_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Missing out: Klopp consoles Kevin Grosskreutz after Dortmund\'s best season finished without silverware</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Familiar sight: Bayern parade the Champions League trophy after their triumph at Wembley\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"346\" id=\"i-a96b0e74\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1A00AB59000005DC-210_634x346.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Familiar sight: Bayern parade the Champions League trophy after their triumph at Wembley</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599870/Dortmund-2-0-Real-Madrid-agg-2-3-Reus-double-not-quite-Ronaldo-Madrid-sneak-finest-margin.html\"> Dortmund 2-0 Real Madrid (agg 2-3): Reus double not quite enough as Ronaldo-less Madrid sneak through by finest margin</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601305/Messi-blamed-Barcelonas-defeat-running-just-1km-KEEPER.html\"> Messi blamed for Barcelona\'s defeat after running just 1 mile more than the KEEPER</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600692/The-Happy-One-After-Jose-Mourinhos-moans-Premier-League-Chelseas-fixtures-aid-European-quest.html\"> The Happy One? After Mourinho\'s moans, the Premier League are to move Chelsea\'s fixtures to aid their European quest</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/article-2601048/Bale-pens-six-year-adidas-contract-extension-joining-elite-20m-jackpot-deal.html\"> Bale to pen six-year adidas contract extension, joining the elite with £20m jackpot deal</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">At Wembley, Arjen Robben\'s late winner for Bayern, sealing the Treble, left Klopp and co heart-broken. Mario Gotze defected to Bavaria and Lewandowski is about to follow. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Realistically, Klopp has taken them as far as he can. Just look at the 20-point gulf to Bayern in the Bundesliga table. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Bayern were crowned champions on March 25, an embarrassingly early title conclusion for a league that wins many plaudits for the effective and fan-friendly way in which things are done. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">But what league is competitive when the best team can poach the best two players of the side in second place? </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And unfortunately, that could be just the beginning for Borussia as wealthy, carnivorous clubs around Europe strip them of their best players. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There is constant speculation that the likes of Marco Reus, Ilkay Gundogan and Sven Bender are about to move, perhaps to the Premier League. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Open to offers: Marco Reus could be the next of Dortmund\'s golden generation to leave\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"403\" id=\"i-ab590e7f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF92D9800000578-786_634x403.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Open to offers: Marco Reus could be the next of Dortmund\'s golden generation to leave</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Until next year: The next time Gareth Bale faces Robert Lewandowski, the Pole will be in Bayern colours\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"419\" id=\"i-9b870e38\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CF20E0100000578-78_634x419.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Until next year: The next time Gareth Bale faces Robert Lewandowski, the Pole will be in Bayern colours</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Incoming: Dortmund have signed the Hertha Berlin forward Adrian Ramos to replace Lewandowski\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"408\" id=\"i-9af10e2d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CE302D000000578-42_634x408.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Incoming: Dortmund have signed the Hertha Berlin forward Adrian Ramos to replace Lewandowski</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This phenomenally strong and entertaining side, who have scaled such great heights together, will be dismantled. All good things must pass.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">On Wednesday, Borussia announced the signing of Hertha Berlin\'s Colombian striker Adrian Ramos. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He\'s undoubtedly prolific but bringing in a 28-year-old to replace Lewandowski doesn\'t inspire confidence in a long-term plan. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It\'s time for Klopp to make a clean break of it, enjoy a change of scenery and begin a new project in the Premier League. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Like Mourinho, we\'ll quickly grow to love him. Or at least grudgingly admire his success. </font></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2599870/Dortmund-2-0-Real-Madrid-agg-2-3-Reus-double-not-quite-Ronaldo-Madrid-sneak-finest-margin.html\"> Dortmund 2-0 Real Madrid (agg 2-3): Reus double not quite enough as Ronaldo-less Madrid sneak through by finest margin</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601305/Messi-blamed-Barcelonas-defeat-running-just-1km-KEEPER.html\"> Messi blamed for Barcelona\'s defeat after running just 1 mile more than the KEEPER</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600692/The-Happy-One-After-Jose-Mourinhos-moans-Premier-League-Chelseas-fixtures-aid-European-quest.html\"> The Happy One? After Mourinho\'s moans, the Premier League are to move Chelsea\'s fixtures to aid their European quest</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/article-2601048/Bale-pens-six-year-adidas-contract-extension-joining-elite-20m-jackpot-deal.html\"> Bale to pen six-year adidas contract extension, joining the elite with £20m jackpot deal</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/Jurgen-Klopp-swap-Borussia-Dortmund-Premier-League.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Klopp has taken Borussia Dortmund as far as he can... it\'s time the colourful German took a leap to the Premier League\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601398/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">205</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> <li class=\"add-comment\" id=\"addCommentButton\"> <a href=\"#newcomment\" rel=\"nofollow\"> </a> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/10/article-2601398-1CFD70F800000578-442_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:51','2014-04-10 13:39:29'),(107,'647325c1aeba717850e512dc07799b325755023f014499631c963cf17b876642','dailymail',NULL,'Manchester United fought like a brave Old Trafford side of old - it was their best display of the season','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html',' The first 60 minutes was as good a performance as any from Manchester United this seasonThere looks to be a future for Chris Smalling at centre-halfBayern Munich looked ordinary with a lack of width By Martin Keown Follow @@martinkeown5 Published: 15:45 EST, 9 April 2014 | Updated: 03:43 EST, 10 April 2014 86 shares 76 View comments  It was not a rigid formation in attack for United. In particular Shinji Kagawa drifted from the left into the middle and was a threat when on the ball. Danny Welbeck would go out wide and his pace scared Bayern at times. Wayne Rooney would drop back if he needed to. VIDEO Scroll down to watch Eleven players who should leave Old Trafford in the summer  Drifting: Shinji Kagawa (left) continued his recent renaissance with a decent display   Pure pace: Danny Welbeck skips past Jerome Boateng  More... Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Moyes shows he has stomach for fight as United boss shrugs off early blow in Munich Moyes admits Rooney gamble backfired after United striker\'s struggles in Munich Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League MATCH ZONE SPECIAL: Rooney made his mark but brilliant Bayern were too strong Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night It was in general a good tempo from United and what Moyes must have expected when he took over this job. It was more like the United of old, and for the first 60 minutes as good a performance as any this season given the calibre of opponent they were up against. This was the all-conquering Bayern Munich. Maybe United do not need the massive overhaul that has been suggested. They looked a good side. It was a brave fight. Patrice Evra’s goal was a thunderbolt struck because he sensed blood at the start of the second half. Bayern responded like champions and it was Evra who allowed Mario Mandzukic to steal in for his header.  I was very impressed with Chris Smalling, there now looks to be a future for him at centre-half; which is a positive from an England point of view. It was a big call by David Moyes to play Smalling in place of Rio Ferdinand but it worked. He looked dominant in the air – and beat Thomas Muller to a commanding header early on – and also coped well in one-on-ones with Franck Ribery when dragged to the wing. He was mobile and used the ball well.  Steppingup: Chris Smalling (right) tussles with Thomas Muller as the centre back covered admirably   Plus point: Phil Jones (centre) has shown promise at right back this season  Phil Jones was another plus point at right back. Moyes will have to play at least one of the youngsters, perhaps both, with Nemanja Vidic and Ferdinand leaving in the summer. This will have been an important experience for both of them and given them confidence. Conversely, Jerome Boateng and Dante did not look comfortable at times in possession. Pep Guardiola likes to play out from the back but when questioned by United’s high pressing they would often go back to Manuel Neuer. The eleven players who should leave Old Trafford in the summer  I was disappointed with Bayern Munich, it was not as difficult for Manchester United as we would have expected. Usually in wide positions they have carousel of players and the full-backs bomb forward. But David Alaba and Philipp Lahm played very central, they came right in to central midfield. It was underlapping rather than overlapping. That made it easier for United to work out who should be picking up who.  Over-tinkering: Although Arjen Robben (right) scored, he will have been frustrated with Bayern\'s system   Game-changer: The introduction of Rafinha (left) gave Bayern added impetus and gave them better shape  It might be because Pep Guardiola wanted Lahm on ball more often, and it also meant Mario Gotze and Thomas Muller could push further forwards. But instead they looked ordinary; it just didn’t work. It’s a system that would drive someone like Arjen Robben mad. He loves short passes with his full-back to cut in and find space in dangerous areas, but there was little chance of that. There was no-one running down the wings to create width. It seemed a case of Guardiola over-tinkering. When Rafinha came on to provide width, Bayern looked a different side.   More... Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword Moyes shows he has stomach for fight as United boss shrugs off early blow in Munich Moyes admits Rooney gamble backfired after United striker\'s struggles in Munich Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League MATCH ZONE SPECIAL: Rooney made his mark but brilliant Bayern were too strong Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night  Share or comment on this article 86shares','\n<ul class=\"article-summary sport\"><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">The first 60 minutes was as good a performance as any from Manchester United this season</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">There looks to be a future for Chris Smalling at centre-half</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Bayern Munich looked ordinary with a lack of width<br/></font></b></li></ul>\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1047409/Martin-Keown.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Martin Keown</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@martinkeown5\">Follow @@martinkeown5</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 15:45 EST, 9 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 03:43 EST, 10 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Manchester United fought like a brave Old Trafford side of old - it was their best display of the season\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 86</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">76</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It was not a rigid formation in attack for United. In particular Shinji Kagawa drifted from the left into the middle and was a threat when on the ball. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Danny Welbeck would go out wide and his pace scared Bayern at times. Wayne Rooney would drop back if he needed to. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b><font color=\"FFFFFF\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(12, 172, 12);\">VIDEO</span></font> Scroll down to watch Eleven players who should leave Old Trafford in the summer</b><br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Drifting: Shinji Kagawa (left) continued his recent renaissance with a decent display\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"479\" id=\"i-5eab0d4a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-0-1CF90C4900000578-672_634x479.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Drifting: Shinji Kagawa (left) continued his recent renaissance with a decent display</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Pure pace: Danny Welbeck skips past Jerome Boateng\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"429\" id=\"i-60290d58\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-0-1CF91DB500000578-697_634x429.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Pure pace: Danny Welbeck skips past Jerome Boateng</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600972/David-Moyes-shows-stomach-fight-Manchester-United-boss-shrugs-early-blow-Munich.html\"> Moyes shows he has stomach for fight as United boss shrugs off early blow in Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600879/Moyes-admits-Rooney-gamble-backfired-United-strikers-struggles-Munich.html\"> Moyes admits Rooney gamble backfired after United striker\'s struggles in Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601037/Moyes-trips-learning-curve-United-crash-Champions-League.html\"> Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601014/MATCH-ZONE-SPECIAL-Rooney-mark-brilliant-Bayern-strong.html\"> MATCH ZONE SPECIAL: Rooney made his mark but brilliant Bayern were too strong</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601023/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Manchester-United-4-2-agg-Player-ratings.html\"> Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It was in general a good tempo from United and what Moyes must have expected when he took over this job. It was more like the United of old, and for the first 60 minutes as good a performance as any this season given the calibre of opponent they were up against. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This was the all-conquering Bayern Munich. Maybe United do not need the massive overhaul that has been suggested. They looked a good side. It was a brave fight. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Patrice Evra’s goal was a thunderbolt struck because he sensed blood at the start of the second half. Bayern responded like champions and it was Evra who allowed Mario Mandzukic to steal in for his header.</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I was very impressed with Chris Smalling, there now looks to be a future for him at centre-half; which is a positive from an England point of view. It was a big call by David Moyes to play Smalling in place of Rio Ferdinand but it worked. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He looked dominant in the air – and beat Thomas Muller to a commanding header early on – and also coped well in one-on-ones with Franck Ribery when dragged to the wing. He was mobile and used the ball well. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Steppingup: Chris Smalling (right) tussles with Thomas Muller as the centre back covered admirably\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"499\" id=\"i-68050d5b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-0-1CF9040900000578-1000_634x499.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Steppingup: Chris Smalling (right) tussles with Thomas Muller as the centre back covered admirably</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Plus point: Phil Jones (centre) has shown promise at right back this season\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"479\" id=\"i-ab620e85\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-2601016-1CF92CB100000578-954_634x479.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Plus point: Phil Jones (centre) has shown promise at right back this season</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Phil Jones was another plus point at right back. Moyes will have to play at least one of the youngsters, perhaps both, with Nemanja Vidic and Ferdinand leaving in the summer. This will have been an important experience for both of them and given them confidence. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Conversely, Jerome Boateng and Dante did not look comfortable at times in possession. Pep Guardiola likes to play out from the back but when questioned by United’s high pressing they would often go back to Manuel Neuer.</font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"> <a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3403574129001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">The eleven players who should leave Old Trafford in the summer</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/28/video-undefined-1CA67CD200000578-653_638x378.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">I was disappointed with Bayern Munich, it was not as difficult for Manchester United as we would have expected. Usually in wide positions they have carousel of players and the full-backs bomb forward. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">But David Alaba and Philipp Lahm played very central, they came right in to central midfield. It was underlapping rather than overlapping. That made it easier for United to work out who should be picking up who.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Over-tinkering: Although Arjen Robben (right) scored, he will have been frustrated with Bayern\'s system\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"446\" id=\"i-5f070d49\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-0-1CF956E500000578-456_634x446.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Over-tinkering: Although Arjen Robben (right) scored, he will have been frustrated with Bayern\'s system</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Game-changer: The introduction of Rafinha (left) gave Bayern added impetus and gave them better shape\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"433\" id=\"i-a87d0e60\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-2601016-1CF9623500000578-366_634x433.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Game-changer: The introduction of Rafinha (left) gave Bayern added impetus and gave them better shape</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It might be because Pep Guardiola wanted Lahm on ball more often, and it also meant Mario Gotze and Thomas Muller could push further forwards. But instead they looked ordinary; it just didn’t work. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It’s a system that would drive someone like Arjen Robben mad. He loves short passes with his full-back to cut in and find space in dangerous areas, but there was little chance of that. There was no-one running down the wings to create width. It seemed a case of Guardiola over-tinkering.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">When Rafinha came on to provide width, Bayern looked a different side.<br/></font></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600859/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Man-United-agg-4-2-Match-report-David-Moyes-Arjen-Robben-Mario-Mandzukic-Thomas-Muller-Patrice-Evra-scores.html\"> Bayern Munich 3-1 Man United (agg 4-2): Ecstasy to agony for Moyes as ruthless Germans put visitors to the sword</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600972/David-Moyes-shows-stomach-fight-Manchester-United-boss-shrugs-early-blow-Munich.html\"> Moyes shows he has stomach for fight as United boss shrugs off early blow in Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2600879/Moyes-admits-Rooney-gamble-backfired-United-strikers-struggles-Munich.html\"> Moyes admits Rooney gamble backfired after United striker\'s struggles in Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601037/Moyes-trips-learning-curve-United-crash-Champions-League.html\"> Moyes trips on the learning curve as United crash out of the Champions League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601014/MATCH-ZONE-SPECIAL-Rooney-mark-brilliant-Bayern-strong.html\"> MATCH ZONE SPECIAL: Rooney made his mark but brilliant Bayern were too strong</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2601023/Bayern-Munich-3-1-Manchester-United-4-2-agg-Player-ratings.html\"> Allianz Arena player ratings: Rooney battled hard but it wasn\'t his or United\'s night</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/They-fought-bravely-like-Manchester-United-old-maybe-Moyes-doesnt-need-overhaul.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Manchester United fought like a brave Old Trafford side of old - it was their best display of the season\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2601016/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">86</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/09/article-0-1CF90C4900000578-345_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:52','2014-04-10 10:43:34'),(108,'408447a415cc7aaa0c534ff109801420eb475d97538d3d34e09409a06cf2f4ef','dailymail',NULL,'Adrian Durham: Liverpool\'s Steven Gerrard deserves to beat Luis Suarez in Player of Year award','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2599443/Adrian-Durham-column-Liverpools-Steven-Gerrard-deserves-win-player-year-ahead-Luis-Suarez.html',' By Adrian Durham Follow @@talkSPORTDrive Published: 01:12 EST, 8 April 2014 | Updated: 11:11 EST, 9 April 2014 232 shares 187 View comments  MORE FROM ADRIAN DURHAM KANE MUST NOT BE ALLOWED TO FALL DOWN THE ENGLISH TALENT DRAIN WHY HODGSON MUST TAKE STONES AND FLANAGAN TO BRAZIL Luis Suarez will probably win a player of the year double, and understandably so. Other players have impressed, notably Chelsea’s Eden Hazard, but unfortunately he finds himself vulnerable to Jose Mourinho’s tactical preferences, and selection whims. Manchester City’s Yaya Toure is truly world class, but occasionally lazy as well. If you were to ask the general football public to vote, based on talent, heart, and the commitment to the club on and off the pitch, I’m certain Steven Gerrard would be the people’s choice. VIDEO Scroll down to watch Rodgers talk about Gerrard\'s penalty-taking ability  Leading the way: Steven Gerrard deserves to be the Premier League player of the season for his \'exemplary\' leadership and crucial contributions   Spot on: Gerrard converted two penalties in Liverpool\'s 2-1 win at West Ham on Sunday, maintaining their two-point cushion at the top of the Premier League   Flying: Liverpool are on course to win their first league title in 24 years   On their perch: Liverpool are well-placed entering the title run-in  Rodgers reveals the secrets behind Gerrard\'s penalty successes As a captain he means as much to his club as John Terry means to Chelsea. The difference is that Gerrard has never let his club down either on or off the pitch. As a loyal servant I can think of no better example in football than Gerrard. It’s easy for the likes of Terry and Scholes to stay at their clubs – they were winning medals and trophies. Gerrard remained loyal despite the title eluding Liverpool season after season. He stayed even when Liverpool didn’t make the Champions League. This season he has been reliable from the penalty spot, staying calm to slot home crucial penalties in cauldrons like Old Trafford and Upton Park to help Liverpool to vital victories. His passing from deep has been world class. Hard to believe that after the 2-0 defeat at Arsenal in November a small number of Liverpool fans went on Twitter to suggest Gerrard needed replacing. Never doubt the captain, he’s fantastic. Rodgers: The 96 are motivating our title charge  Clear favourite: Luis Suarez is likely to scoop the Player of the Year awards by virtue of his 29 goals this season   In the running: Eden Hazard is another strong candidate to be named the best player of the season   Front runner: Manchester City\'s Yaya Toure is another contenders for the end-of-season accolades  More... Gerrard: A hot dressing room, dry pitch and the bus had to park a mile away... West Ham did everything they could to upset Liverpool Suarez and Rodgers are going nowhere: Liverpool chief gives sponsors assurances pair will be at Anfield next season Gerrard has scored 10 penalties for Liverpool this season... but how many should have been given? Do the Sturridge! Liverpool star surprises young fans and teaches them THAT dance His leadership has been exemplary. The young players have a star to look up to and learn from, the senior professionals are full of admiration for one of the finest players this country has ever produced. Luis Suarez has been disciplined all season: it’s stretching plausible thinking to believe the Liverpool captain has said nothing to and had no influence on the Uruguayan star. Even if Liverpool don’t win the title, the remarkable improvement from last season is enough for Gerrard to win it. What seals it for me though is what Gerrard has done as England captain. It’s this that sets him apart from the rest this season.  Leading by example: Gerrard celebrates the goal against Poland that made absolutely sure of England\'s progress to the World Cup finals in Brazil     As undisputed skipper for the first time, with no chance of the manager inexplicably giving the armband to John Terry or Rio Ferdinand, Gerrard has flourished. There will be those who claim they don’t care about international football, club comes first. Steven Gerrard is sensible enough to realise you can actually have commitment to both club and country. And we all know that once England get to a World Cup everyone in this country gets interested. Last October, England faced two must-win qualifiers in the space of four days. The mood of the football nation depended on the results of these games.  The dream: Can Gerrard emulate the great Bobby Moore in 1966 and lift the World Cup in Brazil this summer?  Gerrard led his country to a 4-1 victory over Montenegro. And then, late in the game, with England holding a precarious 1-0 lead over Poland, he strode through on goal, showing strength and riding challenges, before poking the ball into the back of the net. At that moment we all breathed a huge sigh of relief. The captain had delivered. He now has an opportunity to be the best captain England have had since Bobby Moore. I hope he takes it. For club and country, Steven Gerrard is my number one this season. As player, captain, and leader – for club and country - nobody comes close. CLICK HERE TO READ ADRIAN DURHAM ON THE SHAMEFUL WASTE OF ENGLISH TALENT CLICK HERE TO READ ADRIAN DURHAM ON HODGSON\'S WORLD CUP SQUAD   More... Gerrard: A hot dressing room, dry pitch and the bus had to park a mile away... West Ham did everything they could to upset Liverpool Suarez and Rodgers are going nowhere: Liverpool chief gives sponsors assurances pair will be at Anfield next season Gerrard has scored 10 penalties for Liverpool this season... but how many should have been given? Do the Sturridge! Liverpool star surprises young fans and teaches them THAT dance   Share or comment on this article 232shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1076414/Adrian-Durham.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Adrian Durham</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@talkSPORTDrive\">Follow @@talkSPORTDrive</a> </span> </p>\n<p