But Perera did what any reputable pro would do: he held on.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Staring into the abyss: Yuvraj Singh contemplates his batting meltdown after the World Twenty20 final\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"452\" id=\"i-aaeb0e73\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE7158000000578-189_634x452.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Staring into the abyss: Yuvraj Singh contemplates his batting meltdown after the World Twenty20 final</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"The end: Yuvraj (right) looks disgusted as Nuwan Kulasekara (left) celebrates his dismissal\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"455\" id=\"i-ad300e8d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE255E900000578-929_634x455.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">The end: Yuvraj (right) looks disgusted as Nuwan Kulasekara (left) celebrates his dismissal</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"item\"> <div class=\"columnist-archive-narrow bogr1\"> <span class=\"tl\"> </span> <span class=\"tr\"> </span> <h3>More from Lawrence Booth...</h3> <ul> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598932/THE-TOP-SPIN-Yuvrajs-tortuous-final-meltdown-just-Twenty20-favour-yes-really.html\">THE TOP SPIN: Yuvraj\'s tortuous final meltdown might just have done Twenty20 a favour (yes, really)</a> <span class=\"date\">07/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2594007/THE-TOP-SPIN-These-difficult-times-England-worse.html\">THE TOP SPIN: These are difficult times for England and they may get worse... but that\'s no reason to turn on Giles before he\'s had a proper crack</a> <span class=\"date\">01/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2588783/TOP-SPIN-Broad-bothered-safety-defeat-knows-better-dead-match-dead-player.html\">TOP SPIN: Broad was more bothered about safety than defeat - he knows it\'s better to have a dead match than a dead player</a> <span class=\"date\">25/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2534578/THE-TOP-SPIN-Things-worse-better-England.html\">THE TOP SPIN: Cook and Flower deserve some sympathy but England fans be warned, it could get worse before it gets better</a> <span class=\"date\">06/01/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2531187/ASHES-2013-14-THE-TOP-SPIN-It-curtains-Tim-Bresnan-Michael-Carberry-Monty-Panesar.html\">THE TOP SPIN: It could and should be curtains for Bresnan, Carberry and Panesar... and Bairstow already has Buttler breathing down his neck</a> <span class=\"date\">30/12/13</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2528398/THE-TOP-SPIN-Watching-Graeme-Swann-one-highlights-career.html\">THE TOP SPIN: Forget the moaners, watching Swann whirl away has been one of the highlights of my career</a> <span class=\"date\">23/12/13</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2525598/The-Ashes-Mickey-Arthur-looking-future-sacked-Australia-better-ever.html\">THE TOP SPIN: Arthur was looking to the future when he got the chop... and now the Aussies are better in every department</a> <span class=\"date\">18/12/13</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2525078/The-Ashes-2013-14-Top-Spin-Test--The-good-bad-ugly-day-Perth.html\">TOP SPIN AT THE TEST: The good, the bad and the ugly from day five in Perth</a> <span class=\"date\">17/12/13</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2524563/TOP-SPIN-AT-THE-TEST-The-good-bad-ugly-day-Perth.html\">TOP SPIN AT THE TEST: The good, the bad and the ugly from day four in Perth</a> <span class=\"date\">16/12/13</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"columnist-1036920/Lawrence-Booth.html\">VIEW FULL ARCHIVE</a> </li> </ul> </div> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Needless to say, reports emerged after Sri Lanka had comfortably overhauled India’s curious total of 130 for four that Yuvraj’s home in Chandigarh had been stoned. His dad Yograj has already issued a ‘don’t blame my boy’ plea. We await the burning effigies.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Meltdowns in cricket are supposed to be the preserve of bowlers – especially left-arm spinners, though Leicestershire seamer Scott Boswell’s 14-ball over in the final of the 2001 C&amp;G Trophy at Lord’s remains perhaps the most famous example.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yet Yuvraj’s tortured half-hour in Dhaka must take its place among cricket’s cruellest vignettes. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And it’s unclear whether the post-match words of his captain MS Dhoni will have helped. ‘Yuvi tried his best,’ said Dhoni, falling awkwardly between an arm round the shoulder and a patronising pat on the head. It’s the kind of thing my sports teachers used to say to me.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The sense of cruelty on Sunday stemmed from a few factors. Seven years ago, during the inaugural World Twenty20 in South Africa, Yuvraj hit Stuart Broad for six sixes in an over at Durban. That, not 21 boundary-less balls, was supposed to be his T20 epitaph.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And this was the final of a tournament in which India had been the best – and, until now, only unbeaten – team. Victory here, and they would hold all three global ICC trophies. A miserable few months would be glossed over!</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Then there was the impending IPL, a competition which routinely turns the other cheek to its latest corruption scandal and proclaims itself the zenith of all things T20. What better way to whet appetites than for Yuvraj, one of the IPL’s poster boys, to go berserk?</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">All the while, at the other end, was Virat Kohli, a smouldering ball of fury at the best of times and comfortably the best batsman in the competition. Yet during India’s dreadful final four overs, he managed to face only eight balls.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The script was being torn up in front of his face – by a team-mate. When Yuvraj approached Kohli during the presentation ceremony and gave him a hug – half-consoling, half-apologetic – Kohli barely glanced up from his smartphone. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Missing out: A struggling Yuvraj watches the ball go by\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"426\" id=\"i-abc10e7b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE26A2300000578-187_634x426.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Missing out: A struggling Yuvraj watches the ball go by</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598924/Kevin-Pietersen-set-Indian-Premier-League-Alastair-Cook-scores-39-Essex.html\"> Pietersen jets off to India for IPL as Cook returns to the crease after Ashes nightmare</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598739/Joe-Root-signs-two-year-contract-extension-Yorkshire.html\"> Root signs two-year extension to stay with Yorkshire through to 2016</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598348/James-Anderson-takes-five-Lancashire-England-hopefuls-struggle-opening-day-County-Championship.html\"> Anderson takes five but England hopefuls struggle on opening day of County Championship</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598206/Sri-Lanka-win-major-trophy-1996-defeat-India-World-T20.html\"> Sri Lanka legends Sangakkara and Jayawardene bow out in style with World Twenty20 triumph</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598079/England-Women-slump-six-wicket-defeat-World-T20-final-against-superb-Aussies.html\"> England Women slump to six wicket defeat in World T20 final against superb Aussies</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2597800/England-captain-Charlotte-Edwards-dreams-Aussie-double-ahead-Womens-World-T20-final.html\"> England captain Edwards dreams of Aussie double ahead of Women\'s World T20 final</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It was dramatic, all right. And it was a reminder that a poor innings can be just as destructive to a team’s chances in Twenty20 as a poor spell. Batting can be as lonely as bowling.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The former New Zealand captain Martin Crowe suggested on Twitter that ‘it was like watching Bradman at one end and Chris Martin at the other. T20 at its worst. Bring in the batting sub rule.’ </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It’s a nicely quirky idea, and few are better at those than Crowe. But Yuvraj’s struggles were grimly compelling. Boswell had to complete that over 13 years ago – so why should Yuvraj have been allowed to escape Sri Lanka’s bowlers? </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">One of them couldn’t hit the cut strip, and the other couldn’t get it off the square. But, really, what’s the difference? Twenty20 is a batsman’s game, so let’s occasionally hear it for the bowlers.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Besides, Sri Lanka’s seamers were not easy to hit. In the 11 legal deliveries that followed Yuvraj’s departure, India scored just seven off the bat. Dhoni, regarded as one of history’s finest finishers, made four runs off seven balls. Had no one watched Ravi Bopara’s handling of Lasith Malinga in Chittagong?</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">So, yes, Yuvraj had a shocker. But should he have been put in that position in the first place? He had, after all, produced only one innings of note all tournament – 60 off 43 balls against a poor Australian side in a game India didn’t need to win. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">His three other innings ahead of the final had produced 29 runs from 38 balls. He was manifestly out of touch, as he has been in international cricket for some time.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Dhoni did his best to defend Yuvraj afterwards, protesting that only Suresh Raina among India’s batsmen was capable of timing the ball from the very start. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">But this didn’t deal with the obvious fact that Yuvraj was badly out of nick, nor did it tally with Dhoni’s promotion of himself above Raina. India’s experience of the semi-final win over South Africa, when Raina made 21 off 10 balls to turn the chase into a stroll, seemed to have been completely forgotten.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Contrast: As Yuvraj struggled, Virat Kohli (right) was in superb nick but did not face enough deliveries\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"652\" id=\"i-9eed0e4c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE248B600000578-62_634x652.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Contrast: As Yuvraj struggled, Virat Kohli (right) was in superb nick but did not face enough deliveries</p> </div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>THE TOP SPIN ON TWITTER</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p> <font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">For more cricket-related snippets, feel free to go to </font><a href=\"https://twitter.com/the_topspin\" rel=\"nofollow\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">twitter.com/the_topspin</font> </a><br/></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Logic suggested a batting order of Raina-Dhoni-Yuvraj. In the event, Yuvraj-Dhoni-Raina cost India the title.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And yet, as Boris Becker once said after losing at Wimbledon, ‘Nobody died.’ In fact, a few people – especially in Colombo – may even have come alive. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Besides, Twenty20’s critics often complain of its tedious predictability, of one six after another robbing it of tension. Yuvraj’s innings, in the most-watched Twenty20 international for years, bucked the trend spectacularly. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He may not appreciate the thought right now, but Yuvraj may just have done Twenty20 a favour. <br/></font></p>\n<p><br/></p>\n<div class=\"cleared art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>THAT WAS THE WEEK THAT WAS</b><br/></h3></div>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Long live the King!</font></h2>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598924/Kevin-Pietersen-set-Indian-Premier-League-Alastair-Cook-scores-39-Essex.html\"> Pietersen jets off to India for IPL as Cook returns to the crease after Ashes nightmare</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598739/Joe-Root-signs-two-year-contract-extension-Yorkshire.html\"> Root signs two-year extension to stay with Yorkshire through to 2016</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598348/James-Anderson-takes-five-Lancashire-England-hopefuls-struggle-opening-day-County-Championship.html\"> Anderson takes five but England hopefuls struggle on opening day of County Championship</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598206/Sri-Lanka-win-major-trophy-1996-defeat-India-World-T20.html\"> Sri Lanka legends Sangakkara and Jayawardene bow out in style with World Twenty20 triumph</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598079/England-Women-slump-six-wicket-defeat-World-T20-final-against-superb-Aussies.html\"> England Women slump to six wicket defeat in World T20 final against superb Aussies</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2597800/England-captain-Charlotte-Edwards-dreams-Aussie-double-ahead-Womens-World-T20-final.html\"> England captain Edwards dreams of Aussie double ahead of Women\'s World T20 final</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No one at the ICC seems quite sure what to do with N Srinivasan following his enforced abdication – temporary or otherwise – as president of the BCCI. In private, the message is being conveyed that other boards are dealing with an organisation and not an individual. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">In other words, the ground is being prepared: if the embarrassment of appointing as ICC chairman a man who has redefined ‘conflicts of interest’, who seemed remarkably unclear about the role his son-in-law played at Chennai Super Kings, and who has presided over the most bullying organisation in cricket since the days of the old Anglo-Australian veto – if the embarrassment grows too strong, the likes of the ECB and Cricket Australia can always claim they were negotiating with the BCCI and not Srini himself.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Brilliant, eh? In the meantime, let’s leave you with the words of Paul Marsh, boss of FICA: ‘The prospect of Mr Srinivasan taking the highest posting in world cricket, while these matters are unresolved, is an impossible one.’ But is anyone listening?</font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Sneaking up on the rails</font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Last week this column argued that Ashley Giles – everyone’s favourite new punchbag – deserved not to be written off on the basis of one Twenty20 shocker (just as he didn’t deserve a knighthood for England’s now forgotten victory over Sri Lanka). But the rumour mill is cranking into gear. What price a return to the coaching job for Peter Moores?</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Moores the merrier: Peter Moores, here in charge of Lancashire, is in the frame for a return as England coach\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"433\" id=\"i-afa10e9d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE7EA4D00000578-328_634x433.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Moores the merrier: Peter Moores, here in charge of Lancashire, is in the frame for a return as England coach</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">His supporters will tell you that the England dressing-room no longer contains Kevin Pietersen and Michael Vaughan, two of Moores’s greatest critics during his two years in charge. But it does contain three players – Alastair Cook, Ian Bell and Jimmy Anderson – who all rated Moores highly, and felt that extra-curricular dramas (read: KP) distracted him from the main job.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">One intriguing figure is Paul Collingwood, who was no fan of Moores’s intense coaching methods during his time as a player, but has recently found himself back in the inner sanctum as a part-time assistant and fielding coach. More crucial, perhaps, is Andy Flower – who replaced Moores in 2009 but swears by his methods after working as his No 2. Watch this space.</font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Pure sixism</font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Spare a thought for England’s women, who were trying to win a global tournament without the injured duo of strike bowler Katherine Brunt and off-spinner Laura Marsh. But that didn’t explain their main deficiency out in Bangladesh: an inability to clear the rope. Not once in six games did an England player hit a six.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No six appeal: England batsmen such as Charlotte Edwards (right) failed to clear the ropes at the World T20\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"325\" id=\"i-ab940e74\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE039F000000578-232_634x325.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">No six appeal: England batsmen such as Charlotte Edwards (right) failed to clear the ropes at the World T20</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">If you suspect this might be a failure of the women’s game in general, think again. There were 57 sixes in the women’s World Twenty20, and 18 were hit by the eventual champions Australia. In fact, only two of the 10 teams failed to clear the rope – England and Ireland. That England reached the final at all says plenty for their skill. But there is a gaping hole in the jigsaw.</font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Hold your horses!</font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Despair behind the scenes that the Pietersen message is trumping the ECB’s may have grown last week when Graeme Smith, KP’s captain at Surrey, spoke out in defence of his county colleague. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">And while the pro-KP camp leapt on Smith’s suggestion of poor management by the ECB as evidence that their man was hard done by, it may have been just as relevant to note one of Smith’s caveats. For he was honest enough to admit: ‘I’m uninformed at the moment, and speaking from an outsider’s perspective.’</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Quite.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"\'Outsider\'s perspective\': Graeme Smith spoke out in defence of his Surrey team-mate Kevin Pietersen\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"502\" id=\"i-ad860e87\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE1F50F00000578-175_634x502.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">\'Outsider\'s perspective\': Graeme Smith spoke out in defence of his Surrey team-mate Kevin Pietersen</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><br/></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598924/Kevin-Pietersen-set-Indian-Premier-League-Alastair-Cook-scores-39-Essex.html\"> Pietersen jets off to India for IPL as Cook returns to the crease after Ashes nightmare</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598739/Joe-Root-signs-two-year-contract-extension-Yorkshire.html\"> Root signs two-year extension to stay with Yorkshire through to 2016</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598348/James-Anderson-takes-five-Lancashire-England-hopefuls-struggle-opening-day-County-Championship.html\"> Anderson takes five but England hopefuls struggle on opening day of County Championship</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598206/Sri-Lanka-win-major-trophy-1996-defeat-India-World-T20.html\"> Sri Lanka legends Sangakkara and Jayawardene bow out in style with World Twenty20 triumph</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2598079/England-Women-slump-six-wicket-defeat-World-T20-final-against-superb-Aussies.html\"> England Women slump to six wicket defeat in World T20 final against superb Aussies</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2597800/England-captain-Charlotte-Edwards-dreams-Aussie-double-ahead-Womens-World-T20-final.html\"> England captain Edwards dreams of Aussie double ahead of Women\'s World T20 final</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"item\" data-track-module=\"am-external-links^external-links\" id=\"external-source-links\"> <span>Read more:</span> <ul> <li><a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"https://twitter.com/the_topspin\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://twitter.com/the_topspin</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2598932/THE-TOP-SPIN-Yuvrajs-tortuous-final-meltdown-just-Twenty20-favour-yes-really.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2598932/THE-TOP-SPIN-Yuvrajs-tortuous-final-meltdown-just-Twenty20-favour-yes-really.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"THE TOP SPIN: Yuvraj\'s tortuous final meltdown might just have done Twenty20 a favour (yes, really)\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2598932/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">5</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598932-1CE26A2300000578-225_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:58','2014-04-08 11:21:11'),(113,'c2e3ec4d1c07ccffb8fc821cb7d4459b7e742e0e080c8694757d2817eb7a3a9d','dailymail',NULL,'Power Rankings: Can Luis Suarez retain top spot after drawing a blank against West Ham United as team-mate Steven Gerrard scores twice?','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html',' By Dan Willis Follow @@danwillis23 and Ashley Clements Follow @@Ashley_Clements Published: 06:30 EST, 7 April 2014 | Updated: 08:13 EST, 7 April 2014 31 shares 13 View comments Liverpool\'s star striker Luis Suarez maintained his place at the top of our Power Rankings last week, but will his lack of goals against West Ham on Sunday count against him? Reds skipper Steven Gerrard scored his ninth and 10th penalties of the season, while Yaya Toure put in a spot-kick inspired performance of his own for Manchester City. Will the performance of Manchester United\'s January signing Juan Mata earn a place in the top 10 after a brace against Newcastle United on Saturday?  Unstoppable? Luis Suarez (left) tops the Power Rankings after an excellent performance against West Ham  Here, with football data analysts Kickdex, we assess which players have played the biggest role for their team over the past six games - either by helping them score or by stopping their opponents from scoring.  Everything that happens on the pitch is taken into account, from the easiest pass to the unluckiest deflection.  We\'ll reveal the top 10 players each Monday after a weekend of Premier League fixtures, as well as a top five breakdown of the four main positions.  Tricky: Suarez didn\'t score but earned his side a first half penalty after forcing James Tomkins into a handball At the double: Juan Mata score twice and grabbed an assist for Manchester Untied against Newcastle  More... Liverpool players furious as Carroll foul is shown on big screen moments after controversial goal is awarded... did West Ham break rules by replaying incident? MAD DOG ON MONDAY: Torres used to be like an F1 car but he\'s slowed down so it\'s time to let him go... and why I chose Woking over Bayern Munich Rodgers would love it if he could beat them to it... but unlike Keegan, the Liverpool boss is staying cool on the road to greatness JAMIE REDKNAPP: Toure, Lambert and Gerrard are the penalty perfectionists... but there\'s no point in practising spot-kicks before the World Cup Gerrard praises Liverpool resolve after Carroll foul leads to Hammers equaliser... but still isn\'t convinced they can win the title  10. Juan Mata (Manchester United) +32 Two goals and an assist during United\'s 4-0 win against Newcastle moves the Spaniard into the top 10. 9. Tim Howard (Everton) +2 The Everton goalkeeper grabbed another clean sheet as his side defeated Arsenal in the pivotal Premier League clash a Goodison Park. Howard made several excellent saves including keeping out a Lukas Podolski volley. 8. Jay Rodriguez (Southampton) -2 Sadly, the English striker\'s season looks to be over after a knee injury forced Rodriguez off at half-time. The knock comes at a terrible time for the 24-year-old who looks likely to miss out on the 2014 World Cup. 7. Nemanja Matic (Chelsea) +1 Chelsea\'s January signing put in another lung-busting performance for the west London side and even managed an assist - setting up Mohamed Salah for the first goal against Stoke.  Blow: Jay Rodriguez suffered a nasty looking knee injury which has cast doubt over a World Cup place    Spider: Chelsea\'s Nemanja Matic moved from eighth to seventh in the Power Rankings list  6. David Silva (Manchester City) +1 The Spanish maestro inspired City to another Premier League win and was key to his side\'s first half comeback after a Rickie Lambert penalty levelled the scoring.  Maestro: Manchester City midfielder David Silva put in another superb performance on Saturday  5. Martin Skrtel (Liverpool) +9 The Liverpool defender faced a difficult task on Sunday as he looked to battle West Ham striker Andy Carroll in the air at every opportunity. Skrtel passed the test and was vital to Liverpool\'s win.  Power: Youssouf Mulumbu enters the Power Ranking top 10 after West Brom\'s win against Norwich  4. Youssouf Mulumbu (West Brom) +9 The Congolese star put in a huge shift for the Baggies as Morgan Amalfitano grabbed the only goal to take all three points away from Carrow Road.  Captain fantastic: Steven Gerrard scored two penalties to hand Liverpool victory against West Ham    3. Steven Gerrard (Liverpool) +1 The Liverpool skipper has been in brilliant form this season and showed his class once again to score two penalties which inspired Liverpool to a vital win against West Ham. Gerrard also played a stunning 40-yard pass to Luis Suarez which lead to Liverpool\'s first spot-kick.  Form: Yaya Toure scored another penalty for Manchester City during their 4-1 win against Southampton  2. Yaya Toure (Manchester City) +2 Toure keeps hold of second spot after scoring his 18th Premier League goal of the season on Saturday as the Ivorian lead City to an impressive 4-1 win against Southampton. 1. Luis Suarez (Liverpool) The Uruguayan marksman retains his place at the top of this week\'s Power Ranking despite not actually scoring against West Ham on Sunday afternoon. Suarez was a constant threat to the Hammers\' defence and earned the first penalty of the game by being too quick for James Tomkins.  Leading the way: Suarez keeps his spot at the top of the Power Rankings after another excellent week     Engine room: Find out which players are the masters all over the pitch in our position-by-position breakdown    More... Liverpool players furious as Carroll foul is shown on big screen moments after controversial goal is awarded... did West Ham break rules by replaying incident? MAD DOG ON MONDAY: Torres used to be like an F1 car but he\'s slowed down so it\'s time to let him go... and why I chose Woking over Bayern Munich Rodgers would love it if he could beat them to it... but unlike Keegan, the Liverpool boss is staying cool on the road to greatness JAMIE REDKNAPP: Toure, Lambert and Gerrard are the penalty perfectionists... but there\'s no point in practising spot-kicks before the World Cup Gerrard praises Liverpool resolve after Carroll foul leads to Hammers equaliser... but still isn\'t convinced they can win the title  Share or comment on this article 31shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=Dan+Willis\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dan Willis</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@danwillis23\">Follow @@danwillis23</a> </span> and <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=Ashley+Clements\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ashley Clements</a> <span class=\"follow-author\"> <a class=\"twitter-follow-button twitter-follow-author\" data-show-count=\"false\" href=\"https://twitter.com/@Ashley_Clements\">Follow @@Ashley_Clements</a> </span> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 06:30 EST, 7 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 08:13 EST, 7 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Power Rankings: Can Suarez retain top spot after drawing a blank against West Ham as team-mate Gerrard scores twice?\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 31</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">13</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Liverpool\'s star striker Luis Suarez maintained his place at the top of our Power Rankings last week, but will his lack of goals against West Ham on Sunday count against him?<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Reds skipper Steven Gerrard scored his ninth and 10th penalties of the season, while Yaya Toure put in a spot-kick inspired performance of his own for Manchester City.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Will the performance of Manchester United\'s January signing Juan Mata earn a place in the top 10 after a brace against Newcastle United on Saturday?<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unstoppable? Luis Suarez (left) tops the Power Rankings after an excellent performance against West Ham\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"445\" id=\"i-ac570e83\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE3745A00000578-296_634x445.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unstoppable? Luis Suarez (left) tops the Power Rankings after an excellent performance against West Ham</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Here, with </font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">football data analysts </font><a href=\"http://www.kickdex.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" target=\"_blank\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Kickdex</font></a><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">, </font>we assess which players have played the biggest role for their team over the past six games - either by helping them score or by stopping their opponents from scoring.<br/></font></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Everything that happens on the pitch is taken into account, from the easiest pass to the unluckiest deflection.</font></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">We\'ll reveal the top 10 players each Monday after a weekend of Premier League fixtures, as well as a top five breakdown of the four main positions.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Tricky: Suarez didn\'t score but earned his side a first half penalty after forcing James Tomkins into a handball\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"379\" id=\"i-ad5f0e91\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE30CA600000578-538_634x379.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Tricky: Suarez didn\'t score but earned his side a first half penalty after forcing James Tomkins into a handball</p> </div><p> </p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"At the double: Juan Mata score twice and grabbed an assist for Manchester Untied against Newcastle\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"399\" id=\"i-af6a0ea5\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDC2CC400000578-593_634x399.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">At the double: Juan Mata score twice and grabbed an assist for Manchester Untied against Newcastle</p> </div><p> </p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598709/West-Ham-broke-Premier-League-rules-showing-replay-controversial-equaliser-against-Liverpool.html\"> Liverpool players furious as Carroll foul is shown on big screen moments after controversial goal is awarded... did West Ham break rules by replaying incident?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598376/MAD-DOG-ON-MONDAY-Torres-used-like-F1-car-hes-slowed-time-let-go.html\"> MAD DOG ON MONDAY: Torres used to be like an F1 car but he\'s slowed down so it\'s time to let him go... and why I chose Woking over Bayern Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598375/Rodgers-love-beat-unlike-Keegan-Liverpool-boss-staying-cool-road-greatness.html\"> Rodgers would love it if he could beat them to it... but unlike Keegan, the Liverpool boss is staying cool on the road to greatness</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598332/Jamie-Redknapp-Yaya-Toure-Rickie-Lambert-Steven-Gerrard-spot-kick-kings-theres-no-point-practicing-them.html\"> JAMIE REDKNAPP: Toure, Lambert and Gerrard are the penalty perfectionists... but there\'s no point in practising spot-kicks before the World Cup</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598282/Steven-Gerrard-praises-Liverpool-resolve-Andy-Carroll-foul-leads-West-Ham-equaliser-isnt-convinced-win-title.html\"> Gerrard praises Liverpool resolve after Carroll foul leads to Hammers equaliser... but still isn\'t convinced they can win the title</a></li> </ul> </div> <br/> </div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">10. Juan Mata (Manchester United) +32</font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Two goals and an assist during United\'s 4-0 win against Newcastle moves the Spaniard into the top 10.<br/></font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">9. Tim Howard (Everton) +2<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Everton goalkeeper grabbed another clean sheet as his side defeated Arsenal in the pivotal Premier League clash a Goodison Park. Howard made several excellent saves including keeping out a Lukas Podolski volley. <br/></font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">8. Jay Rodriguez (Southampton) -2<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Sadly, the English striker\'s season looks to be over after a knee injury forced Rodriguez off at half-time. The knock comes at a terrible time for the 24-year-old who looks likely to miss out on the 2014 World Cup.<br/></font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">7. Nemanja Matic (Chelsea) +1<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Chelsea\'s January signing put in another lung-busting performance for the west London side and even managed an assist - setting up Mohamed Salah for the first goal against Stoke.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Blow: Jay Rodriguez suffered a nasty looking knee injury which has cast doubt over a World Cup place\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"442\" id=\"i-af630e9c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDAB37E00000578-529_634x442.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Blow: Jay Rodriguez suffered a nasty looking knee injury which has cast doubt over a World Cup place</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Spider: Chelsea\'s Nemanja Matic moved from eighth to seventh in the Power Rankings list\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"386\" id=\"i-b0050ea8\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDCE4A700000578-757_634x386.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Spider: Chelsea\'s Nemanja Matic moved from eighth to seventh in the Power Rankings list</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">6. David Silva (Manchester City) +1<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Spanish maestro inspired City to another Premier League win and was key to his side\'s first half comeback after a Rickie Lambert penalty levelled the scoring.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Maestro: Manchester City midfielder David Silva put in another superb performance on Saturday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"449\" id=\"i-9fa30e56\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDB199700000578-45_634x449.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Maestro: Manchester City midfielder David Silva put in another superb performance on Saturday</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">5. Martin Skrtel (Liverpool) +9<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Liverpool defender faced a difficult task on Sunday as he looked to battle West Ham striker Andy Carroll in the air at every opportunity. Skrtel passed the test and was vital to Liverpool\'s win.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Power: Youssouf Mulumbu enters the Power Ranking top 10 after West Brom\'s win against Norwich\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-ae0b0e8d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDC54E500000578-482_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Power: Youssouf Mulumbu enters the Power Ranking top 10 after West Brom\'s win against Norwich</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">4. Youssouf Mulumbu (West Brom) +9<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Congolese star put in a huge shift for the Baggies as Morgan Amalfitano grabbed the only goal to take all three points away from Carrow Road.  <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Captain fantastic: Steven Gerrard scored two penalties to hand Liverpool victory against West Ham\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"335\" id=\"i-ab120e74\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE3469200000578-718_634x335.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Captain fantastic: Steven Gerrard scored two penalties to hand Liverpool victory against West Ham</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">3. Steven Gerrard (Liverpool) +1<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Liverpool skipper has been in brilliant form this season and showed his class once again to score two penalties which inspired Liverpool to a vital win against West Ham. Gerrard also played a stunning 40-yard pass to Luis Suarez which lead to Liverpool\'s first spot-kick.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Form: Yaya Toure scored another penalty for Manchester City during their 4-1 win against Southampton\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"484\" id=\"i-a1df0e6c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CDAAC5500000578-94_634x484.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Form: Yaya Toure scored another penalty for Manchester City during their 4-1 win against Southampton</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">2. Yaya Toure (Manchester City) +2<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Toure keeps hold of second spot after scoring his 18th Premier League goal of the season on Saturday as the Ivorian lead City to an impressive 4-1 win against Southampton. <br/></font></p>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">1. Luis Suarez (Liverpool) <br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Uruguayan marksman retains his place at the top of this week\'s Power Ranking despite not actually scoring against West Ham on Sunday afternoon. Suarez was a constant threat to the Hammers\' defence and earned the first penalty of the game by being too quick for James Tomkins.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Power Ranking\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"788\" id=\"i-b05d0eab\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE6EF8C00000578-371_306x788.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Top stuff: Luis Suarez\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"788\" id=\"i-acae0e89\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE39E2400000578-446_306x788.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Leading the way: Suarez keeps his spot at the top of the Power Rankings after another excellent week<br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Engine room: Find out which players are the masters all over the pitch in our position-by-position breakdown\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"869\" id=\"i-acf00e8d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE6F05700000578-175_634x869.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Engine room: Find out which players are the masters all over the pitch in our position-by-position breakdown</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598709/West-Ham-broke-Premier-League-rules-showing-replay-controversial-equaliser-against-Liverpool.html\"> Liverpool players furious as Carroll foul is shown on big screen moments after controversial goal is awarded... did West Ham break rules by replaying incident?</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598376/MAD-DOG-ON-MONDAY-Torres-used-like-F1-car-hes-slowed-time-let-go.html\"> MAD DOG ON MONDAY: Torres used to be like an F1 car but he\'s slowed down so it\'s time to let him go... and why I chose Woking over Bayern Munich</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598375/Rodgers-love-beat-unlike-Keegan-Liverpool-boss-staying-cool-road-greatness.html\"> Rodgers would love it if he could beat them to it... but unlike Keegan, the Liverpool boss is staying cool on the road to greatness</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598332/Jamie-Redknapp-Yaya-Toure-Rickie-Lambert-Steven-Gerrard-spot-kick-kings-theres-no-point-practicing-them.html\"> JAMIE REDKNAPP: Toure, Lambert and Gerrard are the penalty perfectionists... but there\'s no point in practising spot-kicks before the World Cup</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2598282/Steven-Gerrard-praises-Liverpool-resolve-Andy-Carroll-foul-leads-West-Ham-equaliser-isnt-convinced-win-title.html\"> Gerrard praises Liverpool resolve after Carroll foul leads to Hammers equaliser... but still isn\'t convinced they can win the title</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/Power-Rankings-Can-Luis-Suarez-retain-spot-drawing-blank-against-West-Ham-United-team-mate-Steven-Gerrard-scores-twice.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Power Rankings: Can Suarez retain top spot after drawing a blank against West Ham as team-mate Gerrard scores twice?\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2598707/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">31</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598707-1CE787E600000578-874_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:58:59','2014-04-07 15:13:59'),(114,'c05ad0a0abb65663fa243ae8eb36cc8352e96cfbd7f14e3c412ec28abc1420cf','dailymail',NULL,'MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html',' Mauricio Pochettino did not think Manchester City should have been awarded a penalty so early in the gameSunderland fielded an ineligible player, Ji Dong-won, for five matches, but lost no points and somehow kept the matter secretThe Carlos Tevez case was a landmark because it sums up the way football administration has changedClubs do not wish to be told what to do, on or off the field; they just want help in doing as they pleaseThe jockeys were ready at the appropriate time at the Grand National; it was the starter who needed to get his act together By Martin Samuel - Sport Published: 18:04 EST, 6 April 2014 | Updated: 02:12 EST, 7 April 2014 17 shares 70 View comments Mauricio Pochettino, the Southampton manager, did not want a referee at Manchester City on Saturday. He wanted a facilitator. It is football’s modern way. Rules are out, game management is in; regulation is out, assistance is in; black and white is out, the Wild West is in. The clubs do not wish to be told what to do, on or off the field; they just want help in doing as they please. So a foul is not a foul, a contract is not a contract and paperwork is for the little people in the leagues below — or merely a basis for negotiation. Leave aside Pochettino’s complaint about Manchester City’s second goal being offside. Yes it was, by some distance. A huge mistake by the linesman. Very unfortunate, but they happen and there really is no way around it unless we rewind the film every time a goal is scored to see if some minor infringement occurred in the build-up. The game would be delayed, and goals could be wiped off but not added on — so we would cure one form of injustice, but create another.  Contentious: Manchester City\'s second goal, scored by Samir Nasri, was clearly offside   Flick: Edin Dzeko played Yaya Toure\'s pass (above) into the path of Silva, who was yards offside   Wild thing: Mauricio Pochettino was livid that the goal was given after seeing his team push City all the way Pochettino: It seemed like the type of decision you get at school  Time to come clean over KP Alastair Cook hopes he will be able to explain precisely why Kevin Pietersen was sacked at some date in the future. He implies there is much more that is not known, that cannot be known, for now. So was Pietersen an MI5 spy? Was he engaged in counter-espionage? Are there agents in the field that could be placed at risk by Cook’s disclosures, their cover blown? For if Pietersen was simply a gifted but high-maintenance cricketer, who fell out with a lot of team-mates, stopped scoring prolifically and was ultimately considered too much trouble, then this mutual confidentiality agreement is ludicrous and  Cook should stop the secret-squirrel act and front up. No, it is Pochettino’s complaint about City’s first goal that tells us about the nature of modern football. That third-minute penalty. Edin Dzeko goes past Southampton defender Jose Fonte at pace. He beats him so comprehensively that he actually runs outside Fonte, who now has his back to the player. So Fonte sticks out a leg behind him, as if drawing it back to shoot, and brings down Dzeko. This is the judgment call that Pochettino finds so objectionable. ‘I don’t think you can give a penalty like that after just two minutes,’ he says. It’s an interesting take on the laws of the game. Anything goes, as long as it happens early enough. Kick who you like, trip who you like, just make sure you get it done quick. Football for 80 minutes, Rollerball the first 10. Inexplicable, Pochettino called the penalty. And there is a lot that needs explaining these days.Take the saga at Sunderland, who fielded an ineligible player, Ji Dong-won, for five matches, but lost no points and somehow kept the matter secret. Just as Pochettino wanted Chris Foy to manage his game so that early infringements had no consequence, so the Premier League did not even deduct the single point Sunderland had gained (against Southampton) from Ji Dong-won’s appearances. Just as they ignored the impact Carlos Tevez had on West Ham’s survival in 2006-07.  Leg up: Jose Fonte fouls Dzeko for the penalty... which Pochettino said happened too early in the game   No question: Referee Chris Foy points to the spot, with Yaya Toure duly converting the subsequent penalty   No penalty: Sunderland have avoided a points deduction for fielding Ji Dong-won, an ineligible player, for four Premier League matches  More... Pochettino so angry at offside Nasri goal that \'killed\' the game he gives first interview in English since arriving last January Man City 4-1 Southampton: Pellegrini\'s men close gap on Liverpool with comfortable win Baggies furious after Sunderland escape points deduction for fielding illegal player Sunderland say case is closed after playing Ji when he was ineligible... but rivals say Black Cats are lucky to escape with a fine Crooks charter: Football fears the worst after fraudster Cellino is given go-ahead for £35m takeover at Leeds 39 of the 40 Grand National jockeys in revolt over race\'s manic start The Tevez case really is a landmark because it sums up the way football administration has changed. In a key revelation from the time, Premier League chief executive Richard Scudamore explained what would have happened had West Ham not lied about the third party ownership portion of Tevez’s contract and instead presented it to the league. Nothing. Tevez would still have been registered a West Ham player before the transfer deadline, would still have been free to make his debut that weekend, but then on Monday, the league’s lawyers and the club’s representatives would have met and redrafted the contract in a form that was acceptable. They would have facilitated West Ham’s aim. This is not Scudamore’s fault. He is employed by the 20 Premier League chairmen and provides the service they desire. If they wanted a tough administrator, he could be that, too. They don’t. They want someone to look kindly on their indiscretions and sort out any complications, so that if Sunderland end up with a player in the team who has not received international clearance, it is viewed benignly as a misunderstanding, not an offence. The Premier League were even sending media guidance letters around this weekend, explaining Sunderland’s position in the mildest terms, that Ji Dong-won was correctly registered with them, and with FIFA, but then went on loan to Augsburg in Germany, and it was only on his return that he dropped off the international list.  Carlito\'s way: Carlos Tevez remains a hero at West Ham after scoring this goal on the final day of the 2006-07 season at Old Trafford to preserve the club\'s top flight status   Hammer of the year: Tevez was a huge hit in east London, but his tenure at Upton Park saw the club fined £5.5million after being found guilty of acting improperly and withholding vital documentation  More from Martin Samuel - Sport...   MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football 06/04/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: How can you NOT blame Giles for English cricket\'s latest shambles? 01/04/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: Ferguson had to pick a successor or tell United to get stuffed. It was an easy choice... he wanted to leave the club in safe hands 30/03/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: Michel Platini is the unstoppable idiot... his latest crazy plan will destroy brilliant Euros 27/03/14   Benzema to Arsenal, Kroos to United and Costa to Chelsea? Get real, big stars don\'t come to the Premier League any more 26/03/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: Platini\'s secret plan to alienate the England faithful with plot to change the way YOU watch football... and he doesn\'t care 25/03/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: The proof FIFA gave the 2022 World Cup to sponsors of terror 23/03/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: New Qatar controversy as World Cup hosts are linked to terrorism 18/03/14   MARTIN SAMUEL: The truth about Trott is that the ECB are the best spinners of all 16/03/14   VIEW FULL ARCHIVE ‘Sunderland officials maintain that they did correctly fill out the online form and that it was a technical error rather than them being at fault,’ the League stated. So they filled it in, but forgot to press send. Try that one with the Inland Revenue if your tax returns don’t arrive next January. Sunderland are not in the same realm as West Ham in 2007. There was genuine deception over Tevez, whereas what happened with Ji Dong-won seems more of a cock-up, but the response is the same. Just as the independent adjudicators did not want to take points from West Ham — or Sheffield United, Watford, Manchester United and Everton, who all entered into gentleman’s agreements amounting to third-party interference that season — so Sunderland’s punishment was kept under wraps, and was met by writing an insubstantial cheque. An easy solution would be simple, and finite. Every match that Tevez played, every match that Ji Dong-won played, three points awarded to the opposition. Sunderland were so poor at the start of the season that they would only be a point worse off — and opponents Southampton’s two additional points would not alter their League position at all. Yet, the League did not know this at the time. They were gambling that this would not come back to haunt them, as it did with Tevez. One club at the bottom is now considering its legal position, but the interesting aspect is none of the others are — including Southampton. As long as it does not directly affect them, they are happy for the Wild West show to continue just as it is.   Indeed, the last time Scudamore tried to outlaw loan signings, the chairmen not only voted against it but added some of the loan-market rules to permanent transfers; this is why Stephen Ireland couldn’t play for Stoke City against Aston Villa last month.  Inexplicable: Pochettino mocked up as the man with no name from Sergio Leone\'s Dollars trilogy  The next stage, and it is already here, is for the actual games to be refereed along these lines. Managed, not regulated, handled, not administered. Inexplicable, Pochettino called it. For someone who claims to speak little English, he got that much right.  Craven council is destroying Glasgow’s reputation crashes There is a reason April Fools’ Day hoaxes in newspapers rarely work these days. Our modern reality is more outlandish than anything a prankster can dream up. For instance: as part of the opening ceremony for the Commonwealth Games this summer, five of Glasgow’s Red Road tower blocks will be blown up, and the demolition beamed around the world. The stunt will last 15 seconds and will obliterate homes that once housed close to 5,000 people. As the Red Road flats were inhabited from 1966, that is a lot of memories, a lot of love and laughter that will go up in smoke for the temporary amusement of a global television audience.  Iconic: The Red Road flats will be demolished as part of the Commonwealth Games opening ceremony   Up in smoke: Five of the six tower blocks will be demolished - a ritual which will take just 15 seconds  Eileen Gallagher, chair of the Glasgow 2014 Ceremonies, Culture and Queen’s Baton Relay Committee, said: ‘By sharing the final moments of the Red Road flats with the world, Glasgow is proving it is a city that is proud of its history but doesn’t stand still, a city that is constantly regenerating, renewing and re-inventing itself.’ No it isn’t. It is proving that the organisers of its Games are crass, unfeeling and will do anything for publicity, and that its council thinks nothing of housing its citizens in asbestos-riddled  high-rise hutches, which it then randomly detonates as if the whole exercise was an episode of Game For A Laugh. The Red Road flats may have ended up horrible places to live, but the former residents deserve to see them demolished with dignity and respect for their existence, not in the manner of some prank by Jeremy Beadle. Asylum seekers now occupy the sixth block which will remain standing. What message does the collapse of all around them send about the attitude of their adopted country? That it houses its newest citizens in homes that are little better than rubble. The joke is on them — and live on television, too.  Reduced to rubble: The Red Road flats will no longer be a feature of Glasgow\'s skyline   Final inspection: workers inspect the flats in north Glasgow before their live demolition  The world will be watching, according to the organisers, and this being the Commonwealth Games that audience will include people affected by war or extreme forces of nature, such as tropical storms and hurricanes; people who might look at the Red Road flats, compare their own humble living conditions, and wonder why this wealthy European nation is blowing up what would appear perfectly decent forms of shelter. A lot of the food we consume in the west is unhealthy, too. Yet we wouldn’t dump it on a fire in front of people who are starving, because that would be grossly insensitive. This stunt says nothing about the new Glasgow, but all too much about the craven nature of the city’s council overseers.  And while we\'re at it The start of the Grand National was the usual fiasco and now 39 of its 40 riders face action for approaching the start before being  officially called forward. Only Brendan Powell, whose stubborn mount Battle Group refused to race, has escaped. The jockeys are in open revolt over the prospect of sanction and the mess now moves to the British Horseracing Authority’s headquarters in London. There remains an unhealthy attitude that racing is a gentlemen’s sport, and riders are no better than staff. They need to be put in their place.  Questioned: Jockeys were asked why they had approached the tape before the starter invited them   On your marks: The starter attempts to get the Grand National underway  Yet what was the problem? It was 4.15pm. Time to go. If your horse won’t move or is facing the wrong way when the race is due to begin, tough. They’re off. The jockeys were ready at the appropriate time; it was the starter who needed to get his act together.  If Tess Daly and Claudia Winkleman don’t get the Strictly Come Dancing gig, will there be an outcry about sexism on Charlotte Moore’s watch at BBC1? It wasn’t so long ago that Moore, the channel controller, was advocating that women should have a dedicated role on Match of the Day — presumably in a pundit’s seat, as the presenter’s chair is already occupied by Gary Lineker.  Double act: Bruce Forsyth is leaving Tess Daly\'s side after 11 years of Strictly Come Dancing   Options: Claudia Winkleman has been touted as Forsyth\'s replacement, as has the impish Graham Norton  Now it gets interesting. Daly and Winkleman have been fronting Strictly’s Sunday results show with charisma and professional ease for several years now. They would be the obvious choices to take over on Saturday, too, now that Sir Bruce Forsyth has stood down. Yet, suddenly, Graham Norton has been installed as favourite to anchor the show. Why? What is wrong with two women hosting on Saturday prime time — or do Moore’s principles only extend to hitching a ride on the latest bandwagon?  Damian Collins (Conservative, Folkestone and Hythe) submitted a private member’s bill to the House of Commons last week calling for an extension to football’s fit and proper persons’ test. As the one that exists would appear to be worthless, following the decision of Tim Kerr QC to overturn the Football League’s ban on Massimo Cellino buying Leeds United, he has his work cut out, but still. Collins would give the Football Association power to reject any owner whose influence would not be healthy for the game. Corrupt or untrustworthy people could be banned, whether or not they can skirt around the official criteria.  Convicted fraudster: Massimo Cellino is the new owner of Leeds United despite a chequered past   Expenses cheat: Maria Miller gave a 32-second apology in the House of Parliament for overclaiming mortgage costs  A fine idea, but why stop there? Corrupt or untrustworthy people who inexplicably escape significant official sanction exist in every walk of life. Say one became Minister for Culture, Media and Sport, for instance. Say that person was the type who fiddled her expenses, attempted to use her power and influence to bully the watchdog conducting the investigation into  her offence and even had a two-bob lickspittle making threats to journalists working on the story? Well, that sort of person is the last that should be in authority, and we could act accordingly. It really is a super idea. Unless, of course, Collins knows the separation in principle between Cellino, convicted fraudster and now owner of Leeds, and Maria Miller, exposed expenses cheat and Minister for Culture, Media and Sport. ‘Capable of using every kind of deception,’ the arrest  warrant said of Cellino. And the difference is?   More... Pochettino so angry at offside Nasri goal that \'killed\' the game he gives first interview in English since arriving last January Man City 4-1 Southampton: Pellegrini\'s men close gap on Liverpool with comfortable win Baggies furious after Sunderland escape points deduction for fielding illegal player Sunderland say case is closed after playing Ji when he was ineligible... but rivals say Black Cats are lucky to escape with a fine Crooks charter: Football fears the worst after fraudster Cellino is given go-ahead for £35m takeover at Leeds 39 of the 40 Grand National jockeys in revolt over race\'s manic start  Share or comment on this article 17shares','\n<ul class=\"article-summary sport\"><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Mauricio Pochettino did not think Manchester City should have been awarded a penalty so early in the game</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Sunderland fielded an ineligible player, Ji Dong-won, for five matches, but lost no points and somehow kept the matter secret</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">The Carlos Tevez case was a landmark because it sums up the way football administration has changed</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Clubs do not wish to be told what to do, on or off the field; they just want help in doing as they please</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">The jockeys were ready at the appropriate time at the Grand National; it was the starter who needed to get his act together</font></b></li></ul>\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1020688/Martin-Samuel---Sport.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Martin Samuel - Sport</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 18:04 EST, 6 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 02:12 EST, 7 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 17</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">70</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Mauricio Pochettino, the Southampton manager, did not want a referee at Manchester City on Saturday. He wanted a facilitator. It is football’s modern way. Rules are out, game management is in; regulation is out, assistance is in; black and white is out, the Wild West is in. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The clubs do not wish to be told what to do, on or off the field; they just want help in doing as they please. So a foul is not a foul, a contract is not a contract and paperwork is for the little people in the leagues below — or merely a basis for negotiation.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Leave aside Pochettino’s complaint about Manchester City’s second goal being offside. Yes it was, by some distance. A huge mistake by the linesman. Very unfortunate, but they happen and there really is no way around it unless we rewind the film every time a goal is scored to see if some minor infringement occurred in the build-up. The game would be delayed, and goals could be wiped off but not added on — so we would cure one form of injustice, but create another.</font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Contentious: Manchester City\'s second goal, scored by Samir Nasri, was clearly offside\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"469\" id=\"i-60070d55\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDABD1500000578-912_634x469.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Contentious: Manchester City\'s second goal, scored by Samir Nasri, was clearly offside</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Flick: Edin Dzeko played Yaya Toure\'s pass (above) into the path of Silva, who was yards offside\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"459\" id=\"i-61120d5d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDABD0D00000578-322_634x459.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Flick: Edin Dzeko played Yaya Toure\'s pass (above) into the path of Silva, who was yards offside</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Wild thing: Mauricio Pochettino was livid that the goal was given after seeing his team push City all the way\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5e7d0d41\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDB0D8100000578-925_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Wild thing: Mauricio Pochettino was livid that the goal was given after seeing his team push City all the way</p><div class=\"moduleFull\"><a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3434760786001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Pochettino: It seemed like the type of decision you get at school</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/05/video-undefined-1CDBEE0A00000578-66_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>Time to come clean over KP</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p> <font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Alastair Cook hopes he will be able to explain precisely why Kevin Pietersen was sacked at some date in the future. <br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He implies there is much more that is not known, that cannot be known, for now. <br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">So was Pietersen an MI5 spy? Was he engaged in counter-espionage? Are there agents in the field that could be placed at risk by Cook’s disclosures, their cover blown? </font><br/></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">For if Pietersen was simply a gifted but high-maintenance cricketer, who fell out with a lot of team-mates, stopped scoring prolifically and was ultimately considered too much trouble, then this mutual confidentiality agreement is ludicrous and  <br/></font></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Cook should stop the secret-squirrel act and front up.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">No, it is Pochettino’s complaint about City’s first goal that tells us about the nature of modern football. That third-minute penalty. Edin Dzeko goes past Southampton defender Jose Fonte at pace. He beats him so comprehensively that he actually runs outside Fonte, who now has his back to the player. So Fonte sticks out a leg behind him, as if drawing it back to shoot, and brings down Dzeko. This is the judgment call that Pochettino finds so objectionable. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">‘I don’t think you can give a penalty like that after just two minutes,’ he says. It’s an interesting take on the laws of the game. Anything goes, as long as it happens early enough. Kick who you like, trip who you like, just make sure you get it done quick. Football for 80 minutes, Rollerball the first 10. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Inexplicable, Pochettino called the penalty. And there is a lot that needs explaining these days.</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Take the saga at Sunderland, who fielded an ineligible player, Ji Dong-won, for five matches, but lost no points and somehow kept the matter secret.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Just as Pochettino wanted Chris Foy to manage his game so that early infringements had no consequence, so the Premier League did not even deduct the single point Sunderland had gained (against Southampton) from Ji Dong-won’s appearances. Just as they ignored the impact Carlos Tevez had on West Ham’s survival in 2006-07.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Leg up: Jose Fonte fouls Dzeko for the penalty... which Pochettino said happened too early in the game\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"470\" id=\"i-5e0e0d3b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDAA25400000578-703_634x470.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Leg up: Jose Fonte fouls Dzeko for the penalty... which Pochettino said happened too early in the game</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No question: Referee Chris Foy points to the spot, with Yaya Toure duly converting the subsequent penalty\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"417\" id=\"i-5ffb0d50\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDAA4C600000578-543_634x417.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">No question: Referee Chris Foy points to the spot, with Yaya Toure duly converting the subsequent penalty</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No penalty: Sunderland have avoided a points deduction for fielding Ji Dong-won, an ineligible player, for four Premier League matches\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"412\" id=\"i-5f320d47\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CCEA36600000578-982_634x412.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">No penalty: Sunderland have avoided a points deduction for fielding Ji Dong-won, an ineligible player, for four Premier League matches</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597668/Pochettino-angry-offside-Nasri-goal-killed-game-gives-interview-English-arriving-January.html\"> Pochettino so angry at offside Nasri goal that \'killed\' the game he gives first interview in English since arriving last January</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597612/Man-City-4-1-Southampton-match-report-Pellegrinis-men-close-gap-Liverpool-comfortable-win.html\"> Man City 4-1 Southampton: Pellegrini\'s men close gap on Liverpool with comfortable win</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597325/Baggies-furious-Sunderland-escape-points-deduction-fielding-illegal-player.html\"> Baggies furious after Sunderland escape points deduction for fielding illegal player</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596994/Sunderland-say-case-closed-playing-Ji-Dong-won-ineligible.html\"> Sunderland say case is closed after playing Ji when he was ineligible... but rivals say Black Cats are lucky to escape with a fine</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597913/Crooks-charter-Football-fears-worst-fraudster-Cellino-given-ahead-35m-takeover-Leeds.html\"> Crooks charter: Football fears the worst after fraudster Cellino is given go-ahead for £35m takeover at Leeds</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/racing/article-2597916/39-40-Grand-National-jockeys-revolt-races-manic-start.html\"> 39 of the 40 Grand National jockeys in revolt over race\'s manic start</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Tevez case really is a landmark because it sums up the way football administration has changed. In a key revelation from the time, Premier League chief executive Richard Scudamore explained what would have happened had West Ham not lied about the third party ownership portion of Tevez’s contract and instead presented it to the league. Nothing. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Tevez would still have been registered a West Ham player before the transfer deadline, would still have been free to make his debut that weekend, but then on Monday, the league’s lawyers and the club’s representatives would have met and redrafted the contract in a form that was acceptable. They would have facilitated West Ham’s aim.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">This is not Scudamore’s fault. He is employed by the 20 Premier League chairmen and provides the service they desire. If they wanted a tough administrator, he could be that, too. They don’t. They want someone to look kindly on their indiscretions and sort out any complications, so that if Sunderland end up with a player in the team who has not received international clearance, it is viewed benignly as a misunderstanding, not an offence. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Premier League were even sending media guidance letters around this weekend, explaining Sunderland’s position in the mildest terms, that Ji Dong-won was correctly registered with them, and with FIFA, but then went on loan to Augsburg in Germany, and it was only on his return that he dropped off the international list. </font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Carlito\'s way: Carlos Tevez remains a hero at West Ham after scoring this goal on the final day of the 2006-07 season at Old Trafford to preserve the club\'s top flight status\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"427\" id=\"i-5aa20d29\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-00973B49000004B0-878_634x427.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Carlito\'s way: Carlos Tevez remains a hero at West Ham after scoring this goal on the final day of the 2006-07 season at Old Trafford to preserve the club\'s top flight status</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Hammer of the year: Tevez was a huge hit in east London, but his tenure at Upton Park saw the club fined £5.5million after being found guilty of acting improperly and withholding vital documentation\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"463\" id=\"i-5c070d31\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-00888DE4000004B0-417_634x463.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Hammer of the year: Tevez was a huge hit in east London, but his tenure at Upton Park saw the club fined £5.5million after being found guilty of acting improperly and withholding vital documentation</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"item\"> <div class=\"columnist-archive-narrow bogr1\"> <span class=\"tl\"> </span> <span class=\"tr\"> </span> <h3>More from Martin Samuel - Sport...</h3> <ul> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football</a> <span class=\"date\">06/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/article-2594517/How-NOT-blame-Ashley-Giles-English-crickets-latest-shambles-Martin-Samuel.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: How can you NOT blame Giles for English cricket\'s latest shambles?</a> <span class=\"date\">01/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/article-2592983/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Ferguson-pick-successor-tell-United-stuffed-It-easy-choice.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: Ferguson had to pick a successor or tell United to get stuffed. It was an easy choice... he wanted to leave the club in safe hands</a> <span class=\"date\">30/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2591032/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Michel-Platini-unstoppable-idiot-latest-crazy-plan-destroy-international-football.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: Michel Platini is the unstoppable idiot... his latest crazy plan will destroy brilliant Euros</a> <span class=\"date\">27/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2589675/Benzema-Arsenal-Kroos-United-Costa-Chelsea-Get-real-big-stars-dont-come-Premier-League-more.html\">Benzema to Arsenal, Kroos to United and Costa to Chelsea? Get real, big stars don\'t come to the Premier League any more</a> <span class=\"date\">26/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/article-2589313/Platinis-secret-plan-alienate-England-faithful-plot-change-way-YOU-watch-football-doesnt-care.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: Platini\'s secret plan to alienate the England faithful with plot to change the way YOU watch football... and he doesn\'t care</a> <span class=\"date\">25/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/worldcup2014/article-2587476/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Proof-FIFA-gave-2022-World-Cup-sponsors-terror.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: The proof FIFA gave the 2022 World Cup to sponsors of terror</a> <span class=\"date\">23/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/worldcup2014/article-2583721/MARTIN-SAMUEL-The-World-Cup-hosts-bed-terrorists.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: New Qatar controversy as World Cup hosts are linked to terrorism</a> <span class=\"date\">18/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/cricket/article-2582182/MARTIN-SAMUEL-COLUMN-Truth-Jonathan-Trott-depression-ECB-best-spinners-all.html\">MARTIN SAMUEL: The truth about Trott is that the ECB are the best spinners of all</a> <span class=\"date\">16/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"columnist-1020688/Martin-Samuel---Sport.html\">VIEW FULL ARCHIVE</a> </li> </ul> </div> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">‘Sunderland officials maintain that they did correctly fill out the online form and that it was a technical error rather than them being at fault,’ the League stated. So they filled it in, but forgot to press send. Try that one with the Inland Revenue if your tax returns don’t arrive next January.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Sunderland are not in the same realm as West Ham in 2007. There was genuine deception over Tevez, whereas what happened with Ji Dong-won seems more of a cock-up, but the response is the same. Just as the independent adjudicators did not want to take points from West Ham — or Sheffield United, Watford, Manchester United and Everton, who all entered into gentleman’s agreements amounting to third-party interference that season — so Sunderland’s punishment was kept under wraps, and was met by writing an insubstantial cheque.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">An easy solution would be simple, and finite. Every match that Tevez played, every match that Ji Dong-won played, three points awarded to the opposition. Sunderland were so poor at the start of the season that they would only be a point worse off — and opponents Southampton’s two additional points would not alter their League position at all. Yet, the League did not know this at the time. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They were gambling that this would not come back to haunt them, as it did with Tevez. One club at the bottom is now considering its legal position, but the interesting aspect is none of the others are — including Southampton. As long as it does not directly affect them, they are happy for the Wild West show to continue just as it is. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Indeed, the last time Scudamore tried to outlaw loan signings, the chairmen not only voted against it but added some of the loan-market rules to permanent transfers; this is why Stephen Ireland couldn’t play for Stoke City against Aston Villa last month.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Inexplicable: Pochettino mocked up as the man with no name from Sergio Leone\'s Dollars trilogy\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"487\" id=\"i-ac5a0e8a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/07/article-2598362-1CE3912F00000578-893_634x487.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Inexplicable: Pochettino mocked up as the man with no name from Sergio Leone\'s Dollars trilogy</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The next stage, and it is already here, is for the actual games to be refereed along these lines. Managed, not regulated, handled, not administered. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Inexplicable, Pochettino called it. For someone who claims to speak little English, he got that much right.</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Craven council is destroying Glasgow’s reputation crashes</font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There is a reason April Fools’ Day hoaxes in newspapers rarely work these days. Our modern reality is more outlandish than anything a prankster can dream up. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">For instance: as part of the opening ceremony for the Commonwealth Games this summer, five of Glasgow’s Red Road tower blocks will be blown up, and the demolition beamed around the world.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The stunt will last 15 seconds and will obliterate homes that once housed close to 5,000 people. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As the Red Road flats were inhabited from 1966, that is a lot of memories, a lot of love and laughter that will go up in smoke for the temporary amusement of a global television audience. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Iconic: The Red Road flats will be demolished as part of the Commonwealth Games opening ceremony\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"416\" id=\"i-4fcf0cf6\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CD7296000000578-64_634x416.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Iconic: The Red Road flats will be demolished as part of the Commonwealth Games opening ceremony</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Up in smoke: Five of the six tower blocks will be demolished - a ritual which will take just 15 seconds\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"419\" id=\"i-5b400d22\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CD6461500000578-140_634x419.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Up in smoke: Five of the six tower blocks will be demolished - a ritual which will take just 15 seconds</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Eileen Gallagher, chair of the Glasgow 2014 Ceremonies, Culture and Queen’s Baton Relay Committee, said: ‘By sharing the final moments of the Red Road flats with the world, Glasgow is proving it is a city that is proud of its history but doesn’t stand still, a city that is constantly regenerating, renewing and re-inventing itself.’ <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">No it isn’t. It is proving that the organisers of its Games are crass, unfeeling and will do anything for publicity, and that its council thinks nothing of housing its citizens in asbestos-riddled  high-rise hutches, which it then randomly detonates as if the whole exercise was an episode of <i>Game For A Laugh</i>.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The Red Road flats may have ended up horrible places to live, but the former residents deserve to see them demolished with dignity and respect for their existence, not in the manner of some prank by Jeremy Beadle. Asylum seekers now occupy the sixth block which will remain standing. What message does the collapse of all around them send about the attitude of their adopted country? That it houses its newest citizens in homes that are little better than rubble. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The joke is on them — and live on television, too.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Reduced to rubble: The Red Road flats will no longer be a feature of Glasgow\'s skyline\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"418\" id=\"i-5d560d3a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CD645B500000578-374_634x418.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Reduced to rubble: The Red Road flats will no longer be a feature of Glasgow\'s skyline</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Final inspection: workers inspect the flats in north Glasgow before their live demolition\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-5f430d46\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CCE9C6100000578-590_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Final inspection: workers inspect the flats in north Glasgow before their live demolition</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The world will be watching, according to the organisers, and this being the Commonwealth Games that audience will include people affected by war or extreme forces of nature, such as tropical storms and hurricanes; people who might look at the Red Road flats, compare their own humble living conditions, and wonder why this wealthy European nation is blowing up what would appear perfectly decent forms of shelter. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">A lot of the food we consume in the west is unhealthy, too. Yet we wouldn’t dump it on a fire in front of people who are starving, because that would be grossly insensitive. This stunt says nothing about the new Glasgow, but all too much about the craven nature of the city’s council overseers.</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<h2>And while we\'re at it</h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The start of the Grand National was the usual fiasco and now 39 of its 40 riders face action for approaching the start before being  officially called forward. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Only Brendan Powell, whose stubborn mount Battle Group refused to race, has escaped. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The jockeys are in open revolt over the prospect of sanction and the mess now moves to the British Horseracing Authority’s headquarters in London. There remains an unhealthy attitude that racing is a gentlemen’s sport, and riders are no better than staff. They need to be put in their place.</font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Questioned: Jockeys were asked why they had approached the tape before the starter invited them\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-509d0cfe\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDE400300000578-97_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Questioned: Jockeys were asked why they had approached the tape before the starter invited them</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"On your marks: The starter attempts to get the Grand National underway\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"286\" id=\"i-5feb0d54\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CDC11FE00000578-227_634x286.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">On your marks: The starter attempts to get the Grand National underway</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Yet what was the problem? It was 4.15pm. Time to go. If your horse won’t move or is facing the wrong way when the race is due to begin, tough. They’re off. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The jockeys were ready at the appropriate time; it was the starter who needed to get his act together.</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><p> </p></font></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"> If Tess Daly and Claudia Winkleman don’t get the <i>Strictly Come Dancing</i> gig, will there be an outcry about sexism on Charlotte Moore’s watch at BBC1? </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It wasn’t so long ago that Moore, the channel controller, was advocating that women should have a dedicated role on <i>Match of the Day</i> — presumably in a pundit’s seat, as the presenter’s chair is already occupied by Gary Lineker. </font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Double act: Bruce Forsyth is leaving Tess Daly\'s side after 11 years of Strictly Come Dancing\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-60620d53\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CD5CE2F00000578-228_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Double act: Bruce Forsyth is leaving Tess Daly\'s side after 11 years of Strictly Come Dancing</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"In the hunt: Claudia Winkleman\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5d720d44\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-15685E0E000005DC-874_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Favourite: Graham Norton\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-615c0d5d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CC9FC7D00000578-469_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Options: Claudia Winkleman has been touted as Forsyth\'s replacement, as has the impish Graham Norton<br/></p></div> <p> </p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Now it gets interesting. Daly and Winkleman have been fronting <i>Strictly’s</i> Sunday results show with charisma and professional ease for several years now. They would be the obvious choices to take over on Saturday, too, now that Sir Bruce Forsyth has stood down. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Yet, suddenly, Graham Norton has been installed as favourite to anchor the show. Why? What is wrong with two women hosting on Saturday prime time — or do Moore’s principles only extend to hitching a ride on the latest bandwagon?</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Damian Collins (Conservative, Folkestone and Hythe) submitted a private member’s bill to the House of Commons last week calling for an extension to football’s fit and proper persons’ test. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">As the one that exists would appear to be worthless, following the decision of Tim Kerr QC to overturn the Football League’s ban on Massimo Cellino buying Leeds United, he has his work cut out, but still.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Collins would give the Football Association power to reject any owner whose influence would not be healthy for the game. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Corrupt or untrustworthy people could be banned, whether or not they can skirt around the official criteria.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Convicted fraudster: Massimo Cellino is the new owner of Leeds United despite a chequered past\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"445\" id=\"i-5bc20d2d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CB8621400000578-785_634x445.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Convicted fraudster: Massimo Cellino is the new owner of Leeds United despite a chequered past</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Expenses cheat: Maria Miller gave a 32-second apology in the House of Parliament for overclaiming mortgage costs\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"384\" id=\"i-60b20d59\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CCAC8B800000578-750_634x384.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Expenses cheat: Maria Miller gave a 32-second apology in the House of Parliament for overclaiming mortgage costs</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">A fine idea, but why stop there? Corrupt or untrustworthy people who inexplicably escape significant official sanction exist in every walk of life. Say one became Minister for Culture, Media and Sport, for instance. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Say that person was the type who fiddled her expenses, attempted to use her power and influence to bully the watchdog conducting the investigation into  her offence and even had a two-bob lickspittle making threats to journalists working on the story? </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Well, that sort of person is the last that should be in authority, and we could act accordingly. It really is a super idea. Unless, of course, Collins knows the separation in principle between Cellino, convicted fraudster and now owner of Leeds, and Maria Miller, exposed expenses cheat and Minister for Culture, Media and Sport.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">‘Capable of using every kind of deception,’ the arrest  warrant said of Cellino. And the difference is?</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597668/Pochettino-angry-offside-Nasri-goal-killed-game-gives-interview-English-arriving-January.html\"> Pochettino so angry at offside Nasri goal that \'killed\' the game he gives first interview in English since arriving last January</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597612/Man-City-4-1-Southampton-match-report-Pellegrinis-men-close-gap-Liverpool-comfortable-win.html\"> Man City 4-1 Southampton: Pellegrini\'s men close gap on Liverpool with comfortable win</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597325/Baggies-furious-Sunderland-escape-points-deduction-fielding-illegal-player.html\"> Baggies furious after Sunderland escape points deduction for fielding illegal player</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596994/Sunderland-say-case-closed-playing-Ji-Dong-won-ineligible.html\"> Sunderland say case is closed after playing Ji when he was ineligible... but rivals say Black Cats are lucky to escape with a fine</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597913/Crooks-charter-Football-fears-worst-fraudster-Cellino-given-ahead-35m-takeover-Leeds.html\"> Crooks charter: Football fears the worst after fraudster Cellino is given go-ahead for £35m takeover at Leeds</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/racing/article-2597916/39-40-Grand-National-jockeys-revolt-races-manic-start.html\"> 39 of the 40 Grand National jockeys in revolt over race\'s manic start</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/The-rules-Wild-West-run-run-Premier-League-just-ask-Pochettino-state-football.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MARTIN SAMUEL: The rules are out and this Wild West show can run and run in the Premier League... just ask Pochettino about the state of football\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2598362/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">17</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/06/article-0-1CE3913E00000578-419_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:02','2014-04-07 09:12:43'),(115,'0dcbd08134258b8f5666d727515b1ac299357c590ee3f9fd4fa3d35ed4eaa818','dailymail',NULL,'JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Andy Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Didier Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html',' By Jamie Carragher Published: 16:56 EST, 4 April 2014 | Updated: 19:50 EST, 4 April 2014 568 shares 105 View comments What happened to the big No 9? When I was growing up, it seemed like nearly every team had a powerful centre-forward leading the line. Graeme Sharp and Andy Gray, for instance, were the spearheads of the Everton team I watched but plenty of other clubs went to war with imposing main strikers. Football has changed since then. Forwards are quick, nimble; the emphasis is on pace and movement. So when you get a striker who is a throwback to a different era, one who is big, strong and aggressive, defenders struggle to cope with the challenge.  Double act: Andy Gray and Graeme Sharp both scored as Everton saw off Watford to win the FA Cup in 1984   Strike force: Sharp and Gray were only together at Everton for two seasons, but the club won the FA Cup, the First Division title and the Cup-Winners\' Cup in that spell  More... Merseyside has got its swagger back as Liverpool and Everton fly high in the Premier League \'We can stop him!\' Liverpool boss Rodgers insists his Reds defence will cope with West Ham striker Carroll West Ham would be chasing Europe if Carroll had been fit all season, claims Allardyce as he eyes Liverpool upset The view from Liverpool: The five reasons why the Reds WILL win the title Ayre relaxed over offering Rodgers a new deal at title-chasing Reds Liverpool might be the best team in the world on current form, says West Ham owner Sullivan... but we won\'t roll over I saw that in Andy Carroll when I watched West Ham beat Sunderland on Monday. When he is on song, Andy can be unplayable and there was a great scene after he had scored his goal of him wheeling away to celebrate as two defenders lay flat on their backs. It took me back to the days of the ‘battering rams’ and evoked memories of men such as Mick Harford and Duncan Ferguson, those who would launch themselves to get their head to a ball. Nobody would stand in their way. Trust me: those forwards are a nightmare to face. It’s impossible to enjoy a game when you have to mark them as it becomes a war of attrition. You are constantly grappling and you come off drained as it feels like all you have done is fight for headers. Martin Skrtel and Daniel Agger will know what is coming at Upton Park, as West Ham will look to get it wide, then get it in to Andy during a game that is crucial to Liverpool’s hopes of winning the Barclays Premier League.  A force to be reckoned with: Andy Carroll easily outmuscles Wes Brown and John O\'Shea to thump west Ham into the lead at Sunderland   Laid to waste: Brown is crestfallen alongside keeper Vito Mannone as powerhouse Carroll milks the applause   A nightmare to play against: Few would relish facing the likes of Mick Harford (left) or Duncan Ferguson Andy, no doubt, will believe he has a point to prove given how quickly Brendan Rodgers ended his time at Anfield — he only got two brief substitute appearances that amounted to 18 minutes — but the decision to move him on was in everyone’s best interests. Now, I want to make it clear I’ve no axe to grind with Andy. I found him to be a good lad and his spell at the club wasn’t without highlights. He did what every Liverpool No 9 should do and scored two  winning goals against Everton, including one at Wembley in the 2012 FA Cup semi-final. I wanted Liverpool to sign him, especially after he tormented our defence one day at St James’ Park. If we could have got him for between £12-15m, it would have been good business. The feeling around the club when we were in for him was that maybe he could mature into our Didier Drogba.  Up against it: Martin Skrtel (left) and Daniel Agger (right) will know they are in for a battle at Upton Park   Luxury purchase: Carroll marked his debut in a Merseyside derby with a goal, but it was one of few highlights after Kenny Dalglish opted to spend £35m for his services   Wembley winner: Carroll rose highest in the 87th minute to clinch a pulsating contest in Liverpool\'s favour  More from Jamie Carragher...   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Sterling, Barkley and Januzaj are included but who else makes my list of top young players this season? 11/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend 11/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance 04/04/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: After QPR turned down Zlatan, here\'s my top five stars who got away 28/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Everyone used to fear them, but Arsenal now have no pace or power 28/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Moyes faces a big dilemma over how he gets the best out of United\'s £37m man Mata 21/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Ronaldo needs a Zidane moment to become a true great 21/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER EXCLUSIVE: Beating United at Old Trafford was twice as good as 2009... this would be up there with the glory days of Shankly and Paisley 17/03/14   JAMIE CARRAGHER: Premier League title would be Gerrard’s reward for staying loyal 14/03/14   VIEW FULL ARCHIVE Unfortunately, though, Liverpool’s decision to pay £35million was a big mistake and it never did Andy any favours. He started well, with two goals against Manchester City on his first start, but it quickly became apparent he wasn’t the right fit for the club. In training, he’d complain if the ball was not flung into the box — and I don’t mean from out wide. He wanted the ball to come in to him from close to the halfway line, but at Liverpool that was never going to happen. There were other things. He found the intensity of playing three games every week difficult. Before he might have been used to getting himself right for a match on a Saturday, then spending time socially with his mates — as we all did when we were young — but  at Liverpool the training and  professional demands are relentless. He would very rarely complete a full week on the training field at Melwood and, eventually, that takes a toll. If you aren’t fully conditioned, you are susceptible to injuries and Andy suffered his fair share.Another major issue was the fact he lacked pace. He suits the way Sam Allardyce operates and is West Ham’s focal point but at Liverpool that would never have been the case. Andy may feel Brendan made the decision about him too quickly but it was the right call. How he performs at Upton Park will be intriguing. Allardyce will wind Andy up to deliver a big effort,  primarily to get the win that will secure West Ham’s safety but also to fire out a message to Roy Hodgson with the World Cup in mind.  Legendary status: Carroll was purchased to become Liverpool\'s Didier Drogba, but ended up being sold to West Ham at a £20m loss   Taking its toll: Carroll would rarely complete a week of training at Liverpool, opening himself up to injury problems   Relentless: Carroll (left, with Carragher, Joe Cole and Steven Gerrard) struggled with the demands of training and the intensity of playing three times a week at Liverpool  Allardyce believes Andy will make it ‘impossible for Roy Hodgson to ignore him’ if he reproduces his  finish to last season when scoring six goals in 13 games and he is  moving towards that ratio with two goals in his last five appearances. Personally I believe Rickie Lambert would be closer to the fourth  striker’s spot at the moment, if England’s head coach wants to bring a different kind of player. I think Lambert offers more goals and another string to his bow is his outstanding penalty record. It makes me smile when  I hear people mention him as a ‘plan B’ to go more direct. Do other countries have this ‘plan B’ when things aren’t going well?  In the wilderness? Carroll won the last of his 9 England caps in the 5-0 rout of San Marino in October 2012   Strong option: Rickie Lambert (left) is a better all-round choice to be England\'s fourth striker  Should Andy stay fit and score a few more goals then maybe he will sway Hodgson, who saw him score a brilliant header against Sweden during Euro 2012. The big challenge, however, is for Andy to start playing football consistently. Three of his last four seasons have been ruined by injury and he doesn’t want to be remembered for his fitness record. He is 25 and to get to the highest levels again, he has to realise the importance of looking after himself. Should Andy do that, he’ll have every chance of becoming a true No 9.   Rafa got a lot more out of Torres  Jose Mourinho\'s decision to play without a striker in Paris, followed by his comments after that defeat, clearly spells the end of the road for Chelsea’s frontmen. I have said regularly this season that Chelsea have been playing with 10 men, as Fernando Torres, Samuel Eto’o and Demba Ba have lacked consistency. Torres and Ba have rarely come up with crucial goals and while Eto’o has scored against Liverpool and Manchester United, he hasn’t done enough for a club with Chelsea’s ambitions. It is no wonder Mourinho is looking at signing Atletico Madrid’s Diego Costa.  Stony faced: A gloomy Fernando Torres (second left) sits alongside Demba Ba on Chelsea\'s bench during the midweek misery in Paris   Stunted: Torres takes on former Chelsea player Alex during his poor 31-minute appearance  What will be interesting now, though, is how Torres, Eto’o and Ba react in the closing weeks of the campaign. Chelsea still have a chance to win the Barclays Premier League and I don’t think they are completely out of the Champions League, despite losing 3-1 to Paris Saint-Germain. It was a big call for Mourinho to be so blunt at such a crucial time, as he will need Torres, Eto’o or Ba to produce something for him. They may have under-performed but has Mourinho done enough to get the best out of them? Rafa Benitez, it should be remembered, certainly got more out of Torres and Ba than Mourinho has. The question now is whether Chelsea’s manager will be able to get a response when he really needs it.    My top five players I wish we\'d got to see... Zlatan Ibrahimovic insisted this week he had no regrets about never playing in the Barclays Premier League, but I think it’s a shame he hasn’t taken the chance to test himself in England. There are a few other players, too, who I would have loved to have seen enticed here. 1 Ronaldinho Manchester United tried to sign him from Paris Saint-Germain in 2003 and it would have been fascinating to see how Ronaldinho adapted to the challenge of our league. Instead he chose Barcelona, where he became the best player in the world.  Moving on: Ronaldinho opted to join Barcelona from Paris Saint-Germain, but how the Brazilian fared in the Premier League would have been fascinating to watch  VIDEO: Watch Ronaldinho\'s highlights from PSG  2 Luis Figo I played alongside him last month in a charity match but the Portugal legend could have been my team-mate at Anfield in 2005. Not long after we had won the Champions League, Rafa Benitez thought he had secured a move for him from Real Madrid but Figo ended up at Inter Milan.  Kop out: Luis Figo nearly joined Liverpool from Real Madrid, but chose Inter Milan instead  VIDEO: Watch Figo\'s best moments from Madrid  3 Paolo Maldini One of the things I admire about Maldini is how he gave his career solely to AC Milan but I’d have loved to have seen him in England. When Gianluca Vialli was Chelsea manager, he tried to lure his old international team-mate from the San Siro and was almost successful.  One club man: Paolo Maldini (right) spent his entire career at the San Siro  VIDEO: Watch Maldini\'s highlights reel from his glittering career at AC Milan  4 Xavi When I met Xavi in Madrid last month, he spoke with great enthusiasm about the Premier League and his admiration for the English game. He also indicated that he received offers — Manchester United had a strong interest — but he wanted to stay true to Barcelona.  Aficionado: Xavi is a keen follower of English football, and lists Matthew Le Tissier as one of his footballing heroes  VIDEO: Watch Xavi in action for Barcelona  5 Gianluigi Buffon He was recognised as the best goalkeeper in the world for many years and is a Juventus icon. There was a point, though, when all was not well for Buffon in Turin and he was linked with Manchester City.  He would certainly have added to the quality of our game.  Read all about it: Gigi Buffon was linked with a move to Manchester City and would have been a surefire hit in England  VIDEO: Watch a selection of Buffon\'s best saves    More... Merseyside has got its swagger back as Liverpool and Everton fly high in the Premier League \'We can stop him!\' Liverpool boss Rodgers insists his Reds defence will cope with West Ham striker Carroll West Ham would be chasing Europe if Carroll had been fit all season, claims Allardyce as he eyes Liverpool upset The view from Liverpool: The five reasons why the Reds WILL win the title Ayre relaxed over offering Rodgers a new deal at title-chasing Reds Liverpool might be the best team in the world on current form, says West Ham owner Sullivan... but we won\'t roll over  Share or comment on this article 568shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1076287/Jamie-Carragher.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jamie Carragher</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 16:56 EST, 4 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 19:50 EST, 4 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 568</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">105</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">What happened to the big No 9? When I was growing up, it seemed like nearly every team had a powerful centre-forward leading the line.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Graeme Sharp and Andy Gray, for instance, were the spearheads of the Everton team I watched but plenty of other clubs went to war with imposing main strikers.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Football has changed since then. Forwards are quick, nimble; the emphasis is on pace and movement. So when you get a striker who is a throwback to a different era, one who is big, strong and aggressive, defenders struggle to cope with the challenge.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Double act: Andy Gray and Graeme Sharp both scored as Everton saw off Watford to win the FA Cup in 1984\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"419\" id=\"i-aafe0e7e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/05/article-2597339-007F988A00000258-888_634x419.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Double act: Andy Gray and Graeme Sharp both scored as Everton saw off Watford to win the FA Cup in 1984</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Spearhead: Graeme Sharp\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"436\" id=\"i-4fd80d05\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-0007F39D00000C1D-84_306x436.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Aerial threat: Andy Gray\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"436\" id=\"i-5ae20d31\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-000073CF00000C1D-729_306x436.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Strike force: Sharp and Gray were only together at Everton for two seasons, but the club won the FA Cup, the First Division title and the Cup-Winners\' Cup in that spell<br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div> <div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597275/Merseyside-got-swagger-Liverpool-Everton-fly-high-Premier-League.html\"> Merseyside has got its swagger back as Liverpool and Everton fly high in the Premier League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597202/We-stop-Liverpool-boss-Brendan-Rodgers-insists-Reds-defence-cope-West-Ham-United-striker-Andy-Carroll.html\"> \'We can stop him!\' Liverpool boss Rodgers insists his Reds defence will cope with West Ham striker Carroll</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596955/West-Ham-chasing-Europe-Andy-Carroll-fit-season-claims-Allardyce-eyes-Liverpool-upset.html\"> West Ham would be chasing Europe if Carroll had been fit all season, claims Allardyce as he eyes Liverpool upset</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596945/The-view-Liverpool-The-five-reasons-Reds-WILL-win-title.html\"> The view from Liverpool: The five reasons why the Reds WILL win the title</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597191/Ian-Ayre-relaxed-offering-Brendan-Rodgers-new-deal-title-chasing-Liverpool.html\"> Ayre relaxed over offering Rodgers a new deal at title-chasing Reds</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596788/Liverpool-best-team-world-current-form-says-West-Ham-owner-Sullivan-wont-roll-over.html\"> Liverpool might be the best team in the world on current form, says West Ham owner Sullivan... but we won\'t roll over</a></li> </ul> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I saw that in Andy Carroll when I watched West Ham beat Sunderland on Monday. When he is on song, Andy can be unplayable and there was a great scene after he had scored his goal of him wheeling away to celebrate as two defenders lay flat on their backs.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It took me back to the days of the ‘battering rams’ and evoked memories of men such as Mick Harford and Duncan Ferguson, those who would launch themselves to get their head to a ball. Nobody would stand in their way. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Trust me: those forwards are a nightmare to face. It’s impossible to enjoy a game when you have to mark them as it becomes a war of attrition. You are constantly grappling and you come off drained as it feels like all you have done is fight for headers. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Martin Skrtel and Daniel Agger will know what is coming at Upton Park, as West Ham will look to get it wide, then get it in to Andy during a game that is crucial to Liverpool’s hopes of winning the Barclays Premier League.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"A force to be reckoned with: Andy Carroll easily outmuscles Wes Brown and John O\'Shea to thump west Ham into the lead at Sunderland\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"459\" id=\"i-5bdf0d2f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CB9990100000578-642_634x459.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">A force to be reckoned with: Andy Carroll easily outmuscles Wes Brown and John O\'Shea to thump west Ham into the lead at Sunderland</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Laid to waste: Brown is crestfallen alongside keeper Vito Mannone as powerhouse Carroll milks the applause\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"427\" id=\"i-5dbc0d40\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CB9990C00000578-673_634x427.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Laid to waste: Brown is crestfallen alongside keeper Vito Mannone as powerhouse Carroll milks the applause</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Power: Mick Harford\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-5e820d42\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CD6CB5300000578-496_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Channeled aggression: Duncan Ferguson\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-57e60d10\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-034031770000044D-999_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">A nightmare to play against: Few would relish facing the likes of Mick Harford (left) or Duncan Ferguson<br/></p></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Andy, no doubt, will believe he has a point to prove given how quickly Brendan Rodgers ended his time at Anfield — he only got two brief substitute appearances that amounted to 18 minutes — but the decision to move him on was in everyone’s best interests. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Now, I want to make it clear I’ve no axe to grind with Andy. I found him to be a good lad and his spell at the club wasn’t without highlights. He did what every Liverpool No 9 should do and scored two  winning goals against Everton, including one at Wembley in the 2012 FA Cup semi-final.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I wanted Liverpool to sign him, especially after he tormented our defence one day at St James’ Park. If we could have got him for between £12-15m, it would have been good business. The feeling around the club when we were in for him was that maybe he could mature into our Didier Drogba. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Up against it: Martin Skrtel (left) and Daniel Agger (right) will know they are in for a battle at Upton Park\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"398\" id=\"i-5dcc0d3f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CCD342F00000578-200_634x398.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Up against it: Martin Skrtel (left) and Daniel Agger (right) will know they are in for a battle at Upton Park</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Luxury purchase: Carroll marked his debut in a Merseyside derby with a goal, but it was one of few highlights after Kenny Dalglish opted to spend £35m for his services\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"529\" id=\"i-524c0d12\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CD6F61C00000578-14_634x529.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Luxury purchase: Carroll marked his debut in a Merseyside derby with a goal, but it was one of few highlights after Kenny Dalglish opted to spend £35m for his services</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Wembley winner: Carroll rose highest in the 87th minute to clinch a pulsating contest in Liverpool\'s favour\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"383\" id=\"i-5d210d44\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1299F3A4000005DC-705_634x383.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Wembley winner: Carroll rose highest in the 87th minute to clinch a pulsating contest in Liverpool\'s favour</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"moduleHalf\"><div class=\"item\"> <div class=\"columnist-archive-narrow bogr1\"> <span class=\"tl\"> </span> <span class=\"tr\"> </span> <h3>More from Jamie Carragher...</h3> <ul> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602715/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Daniel-Sturridge-Eden-Hazard-lead-way-five-young-players-year.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Sterling, Barkley and Januzaj are included but who else makes my list of top young players this season?</a> <span class=\"date\">11/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2602712/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Every-child-told-games-kick-seven-minutes-late-weekend.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Hillsborough - every child must be told why games kick off seven minutes late this weekend</a> <span class=\"date\">11/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance</a> <span class=\"date\">04/04/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592009/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-After-QPR-turned-Zlatan-heres-five-stars-got-away.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: After QPR turned down Zlatan, here\'s my top five stars who got away</a> <span class=\"date\">28/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2591855/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Everyone-used-fear-Arsenal-no-pace-power.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Everyone used to fear them, but Arsenal now have no pace or power</a> <span class=\"date\">28/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2586565/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Manchester-United-boss-David-Moyes-faces-big-dilemma-Juan-Mata.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Moyes faces a big dilemma over how he gets the best out of United\'s £37m man Mata</a> <span class=\"date\">21/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2586438/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-Cristiano-Ronaldo-needs-Zinedine-Zidane-moment-true-great.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Ronaldo needs a Zidane moment to become a true great</a> <span class=\"date\">21/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2583008/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-EXCLUSIVE-This-win-twice-good-2009-Liverpool-major-title-contenders.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER EXCLUSIVE: Beating United at Old Trafford was twice as good as 2009... this would be up there with the glory days of Shankly and Paisley</a> <span class=\"date\">17/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"/sport/football/article-2581300/Steven-Gerrard-deserves-win-Premier-League-loyalty-Liverpool-Jamie-Carragher.html\">JAMIE CARRAGHER: Premier League title would be Gerrard’s reward for staying loyal</a> <span class=\"date\">14/03/14</span> </li> <li class=\"cleared\"> <span class=\"arrow-small-r\"> </span> <a href=\"columnist-1076287/Jamie-Carragher.html\">VIEW FULL ARCHIVE</a> </li> </ul> </div> </div>   </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Unfortunately, though, Liverpool’s decision to pay £35million was a big mistake and it never did Andy any favours. He started well, with two goals against Manchester City on his first start, but it quickly became apparent he wasn’t the right fit for the club.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">In training, he’d complain if the ball was not flung into the box — and I don’t mean from out wide. He wanted the ball to come in to him from close to the halfway line, but at Liverpool that was never going to happen. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There were other things. He found the intensity of playing three games every week difficult. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Before he might have been used to getting himself right for a match on a Saturday, then spending time socially with his mates — as we all did when we were young — but  at Liverpool the training and  professional demands are relentless.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He would very rarely complete a full week on the training field at Melwood and, eventually, that takes a toll. If you aren’t fully conditioned, you are susceptible to injuries and Andy suffered his fair share.<br/>Another major issue was the fact he lacked pace. He suits the way Sam Allardyce operates and is West Ham’s focal point but at Liverpool that would never have been the case. Andy may feel Brendan made the decision about him too quickly but it was the right call. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">How he performs at Upton Park will be intriguing. Allardyce will wind Andy up to deliver a big effort,  primarily to get the win that will secure West Ham’s safety but also to fire out a message to Roy Hodgson with the World Cup in mind.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Legendary status: Carroll was purchased to become Liverpool\'s Didier Drogba, but ended up being sold to West Ham at a £20m loss\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"375\" id=\"i-5f520d5f\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1322EDBD000005DC-747_634x375.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Legendary status: Carroll was purchased to become Liverpool\'s Didier Drogba, but ended up being sold to West Ham at a £20m loss</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Taking its toll: Carroll would rarely complete a week of training at Liverpool, opening himself up to injury problems\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"364\" id=\"i-5b970d28\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CD7098200000578-613_634x364.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Taking its toll: Carroll would rarely complete a week of training at Liverpool, opening himself up to injury problems</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Relentless: Carroll (left, with Carragher, Joe Cole and Steven Gerrard) struggled with the demands of training and the intensity of playing three times a week at Liverpool\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"414\" id=\"i-5d4b0d37\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CD709D700000578-417_634x414.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Relentless: Carroll (left, with Carragher, Joe Cole and Steven Gerrard) struggled with the demands of training and the intensity of playing three times a week at Liverpool</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Allardyce believes Andy will make it ‘impossible for Roy Hodgson to ignore him’ if he reproduces his  finish to last season when scoring six goals in 13 games and he is  moving towards that ratio with two goals in his last five appearances.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Personally I believe Rickie Lambert would be closer to the fourth  striker’s spot at the moment, if England’s head coach wants to bring a different kind of player. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I think Lambert offers more goals and another string to his bow is his outstanding penalty record.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It makes me smile when  I hear people mention him as a ‘plan B’ to go more direct. Do other countries have this ‘plan B’ when things aren’t going well?</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"In the wilderness? Carroll won the last of his 9 England caps in the 5-0 rout of San Marino in October 2012\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"418\" id=\"i-5ad50d1e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-01FAA50500000514-801_634x418.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">In the wilderness? Carroll won the last of his 9 England caps in the 5-0 rout of San Marino in October 2012</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Strong option: Rickie Lambert (left) is a better all-round choice to be England\'s fourth striker\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"360\" id=\"i-61f10d69\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1BBDEE91000005DC-615_634x360.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Strong option: Rickie Lambert (left) is a better all-round choice to be England\'s fourth striker</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Should Andy stay fit and score a few more goals then maybe he will sway Hodgson, who saw him score a brilliant header against Sweden during Euro 2012. The big challenge, however, is for Andy to start playing football consistently.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Three of his last four seasons have been ruined by injury and he doesn’t want to be remembered for his fitness record. He is 25 and to get to the highest levels again, he has to realise the importance of looking after himself. Should Andy do that, he’ll have every chance of becoming a true No 9. </font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"><h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Rafa got a lot more out of Torres</font></h2></div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Jose Mourinho\'s decision to play without a striker in Paris, followed by his comments after that defeat, clearly spells the end of the road for Chelsea’s frontmen.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">I have said regularly this season that Chelsea have been playing with 10 men, as Fernando Torres, Samuel Eto’o and Demba Ba have lacked consistency. Torres and Ba have rarely come up with crucial goals and while Eto’o has scored against Liverpool and Manchester United, he hasn’t done enough for a club with Chelsea’s ambitions. </font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It is no wonder Mourinho is looking at signing Atletico Madrid’s Diego Costa.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Stony faced: A gloomy Fernando Torres (second left) sits alongside Demba Ba on Chelsea\'s bench during the midweek misery in Paris\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"309\" id=\"i-60010d52\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CC5DB5F00000578-730_634x309.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Stony faced: A gloomy Fernando Torres (second left) sits alongside Demba Ba on Chelsea\'s bench during the midweek misery in Paris</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Stunted: Torres takes on former Chelsea player Alex during his poor 31-minute appearance\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"383\" id=\"i-5cd70d37\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CC6374C00000578-408_634x383.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Stunted: Torres takes on former Chelsea player Alex during his poor 31-minute appearance</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">What will be interesting now, though, is how Torres, Eto’o and Ba react in the closing weeks of the campaign. Chelsea still have a chance to win the Barclays Premier League and I don’t think they are completely out of the Champions League, despite losing 3-1 to Paris Saint-Germain.</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It was a big call for Mourinho to be so blunt at such a crucial time, as he will need Torres, Eto’o or Ba to produce something for him. They may have under-performed but has Mourinho done enough to get the best out of them?</font><br/></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Rafa Benitez, it should be remembered, certainly got more out of Torres and Ba than Mourinho has. The question now is whether Chelsea’s manager will be able to get a response when he really needs it.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<h2><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">My top five players I wish we\'d got to see...<br/></font></h2>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Zlatan Ibrahimovic insisted this week he had no regrets about never playing in the Barclays Premier League, but I think it’s a shame he hasn’t taken the chance to test himself in England. There are a few other players, too, who I would have loved to have seen enticed here.</font></p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">1 Ronaldinho</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"> Manchester United tried to sign him from Paris Saint-Germain in 2003 and it would have been fascinating to see how Ronaldinho adapted to the challenge of our league. Instead he chose Barcelona, where he became the best player in the world.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Moving on: Ronaldinho opted to join Barcelona from Paris Saint-Germain, but how the Brazilian fared in the Premier League would have been fascinating to watch\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"538\" id=\"i-5c970d33\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1CD757A000000578-413_634x538.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Moving on: Ronaldinho opted to join Barcelona from Paris Saint-Germain, but how the Brazilian fared in the Premier League would have been fascinating to watch</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">VIDEO: Watch Ronaldinho\'s highlights from PSG</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/Z5nZKAziam8\" width=\"638\"></iframe></font><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><br/></font></b></p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">2 Luis Figo</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"> I played alongside him last month in a charity match but the Portugal legend could have been my team-mate at Anfield in 2005. Not long after we had won the Champions League, Rafa Benitez thought he had secured a move for him from Real Madrid but Figo ended up at Inter Milan.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Kop out: Luis Figo nearly joined Liverpool from Real Madrid, but chose Inter Milan instead\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"460\" id=\"i-5f170d51\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-00B98CFE1000044C-258_634x460.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Kop out: Luis Figo nearly joined Liverpool from Real Madrid, but chose Inter Milan instead</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>VIDEO: Watch Figo\'s best moments from Madrid<br/></b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/FFpeEyKrqM0\" width=\"638\"></iframe><b><br/></b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>3 Paolo Maldini</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"> One of the things I admire about Maldini is how he gave his career solely to AC Milan but I’d have loved to have seen him in England. When Gianluca Vialli was Chelsea manager, he tried to lure his old international team-mate from the San Siro and was almost successful.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"One club man: Paolo Maldini (right) spent his entire career at the San Siro\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"493\" id=\"i-58950d14\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-000C411B00000258-429_634x493.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">One club man: Paolo Maldini (right) spent his entire career at the San Siro</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>VIDEO: Watch Maldini\'s highlights reel from his glittering career at AC Milan</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/E5sqyEtzz3A\" width=\"638\"></iframe><b><br/></b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><b>4 Xavi <br/></b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">When I met Xavi in Madrid last month, he spoke with great enthusiasm about the Premier League and his admiration for the English game. He also indicated that he received offers — Manchester United had a strong interest — but he wanted to stay true to Barcelona.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Aficionado: Xavi is a keen follower of English football, and lists Matthew Le Tissier as one of his footballing heroes\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"517\" id=\"i-60030d56\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-1C0FCDD500000578-493_634x517.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Aficionado: Xavi is a keen follower of English football, and lists Matthew Le Tissier as one of his footballing heroes</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">VIDEO: Watch Xavi in action for Barcelona</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/ybbqDkr2HgA\" width=\"638\"></iframe></font><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><br/></font></b></p>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">5 Gianluigi Buffon</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"> He was recognised as the best goalkeeper in the world for many years and is a Juventus icon. There was a point, though, when all was not well for Buffon in Turin and he was linked with Manchester City.  He would certainly have added to the quality of our game.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Read all about it: Gigi Buffon was linked with a move to Manchester City and would have been a surefire hit in England\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"430\" id=\"i-571a0d06\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-0-000307371000044C-875_634x430.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Read all about it: Gigi Buffon was linked with a move to Manchester City and would have been a surefire hit in England</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">VIDEO: </font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">W</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">atch a selection of Buffon\'s best saves</font></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/9S2m2Mcy49E\" width=\"638\"></iframe></font><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><br/></font></span></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597275/Merseyside-got-swagger-Liverpool-Everton-fly-high-Premier-League.html\"> Merseyside has got its swagger back as Liverpool and Everton fly high in the Premier League</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597202/We-stop-Liverpool-boss-Brendan-Rodgers-insists-Reds-defence-cope-West-Ham-United-striker-Andy-Carroll.html\"> \'We can stop him!\' Liverpool boss Rodgers insists his Reds defence will cope with West Ham striker Carroll</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596955/West-Ham-chasing-Europe-Andy-Carroll-fit-season-claims-Allardyce-eyes-Liverpool-upset.html\"> West Ham would be chasing Europe if Carroll had been fit all season, claims Allardyce as he eyes Liverpool upset</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596945/The-view-Liverpool-The-five-reasons-Reds-WILL-win-title.html\"> The view from Liverpool: The five reasons why the Reds WILL win the title</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2597191/Ian-Ayre-relaxed-offering-Brendan-Rodgers-new-deal-title-chasing-Liverpool.html\"> Ayre relaxed over offering Rodgers a new deal at title-chasing Reds</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2596788/Liverpool-best-team-world-current-form-says-West-Ham-owner-Sullivan-wont-roll-over.html\"> Liverpool might be the best team in the world on current form, says West Ham owner Sullivan... but we won\'t roll over</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/JAMIE-CARRAGHER-We-thought-Andy-Carroll-Liverpools-Didier-Drogba-35m-price-tag-gave-no-chance.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE CARRAGHER: We thought Carroll would be Liverpool\'s Drogba... but his £35m price tag gave him no chance\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2597339/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">568</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-2597339-1CD78ED300000578-445_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:04','2014-04-05 02:50:05'),(116,'5da7bd64ad99d71f84a45b96501a364d2d58a45682f4f83d0e5eb53b78737e78','dailymail',NULL,'MASTERS COURSE GUIDE: Let McIlroy, Poulter and Co take you round Augusta National with the help of our superb graphic','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html','  Published: 11:31 EST, 4 April 2014 | Updated: 11:42 EST, 4 April 2014 22 shares 0 View comments The Masters is almost here and to get you in the mood for the first major of the year we\'ve got a brilliant course guide to tell you everything you need to know about Augusta National. Rory McIlroy, Ian Poulter and Graeme McDowell along with the likes of Justin Rose and past Masters champions Nick Faldo and Charl Schwartzel give the rundown on every hole at the famous Georgia Course. There\'s no Tiger Woods this year, the world No 1 is recovering from a back operation, and Eisenhower\'s Tree is also a goner but McIlroy, looking to land his third major, and defending champion Adam Scott head a star-studded field. Click on the graphic below to get a closer look at what the biggest names in the game will face when they tee off on Thursday.    More... Phil shows he is fighting fit for The Masters with a speedy recovery and strong start at the Houston Open \'Woods can\'t be fit in three months\', says DeLaet (who underwent the same back operation as the world No 1) Masters doesn\'t need Woods to be \'the greatest golf tournament\', insists Kuchar England\'s hot new property Fitzpatrick ready to take on the world at Augusta Woods out of Masters after undergoing back surgery... World No 1 set to miss every major and faces race to stay in Ryder Cup   Share or comment on this article 22shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\"></p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 11:31 EST, 4 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 11:42 EST, 4 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MASTERS COURSE GUIDE: Let McIlroy, Poulter and Co take you round Augusta National with the help of our superb graphic\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 22</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">0</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Masters is almost here and to get you in the mood for the first major of the year we\'ve got a brilliant course guide to tell you everything you need to know about Augusta National.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Rory McIlroy, Ian Poulter and Graeme McDowell along with the likes of Justin Rose and past Masters champions Nick Faldo and Charl Schwartzel give the rundown on every hole at the famous Georgia Course.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">There\'s no Tiger Woods this year, the world No 1 is recovering from a back operation, and Eisenhower\'s Tree is also a goner but McIlroy, looking to land his third major, and defending champion Adam Scott head a star-studded field.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Click on the graphic below to get a closer look at what the biggest names in the game will face when they tee off on Thursday.</font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleTriple\">  <div class=\"home item html_snippet_module\"> <center><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"630\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/graphics/2014/04/AUGUSTA_MASTERS4/MASTERS_INTERACTIVE.html\" width=\"964\"></iframe></center> </div> </div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/golf/article-2596477/Phil-shows-fighting-fit-Augusta-strong-start-Houston-Open.html\"> Phil shows he is fighting fit for The Masters with a speedy recovery and strong start at the Houston Open</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/golf/article-2595623/Tiger-Woods-fit-three-months-says-Graham-DeLaet-underwent-operation-world-No-1-will.html\"> \'Woods can\'t be fit in three months\', says DeLaet (who underwent the same back operation as the world No 1)</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/golf/article-2595250/Masters-doesnt-need-Tiger-Woods-greatest-golf-tournament-insists-Matt-Kuchar.html\"> Masters doesn\'t need Woods to be \'the greatest golf tournament\', insists Kuchar</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/golf/article-2594531/Englands-hot-new-property-Matt-Fitzpatrick-ready-world-Augusta.html\"> England\'s hot new property Fitzpatrick ready to take on the world at Augusta</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/golf/article-2594395/Tiger-Woods-miss-Masters-undergoing-surgery-sit-major.html\"> Woods out of Masters after undergoing back surgery... World No 1 set to miss every major and faces race to stay in Ryder Cup</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<br/>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/MASTERS-COURSE-GUIDE-Let-McIlroy-Poulter-Co-round-Augusta-National-help-superb-graphic.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MASTERS COURSE GUIDE: Let McIlroy, Poulter and Co take you round Augusta National with the help of our superb graphic\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2597131/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">22</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/04/article-2597131-1CD68ADF00000578-192_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:05','2014-04-04 18:42:18'),(117,'18305968342146cff853d3d9e50cfbff39e19bb1a5a56095302359e10ef5d2f1','dailymail',NULL,'Martin Samuel - The debate: Should Manchester United fans blame Sir Alex Ferguson for the poor season under David Moyes','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2595752/Martin-Samuel-The-debate-Should-Manchester-United-fans-blame-Sir-Alex-Ferguson-poor-season-David-Moyes.html',' By Martin Samuel - Debate Published: 03:02 EST, 3 April 2014 | Updated: 09:05 EST, 3 April 2014 51 shares 136 View comments  Is Sir Alex Ferguson to blame for the wobble at Manchester United? Should he have minded his own business when asked about his successor; or do United fans have short memories? All will be revealed below. But first, a little touch of Frankie in the night. Rest in peace, Godfather of House.    Time for another change? After a season of poor results, Sir Alex Ferguson (left) has come under scrutiny for his recommendation of David Moyes (right) as his replacement at Manchester United last summer  Showing the strain: Michael Carrick, Wayne Rooney and Rio Ferdinand have endured a tough time this term David Moyes reacting after each of United\'s 10 League losses     You continually take shots at Kenny Dalglish and it seems quite out of place. The Andy Carroll signing was a poor one, as it turned out, but this was primarily a result of Dalglish being released by the club and Carroll not being part of Brendan Rodgers\' plan. He was signed in the context of getting £15m more for Fernando Torres than they were paying for Carroll. They have recouped some of that money already and it will prove less of a loss, from a financial and PR point of view, than Torres will for Chelsea. Are you going to be similarly scathing about the signing of Marouane Fellaini, who has shown zero upside; or about the way the \'chosen one\' is leading Manchester United to their lowest finish in Premiership history? How about the way Dalglish took Liverpool to a trophy and a cup final in his one bad season – bad only by his very high standards. Moyes has a higher net spend than Dalglish in his second spell at Liverpool, took over the Champions and has no silverware to show for it. There’s some balance for you. Paul McCabe, Dundee  Paul, I don’t need lessons in balance from someone who cannot admit that Dalglish was sacked by Liverpool. Doves get released, mate. Prison inmates get released. Kenny got the bullet. There were two pieces in Monday’s column that mentioned Dalglish, probably the first time I have referred to him this season. One noted his achievements as player, manager and man and the love for him at Anfield, no matter the odd mistake in his second managerial spell; the other took issue with his assertion that Sam Allardyce needed greater financial support from the West Ham United board and ‘better players’ – considering that two of those players, Carroll and Stewart Downing, were bought by Dalglish at Liverpool for £55m. I’d say that is balance. I thought Kenny made an inconsistent argument regarding Allardyce, much like yours over Carroll. He worked out as a £20m loss for Liverpool and that is not excused by Torres’s failure at Chelsea or Fellaini’s at Manchester United. As for Moyes, he’s hardly getting an easy ride; least of all over Fellaini.  Released or sacked: Kenny Dalglish pictured in the Anfield stands with Ian Rush last Sunday Difficult ride: Marouane Fellaini, who cost £28.5m last summer, has struggled to make an impact at Old Trafford      It is Sir Alex Ferguson’s fault. He knew an aging team over-achieved last season, so thought he could drop them and make himself look great. Scouseblue, Liverpool He didn’t need that last title to look great. What went before had pretty much guaranteed that epitaph. And every team is aging. The word you are looking for is old, and United are not actually old. David De Gea, Phil Jones, Chris Smalling, Rafael, Danny Welbeck, Wilfried Zaha and Tom Cleverley are not old, and this year Moyes has introduced Adnan Januzaj. You may think they are not good enough – but they’re not old.  Despite Ferguson’s fantastic record over the years, it doesn\'t change the fact he is to blame for the current situation. He let the squad stagnate for five years and played with a big hole in midfield. He should have replaced Roy Keane and Paul Scholes and instead was an apologist for the Glazers by claiming repeatedly there was no value in the transfer market. The centre backs were aging yet he didn\'t bother buying replacements for Rio Ferdinand or Nemanja Vidic. In the past he had his eye on the future and replaced players well before they were past their best, but didn\'t bother as he was going to retire. Then he made a terrible mistake by appointing Moyes. So whose fault is it? Nobody is perfect, not even Ferguson. He is not beyond criticism. All around were buying class players and have overtaken us. Nick63 Menston, Leeds Jones and Smalling were bought to replace Vidic and Ferdinand, and I would imagine Shinji Kagawa was seen as key to reinventing midfield creativity following the retirement of Scholes. Good luck finding that replacement for Roy Keane, though, because I don’t see one at too many other clubs, either. Fernandinho at Manchester City, perhaps. Most likely, Ferguson did not see the crash coming because he got extraordinary levels of performance from his players, so did not realise their weakness in the hands of another manager. I don’t know why it has to be somebody’s fault all of the time. At worst, Ferguson recommended the wrong man – but he did so with the best intentions.  Forward planning: United have not properly replaced centre-back pairing Rio Ferdinand and Nemanja Vidic, according to some   Replacement: Phil Jones was signed to be United\'s centre-back in the long-term   Compared to Paris St Germain, Bayern Munich and Manchester City, United have done nothing over the past three years to build strength. This was on Ferguson’s watch and he must take 100 per cent responsibility for this dismal and pathetic team. Angst06, TorontoThe dismal and pathetic team that came close to beating Bayern Munich on Tuesday night, you mean? That dismal and pathetic team? Bayern Munich are currently taking advantage of a spell in which their academy has produced a clutch of world-class players, as happened to Manchester United two decades ago; PSG and Manchester City have limitless funds under Gulf ownership. Despite this, Manchester United are the reigning champions. That was on Ferguson’s watch; or have you forgotten already?  The problem with the poll regarding who is to blame for Manchester United\'s current situation is that it deals in absolutes. There is no single reason for their problems, but a variety of different elements combining to make it a really tough season for whoever took charge. What manager at the end of any campaign could say that no area of his team needed improvement? Ideally, Ferguson would have let Moyes know much earlier that he would be the next manager leading to a smoother transition. I guess he just wasn\'t willing to take the risk of it leaking and potentially ruining his final season. Jbers, France Ferguson always regretted prematurely announcing his intention to retire at the end of the 2001-02 season. He thought the players switched off, and he couldn’t stand the idea of Sven Goran Eriksson reaping the benefit of his good work, so changed his mind. Without doubt his plans were kept under wraps this time to avoid a repeat.  Why not me? Sven Goran Eriksson was lined up to replace Sir Alex Ferguson back in 2002   You wrote: ‘Some would say he picked the wrong manager, but he didn’t. He just picked the wrong club; one with very short memories and a well-honed sense of entitlement.’ Correction, Mr Samuel: Ferguson picked the right club, you just happen to be listening to the wrong fans. If, as you say, 25 per cent are blaming Sir Alex, then I and the other 75 per cent need to continue the vocal support we witnessed at Old Trafford on Saturday. United we stand, divided we fall. Babs7Falmouth, Truro United we stand, divided we’re lumbered. My favourite line from Performance, and there are a few contenders, some of which you’ll find in the song below. (I take your point, by the way – 25 per cent is not a majority, but it’s still a significant number).    Not getting all the talk coming out of Old Trafford that the club is built on stability and they don\'t hire and fire. They had one manager for nearly three decades winning a trophy if not every year then pretty close to it – so of course you are going to have stability. They should have gone for Carlo Ancelotti, he was the perfect fit for United, a manager that works well with all players and clearly wasn\'t comfortable at Paris St Germain last summer. Ancelotti’s teams play good football and he is a proven winner. SpannersXI, CoventryI agree about Ancelotti being a good fit. My information is that he wins the league, or Champions League, at Real Madrid this summer or is sacked. If that happens, he should be on the radar of a number of English clubs – most particularly Manchester United and Tottenham Hotspur if they decide to change. He is a healing type, too, not the sort to come in at Old Trafford and create turmoil.  Good fit: Carlo Ancelotti could be brought in at the end of the season if United decide to dispense with Moyes   Moyes got the job at Everton because he was recommended by his predecessor, Walter Smith, he was also offered a job on the Old Trafford coaching staff by Ferguson but preferred to be a manager. He is well thought of in the coaching fraternity and a couple of years ago even Arsene Wenger stated that he thought Moyes one of our best. Bill, United Kingdom You’re right. If Ferguson made a mistake there are a few that would have followed him down that road – some of the best judges in the game, in fact.  Maybe the fans are blaming Ferguson for leaving Moyes with an aging squad who are coming to the end of their contracts at the club? Maybe they are blaming him for the lack of real investment in the squad over the last few seasons of his reign? He relied on Scholes and Ryan Giggs in midfield and never replaced them, and at the end of this season three out of four first team defenders are probably off elsewhere. Rhod, Wrexham, 1 day ago The average age of the team that beat Aston Villa 4-1 was 26, after substitutions it was still 26 and the average age of the bench, which included 40-year-old Giggs, was 27. This aging squad is a myth. You’ll find these false presumptions occurring throughout football. Say it enough times and everybody believes it.  The veteran: Despite the presence of 40-year-old Ryan Giggs, United\'s squad still has a relatively young average age   United need a major overhaul, let Moyes do it, then judge. Enjoy the past glories and memories, we all do and share those with United fans, but the future needs change. Every team has to go through it so stop the whining guys and get on with the planning for next year and beyond. Wbafan, Canada Sage advice from a West Bromwich Albion fan living in Canada. Do you want me to deal with this, or is it over to you? I’m feeling generous, you have this one. Try to keep it clean.  For the world\'s biggest club to have no succession plan is farcical. Everyone knew it was just a matter of time before Ferguson retired. Disgraceful and embarrassing incompetence from the owners and the board. Stretfordhead, Texas They did have a succession plan, mate. He’s called David Moyes. Just because you don’t rate him doesn’t mean it wasn’t a plan.  The plan: United handed David Moyes a six-year contract and a brief to take United forward post-Ferguson   No right minded United fan would ever direct ire at Ferguson in his retirement. Every fan base has their idiots, without exception. It is myopic to focus on a handful of disgruntled supporters, fresh from another home humiliation. What happened in the home game that following the comprehensive 3-0 battering by Manchester City? The 70,000 in Old Trafford gave a rapturous supportive ovation to their beleaguered manager and were unanimous in their choral condemnation of that silly plane. It is difficult to imagine the fans of clubs with comparable status such as Real Madrid, Barcelona and Bayern Munich maintaining comparable sympathy for their manager if they were seventh in their league with scant chance of Champions League football next season. All of the support for Moyes is a proxy support of Ferguson. It is because Ferguson chose him that they maintain the respect for Moyes. It\'s certainly not for his promising previous achievements or exciting, expansive football. United fans standing by Moyes is perhaps the greatest testament to the support of Ferguson, more real than any road or statue. It is blind, unquestioning faith in his final instruction \"your job now is to support your new manager\". According to market research company Kantar, United have a total worldwide fan base of 659 million. How many fans were polled by the Manchester Evening News? If we\'re generous and say 50,000, then the 12,500 fans that blame Ferguson for the current predicament comprise 0.0018 per cent of the fan pool. If this is the metric by which our most respected sports journalists can muse indignantly on the over entitled I-phone generation may I direct them to Twitter? How about radio phone-ins? I\'ve heard several Liverpool fans call for Brendan Rodgers\' head this season after a single poor result. Basing your opinion on the ravings of a silly minority is puzzling. Was the enemy not within when Roy Hodgson got the boot from Anfield? He was appointed in July 2010 and was out by January 2011. Hodgson said of Liverpool’s fans: “The famous Anfield support has not really been there.” Moyes was appointed in July 2013 and is still there despite doing a worse job than Hodgson. Moyes said of United fans: “The crowds have been incredible. I\'m not feeling any pressure from inside the club. It\'s all coming from you people [the media].\" Yet it\'s United fans that have no class according to some. The Henery, PortsmouthSpot on. Chrism, ManchesterNo, it isn’t actually, Chris. Take the 0.0018 per cent of the fan pool statistic. It only works if we believe that just under 10 per cent of the world’s population are Manchester United fans. Equally, say we accept 659 million is genuine figure; then on the law of average roughly a quarter of them – close to 165 million – are currently blaming Ferguson. The Hodgson quote is taken from after he was sacked; the Moyes quote while he remains in the job and is desperate for the fans to back him. It is no surprise that they are different in attitude. If Moyes goes in the summer, he might have a more self-pitying take on the pressure he was under. As for the assertion that no United fan would ever blame Ferguson, that simply isn’t true. I go through many comments to produce this debate column – and there is plenty of criticism of Ferguson out there, and not all coming from shallow, aggrieved citizens of Singapore and Chicago who thought the good times would never end. I think the reaction to the plane was less vindication for Moyes, more embarrassment at a stunt that did not reflect well on the supporters, who vocally distanced themselves from it. I do agree, though, that it is only Ferguson’s backing for Moyes and the fans devotion to Ferguson that has prevented the atmosphere becoming more febrile this season.  I think the worst of it may well be over for Moyes and the bulk of the supporters stayed with him, which is admirable, but if he gets this much-vaunted £200m in the summer, it will be interesting to see how long that backing lasts if United are still a conservative team next season.  Unquestioning loyalty: The vast majority of Manchester United supporters continue to have faith in Moyes Show of support: The Chosen One banner hanging from the upper tier of the Stretford End   This is what Roy Hodgson said when he got the job: \'I know Sir Alex is not really a Liverpool man, so I’m a bit concerned about my excellent relationship with him. I sincerely hope he forgives me for moving north and hopefully we can have a glass of wine together, maybe in secret. I hope that’s how he is going to see it.\' He was never a Liverpool manager. Suckdaroot, Old Oswestry No, he was a Liverpool manager who did not understand the rules of engagement in the north-west. Ferguson did, Rafael Benitez did, Brendan Rodgers does, David Moyes doesn’t, strangely. Hodgson didn’t think the rivalry between Liverpool and Manchester United mattered, he thought his friendship with Ferguson was more important than any petty enmity. In displaying this attitude he alienated Liverpool’s fans. Benitez got it straight away, and so did Rodgers by pouncing on Moyes when he said Liverpool were favourites to win at Old Trafford. I think Roy is a very decent guy and there were more valid reasons to criticise him at Liverpool than his relationship with a rival. I think it says a lot for him that he didn’t feel it mattered. Football has always been tribal, but now it’s like the Khmer Rouge. No other viewpoint is acceptable.  United fans are not responsible for camera close-ups of Ferguson’s face each time we concede. The soap opera of the master being in the stands looking down on his chosen apprentice is a storyline that Sky and BT have perpetuated since the beginning of the season. Headjack, Manchester I realise that. I was linking the events because obviously that story-line is also influenced by the discontent around the Moyes reign. I wasn’t suggesting United fans are directly responsible for the camera shots. Anyway, talking of jack, here’s Frankie again. It doesn’t get any better than this. Really it doesn’t.   Focus of attention: Sir Alex Ferguson is picked out in the Old Trafford crowd at every match   Sunday Supplement on Sky, March 30, 2014. “We need Moyes to succeed, if he fails that will just give credence to the clubs that hire successful overseas managers rather than recruit from the Premier League.”  Well, stuff you lot - United should not be a reporters project and Moyes should be judged by his current results, not the results from a mid-table club now doing better than United. This is not the first time this statement has been made on Sunday Supplement, and it is why the press are easy on Moyes. Little Helper, Boston That quote wasn’t mine. I’m on Sunday Supplement about as often as Jim Davidson gets invited on Loose Women. I’m a guest this weekend for the first time since January 26 and the occasion before was November 17. I accept though that the line about needing Moyes to succeed to advance the cause of British managers is a familiar one, and I certainly felt that way at the start of the season. Less so now, though. The job Brendan Rodgers has done at Liverpool shows what can be achieved with a progressive British coach, and the failure of imported managers at the bottom of the Premier League table is rather underlining the suspicion that even Jose Mourinho and Rafael Benitez might not have been so eye-catching had they been lumbered with Fulham and Sunderland mid-season. And, in truth, just because Pepe Mel is making hard work of West Brom it doesn’t make all Spanish coaches useless; so whatever happens to Moyes at Old Trafford should not reflect on British managers. A passport never won the title.  The fact that the MEN poll included Ferguson in the list of people to blame for United’s plight means that the media have also identified him as a potential guilty party. Ferguson should recommend the removal of Moyes at the end of the season: it will surely go on record as one of his best moves. Redtothebones, Mauritius If Ferguson made a big play of removing Moyes, who would want to work for United under that pressure; the former manager up in the stands like a Roman Emperor, thumbs up or thumbs down.  The majority of fans were against the Chosen One banner being put up and even more against that embarrassing plane effort. JB, Manchester Here’s an idea. Why not go along, wear your colours, cheer or boo as you see fit, and don’t let the making and display of banners ruin your lives?  The problem is a generation of United fans know nothing but success, have never suffered with their team and don\'t know how to deal with a transitional phase. The sad truth is had Ferguson stayed another year and the team suffered this way they would probably have turned on him and said it was time to go. For that reason alone I\'m glad he left at the very top where he belonged. Steviejay99, Colchester Me too, Steve. There are not many great managers that bow out in style like Sir Alex. Remember.  Sad farewell: Brian Clough\'s final match saw Nottingham Forest relegated from the Premier League    The fact remains Ferguson was consulted and gave the most asinine advice ever: pick Moyes. Not only that, knowing it was going to be his last season, he went for the title, rather than planning and investing for the future. Although welcome in the short term, that victory will hurt United in the middle and maybe even long term as they try to rebuild. Vadid1, London Yes, I can just imagine that speech to the faithful. \'Well, lads, having seen Manchester City win the title and having to suck that raw all summer, I think it’s fair to tell you that I’ll be letting them win it again this season because I’m going to plan for the future. And then I’m off. So, don’t worry. If anyone asks why we let Robin van Persie sign for City and send them 20 points clear by March, just tell them it’s all under control and we weren’t trying to win the league this season anyway. I’ll be telling the players that, too, so don’t worry if some of them start knocking off a bit early. It’s all part of the plan.\' What a fool, Fergie, eh? He only tried to win the league instead.  The media and supporters have been talking about Moyes as Ferguson’s successor for years. Henry, Colchester I know. He was the Chosen One a long time before there was a banner about it.  Let\'s get serious. Moyes is considering making Rooney captain? Rooney is good at his job, scoring goals, but he\'s about as much captaincy material as I\'m an Eskimo with a herd of camels parked in the drive. Scooter, Norwich Come on Sheikh Abdullah Eeyeekalduk Wentshukumishiteu Al-Ghamdi. We know it’s you. And, frankly, you need to sort those camels out or we’ll never get the van parked.  Captaincy material? Wayne Rooney should be unburdened by responsibility and concentrate on scoring goals   Now Richard Scudamore, the Premier League chief executive, has acknowledged it costs the business lots of money when Manchester United fail, those 20 titles are questionable. The Premier League can be equated with US wrestling. Charlesang, SingaporeI spoke to Richard on Monday. His explanation is that he got tucked up by a South African reporter, who ignored his initial answer to the question, ‘Is United’s failure bad for the Premier League?’ Richard says his answer was, ‘No.’ He then went on to explain that continued failure could cost United overseas fans, but that in his experience those supporters would be picked up by other clubs, such as Chelsea, which is what happened with Liverpool and Manchester United. He said the reporter selected his quotes to make it appear as if he was saying the League needed United to be successful. I have no confirmation either way. All I would say is that, as I put in my little commentary, I have known Richard for a long time and he is far from stupid. I was genuinely surprised that he would have endorsed United in this way.  Ferguson could have overseen the new management with certain stipulations, such as not letting the back room team leave. Dastardly, Thailand That would have been a poor start: appointing a manager and then choosing his staff.  I seem to remember Ferguson’s camp claiming to the press that he was single-handedly responsible for choosing Moyes. Now he wants distance from that choice. This is getting more embarrassing by the day. Onegoal, Manchester Camp? What camp? I imagine the line about Ferguson’s role in Moyes appointment came from a briefing by the club. And he is not distancing himself from the decision; far from it.  Stay or go: Some have suggested that Moyes should have retained Ferguson\'s former assistant Mike Phelan   The really big question is how Ferguson got every referee under his thumb. There should be an independent inquiry into why Moyes has already had more penalties against his side at Old Trafford than Ferguson did during his whole reign. That is of course statistically impossible and in horse racing would result in a stewards inquiry if not a Royal Commission but in the strange world of football – nothing. Ericjimbob, Tunbridge WellsAnd do you know why Ericjimbob? Because as a piece of information, it’s cobblers. United have had three penalties awarded against them in the league this season; compared to six under Ferguson in 2010-11 or five in 2006-07. In his last 11 seasons, Ferguson had 26 penalties awarded against Manchester United in the Premier League. Those are the facts; but here’s Bill with an equally valid theory-based explanation. The more time you spend defending your own penalty area, the more penalties you concede and the more time you spend attacking the other penalty area the more you win. So under Moyes, a weaker United are conceding more penalties and winning fewer. Bill, Barnsley, 1 day ago  The most frustrating thing is that there is absolutely nothing that Moyes has done that indicates progress. Brendan Rodgers at Liverpool showed straight away what his philosophy was. Moyes has no real style of play. What are we working towards exactly? Who do we need to buy to play the Moyes way? It’s all very worrying. Dan The Man, Manchester I can see that Dan. I thought United did well against Bayern Munich, but that type of stoicism is not really a game plan for the Premier League. And now, a Voice of Reason – and a final word from Frankie. RIP.   Given time and patience it will come right. Anyone who has followed United for decades and seen how things have changed since the Glazers took over will know just how much Ferguson has done to keep things sane in insane times. Miracles even. When Moyes was at Everton, everyone to a man said he was a great manager and deserved a big club. He has that now and I trust Ferguson. The Vimto Kid, Gastley Like a cool summer breeze wasn’t it? Ah well. Back to the madhouse.  Moyes has done a horrid job at United. From his ridiculously long vacation, to the naive transfer summer, to the backroom staff, to the defensive and negative football, to the complete lack of tactical nous, to the embarrassing team selections, to the remarkably bad substitutions, to the defeatist interviews, to the pampering of Rooney, to the training methods, to the weak man-management, the man has no plan. I have few heroes and Sir Alex is one of them. This doesn\'t mean he is impervious to criticism. The last few years his tactics became more pragmatic. He didn\'t give young talent enough of a chance. He didn\'t replace the old guard. He didn\'t address the glaring midfield problem. Lastly, he appointed Moyes. A bizarre choice. No level headed United supporter expected a trophy this season or the next, but we expected positive and attractive football. Finishing seventh is also unacceptable for a club of United\'s size and stature. King Cantona, Oslo It is amazing Manchester United even make it to matches without being run over by the team bus or locked in the training ground by mistake with such a band of incompetents in charge. Good shout on his poor training methods, though. That must be a hell of a set of binoculars you’ve got in Oslo.  The Manchester Evening News ran another poll in 1995 after Ferguson sold Mark Hughes, Paul Ince and Andrei Kanchelskis and a majority of fans wanted the manager sacked. Turns out it was hijacked by Manchester City fans. Tom, London Or imbeciles, Tom. Don’t rule out imbeciles. They’re a very strong lobby.  Put to the vote: A 1995 poll after United sold Mark Hughes and Andrei Kanchelskis (below) found that a majority of fans wanted Alex Ferguson sacked      When Bill Shankly retired you did not see him walking the corridors of Anfield and since that day all who followed him at Liverpool did the same. Kenny Dalglish only came back because the club asked him to. It would have been better had Ferguson taken a year holiday from Old Trafford and let Moyes get on with it. The old fool wants to remain in his empire until the day he dies. Crazykopite, Thailand That’s a very rosy picture you paint, Crazy. Shankly wasn’t made particularly welcome at the Liverpool training ground, so took to hanging around places like Everton and Wrexham just to stay involved with football. Why should he go on a cruise for a year? Nobody has more right to watch a game at Old Trafford than Ferguson. Nobody.  He could have said: \'I trust you to make the right choice.\' Anonymous, London Why give a non-committal answer? He wanted to help.  Sir Alex Ferguson with Manchester United was like Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party. Both strong leaders who dominated and changed the landscape, but neither saw suitable successors and ultimately stayed too long. Pro Benitez Cult, North Korea Stayed too long? He won the league last year. BaggsyB, Luxembourg Yes, but don’t you understand Baggsy – he should have let that slide and planned for the future.  Shame on you Martin, a very disappointing page. Oh well, you\'ve always got Wednesday, after our latest battering by Bayern Munich. Bobby, Salford Not easy being Nostradamus, is it mate? Try it six days a week.   More... MARTIN SAMUEL: Ferguson had to pick a successor or tell United to get stuffed. It was an easy choice... he wanted to leave the club in safe hands He\'s given the World Cup to friends of terrorists but Blatter\'s true aim (and try not to laugh) is to win the Nobel Peace Prize! MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE \'He could have hurt me\': Rooney blasts \'cheat\' charge, saying he didn\'t dive to get Schweinsteiger sent off Roy looked out for me! O\'Shea denies rift with former United team-mate Keane United played like a handball team, says Robben after Bayern possession fails to equate to first leg lead   Share or comment on this article 51shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1076417/Martin-Samuel---Debate.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Martin Samuel - Debate</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 03:02 EST, 3 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 09:05 EST, 3 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postTo