dException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"60\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"61\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"62\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"63\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"64\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"65\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"66\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"19\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"21\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"31\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"32\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"33\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Book Title\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"37\" Name=\"Bibliography\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\"/> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]> <style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\"; mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; mso-style-noshow:yes; mso-style-priority:99; mso-style-parent:\"\"; mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; mso-para-margin:0cm; mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:\"Times New Roman\",\"serif\";} </style> <![endif]--> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Time for another change? Sir Alex Ferguson has come under scrutiny for his recommendation of David Moyes as his replacement last summer\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a1340e61\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBEFB7700000578-19_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"The Chosen One: David Moyes has come under pressure following a poor start to his tenure at Manchester United\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-ad580e8c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBFB26900000578-887_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Time for another change? After a season of poor results, Sir Alex Ferguson (left) has come under scrutiny for his recommendation of David Moyes (right) as his replacement at Manchester United last summer<br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Showing the strain: Michael Carrick, Wayne Rooney and Rio Ferdinand have endured a tough time this term\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"469\" id=\"i-ade10e9c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1C90EBAB00000578-935_634x469.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Showing the strain: Michael Carrick, Wayne Rooney and Rio Ferdinand have endured a tough time this term</p> </div><p> </p><div class=\"moduleFull\"> <a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3394953540001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">David Moyes reacting after each of United\'s 10 League losses</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/26/video-undefined-1C959C3E00000578-795_636x358.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"><br/><br/> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:TrackMoves/> <w:TrackFormatting/> <w:PunctuationKerning/> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid> <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent> <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText> <w:DoNotPromoteQF/> <w:LidThemeOther>EN-GB</w:LidThemeOther> <w:LidThemeAsian>X-NONE</w:LidThemeAsian> <w:LidThemeComplexScript>X-NONE</w:LidThemeComplexScript> <w:Compatibility> <w:BreakWrappedTables/> <w:SnapToGridInCell/> <w:WrapTextWithPunct/> <w:UseAsianBreakRules/> <w:DontGrowAutofit/> <w:SplitPgBreakAndParaMark/> <w:EnableOpenTypeKerning/> <w:DontFlipMirrorIndents/> <w:OverrideTableStyleHps/> </w:Compatibility> <w:BrowserLevel>MicrosoftInternetExplorer4</w:BrowserLevel> <m:mathPr> <m:mathFont m:val=\"Cambria Math\"/> <m:brkBin m:val=\"before\"/> <m:brkBinSub m:val=\"--\"/> <m:smallFrac m:val=\"off\"/> <m:dispDef/> <m:lMargin m:val=\"0\"/> <m:rMargin m:val=\"0\"/> <m:defJc m:val=\"centerGroup\"/> <m:wrapIndent m:val=\"1440\"/> <m:intLim m:val=\"subSup\"/> <m:naryLim m:val=\"undOvr\"/> </m:mathPr></w:WordDocument> </xml><![endif]--></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">You continually take shots at Kenny Dalglish and it seems quite out of place. The Andy Carroll signing was a poor one, as it turned out, but this was primarily a result of Dalglish being released by the club and Carroll not being part of Brendan Rodgers\' plan. He was signed in the context of getting £15m more for Fernando Torres than they were paying for Carroll. They have recouped some of that money already and it will prove less of a loss, from a financial and PR point of view, than Torres will for Chelsea. Are you going to be similarly scathing about the signing of Marouane Fellaini, who has shown zero upside; or about the way the \'chosen one\' is leading Manchester United to their lowest finish in Premiership history? How about the way Dalglish took Liverpool to a trophy and a cup final in his one bad season – bad only by his very high standards. Moyes has a higher net spend than Dalglish in his second spell at Liverpool, took over the Champions and has no silverware to show for it. There’s some balance for you.<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"> Paul McCabe, Dundee</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Paul, I don’t need lessons in balance from someone who cannot admit that Dalglish was sacked by Liverpool. Doves get released, mate. Prison inmates get released. Kenny got the bullet. There were two pieces in Monday’s column that mentioned Dalglish, probably the first time I have referred to him this season. One noted his achievements as player, manager and man and the love for him at Anfield, no matter the odd mistake in his second managerial spell; the other took issue with his assertion that Sam Allardyce needed greater financial support from the West Ham United board and ‘better players’ – considering that two of those players, Carroll and Stewart Downing, were bought by Dalglish at Liverpool for £55m. I’d say that is balance. I thought Kenny made an inconsistent argument regarding Allardyce, much like yours over Carroll. He worked out as a £20m loss for Liverpool and that is not excused by Torres’s failure at Chelsea or Fellaini’s at Manchester United. As for Moyes, he’s hardly getting an easy ride; least of all over Fellaini.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Released or sacked: Kenny Dalglish pictured in the Anfield stands with Ian Rush last Sunday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"450\" id=\"i-9ccb0e38\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CB3B13700000578-44_634x450.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Released or sacked: Kenny Dalglish pictured in the Anfield stands with Ian Rush last Sunday</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Difficult ride: Marouane Fellaini, who cost £28.5m last summer, has struggled to make an impact at Old Trafford\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"459\" id=\"i-ac950e87\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBF492D00000578-104_634x459.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Difficult ride: Marouane Fellaini, who cost £28.5m last summer, has struggled to make an impact at Old Trafford</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It is Sir Alex Ferguson’s fault. He knew an aging team over-achieved last season, so thought he could drop them and make himself look great. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Scouseblue, Liverpool</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He didn’t need that last title to look great. What went before had pretty much guaranteed that epitaph. And every team is aging. The word you are looking for is old, and United are not actually old. David De Gea, Phil Jones, Chris Smalling, Rafael, Danny Welbeck, Wilfried Zaha and Tom Cleverley are not old, and this year Moyes has introduced Adnan Januzaj. You may think they are not good enough – but they’re not old.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Despite Ferguson’s fantastic record over the years, it doesn\'t change the fact he is to blame for the current situation. He let the squad stagnate for five years and played with a big hole in midfield. He should have replaced Roy Keane and Paul Scholes and instead was an apologist for the Glazers by claiming repeatedly there was no value in the transfer market. The centre backs were aging yet he didn\'t bother buying replacements for Rio Ferdinand or Nemanja Vidic. In the past he had his eye on the future and replaced players well before they were past their best, but didn\'t bother as he was going to retire. Then he made a terrible mistake by appointing Moyes. So whose fault is it? Nobody is perfect, not even Ferguson. He is not beyond criticism. All around were buying class players and have overtaken us. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Nick63 Menston, Leeds</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Jones and Smalling were bought to replace Vidic and Ferdinand, and I would imagine Shinji Kagawa was seen as key to reinventing midfield creativity following the retirement of Scholes. Good luck finding that replacement for Roy Keane, though, because I don’t see one at too many other clubs, either. Fernandinho at Manchester City, perhaps. Most likely, Ferguson did not see the crash coming because he got extraordinary levels of performance from his players, so did not realise their weakness in the hands of another manager. I don’t know why it has to be somebody’s fault all of the time. At worst, Ferguson recommended the wrong man – but he did so with the best intentions.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Forward planning: United have not properly replaced centre-back pairing Rio Ferdinand and Nemanja Vidic, according to some\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"447\" id=\"i-ac950e86\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBF61B800000578-423_634x447.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Forward planning: United have not properly replaced centre-back pairing Rio Ferdinand and Nemanja Vidic, according to some</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Replacement: Phil Jones was signed to be United\'s centre-back in the long-term\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"473\" id=\"i-ab0e0e79\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBF402900000578-654_634x473.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Replacement: Phil Jones was signed to be United\'s centre-back in the long-term</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Compared to Paris St Germain, Bayern Munich and Manchester City, United have done nothing over the past three years to build strength. This was on Ferguson’s watch and he must take 100 per cent responsibility for this dismal and pathetic team. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Angst06, Toronto</span></font><br/><br/><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The dismal and pathetic team that came close to beating Bayern Munich on Tuesday night, you mean? That dismal and pathetic team? Bayern Munich are currently taking advantage of a spell in which their academy has produced a clutch of world-class players, as happened to Manchester United two decades ago; PSG and Manchester City have limitless funds under Gulf ownership. Despite this, Manchester United are the reigning champions. That was on Ferguson’s watch; or have you forgotten already?</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The problem with the poll regarding who is to blame for Manchester United\'s current situation is that it deals in absolutes. There is no single reason for their problems, but a variety of different elements combining to make it a really tough season for whoever took charge. What manager at the end of any campaign could say that no area of his team needed improvement? Ideally, Ferguson would have let Moyes know much earlier that he would be the next manager leading to a smoother transition. I guess he just wasn\'t willing to take the risk of it leaking and potentially ruining his final season. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Jbers, France</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Ferguson always regretted prematurely announcing his intention to retire at the end of the 2001-02 season. He thought the players switched off, and he couldn’t stand the idea of Sven Goran Eriksson reaping the benefit of his good work, so changed his mind. Without doubt his plans were kept under wraps this time to avoid a repeat. <br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Why not me? Sven Goran Eriksson was lined up to replace Sir Alex Ferguson back in 2002\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"801\" id=\"i-9b410e30\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-004F327E00000258-97_634x801.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Why not me? Sven Goran Eriksson was lined up to replace Sir Alex Ferguson back in 2002</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">You wrote: ‘Some would say he picked the wrong manager, but he didn’t. He just picked the wrong club; one with very short memories and a well-honed sense of entitlement.’ Correction, Mr Samuel: Ferguson picked the right club, you just happen to be listening to the wrong fans. If, as you say, 25 per cent are blaming Sir Alex, then I and the other 75 per cent need to continue the vocal support we witnessed at Old Trafford on Saturday. United we stand, divided we fall. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Babs7Falmouth, Truro</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">United we stand, divided we’re lumbered. My favourite line from Performance, and there are a few contenders, some of which you’ll find in the song below. (I take your point, by the way – 25 per cent is not a majority, but it’s still a significant number).</font></span></p>\n<p><br/><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/cHTDkJ-bQqM\" width=\"640\"></iframe> <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><br/></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Not getting all the talk coming out of Old Trafford that the club is built on stability and they don\'t hire and fire. They had one manager for nearly three decades winning a trophy if not every year then pretty close to it – so of course you are going to have stability. They should have gone for Carlo Ancelotti, he was the perfect fit for United, a manager that works well with all players and clearly wasn\'t comfortable at Paris St Germain last summer. Ancelotti’s teams play good football and he is a proven winner. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">SpannersXI, Coventry</span></font><br/><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">I agree about Ancelotti being a good fit. My information is that he wins the league, or Champions League, at Real Madrid this summer or is sacked. If that happens, he should be on the radar of a number of English clubs – most particularly Manchester United and Tottenham Hotspur if they decide to change. He is a healing type, too, not the sort to come in at Old Trafford and create turmoil.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Good fit: Carlo Ancelotti could be brought in at the end of the season if United decide to dispense with Moyes\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"429\" id=\"i-aa4f0e76\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CC6232A00000578-179_634x429.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Good fit: Carlo Ancelotti could be brought in at the end of the season if United decide to dispense with Moyes</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Moyes got the job at Everton because he was recommended by his predecessor, Walter Smith, he was also offered a job on the Old Trafford coaching staff by Ferguson but preferred to be a manager. He is well thought of in the coaching fraternity and a couple of years ago even Arsene Wenger stated that he thought Moyes one of our best. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Bill, United Kingdom</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">You’re right. If Ferguson made a mistake there are a few that would have followed him down that road – some of the best judges in the game, in fact. </font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Maybe the fans are blaming Ferguson for leaving Moyes with an aging squad who are coming to the end of their contracts at the club? Maybe they are blaming him for the lack of real investment in the squad over the last few seasons of his reign? He relied on Scholes and Ryan Giggs in midfield and never replaced them, and at the end of this season three out of four first team defenders are probably off elsewhere. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Rhod, Wrexham, 1 day ago</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The average age of the team that beat Aston Villa 4-1 was 26, after substitutions it was still 26 and the average age of the bench, which included 40-year-old Giggs, was 27. This aging squad is a myth. You’ll find these false presumptions occurring throughout football. Say it enough times and everybody believes it.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"The veteran: Despite the presence of 40-year-old Ryan Giggs, United\'s squad still has a relatively young average age\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"418\" id=\"i-ac910e88\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBF51F100000578-629_634x418.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">The veteran: Despite the presence of 40-year-old Ryan Giggs, United\'s squad still has a relatively young average age</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">United need a major overhaul, let Moyes do it, then judge. Enjoy the past glories and memories, we all do and share those with United fans, but the future needs change. Every team has to go through it so stop the whining guys and get on with the planning for next year and beyond. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Wbafan, Canada</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Sage advice from a West Bromwich Albion fan living in Canada. Do you want me to deal with this, or is it over to you? I’m feeling generous, you have this one. Try to keep it clean.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">For the world\'s biggest club to have no succession plan is farcical. Everyone knew it was just a matter of time before Ferguson retired. Disgraceful and embarrassing incompetence from the owners and the board. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Stretfordhead, Texas</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They did have a succession plan, mate. He’s called David Moyes. Just because you don’t rate him doesn’t mean it wasn’t a plan.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"The plan: United handed David Moyes a six-year contract and a brief to take United forward post-Ferguson\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"392\" id=\"i-ac7f0e89\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBF0C5200000578-578_634x392.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">The plan: United handed David Moyes a six-year contract and a brief to take United forward post-Ferguson</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">No right minded United fan would ever direct ire at Ferguson in his retirement. Every fan base has their idiots, without exception. It is myopic to focus on a handful of disgruntled supporters, fresh from another home humiliation. What happened in the home game that following the comprehensive 3-0 battering by Manchester City? The 70,000 in Old Trafford gave a rapturous supportive ovation to their beleaguered manager and were unanimous in their choral condemnation of that silly plane. It is difficult to imagine the fans of clubs with comparable status such as Real Madrid, Barcelona and Bayern Munich maintaining comparable sympathy for their manager if they were seventh in their league with scant chance of Champions League football next season. All of the support for Moyes is a proxy support of Ferguson. It is because Ferguson chose him that they maintain the respect for Moyes. It\'s certainly not for his promising previous achievements or exciting, expansive football. United fans standing by Moyes is perhaps the greatest testament to the support of Ferguson, more real than any road or statue. It is blind, unquestioning faith in his final instruction \"your job now is to support your new manager\". According to market research company Kantar, United have a total worldwide fan base of 659 million. How many fans were polled by the Manchester Evening News? If we\'re generous and say 50,000, then the 12,500 fans that blame Ferguson for the current predicament comprise 0.0018 per cent of the fan pool. If this is the metric by which our most respected sports journalists can muse indignantly on the over entitled I-phone generation may I direct them to Twitter? How about radio phone-ins? I\'ve heard several Liverpool fans call for Brendan Rodgers\' head this season after a single poor result. Basing your opinion on the ravings of a silly minority is puzzling. Was the enemy not within when Roy Hodgson got the boot from Anfield? He was appointed in July 2010 and was out by January 2011. Hodgson said of Liverpool’s fans: “The famous Anfield support has not really been there.” Moyes was appointed in July 2013 and is still there despite doing a worse job than Hodgson. Moyes said of United fans: “The crowds have been incredible. I\'m not feeling any pressure from inside the club. It\'s all coming from you people [the media].\" Yet it\'s United fans that have no class according to some. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">The Henery, Portsmouth</span></font><br/><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Spot on. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Chrism, Manchester</span></font><br/><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">No, it isn’t actually, Chris. Take the 0.0018 per cent of the fan pool statistic. It only works if we believe that just under 10 per cent of the world’s population are Manchester United fans. Equally, say we accept 659 million is genuine figure; then on the law of average roughly a quarter of them – close to 165 million – are currently blaming Ferguson. The Hodgson quote is taken from after he was sacked; the Moyes quote while he remains in the job and is desperate for the fans to back him. It is no surprise that they are different in attitude. If Moyes goes in the summer, he might have a more self-pitying take on the pressure he was under. As for the assertion that no United fan would ever blame Ferguson, that simply isn’t true. I go through many comments to produce this debate column – and there is plenty of criticism of Ferguson out there, and not all coming from shallow, aggrieved citizens of Singapore and Chicago who thought the good times would never end. I think the reaction to the plane was less vindication for Moyes, more embarrassment at a stunt that did not reflect well on the supporters, who vocally distanced themselves from it. I do agree, though, that it is only Ferguson’s backing for Moyes and the fans devotion to Ferguson that has prevented the atmosphere becoming more febrile this season.  I think the worst of it may well be over for Moyes and the bulk of the supporters stayed with him, which is admirable, but if he gets this much-vaunted £200m in the summer, it will be interesting to see how long that backing lasts if United are still a conservative team next season. <br/></font></span></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unquestioning loyalty: The vast majority of Manchester United supporters continue to have faith in Moyes\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"402\" id=\"i-aff80ea0\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBEFED200000578-454_634x402.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unquestioning loyalty: The vast majority of Manchester United supporters continue to have faith in Moyes</p><div class=\"clear\"> </div><div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Show of support: The Chosen One banner hanging from the upper tier of the Stretford End\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"391\" id=\"i-acb40e84\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CAAF03A00000578-141_634x391.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Show of support: The Chosen One banner hanging from the upper tier of the Stretford End</p> </div><p> </p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">This is what Roy Hodgson said when he got the job: \'I know Sir Alex is not really a Liverpool man, so I’m a bit concerned about my excellent relationship with him. I sincerely hope he forgives me for moving north and hopefully we can have a glass of wine together, maybe in secret. I hope that’s how he is going to see it.\' He was never a Liverpool manager. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Suckdaroot, Old Oswestry</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">No, he was a Liverpool manager who did not understand the rules of engagement in the north-west. Ferguson did, Rafael Benitez did, Brendan Rodgers does, David Moyes doesn’t, strangely. Hodgson didn’t think the rivalry between Liverpool and Manchester United mattered, he thought his friendship with Ferguson was more important than any petty enmity. In displaying this attitude he alienated Liverpool’s fans. Benitez got it straight away, and so did Rodgers by pouncing on Moyes when he said Liverpool were favourites to win at Old Trafford. I think Roy is a very decent guy and there were more valid reasons to criticise him at Liverpool than his relationship with a rival. I think it says a lot for him that he didn’t feel it mattered. Football has always been tribal, but now it’s like the Khmer Rouge. No other viewpoint is acceptable.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span>United fans are not responsible for camera close-ups of Ferguson’s face each time we concede. The soap opera of the master being in the stands looking down on his chosen apprentice is a storyline that Sky and BT have perpetuated since the beginning of the season. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Headjack, Manchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">I realise that. I was linking the events because obviously that story-line is also influenced by the discontent around the Moyes reign. I wasn’t suggesting United fans are directly responsible for the camera shots. Anyway, talking of jack, here’s Frankie again. It doesn’t get any better than this. Really it doesn’t. <br/></span></font></p>\n<p><br/><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/8es4gOoJgXc\" width=\"640\"></iframe></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Focus of attention: Sir Alex Ferguson is picked out in the Old Trafford crowd at every match\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"444\" id=\"i-a9d60e6d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1C9002FB00000578-810_634x444.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Focus of attention: Sir Alex Ferguson is picked out in the Old Trafford crowd at every match</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Sunday Supplement on Sky, March 30, 2014. “We need Moyes to succeed, if he fails that will just give credence to the clubs that hire successful overseas managers rather than recruit from the Premier League.”  Well, stuff you lot - United should not be a reporters project and Moyes should be judged by his current results, not the results from a mid-table club now doing better than United. This is not the first time this statement has been made on Sunday Supplement, and it is why the press are easy on Moyes. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Little Helper, Boston</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">That quote wasn’t mine. I’m on Sunday Supplement about as often as Jim Davidson gets invited on Loose Women. I’m a guest this weekend for the first time since January 26 and the occasion before was November 17. I accept though that the line about needing Moyes to succeed to advance the cause of British managers is a familiar one, and I certainly felt that way at the start of the season. Less so now, though. The job Brendan Rodgers has done at Liverpool shows what can be achieved with a progressive British coach, and the failure of imported managers at the bottom of the Premier League table is rather underlining the suspicion that even Jose Mourinho and Rafael Benitez might not have been so eye-catching had they been lumbered with Fulham and Sunderland mid-season. And, in truth, just because Pepe Mel is making hard work of West Brom it doesn’t make all Spanish coaches useless; so whatever happens to Moyes at Old Trafford should not reflect on British managers. A passport never won the title.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span>The fact that the MEN poll included Ferguson in the list of people to blame for United’s plight means that the media have also identified him as a potential guilty party. Ferguson should recommend the removal of Moyes at the end of the season: it will surely go on record as one of his best moves. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Redtothebones, Mauritius</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">If Ferguson made a big play of removing Moyes, who would want to work for United under that pressure; the former manager up in the stands like a Roman Emperor, thumbs up or thumbs down. <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span>The majority of fans were against the Chosen One banner being put up and even more against that embarrassing plane effort. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">JB, Manchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Here’s an idea. Why not go along, wear your colours, cheer or boo as you see fit, and don’t let the making and display of banners ruin your lives? <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The problem is a generation of United fans know nothing but success, have never suffered with their team and don\'t know how to deal with a transitional phase. The sad truth is had Ferguson stayed another year and the team suffered this way they would probably have turned on him and said it was time to go. For that reason alone I\'m glad he left at the very top where he belonged. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Steviejay99, Colchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Me too, Steve. There are not many great managers that bow out in style like Sir Alex. Remember.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Sad farewell: Brian Clough\'s final match saw Nottingham Forest relegated from the Premier League\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-9dbc0e41\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CCA856200000578-47_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Sad farewell: Brian Clough\'s final match saw Nottingham Forest relegated from the Premier League</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The fact remains Ferguson was consulted and gave the most asinine advice ever: pick Moyes. Not only that, knowing it was going to be his last season, he went for the title, rather than planning and investing for the future. Although welcome in the short term, that victory will hurt United in the middle and maybe even long term as they try to rebuild. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Vadid1, London</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Yes, I can just imagine that speech to the faithful. \'Well, lads, having seen Manchester City win the title and having to suck that raw all summer, I think it’s fair to tell you that I’ll be letting them win it again this season because I’m going to plan for the future. And then I’m off. So, don’t worry. If anyone asks why we let Robin van Persie sign for City and send them 20 points clear by March, just tell them it’s all under control and we weren’t trying to win the league this season anyway. I’ll be telling the players that, too, so don’t worry if some of them start knocking off a bit early. It’s all part of the plan.\' What a fool, Fergie, eh? He only tried to win the league instead.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The media and supporters have been talking about Moyes as Ferguson’s successor for years. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Henry, Colchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">I know. He was the Chosen One a long time before there was a banner about it.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Let\'s get serious. Moyes is considering making Rooney captain? Rooney is good at his job, scoring goals, but he\'s about as much captaincy material as I\'m an Eskimo with a herd of camels parked in the drive. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Scooter, Norwich</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Come on Sheikh Abdullah Eeyeekalduk Wentshukumishiteu Al-Ghamdi. We know it’s you. And, frankly, you need to sort those camels out or we’ll never get the van parked.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Captaincy material? Wayne Rooney should be unburdened by responsibility and concentrate on scoring goals\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"437\" id=\"i-ad760e95\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CBFA07800000578-899_634x437.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Captaincy material? Wayne Rooney should be unburdened by responsibility and concentrate on scoring goals</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Now Richard Scudamore, the Premier League chief executive, has acknowledged it costs the business lots of money when Manchester United fail, those 20 titles are questionable. The Premier League can be equated with US wrestling. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Charlesang, Singapore</span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><br/><br/>I spoke to Richard on Monday. His explanation is that he got tucked up by a South African reporter, who ignored his initial answer to the question, ‘Is United’s failure bad for the Premier League?’ Richard says his answer was, ‘No.’ He then went on to explain that continued failure could cost United overseas fans, but that in his experience those supporters would be picked up by other clubs, such as Chelsea, which is what happened with Liverpool and Manchester United. He said the reporter selected his quotes to make it appear as if he was saying the League needed United to be successful. I have no confirmation either way. All I would say is that, as I put in my little commentary, I have known Richard for a long time and he is far from stupid. I was genuinely surprised that he would have endorsed United in this way. <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Ferguson could have overseen the new management with certain stipulations, such as not letting the back room team leave. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Dastardly, Thailand</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">That would have been a poor start: appointing a manager and then choosing his staff. <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">I seem to remember Ferguson’s camp claiming to the press that he was single-handedly responsible for choosing Moyes. Now he wants distance from that choice. This is getting more embarrassing by the day. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Onegoal, Manchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Camp? What camp? I imagine the line about Ferguson’s role in Moyes appointment came from a briefing by the club. And he is not distancing himself from the decision; far from it. <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Stay or go: Some have suggested that Moyes should have retained Ferguson\'s former assistant Mike Phelan\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-9d1c0e3d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CCA801400000578-77_634x423.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Stay or go: Some have suggested that Moyes should have retained Ferguson\'s former assistant Mike Phelan</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The really big question is how Ferguson got every referee under his thumb. There should be an independent inquiry into why Moyes has already had more penalties against his side at Old Trafford than Ferguson did during his whole reign. That is of course statistically impossible and in horse racing would result in a stewards inquiry if not a Royal Commission but in the strange world of football – nothing. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Ericjimbob, Tunbridge Wells</span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><br/><br/>And do you know why Ericjimbob? Because as a piece of information, it’s cobblers. United have had three penalties awarded against them in the league this season; compared to six under Ferguson in 2010-11 or five in 2006-07. In his last 11 seasons, Ferguson had 26 penalties awarded against Manchester United in the Premier League. Those are the facts; but here’s Bill with an equally valid theory-based explanation.</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The more time you spend defending your own penalty area, the more penalties you concede and the more time you spend attacking the other penalty area the more you win. So under Moyes, a weaker United are conceding more penalties and winning fewer. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Bill, Barnsley, 1 day ago</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span>The most frustrating thing is that there is absolutely nothing that Moyes has done that indicates progress. Brendan Rodgers at Liverpool showed straight away what his philosophy was. Moyes has no real style of play. What are we working towards exactly? Who do we need to buy to play the Moyes way? It’s all very worrying. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Dan The Man, Manchester</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">I can see that Dan. I thought United did well against Bayern Munich, but that type of stoicism is not really a game plan for the Premier League. And now, a Voice of Reason – and a final word from Frankie. RIP.</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><br/><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/wwLvDcZeJCo\" width=\"640\"></iframe></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Given time and patience it will come right. Anyone who has followed United for decades and seen how things have changed since the Glazers took over will know just how much Ferguson has done to keep things sane in insane times. Miracles even. When Moyes was at Everton, everyone to a man said he was a great manager and deserved a big club. He has that now and I trust Ferguson. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">The Vimto Kid, Gastley</span></font></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Like a cool summer breeze wasn’t it? Ah well. Back to the madhouse.</font></span></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span>Moyes has done a horrid job at United. From his ridiculously long vacation, to the naive transfer summer, to the backroom staff, to the defensive and negative football, to the complete lack of tactical nous, to the embarrassing team selections, to the remarkably bad substitutions, to the defeatist interviews, to the pampering of Rooney, to the training methods, to the weak man-management, the man has no plan. I have few heroes and Sir Alex is one of them. This doesn\'t mean he is impervious to criticism. The last few years his tactics became more pragmatic. He didn\'t give young talent enough of a chance. He didn\'t replace the old guard. He didn\'t address the glaring midfield problem. Lastly, he appointed Moyes. A bizarre choice. No level headed United supporter expected a trophy this season or the next, but we expected positive and attractive football. Finishing seventh is also unacceptable for a club of United\'s size and stature. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">King Cantona, Oslo</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">It is amazing Manchester United even make it to matches without being run over by the team bus or locked in the training ground by mistake with such a band of incompetents in charge. Good shout on his poor training methods, though. That must be a hell of a set of binoculars you’ve got in Oslo. <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\"></span>The Manchester Evening News ran another poll in 1995 after Ferguson sold Mark Hughes, Paul Ince and Andrei Kanchelskis and a majority of fans wanted the manager sacked. Turns out it was hijacked by Manchester City fans. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Tom, London</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Or imbeciles, Tom. Don’t rule out imbeciles. They’re a very strong lobby.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Put to the vote: A 1995 poll after United sold Mark Hughes and Andrei Kanchelskis (below) found that a majority of fans wanted Alex Ferguson sacked\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-ad660e8c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CCA43CB00000578-591_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Put to the vote: A 1995 poll after United sold Mark Hughes and Andrei Kanchelskis (below) found that a majority of fans wanted Alex Ferguson sacked</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Put to the vote: A 1995 poll after United sold Mark Hughes and Andrei Kanchelskis (below) found that a majority of fans wanted Alex Ferguson sacked\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"422\" id=\"i-ac440e81\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CCA3D1700000578-719_634x422.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">When Bill Shankly retired you did not see him walking the corridors of Anfield and since that day all who followed him at Liverpool did the same. Kenny Dalglish only came back because the club asked him to. It would have been better had Ferguson taken a year holiday from Old Trafford and let Moyes get on with it. The old fool wants to remain in his empire until the day he dies.<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"> Crazykopite, Thailand</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">That’s a very rosy picture you paint, Crazy. Shankly wasn’t made particularly welcome at the Liverpool training ground, so took to hanging around places like Everton and Wrexham just to stay involved with football. Why should he go on a cruise for a year? Nobody has more right to watch a game at Old Trafford than Ferguson. Nobody.  <br/></span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">He could have said: \'I trust you to make the right choice.\' <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Anonymous, London</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Why give a non-committal answer? He wanted to help.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Sir Alex Ferguson with Manchester United was like Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party. Both strong leaders who dominated and changed the landscape, but neither saw suitable successors and ultimately stayed too long. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Pro Benitez Cult, North Korea</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span>Stayed too long? He won the league last year. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">BaggsyB, Luxembourg</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Yes, but don’t you understand Baggsy – he should have let that slide and planned for the future.</span></font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Shame on you Martin, a very disappointing page. Oh well, you\'ve always got Wednesday, after our latest battering by Bayern Munich. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Bobby, Salford</span></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"></span><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Not easy being Nostradamus, is it mate? Try it six days a week.</span></font></p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/article-2592983/MARTIN-SAMUEL-Ferguson-pick-successor-tell-United-stuffed-It-easy-choice.html\"> MARTIN SAMUEL: Ferguson had to pick a successor or tell United to get stuffed. It was an easy choice... he wanted to leave the club in safe hands</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2590525/Hes-given-World-Cup-friends-terrorists-Blatters-true-aim-try-not-laugh-win-Nobel-Peace-Prize-MARTIN-SAMUEL-DEBATE-COLUMN.html\"> He\'s given the World Cup to friends of terrorists but Blatter\'s true aim (and try not to laugh) is to win the Nobel Peace Prize! MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2595481/He-hurt-Rooney-blasts-cheat-charge-Bayern-red-Schweinsteigers-dismissal.html\"> \'He could have hurt me\': Rooney blasts \'cheat\' charge, saying he didn\'t dive to get Schweinsteiger sent off</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2595374/John-OShea-denies-rift-claims-former-United-team-mate-Roy-Keane.html\"> Roy looked out for me! O\'Shea denies rift with former United team-mate Keane</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2595209/Manchester-United-1-1-Bayern-Munich-Arjen-Robben-says-United-played-like-handball-team.html\"> United played like a handball team, says Robben after Bayern possession fails to equate to first leg lead</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\"><br/></font>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2595752/Martin-Samuel-The-debate-Should-Manchester-United-fans-blame-Sir-Alex-Ferguson-poor-season-David-Moyes.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2595752/Martin-Samuel-The-debate-Should-Manchester-United-fans-blame-Sir-Alex-Ferguson-poor-season-David-Moyes.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"MARTIN SAMUEL - THE DEBATE: Should United fans blame Fergie for this season\'s wobble? At worst, he suggested the wrong man in Moyes - but he did so with the best of intentions\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2595752/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">51</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/03/article-2595752-1CCA3C5000000578-327_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:06','2014-04-03 16:05:33'),(118,'9abbe7d77d4da9f9382eab96588c523d95a79f1d180c6467977c628a1d7fd219','dailymail',NULL,'Arsenal are not the tight-knit family unit they were... Wenger can\'t do it all on his own','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/Arsenal-not-tight-knit-family-unit-Wenger-own.html',' By Neil Ashton Published: 18:01 EST, 1 April 2014 | Updated: 18:01 EST, 1 April 2014 133 shares 40 View comments  When Arsene Wenger was appointed manager of Arsenal in September 1996 the club employed around 70 full-time staff. There was dear old Maureen the tea lady, pushing her trolley through the marble halls and making sure everyone at Highbury was happy. In the warehouse, down the road from the famous old stadium, Arsenal had six or seven old boys making sure the club shop was fully stocked.  Historic: Arsenal\'s moved out of their former home at Highbury Stadium in 2006   Take a seat: Wenger is unveiled as the new Arsenal manager way back in September 1996    More... Wenger is behind the game, but there won\'t be an Arsenal uprising despite fans being sick to the stomach of broken promises As Hillsborough anniversary approaches, football must not forget all those who have been loved and lost in stadium tragedies Until English football takes a lesson from Bayern Munich\'s pass masters and turns possession into an obsession, we don\'t stand a chance ADRIAN DURHAM: Arsenal should do English football a favour and give Everton a go in the Champions League... And Terry\'s far from a captain, leader, legend - he\'s a Chelsea let-down Celtic join race for Arsenal\'s Fabianski as Drmic could snub Gunners for Leverkusen All the latest Arsenal news, features and opinion The box office employed another 10, eight in the commercial department, six more in the general office and a few manning the phones in the general office. Most would agree that it was a pretty tight, family unit. Vice-chairman David Dein kept the club ticking over and secretary Ken Friar was in charge of the club’s administrative matters. They were such a homely club that some days Ian Wright used to turn up at Highbury and start picking up phones on the general switchboard. It certainly surprised a few callers. Times change and Arsenal, just like Manchester City, Manchester United and Chelsea, have turned into giant, corporate monoliths. Today Arsenal, with a turnover of £250m and a wage bill in the region of £145m per annum, employ around 450 full-time staff. It would be stretching the imagination to think that Wenger is managing a staff of that size, but his tentacles at Arsenal reach far and wide. Everybody knows Wenger rules the roost at Arsenal. Last Friday, ahead of their clash with City at the Emirates, Wenger was asked whether he is accountable to anyone at the club. This was his response: ‘I don’t know’.  Dropping points: Arsenal have not won in three league games after drawing against Man City on Saturday   Unsure: Wenger says he does not know who he is accountable to   Call centre: Ian Wright (second left) often answered the phones at Highbury  Pressed further, he replied: ‘Look, our ambitions for the season - we are in a position where we can still fight for the top, we are in the semi-final of the FA Cup, we went out of the Champions League against Bayern Munich with 10 men and we have been consistent all season so I don’t think you can say our season up to now is a failure.’ In other words, he didn’t really answer the question. At 64, managing a club with the ambitions of a club the size of Arsenal, Wenger could do with some assistance in the day-to-day running of the football department. It makes an awful lot of sense. Take the top leagues in Europe - Spain, Italy, Germany, England and add the newbies Paris St Germain - as an example. Of the 17 clubs who qualified for the Champions League group stages, Arsenal and Manchester United are the only two clubs soldiering on without them. Here they are: Bayern Munich (Mathias Sammer), Borussia Dortmund (Michael Zorc), Bayer Leverkusen (Rudi Voller) and Schalke 04 (Horst Heldt). Juventus (Fabio Paratici), Inter (Marco Branca), Milan (Ariedo Braida) and Napoli (Ricardo Bijon). Barcelona (Andoni Zubizaretta), Real Madrid (Miguel Pardeza), Atletico Madrid (Miguel Angel Gil Marin) and Real Sociedad (Lorenzo Juarros). At Paris St Germain (Olivier Letang and CEO Jean-Claude Blanc share the role).  Old allies: Former Arsenal vice-president David Dein (left) left the club in 2007   Deal-broker: Dein and Wenger unveil Croatian striker Davor Suker in 1999  In England, Chelsea employ Michael Emenalo as director of football and Marina Granovskaia is the conduit between the football board and owner Roman Abramovich. This set-up allows Jose Mourinho to concentrate on the main business of the club, which is planning training sessions and working with his team. At Manchester City, the Barcelona axis of Ferran Soriano (chief executive) and Txiki Begiristain (sporting director) were brought in to take the heat off Roberto Mancini and now Manuel Pellegrini. Even down the road at Tottenham, where there has been an obsession with a continental management structure, chairman Daniel Levy employs Italian Franco Baldini in the role. There have been times in the past when Wenger has considered appointing someone into the role after Dein was fired by Arsenal’s former owner Danny Fiszman in 2007. Reading’s director of football Nicky Hammond was interviewed in the summer of 2007, but in the end it came to nothing.  State of the art: But Arsenal have not won a trophy since moving to the Emirates in 2006  Instead Wenger soldiered on with chief scout Steve Rowley and has found a niche role for Dick Law, previously based in Dallas, to make in roads into transfer business. Arsenal are already preparing for life beyond Wenger and will bring in a director of football to work with a first-team coach when the time comes. That is a decision that has been made by the chief executive Ivan Gazidis as he begins long-term preparations for the day when they need to find a new manager. Last Friday, Wenger reiterated that ‘I have given my word’ when he was asked about the renewal of his contract and Arsenal fans can expect him in the dug-out next season. He is unlikely to walk away now. Instead he will be there and the ambitions of the club - to win the Premier League or Champions League - will remain. To achieve them, it looks like he will need to accept some help.  Forward planning: Chief executive Gazidis (left) is looking to bring in someone above Wenger    More... Wenger is behind the game, but there won\'t be an Arsenal uprising despite fans being sick to the stomach of broken promises As Hillsborough anniversary approaches, football must not forget all those who have been loved and lost in stadium tragedies Until English football takes a lesson from Bayern Munich\'s pass masters and turns possession into an obsession, we don\'t stand a chance ADRIAN DURHAM: Arsenal should do English football a favour and give Everton a go in the Champions League... And Terry\'s far from a captain, leader, legend - he\'s a Chelsea let-down Celtic join race for Arsenal\'s Fabianski as Drmic could snub Gunners for Leverkusen All the latest Arsenal news, features and opinion  Share or comment on this article 133shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-1000161/Neil-Ashton.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Neil Ashton</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 18:01 EST, 1 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 18:01 EST, 1 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/Arsenal-not-tight-knit-family-unit-Wenger-own.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/Arsenal-not-tight-knit-family-unit-Wenger-own.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Arsenal are not the tight-knit family unit they were... Wenger can\'t do it all on his own\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 133</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football