senal uprising despite fans being sick to the stomach of broken promises</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2588939/As-Hillsborough-anniversary-approaches-football-not-forget-loved-lost.html\"> As Hillsborough anniversary approaches, football must not forget all those who have been loved and lost in stadium tragedies</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2589724/Until-English-football-takes-lesson-Bayern-Munichs-pass-masters-turns-possession-obsession-dont-stand-chance.html\"> Until English football takes a lesson from Bayern Munich\'s pass masters and turns possession into an obsession, we don\'t stand a chance</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2594042/Arsenal-English-football-favour-Everton-Champions-League-And-Terrys-far-captain-leader-legend-hes-Chelsea-let-ADRIAN-DURHAM-COLUMN.html\"> ADRIAN DURHAM: Arsenal should do English football a favour and give Everton a go in the Champions League... And Terry\'s far from a captain, leader, legend - he\'s a Chelsea let-down</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2593350/Celtic-join-race-Arsenals-Fabianski-Drmic-snub-Gunners-Leverkusen.html\"> Celtic join race for Arsenal\'s Fabianski as Drmic could snub Gunners for Leverkusen</a></li> <li><a class=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/teampages/arsenal.html\"> All the latest Arsenal news, features and opinion</a></li> </ul> </div> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">The box office employed another 10, eight in the commercial department, six more in the general office and a few manning the phones in the general office. Most would agree that it was a pretty tight, family unit.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Vice-chairman David Dein kept the club ticking over and secretary Ken Friar was in charge of the club’s administrative matters.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">They were such a homely club that some days Ian Wright used to turn up at Highbury and start picking up phones on the general switchboard. It certainly surprised a few callers.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Times change and Arsenal, just like Manchester City, Manchester United and Chelsea, have turned into giant, corporate monoliths.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Today Arsenal, with a turnover of £250m and a wage bill in the region of £145m per annum, employ around 450 full-time staff.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">It would be stretching the imagination to think that Wenger is managing a staff of that size, but his tentacles at Arsenal reach far and wide.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Everybody knows Wenger rules the roost at Arsenal.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Last Friday, ahead of their clash with City at the Emirates, Wenger was asked whether he is accountable to anyone at the club.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">This was his response: ‘I don’t know’.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Dropping points: Arsenal have not won in three league games after drawing against Man City on Saturday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"421\" id=\"i-aa2f0e71\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-1CAC976100000578-496_634x421.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Dropping points: Arsenal have not won in three league games after drawing against Man City on Saturday</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unsure: Wenger says he does not know who he is accountable to\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"420\" id=\"i-aaa40e72\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-1CACA15800000578-148_634x420.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unsure: Wenger says he does not know who he is accountable to</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Call centre: Ian Wright (second left) often answered the phones at Highbury\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"435\" id=\"i-a5360e4a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-0161536A000004B0-715_634x435.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Call centre: Ian Wright (second left) often answered the phones at Highbury</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Pressed further, he replied: ‘Look, our ambitions for the season - we are in a position where we can still fight for the top, we are in the semi-final of the FA Cup, we went out of the Champions League against Bayern Munich with 10 men and we have been consistent all season so I don’t think you can say our season up to now is a failure.’ In other words, he didn’t really answer the question.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">At 64, managing a club with the ambitions of a club the size of Arsenal, Wenger could do with some assistance in the day-to-day running of the football department. It makes an awful lot of sense.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Take the top leagues in Europe - Spain, Italy, Germany, England and add the newbies Paris St Germain - as an example.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Of the 17 clubs who qualified for the Champions League group stages, Arsenal and Manchester United are the only two clubs soldiering on without them.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Here they are: Bayern Munich (Mathias Sammer), Borussia Dortmund (Michael Zorc), Bayer Leverkusen (Rudi Voller) and Schalke 04 (Horst Heldt).</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Juventus (Fabio Paratici), Inter (Marco Branca), Milan (Ariedo Braida) and Napoli (Ricardo Bijon).</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Barcelona (Andoni Zubizaretta), Real Madrid (Miguel Pardeza), Atletico Madrid (Miguel Angel Gil Marin) and Real Sociedad (Lorenzo Juarros). At Paris St Germain (Olivier Letang and CEO Jean-Claude Blanc share the role).</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Old allies: Former Arsenal vice-president David Dein (left) left the club in 2007\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"508\" id=\"i-a54e0e4b\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-014816A10000044D-620_634x508.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Old allies: Former Arsenal vice-president David Dein (left) left the club in 2007</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Deal-broker: Dein and Wenger unveil Croatian striker Davor Suker in 1999\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"408\" id=\"i-a74e0e56\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-001DF1C400000258-103_634x408.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Deal-broker: Dein and Wenger unveil Croatian striker Davor Suker in 1999</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">In England, Chelsea employ Michael Emenalo as director of football and Marina Granovskaia is the conduit between the football board and owner Roman Abramovich. This set-up allows Jose Mourinho to concentrate on the main business of the club, which is planning training sessions and working with his team.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">At Manchester City, the Barcelona axis of Ferran Soriano (chief executive) and Txiki Begiristain (sporting director) were brought in to take the heat off Roberto Mancini and now Manuel Pellegrini.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Even down the road at Tottenham, where there has been an obsession with a continental management structure, chairman Daniel Levy employs Italian Franco Baldini in the role.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">There have been times in the past when Wenger has considered appointing someone into the role after Dein was fired by Arsenal’s former owner Danny Fiszman in 2007.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Reading’s director of football Nicky Hammond was interviewed in the summer of 2007, but in the end it came to nothing.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"State of the art: But Arsenal have not won a trophy since moving to the Emirates in 2006\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"424\" id=\"i-a7800e5e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-02C22A78000004B0-395_634x424.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">State of the art: But Arsenal have not won a trophy since moving to the Emirates in 2006</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Instead Wenger soldiered on with chief scout Steve Rowley and has found a niche role for Dick Law, previously based in Dallas, to make in roads into transfer business.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Arsenal are already preparing for life beyond Wenger and will bring in a director of football to work with a first-team coach when the time comes.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">That is a decision that has been made by the chief executive Ivan Gazidis as he begins long-term preparations for the day when they need to find a new manager.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">Last Friday, Wenger reiterated that ‘I have given my word’ when he was asked about the renewal of his contract and Arsenal fans can expect him in the dug-out next season. He is unlikely to walk away now. Instead he will be there and the ambitions of the club - to win the Premier League or Champions League - will remain.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size:1.2em;\">To achieve them, it looks like he will need to accept some help.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Forward planning: Chief executive Gazidis (left) is looking to bring in someone above Wenger\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"458\" id=\"i-9b990e38\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-1C778F5200000578-17_634x458.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Forward planning: Chief executive Gazidis (left) is looking to bring in someone above Wenger</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2589399/Arsene-Wenger-game-wont-Arsenal-uprising-despite-fans-sick-stomach-promises.html\"> Wenger is behind the game, but there won\'t be an Arsenal uprising despite fans being sick to the stomach of broken promises</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2588939/As-Hillsborough-anniversary-approaches-football-not-forget-loved-lost.html\"> As Hillsborough anniversary approaches, football must not forget all those who have been loved and lost in stadium tragedies</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2589724/Until-English-football-takes-lesson-Bayern-Munichs-pass-masters-turns-possession-obsession-dont-stand-chance.html\"> Until English football takes a lesson from Bayern Munich\'s pass masters and turns possession into an obsession, we don\'t stand a chance</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2594042/Arsenal-English-football-favour-Everton-Champions-League-And-Terrys-far-captain-leader-legend-hes-Chelsea-let-ADRIAN-DURHAM-COLUMN.html\"> ADRIAN DURHAM: Arsenal should do English football a favour and give Everton a go in the Champions League... And Terry\'s far from a captain, leader, legend - he\'s a Chelsea let-down</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2593350/Celtic-join-race-Arsenals-Fabianski-Drmic-snub-Gunners-Leverkusen.html\"> Celtic join race for Arsenal\'s Fabianski as Drmic could snub Gunners for Leverkusen</a></li> <li><a class=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/teampages/arsenal.html\"> All the latest Arsenal news, features and opinion</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/Arsenal-not-tight-knit-family-unit-Wenger-own.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/Arsenal-not-tight-knit-family-unit-Wenger-own.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Arsenal are not the tight-knit family unit they were... Wenger can\'t do it all on his own\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2594332/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">133</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/01/article-2594332-1CBE735400000578-87_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:07','2014-04-02 01:01:20'),(119,'f3b449901a022b44f8cc06df5e4eaed47402d6aeaea46cf7c0905cf3ba38c74d','dailymail',NULL,'Liverpool deserve to win the title, it would be great for English football too - JAMIE REDKNAPP column','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html',' Liverpool were 28 points off Premier League title last seasonNow Anfield club are two points clear at the summitChelsea played into Tony Pulis\' hands with two defensive midfieldersMathieu Flamini gives Arsenal much-needed stability in midfieldPlus, a special mention for Scunthorpe boss Russ Wilcox By Jamie Redknapp Published: 16:30 EST, 30 March 2014 | Updated: 00:38 EST, 31 March 2014 909 shares 301 View comments PREMIER LEAGUE TOP SCORERSLuis Suarez: 29Daniel Sturridge: 20Yaya Toure: 17Sergio Aguero: 15Jay Rodriguez: 15Wayne Rooney: 15Eden Hazard: 14 It\'s the time when people start talking about awards, but there is no question Liverpool should win the double. Luis Suarez has been magnificent and Brendan Rodgers is a class act. They are the player and manager of the year. Liverpool had success under Gerard Houllier and Rafa Benitez, but never played with the same style as Rodgers’ side. VIDEO Scroll down to watch Liverpool fans singing: We\'re going to win the league  Unstoppable? Luis Suarez slides on his knees after netting one of Liverpool\'s four goals against Tottenham   Mastermind: Brendan Rodgers has guided his side to the top of the Premier League table   Slip up: Manchester City dropped points at Arsenal on a decent weekend for Liverpool   Woe: John Terry is consoled by Chelsea team-mate Petr Cech after heading into his own net    Last year they were 28 points off the title and now they lead by two. That is an incredible turnaround. Glen Johnson said it would be good for neutrals if Liverpool won the title, but it would be great for English football full stop. They play such fantastic football with a British manager and Sunday had six Englishmen in their starting XI. Suarez and Rodgers should win the individual awards, but they will want to make it a magnificent treble with the title. Liverpool fans singing: We\'re going to win the league  MOURINHO ON THE DEFENSIVE You would expect Arsenal to play two defensive midfielders against Manchester City, but it was a surprise to see Jose Mourinho do it against Crystal Palace. He was without the suspended Ramires, and playing Nemanja Matic made sense because he is cup-tied for Wednesday’s Champions League game, but Tony Pulis will have been pleased to see Oscar and Willian on the bench.  No hope? Jose Mourinho believes his Chelsea side stand no chance of pipping City or Liverpol to the title   Defensive: David Luiz (left) and Nemanja Matic (right) both started at Crystal Palace for Chelsea    Starting Matic and David Luiz played into Palace’s hands. They relished the midfield battle rather than having to deal with Chelsea’s smaller playmakers, and Mile Jedinak was so strong. The result showed it’s not just big head-to-heads that can win you the title. Of the top three, only Liverpool have not lost a game to one of the bottom five.  RECORD RUSS A special mention to Scunthorpe’s Russ Wilcox, who set a Football League record on Saturday. After a 0-0 draw with Wycombe, Wilcox has gone 24 games without defeat, the most by a new boss. With Scunthorpe second in League Two, he could be extending that in League One next season.  Hard to beat: Russ Wilcox has gone 24 games undefeated as Scunthorpe United manager   MARTINEZ WOULD LOVE EURO CASH Everton are doing their part to keep up the Merseyside revival. Roberto Martinez is another exciting manager who has his team playing good, stylish football. With another win, next week’s game against Arsenal is now massive. Finishing in the top four and qualifying for the Champions League would be so important for them.  Cruising: Kevin Mirallas and Everton brushed relegation candidates Fulham aside at Craven Cottage   Licence to thrill: Roberto Martinez is an exciting young manager lighting up the Premier League   Here to stay? Romelu Lukaku (left) and Gareth Barry, on loan from Chelsea and Manchester City respectively, are two members of Martinez\'s impressive Everton squad to have dazzled at Goodison Park this season  A lot of their success this season has been built on loans — Romelu Lukaku, Gareth Barry, Gerard Deulofeu. And with Champions League money in the bank, they might just be able to make the signings permanent.  ARSENAL\'S MAIN MIDDLE MAN When Arsenal lost 6-0 to Chelsea, Mathieu Flamini spent the first half on the bench. By the time he came on, his side were 4-0 down.  Pegged back: Mathieu Flamini rallies his Arsenal team-mates after equalising for the Gunners at home   Fighter: Flamini was Arsenal\'s stand-out performer against Manchester City at the Emirates  DISTANCE COVERED DATAMathieu Flamini covered more ground than any other player at the Emirates. Mikel Arteta, at 32 the oldest midfielder on the pitch, was second.Mathieu Flamini: 8.4milesMikel Arteta: 7.5Santi Cazorla: 7.2Fernandinho: 7.1Yaya Toure: 6.9 Data courtesy of the EA SPORTS Player Performance Index, the Official Player Rating Index of the Barclays Premier League Against Manchester City, he gave the midfield the legs they needed. He ruffled a few feathers, too, nicking a goal and providing energy. Mikel Arteta is a good playmaker, but looks much better with Flamini alongside him. Against Chelsea, their attacking midfielders closed Arteta then sprang off the back of him and Arsenal couldn’t cope. Flamini helps close things up against powerful midfields, and there is none more powerful than City’s. For years Arsenal have struggled against stronger sides because they are not good enough without the ball. Is Flamini the long-term solution? No, but, with him in the side, Arsenal look a much more solid outfit.  Grafting: Mikel Arteta (right) also covered a lot of ground against City at the Emirates   ODEMWINGIE\'S LAUGHING NOW When he turned up in the QPR car park looking for a transfer, Peter Odemwingie was a bit of a laughing stock, but now he’s proving his quality. He has scored in three games in a row and Stoke have won them all. He works well with Peter Crouch and, with his side playing good football, Mark Hughes could lead Stoke to their first top-10 Premier League finish. They played brilliantly at Aston Villa last weekend and have a great home record — eight wins and just two defeats.  Easily done: Peter Odemwingie (right) celebrates his winner against Hull City on Saturday     HOTSHOT WAYNE Wayne Rooney is now fourth in the all-time Premier League scorers list. He is four goals away from Thierry Henry and 16 off Andy Cole, but can he beat Alan Shearer’s 260? At this rate, Rooney would have to play for seven more seasons to get there. It’s not impossible for somebody of his quality.  Deadeye: Wayne Rooney rifles home from the penalty spot against Aston Villa on Saturday   Enlarge    More... Pellegrini\'s message to Mourinho: \'Intelligent bosses don\'t play mind games\' Wenger: My players proved mental strength with spirited draw against Man City Suarez is worth £100m! Rodgers insists star striker is on the same level as Ronaldo and Messi \'Immense\' Liverpool make Rodgers proud but boss insists title is still far away Liverpool 4-0 Tottenham: Reds back to the summit after rout over terrible Spurs Read the latest Liverpool news and views here  Share or comment on this article 909shares','\n<ul class=\"article-summary sport\"><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Liverpool were 28 points off Premier League title last season</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Now Anfield club are two points clear at the summit</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Chelsea played into Tony Pulis\' hands with two defensive midfielders</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Mathieu Flamini gives Arsenal much-needed stability in midfield</font></b></li><li><b><font style=\"font-size: 1.4em;\">Plus, a special mention for Scunthorpe boss Russ Wilcox<br/></font></b></li></ul>\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/debate/columnists/columnist-348/Jamie-Redknapp.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jamie Redknapp</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 16:30 EST, 30 March 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 00:38 EST, 31 March 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE REDKNAPP: Manager of the Year? Rodgers. Player of the Year? Suarez... And if Liverpool beat Man City and Chelsea to the Premier League it\'ll be GREAT for English football\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 909</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">301</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 class=\"wocc\"><b>PREMIER LEAGUE TOP SCORERS</b><br/></h3><div align=\"center\" class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Luis <b>Suarez</b>: 29</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Daniel <b>Sturridge: </b>20</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Yaya <b>Toure: </b>17</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Sergio <b>Aguero: </b>15</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Jay <b>Rodriguez: </b>15</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Wayne <b>Rooney: </b>15</font><br/><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Eden <b>Hazard: </b>14</font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></p></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">It\'s the time when people start talking about awards, but there is no question Liverpool should win the double. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Luis Suarez has been magnificent and Brendan Rodgers is a class act. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They are the player and manager of the year. Liverpool had success under Gerard Houllier and Rafa Benitez, but never played with the same style as Rodgers’ side. <b><br/></b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"><b><font color=\"FFFFFF\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(12, 172, 12);\">VIDEO</span></font> Scroll down to watch Liverpool fans singing: We\'re going to win the league</b><br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Unstoppable? Luis Suarez slides on his knees after netting one of Liverpool\'s four goals against Tottenham\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"450\" id=\"i-abb60e7e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB3A56A00000578-915_634x450.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Unstoppable? Luis Suarez slides on his knees after netting one of Liverpool\'s four goals against Tottenham</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Mastermind: Brendan Rodgers has guided his side to the top of the Premier League table\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"487\" id=\"i-ad0f0e98\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB39F2B00000578-898_634x487.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Mastermind: Brendan Rodgers has guided his side to the top of the Premier League table</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Slip up: Manchester City dropped points at Arsenal on a decent weekend for Liverpool\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"428\" id=\"i-ae170e96\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAC6EB800000578-371_634x428.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Slip up: Manchester City dropped points at Arsenal on a decent weekend for Liverpool</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Woe: John Terry is consoled by Chelsea team-mate Petr Cech after heading into his own net\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"499\" id=\"i-ae600ea4\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CABB3C900000578-967_634x499.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Woe: John Terry is consoled by Chelsea team-mate Petr Cech after heading into his own net</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS\"> <img alt=\"Top of the table\" class=\"img-no-border img-share\" height=\"155\" id=\"i-a94d0e64\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB4629800000578-631_306x155.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Last year they were 28 points off the title and now they lead by two. That is an incredible turnaround. Glen Johnson said it would be good for neutrals if Liverpool won the title, but it would be great for English football full stop. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They play such fantastic football with a British manager and Sunday had six Englishmen in their starting XI. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Suarez and Rodgers should win the individual awards, but they will want to make it a magnificent treble with the title.</font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"><a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3397843832001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Liverpool fans singing: We\'re going to win the league</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/27/video-undefined-1C9D126700000578-822_638x384.jpg\"/> </center> </a> </div> <div class=\"sport\"> <div class=\"wocc videoplayer-keyline\"></div> </div> </div> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\"><b>MOURINHO ON THE DEFENSIVE</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">You would expect Arsenal to play two defensive midfielders against Manchester City, but it was a surprise to see Jose Mourinho do it against Crystal Palace. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He was without the suspended Ramires, and playing Nemanja Matic made sense because he is cup-tied for Wednesday’s Champions League game, but Tony Pulis will have been pleased to see Oscar and Willian on the bench. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"No hope? Jose Mourinho believes his Chelsea side stand no chance of pipping City or Liverpol to the title\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"377\" id=\"i-ad570e90\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CABD3D300000578-523_634x377.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">No hope? Jose Mourinho believes his Chelsea side stand no chance of pipping City or Liverpol to the title</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Up for it: David Luiz (right) started against Crystal Palace\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a9950e66\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAB062300000578-843_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Snap: Nemanja Matic battles with Kagisho Dikgacoi\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-aeb80e97\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAB4FBC00000578-543_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Defensive: David Luiz (left) and Nemanja Matic (right) both started at Crystal Palace for Chelsea <br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS\"> <img alt=\"Defensive: The big teams\' stats against Cardiff, Fulham, Sunderland, West Brom and Palace\" class=\"img-no-border img-share\" height=\"132\" id=\"i-aac20e70\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB414BA00000578-642_306x132.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Starting Matic and David Luiz played into Palace’s hands. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They relished the midfield battle rather than having to deal with Chelsea’s smaller playmakers, and Mile Jedinak was so strong. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The result showed it’s not just big head-to-heads that can win you the title. Of the top three, only Liverpool have not lost a game to one of the bottom five.</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\"><b>RECORD RUSS</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">A special mention to Scunthorpe’s Russ Wilcox, who set a Football League record on Saturday. After a 0-0 draw with Wycombe, Wilcox has gone 24 games without defeat, the most by a new boss. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">With Scunthorpe second in League Two, he could be extending that in League One next season.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Hard to beat: Russ Wilcox has gone 24 games undefeated as Scunthorpe United manager\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"409\" id=\"i-aaa60e77\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1C95C31E00000578-354_634x409.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Hard to beat: Russ Wilcox has gone 24 games undefeated as Scunthorpe United manager</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\"><b>MARTINEZ WOULD LOVE EURO CASH</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Everton are doing their part to keep up the Merseyside revival. Roberto Martinez is another exciting manager who has his team playing good, stylish football. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">With another win, next week’s game against Arsenal is now massive. </font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Finishing in the top four and qualifying for the Champions League would be so important for them. </font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Cruising: Kevin Mirallas and Everton brushed relegation candidates Fulham aside at Craven Cottage\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"405\" id=\"i-ae0e0e98\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB1BCE800000578-769_634x405.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Cruising: Kevin Mirallas and Everton brushed relegation candidates Fulham aside at Craven Cottage</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Licence to thrill: Roberto Martinez is an exciting young manager lighting up the Premier League\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"436\" id=\"i-ab630e7e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB1C80A00000578-167_634x436.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Licence to thrill: Roberto Martinez is an exciting young manager lighting up the Premier League</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <div class=\"splitLeft\"> <img alt=\"Sign him up: Romelu Lukaku is on loan from Chelsea\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-af5c0e9a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1C9FBCDD00000578-131_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"splitRight\"> <img alt=\"Man in the middle: Gareth Barry has had a fine season on loan from Manchester City\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"423\" id=\"i-a9b30e66\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB1294D00000578-115_306x423.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div> <div class=\"clear\"> </div> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Here to stay? Romelu Lukaku (left) and Gareth Barry, on loan from Chelsea and Manchester City respectively, are two members of Martinez\'s impressive Everton squad to have dazzled at Goodison Park this season<br/></p></div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">A lot of their success this season has been built on loans — Romelu Lukaku, Gareth Barry, Gerard Deulofeu. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">And with Champions League money in the bank, they might just be able to make the signings permanent.</font></p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><b><font style=\"font-size:1.8em;\">ARSENAL\'S MAIN MIDDLE MAN</font></b></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">When Arsenal lost 6-0 to Chelsea, Mathieu Flamini spent the first half on the bench. By the time he came on, his side were 4-0 down. <br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Pegged back: Mathieu Flamini rallies his Arsenal team-mates after equalising for the Gunners at home\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"416\" id=\"i-af340e9e\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CACB8BE00000578-811_634x416.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Pegged back: Mathieu Flamini rallies his Arsenal team-mates after equalising for the Gunners at home</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Fighter: Flamini was Arsenal\'s stand-out performer against Manchester City at the Emirates\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"478\" id=\"i-ac6b0e8c\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAC386B00000578-455_634x478.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Fighter: Flamini was Arsenal\'s stand-out performer against Manchester City at the Emirates</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"floatRHS art-ins sport\"><h3 align=\"center\" class=\"wocc\"><b>DISTANCE COVERED DATA</b><br/></h3><div class=\"ins cleared xolcc bdrcc\"><p><i><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Mathieu Flamini covered more ground than any other player at the Emirates. Mikel Arteta, at 32 the oldest midfielder on the pitch, was </font><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">second.</font></i></p><p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Mathieu <b>Flamini: </b>8.4miles<br/>Mikel <b>Arteta: </b>7.5<br/>Santi <b>Cazorla: </b>7.2<br/><b>Fernandinho: </b>7.1<br/>Yaya <b>Toure: </b>6.9</font></p><div class=\"clear\"> </div> <img alt=\"EA SPORTS\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"78\" id=\"i-9c2c0e4d\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-14D18993000005DC-362_296x78.jpg\" width=\"296\"/> <p> </p><ul><li><b>Data courtesy of the EA SPORTS Player Performance Index, the Official Player Rating Index of the Barclays Premier League</b><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\"> </font></li></ul></div></div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Against Manchester City, he gave the midfield the legs they needed. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He ruffled a few feathers, too, nicking a goal and providing energy.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Mikel Arteta is a good playmaker, but looks much better with Flamini alongside him.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Against Chelsea, their attacking midfielders closed Arteta then sprang off the back of him and Arsenal couldn’t cope.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Flamini helps close things up against powerful midfields, and there is none more powerful than City’s.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">For years Arsenal have struggled against stronger sides because they are not good enough without the ball.</font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Is Flamini the long-term solution? <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">No, but, with him in the side, Arsenal look a much more solid outfit.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Grafting: Mikel Arteta (right) also covered a lot of ground against City at the Emirates\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"374\" id=\"i-ab180e79\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAC937400000578-660_634x374.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Grafting: Mikel Arteta (right) also covered a lot of ground against City at the Emirates</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\"><b>ODEMWINGIE\'S LAUGHING NOW</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">When he turned up in the QPR car park looking for a transfer, Peter Odemwingie was a bit of a laughing stock, but now he’s proving his quality. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">He has scored in three games in a row and Stoke have won them all. He works well with Peter Crouch and, with his side playing good football, Mark Hughes could lead Stoke to their first top-10 Premier League finish. <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">They played brilliantly at Aston Villa last weekend and have a great home record — eight wins and just two defeats.</font></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Easily done: Peter Odemwingie (right) celebrates his winner against Hull City on Saturday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"402\" id=\"i-abe60e7a\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAC48E100000578-271_634x402.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Easily done: Peter Odemwingie (right) celebrates his winner against Hull City on Saturday</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"pageBreak\"> </div>\n<div class=\"floatRHS\"> <img alt=\"The top-five all-time Premier League goalscorers\" class=\"img-no-border img-share\" height=\"139\" id=\"i-ab300e77\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB416FA00000578-510_306x139.jpg\" width=\"306\"/> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.8em;\"><b>HOTSHOT WAYNE</b></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Wayne Rooney is now fourth in the all-time Premier League scorers list. He is four goals away from Thierry Henry and 16 off Andy Cole, but can he beat Alan Shearer’s 260? <br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">At this rate, Rooney would have to play for seven more seasons to get there. It’s not impossible for somebody of his quality.</font><br/></p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <img alt=\"Deadeye: Wayne Rooney rifles home from the penalty spot against Aston Villa on Saturday\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"395\" id=\"i-ad590e96\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CAB05AF00000578-657_634x395.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> <p class=\"imageCaption\">Deadeye: Wayne Rooney rifles home from the penalty spot against Aston Villa on Saturday</p> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"artSplitter\"> <a class=\"lightboxPopupLink\" href=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB40FBC00000578-828_634x237_popup.jpg\" onclick=\"return false;\" rel=\"\"> <span class=\"clickToEnlargeTop\">Enlarge</span> <span class=\"clickToEnlarge\"></span> <span class=\"clickToEnlargeButton\"> </span> <img alt=\"Jamie Redknapp\'s Premier League number crunching\" class=\"blkBorder img-share\" height=\"237\" id=\"i-ad5b0e93\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB40FBC00000578-828_634x237.jpg\" width=\"634\"/> </a> </div>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592816/Manuel-Pellegrini-claims-intelligent-managers-dont-play-mind-games.html\"> Pellegrini\'s message to Mourinho: \'Intelligent bosses don\'t play mind games\'</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592828/Arsene-Wenger-Arsenal-players-proved-mental-strength.html\"> Wenger: My players proved mental strength with spirited draw against Man City</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592634/Luis-Suarez-worth-100m-Brendan-Rodgers-insists-star-striker-level-Cristiano-Ronaldo-Lionel-Messi.html\"> Suarez is worth £100m! Rodgers insists star striker is on the same level as Ronaldo and Messi</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592844/Immense-Liverpool-make-Rodgers-proud-boss-insists-title-far-away.html\"> \'Immense\' Liverpool make Rodgers proud but boss insists title is still far away</a></li> <li><a href=\"/sport/football/article-2592730/Liverpool-4-0-Tottenham-match-report-Reds-summit-rout-lacklustre-Spurs.html\"> Liverpool 4-0 Tottenham: Reds back to the summit after rout over terrible Spurs</a></li> <li><a class=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/teampages/liverpool.html\"> Read the latest Liverpool news and views here</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/Liverpool-deserve-win-title-great-English-football-JAMIE-REDKNAPP-column.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"JAMIE REDKNAPP: Manager of the Year? Rodgers. Player of the Year? Suarez... And if Liverpool beat Man City and Chelsea to the Premier League it\'ll be GREAT for English football\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2592836/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count_small\">909</div><div class=\"shares_text_small\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/30/article-2592836-1CB40EAB00000578-668_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:08','2014-03-31 07:38:43'),(120,'eb6c36220098818fce00e3464adaf36c6120a8085cb8ae1ae821319e819754f5','dailymail',NULL,'From Australia to Abu Dhabi: Your essential interactive guide to every Formula One race in 2014','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html','  Published: 10:02 EST, 14 March 2014 | Updated: 11:46 EST, 14 March 2014 17 shares 0 View comments The Formula One circus takes on five continents over eight months of gruelling action in 2014. Click on Sportsmail\'s ground-breaking interactive guide below to find out everything you need to know about the 19 races which make up this year\'s calendar.    More... Formula One 2014: The new rules and regulations explained in our brilliant interactive guide     Share or comment on this article 17shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\"></p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 10:02 EST, 14 March 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 11:46 EST, 14 March 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"From Australia to Abu Dhabi: Your essential interactive guide to every Formula One race in 2014\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 17</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">0</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The Formula One circus takes on five continents over eight months of gruelling action in 2014. Click on <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Sportsmail\'s</span> ground-breaking interactive guide below to find out everything you need to know about the 19 races which make up this year\'s calendar.</font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleTriple\">  <div class=\"sport item html_snippet_module\"> <iframe frameborder=\"no\" height=\"765\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/graphics/2014/04/INTERACTIVE/F1_2014.html\" width=\"957\"></iframe> </div> </div>\n<div class=\"moduleTriple\">  </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItemsTopBorder\"> </div>\n<div class=\"relatedItems\"> <h4>More...</h4> <ul> <li><a href=\"/sport/formulaone/article-2581130/Formula-One-2014-The-new-rules-regulations-explained-brilliant-interactive-guide.html\"> Formula One 2014: The new rules and regulations explained in our brilliant interactive guide</a></li> </ul> </div>\n<br/>\n<p><br/></p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"clear\"> </div>\n<div class=\"column-content cleared\"> <div class=\"shareArticles\"> <h3 class=\"social-links-title\">Share or comment on this article</h3> <div class=\"social-links cleared\" id=\"socialLinks\"> <ul class=\"bigLinks sc-icns cleared\"> <li class=\"facebook\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\'postToFB(\"bottom\"); return false;\' rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"twitter\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"pinterest\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'bottom\'); return false;\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </li> <li class=\"googleplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/From-Australia-Abu-Dhabi-Your-essential-interactive-guide-Formula-One-race-2014.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"From Australia to Abu Dhabi: Your essential interactive guide to every Formula One race in 2014\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" onclick=\"postToGPlus(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\"></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"email\"> <a class=\"js-tl\" href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-2581084/emailArticle.html\" onclick=\"emailArticle(\'bottom\');\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_new\" title=\"Email to a friend\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"share\" id=\"shareLinkBottom\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> <li class=\"social-stats social-stats-pipe\" id=\"shareCountBottom\"> <div> <div class=\"shares_count\">17</div><div class=\"shares_text\">shares</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div>','http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/03/14/article-2581084-1C4C30D100000578-499_1024x615_large.jpg',NULL,'2014-04-12 16:59:09','2014-04-12 23:34:44'),(121,'2498aaf6f483d9f5be6795dfc1b99baf56f0b25915520c084e3064a0c8a5a99a','dailymail',NULL,'Rangers 1-3 Dundee United: Stuart Armstrong, Gary Mackay-Steven and Nadir Ciftci goals see Tangerines progress to Scottish Cup final','http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603092/Rangers-1-3-Dundee-United-Stuart-Armstrong-Gary-Mackay-Steven-Nadir-Ciftci-goals-Tangerines-progress-Scottish-Cup-final.html',' By Fraser Mackie Published: 08:44 EST, 12 April 2014 | Updated: 16:24 EST, 12 April 2014 10 shares 61 View comments Nadir Ciftci\'s agent, Pierre van Hooijdonk, was often worn down in his Old Firm pomp by the frustration of losing in one-on-one combat at the Broomloan Road goal with Rangers’ brilliant keeper Andy Goram. The former Celtic striker’s client found it all so laughably easy yesterday. Seven minutes from time, Ciftci rolled the ball into the  empty net after a goalkeeping calamity from  Steve Simonsen, standing in for injured Cammy Bell, to seal a William Hill Scottish Cup Final place for Dundee United. Simonsen’s folly was an example of the  individual incompetence at the back as  the Rangers defence was exposed when stepping up in class. Ciftci: I was celebrating before I scored and nearly missed it  Pure joy: Dundee United celebrate Gary Mackay-Steven\'s goal in their 3-1 semi-final win against Rangers Clincher: Dundee United\'s Nadir Ciftci (right) scored their third goal after Steve Simonsen\'s (left) error All smiles: Ciftci celebrates in front of the Dundee United fans after scoring his side\'s third goal vs Rangers  Match FactsRangers: Simonsen, Foster, McCulloch, Mohsni, Steven Smith, Peralta, Black, Aird (Clark 63), Shiels, Law, Daly. Subs not used: Callum Gallagher, Crawford, Emilson Cribari, Hutton, Faure, Scott Gallagher. Booked: Black Goals: Smith Dundee Utd: Cierzniak, Wilson (Watson 61), Souttar, Gunning, Robertson (Gomis 85), Paton, Rankin, Gauld (Dow 67), Armstrong, Mackay-Steven, Ciftci. Subs not used: Dillon, Graham, McCallum, El Alagui. Booked: Wilson, Gunning, Armstrong Goals: Armstrong, Mackay-Steven, CiftciReferee: Bobby Madden (Scotland) Attendance: 41,059 There was plenty of ineptitude up front, too, as miserable efforts in front of goal by Dean Shiels and Jon Daly undid a display that was markedly better than last weekend’s flop against Raith Rovers — yet not good enough to stifle one of the country’s more potent attacking teams. Rangers actually looked better for taking the game to one of the Premiership’s top sides this season. After flopping as favourites in the Ramsdens Cup, their supporters loved the  status of being embattled underdogs on their home turf. ‘Defytheodds’ was the advertised hashtag on the tournament sponsors’ big screen advert and it was raucous stuff from the first whistle, the closest this stadium has come to rocking in Old Firm game fashion since Rangers beat Celtic six weeks after being sunk into  administration in 2012. Fraser Aird forced the first corner after a John Souttar slip, then launched pressure upon United keeper Radoslaw Cierzniak, with Lee McCulloch and Bilel Mohsni both having efforts at goal in a packed area. Ibrox roared as loud as on a Glasgow derby day and the action was just as frenetic. There was barely time to draw breath in the first half but, upon settling down, the story to tell at the break was one of Stuart Armstrong and Gary Mackay-Steven doling out lessons in being lethal in the aftermath of those Rangers misses.  Lashed home: Stuart Armstrong (centre) gave Dundee United the lead in their Scottish Cup semi-final   Lucky break: Gary Mackay Steven (bottom left) doubled United\'s advantage just before half-time     Ally McCoist had been in the line of fire last week but the manager was let down here by his forwards. Many wondered why Shiels was kept on the bench when that insipid display against Raith at Easter Road was in sore need of a spark last Sunday. Shiels got his movement, run and control all right to latch on to the pass as Daly found  a gap in the United defence. The finish,  however, was all wrong, skewed tamely wide with his left foot from 12 yards. If McCoist has trust issues with the former Kilmarnock man in front of goal, that 19th minute miss explained why. Four minutes later, Armstrong showed Shiels how to keep composed in front of goal. Cifcti gave himself up in his offside position as Armstrong advanced on to Gavin Gunning’s header back into the area. The ball bounced kindly for the Scotland Under-21 midfielder to volley in off Simonsen’s left-hand post. The keeper then palmed away a bouncing effort from Ciftci as the hosts tried and failed to settle in the wake of falling behind. Nicky Law came closest for Rangers when his cross struck an upright, with the unperturbed Cierzniak presumably believing there was no threat. Nor was there any danger from his former colleague Daly who, after Aird’s lay-off, scooped a shot wildly over when left in  penalty-box space for the first and only time on the day. His 18 goals in League One this season counted for little as the Irishman blew it on the big stage.  Getting stuck in: Rangers\' Dean Shiels (left) and Dundee United\'s Paul Paton (right) battle for the ball   Consolation: Steven Smith (centre) pulled one back for Rangers just before the interval at Ibrox Down and out: Shiels looks dejected as Rangers bowed out of the William Hill Scottish Cup on Saturday       United warmed to the theme of Rangers’ failings and struck for a second time against the run of play.Ryan Gauld’s pace and skill took him to the byline and Armstrong helped the cutback on to Mackay-Steven. He took aim with a left-foot shot and Mohsni’s bid to block provided only assistance for United — Simonsen was helpless as that touch sent the ball spinning over the keeper and into the net. With the Rangers forwards flopping in front of goal, it took a set-piece from a defender to drag them into contention. Fair play to left-back Steven Smith for the execution over the wall and accuracy of the effort on target. But the pace should not have caused a top-flight keeper to fail to save at his left-hand post. Cierzniak tried with two hands but the mechanics were all wrong and the ball squirmed in behind him. United were denied an immediate chance to respond when referee Bobby Madden blundered in failing to award a penalty as both Mohsni and Simonsen had an illegal go at stalling Ciftci’s charge. The second half saw Rangers’ pursuit of an equaliser push back a United team seemingly content with a 2-1 scoreline.  Eyes on the prize: Rangers Richard Foster (left) tussles with United\'s Andrew Robertson (right) for the ball   Fervent support: Rangers fans give show their backing for the club before their clash against Dundee United    Smith was in the set-piece mood and, with the aid of a heavy deflection, caused more panic for Cierzniak. As McCulloch and Richard Foster closed in, the keeper clawed the ball off his line. There was always the creeping concern about Rangers that a communication  breakdown would prove costly. With Bell missing and Mohsni as erratic as ever, United were a danger on the break. Ciftci was the length of a stud away from converting substitute Keith Watson’s drilled delivery across the six-yard box. But the Turkish striker was to be presented with another gift that helped him wrap up the win and send United into the Final.  Heavy hit: Ciftci (top) and Rangers captain Lee McCulloch (bottom) collide during their semi-final clash     Foster helped the ball back to Simonsen and the keeper’s terrible touch allowed Ciftci to pinch possession. He could even afford a stumble and another touch before tucking gleefully home in front of a jubilant United contingent, including Stephen Thompson. That was not a bad way to impress his  chairman. In Ciftci’s case, he had managed to please his Celtic-supporting advisor, too.   More... Scotland on the up as Strachan\'s side rise 15 places to 22nd in the FIFA world rankings... with England up to 11th King declares war on Rangers board as he urges fans to withhold season-ticket money Former Dundee United striker Daly aiming to fight flak with firepower as he looks to put Rangers into Scottish Cup final McCoist: We felt the same pain as fans after Raith defeat... we\'ll bounce back in Cup semi Rangers should stick with McCoist through thick and thin, insists Dailly McCoist seeks to put final defeat behind him ahead of Rangers\' Scottish Cup semi-final   Share or comment on this article 10shares','\n<p class=\"author-section\">By <a class=\"author\" href=\"/home/search.html?s=&amp;authornamef=Fraser+Mackie\" rel=\"nofollow\">Fraser Mackie</a> </p>\n<p class=\"byline-section\"><span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-published\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Published:</span> 08:44 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> | <span class=\"article-timestamp article-timestamp-updated\"> <span class=\"article-timestamp-label\">Updated:</span> 16:24 EST, 12 April 2014 </span> </p>\n<div id=\"articleIconLinksContainer\"> <ul> <li class=\"share-facebook\" onclick=\"postToFB(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-twitter\" onclick=\"postToTWTTR(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-pinterest\" onclick=\"postToPinterest(\'top\'); return false;\"></li> <li class=\"share-gplus\"> <span class=\"g-interactivepost\" data-calltoactionlabel=\"VIEW\" data-calltoactionurl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603092/Rangers-1-3-Dundee-United-Stuart-Armstrong-Gary-Mackay-Steven-Nadir-Ciftci-goals-Tangerines-progress-Scottish-Cup-final.html\" data-clientid=\"746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com\" data-contentdeeplinkid=\"/pages\" data-contenturl=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2603092/Rangers-1-3-Dundee-United-Stuart-Armstrong-Gary-Mackay-Steven-Nadir-Ciftci-goals-Tangerines-progress-Scottish-Cup-final.html\" data-cookiepolicy=\"single_host_origin\" data-prefilltext=\"Rangers 1-3 Dundee United: Armstrong, Mackay-Steven and Ciftci goals see Tangerines progress to Scottish Cup final\"> <a onclick=\'postToGPlus(\"top\"); return false;\'></a> </span> </li> <li class=\"share-icons\" id=\"shareLinkTop\"> <a class=\"js-sl share-link\" href=\"#socialLinks\"> </a> </li> </ul> <div class=\"share-count\"> <b> 10</b> <span>shares</span> </div> <a class=\"comments-count home\" href=\"/sport/football/article-2603092/Rangers-1-3-Dundee-United-Stuart-Armstrong-Gary-Mackay-Steven-Nadir-Ciftci-goals-Tangerines-progress-Scottish-Cup-final.html#comments\"> <span></span> <p class=\"count-number\">61</p> <p class=\"count-text\">View <br/> comments</p> </a> </div>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Nadir Ciftci\'s agent, Pierre van Hooijdonk, was often worn down in his Old Firm pomp by the frustration of losing in one-on-one combat at the Broomloan Road goal with Rangers’ brilliant keeper Andy Goram.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">The former Celtic striker’s client found it all so laughably easy yesterday. Seven minutes from time, Ciftci rolled the ball into the  empty net after a goalkeeping calamity from  Steve Simonsen, standing in for injured Cammy Bell, to seal a William Hill Scottish Cup Final place for Dundee United.<br/></font></p>\n<p><font style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">Simonsen’s folly was an example of the  individual incompetence at the back as  the Rangers defence was exposed when stepping up in class.<br/></font></p>\n<div class=\"moduleFull\"> <a class=\"namedLink\" name=\"video\"></a><div class=\"item\"> <div id=\"v-3461238596001\" style=\"width:636px;\"> <div class=\"videoplayer-large\" style=\"overflow-y:hidden\"> <a> <div class=\"videoplayer-title-bg\"></div> <div class=\"videoplayer-title\">Ciftci: I was celebrating before I scored and nearly missed it</div> <div class=\"btnBg\"></div> <span class=\"playbtn\"></span> <center> <img class=\"plcHlder\" src=\"http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2014/04/12/video-undefined-1D0E